<SLUG> BC-OLY-BRIBERY-2NDLEDE-WRITETHRU-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO OLYMPICS ORGANIZERS QUIT IN SALT LAKE CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for complete rewrite, to clarify and restructure, including
moving up info. on impact of resignations on sponsors and adding
details to ID of J.W. Marriott.) 
(ATTN: Utah)  (js) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY _ The top two local organizers of the 2002 Winter
Olympics resigned Friday as new details continued to emerge in a
mushrooming bribery scandal.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two, Frank Joklik, resigned under pressure as
president of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee, and Joklik asked
for the resignation of the other, Dave Johnson, the senior vice
president of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik, 70, has not been linked to the scandal and will remain
in his position until a successor is found. The pressure came from
Gov. Mike Leavitt of Utah, a member of the board of trustees of the
Salt Lake Organizing Committee, and U.S. Olympic officials, who
were concerned about public embarrassment and about wavering
confidence by corporate sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, a member of the International Olympic Committee,
indicated Friday that some members of the committee would be
pressured to resign when it meets later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal became public last November when a Salt Lake City
television station received a copy of a letter from Johnson to the
daughter of an IOC member from Cameroon, stating that a $10,000
tuition payment would be her last. Johnson has refused to talk with
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik acknowledged for the first time that the Salt Lake City
bid committee had taken these improper actions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Provided free health care to IOC members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aided an IOC member in a profitable Utah land deal.
</P>
<P>
   _ Made direct cash payments _ apparently about $70,000 in one
case _ to ``a number'' of IOC members and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, officials of the Salt Lake City committee had
acknowledged that the bid committee had paid housing, travel and
education expenses to relatives of members of the IOC and had given
them expensive gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Thursday
that the payments ranged from $5,000 to $70,000 and had been made
to IOC members from Africa and Latin America. On Friday they said
that Jean-Claude Ganga, an IOC member from Congo Republic, had
received a series of payments totaling approximately $70,000 before
the vote in June 1995 in which Salt Lake City won the 2002 Winter
Games. The investigators said that there did not appear to be any
justifiable reason for the payments but that they were still being
examined. Efforts to reach Ganga Friday and in recent weeks were
unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik also announced Friday that a monthly $10,000 consulting
fee paid to the former president of the Salt Lake City organizing
committee, Tom Welch, would be discontinued. Welch headed the bid
committee that secured the Games and resigned his Olympic position
in 1997 after pleading no contest to a misdemeanor charge of
spousal battery. Welch and Johnson were the two most visible
members of the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Two other employees of the local organizing committee took
administrative leave pending the outcome of the inquiry: Kelly
Flint, senior vice president for marketing and legal affairs, and
Rod Hamson, the licensing director, who worked as finance director
of the bid committee.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said he was ``deeply dismayed'' by the disclosures of
recent weeks and felt that it was necessary to resign to give the
organizing committee a chance to make a fresh start with the Games
only three years away.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation was welcomed by the U.S. Olympic Committee,
which still must raise more than $250 million in a joint marketing
effort with Salt Lake City to achieve the privately financed budget
of $1.45 billion for the 2002 Winter Games. Corporate sponsors have
become jittery in recent weeks as details of the scandal became
public, and US West even withheld a $5 million sponsorship payment.
</P>
<P>
   Without Friday's resignations to signal to sponsors that the
scandal was being handled quickly and thoroughly, it would have
been ``extremely difficult, perhaps impossible, to raise funds
necessary for these Games,'' said John Krimsky Jr., the USOC's
chief fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   While an international search will be conducted for Joklik's
replacement, some names being mentioned here include these
potential candidates:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dave Checketts, the chief executive officer of Madison Square
Garden, a native of Utah whose name surfaced as a possible
replacement for Welch in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jon M. Huntsman Jr., vice chairman of Huntsman Chemical Corp.
</P>
<P>
   _ J.W. Marriott Jr., chairman and chief executive of Marriott
International, the hotel company.
</P>
<P>
   _ Brent Scowcroft, the former national security adviser to
President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   _ David P. Gardner, the former president of the University of
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   _ Henry Marsh, a former Olympic steeple-chaser.
</P>
<P>
   DeFrantz, one of two members of the IOC from the United States,
said here Friday that some IOC members involved in the Salt Lake
City scandal would be asked to resign at a meeting Jan. 23 and 24
at the committee's headquarters in Lausanne, Switzerland. The IOC
also reiterated Friday that it would not take the 2002 Games away
from Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if any heads would roll at the international committee,
DeFrantz said, ``I don't think we will have executions, but we will
have fewer members.'' It was the strongest indication yet from the
IOC that some of its 114 members would be pressured to relinquish
their positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few individuals who have abused their privilege,''
DeFrantz said. ``We must have them removed from the Olympic
movement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One who has come under scrutiny is Ganga, 64, who holds
influence as the president of the national Olympic committees of
Africa. According to Olympic officials, the Salt Lake City bid
committee targeted African votes in their attempt to win the Games.
Investigators have said that Ganga received free medical treatment
for hepatitis in Salt Lake City during the bid process and profited
in a land deal arranged by Bennie Smith Jr., a member of the bid
committee, several months after the Games were awarded to Salt Lake
City.
</P>
<P>
   Ganga achieved international renown as one of the organizers of
the African boycott of the 1976 Summer Games in Montreal. A former
ambassador to China, he is currently Congo Republic's minister for
tourism, sports and leisure as well as president of the country's
Olympic committee. He was recently removed from the IOC's
commission on new sources of financing.
</P>
<P>
   Unless investigators can prove that Ganga received excessive
payments, gifts or services while acting in his official government
capacity, and not as a member of the IOC, a private organization,
it seems unlikely that Salt Lake City officials would be subjected
to charges of violating the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act, said
Jeffrey Weiner, a Miami lawyer who was formerly president of the
national association of criminal defense lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Four investigations are under way: an internal Salt Lake
Organizing Committee ethics panel, the U.S. Olympic Committee, the
IOC and the U.S.Justice Department. The Justice Department inquiry
is to determine whether any laws were broken in the case, which
escalated last month when Marc Hodler, a senior IOC official from
Switzerland, said that as many as 25 of the 114 members of the
international committee had sold their votes in recent elections to
choose Olympic sites. Hodler has said that Salt Lake City was a
victim of agents who demand exorbitant fees for delivering blocs of
votes.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Salt Lake City ethics panel could be made
public as early as next Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday Leavitt said that he deplored the misdeeds of the Salt
Lake City bid committee, ``and we revolt at being associated with
them.'' He also sternly criticized a ``sinister and dark corner of
corruption'' in the Olympic movement that exists because of what
the he called a lack of accountability in the IOC. He called on
Juan Antonio Samaranch, the president of the IOC, to institute
reforms in the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Joklik said that as a member of the Salt Lake City bid committee
he had been unaware of any improper payments. He said the bid
committee's board of trustees had been screened from such
information and had been assured by auditors that all expenditures
were proper.
</P>
<P>
   With the resignations of Joklik and Johnson, 40, Salt Lake City
is now left without the two people who possess the greatest
knowledge in organizing the 2002 Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Joklik's successor, most of the sports
facilities are completed or are well under construction. Major
projects remaining include enclosing the Olympic speed-skating oval
and constructing the 120-kilometer hill for ski jumping. All sports
facilities are expected to be completed by November 2000 so they
can be tested in competition long before the Games open on Feb. 8,
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our reputation has been tarnished around the world,'' Mayor
Deedee Corradini of Salt Lake City said. ``We will make it right
again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
