<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN HIRE A MASTERSTROKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ Ring the Bell (Mark). Raise the Rufus (Porter). Beat
down the Doornink (Dan).
</P>
<P>
   Hip hip Herrera (Efren). The Seattle Seahawks no longer wallow
in the Mirer (Rick). They have emerged from the NFL Raible (Steve)
prepared to shoot the Moon (Warren).
</P>
<P>
   In Kirkland Friday, Springs (Shawn) sprung and horns were Tuten
(Rick).
</P>
<P>
   OK, so hyperbole rules the day. What the Heck (Andy). In the
mostly tepid history of the NFL in Seattle, hundreds of names have
come and gone. Most were little noted and not long remembered. None
were the game's biggest.
</P>
<P>
   Until Slash Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   As vice president of football operations/general manager/head
coach/prime minister/prom king/lama/ /sheriff-of-Nottingham, the
large man acquired the largest job with the largest salary in the
NFL, at least among those who don't dirty themselves on Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   What for? The guy is no Brian Bosworth. His hair is unstriped
and unicolored, fergawdsakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instant respect,'' said Seahawk running back Ricky Watters.
</P>
<P>
   Instant respect. A simple idea, way overemphasized in the jock
world, but something the Seahawks haven't had in a decade, locally
or nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Instant respect isn't cheap. It will cost owner Paul Allen more
than $30 million over eight years, it cost president Bob Whitsitt
some prestige, it cost vice president Randy Mueller some authority,
it cost Dennis Erickson and most of his assistants their coaching
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But from the looks on the faces at the team's headquarters, from
the ringing of the ticket-sales phones, from the buzz throughout
the football nation, instant respect seemed a worthy investment.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the force of Holmgren's accomplishments, personality and
character that the entire franchise bent to accommodate him.
</P>
<P>
   Big money, many years and huge responsibilities for a premier
figure in the business add up to an astonishing, locally
unprecedented commitment to an athletic renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Between Friday and the day of the Behring moving trucks was
almost three years by calendar. But from the standpoint of
progress, the Seahawks have gone abruptly from abacus to laptop.
</P>
<P>
   The swiftness with which the Seahawks moved to yank Holmgren
from the tradition-encrusted Green Bay Packers, who had suffered a
wrenching defeat that ended their season last Sunday, to this
history-free NFL outpost was more than a statement about his
stature in the game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   It was a statement about how annoyed the franchise bosses were
during the first two years of Allen's tenure. To the software
crowd, two years is like the passing of a generation. Even by NFL
standards, with 23 teams making the playoffs during Erickson's four
seasons, the Seahawks were slow on the uptake.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a very short time, I realized these men like to get things
done,'' Holmgren said of his meetings with Allen, Whitsitt and the
rest. ``That's how I am.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's the right fit, it's the right fit. You know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitsitt reached the same conclusion in the same short time. In
the year since the Seahawks sought to fill the vacant post of
general manager, he maintained his preference was that one man not
hold both jobs of GM and coach. But his position started to shift
after the regular season ended, when he saw how close Holmgren was
to shoveling out of the frozen tundra.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never met Mike Holmgren until Wednesday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday, Whitsitt had turned over the keys to the whole
football works and headed to Portland, where his NBA Trail Blazers
were emerging from their various lockouts, jails, rehab programs
and paternity suits.
</P>
<P>
   For Whitsitt to make such a reversal, and surrender
responsibility, the fit must have been perfect. For a time during
his presidency of the Sonics, he wore so many hats that his neck
bowed from the weight. His habit is to seek more power, not less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with his intellect and understanding,''
Whitsitt said. ``He seriously thought about doing both jobs. He's
not a guy who just says, `Gee, this sounds neat.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el1l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   He also made an impression when he admitted not having all the
answers _ something his followers might be surprised to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when I'm interviewing someone, I need to to hear, `I
don't know,''' Whitsitt said. ``He said there were things about
(the dual role) he'd have to learn on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time went on, I really felt comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not an easy development for a control freak. But whatever
misgivings Whitsitt had were no match for the lack of respect he,
Allen and the rest of the franchise felt about being a backwater
outfit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perfect organizational structure,'' he said, ``is getting
the best people you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks would appear to be approaching that, from a
committed owner to an aggressive president to a football mastermind
to a talented roster of experienced players.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a thing Friday, watching a man trade in his
cheesehead for a bag of slug bait. Imagine the feeling when the
Seahawks trade third-and-11 for first-in-AFC West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
