<SLUG> BC-GLF-MERCEDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUVAL FIRES 63 TO TAKE LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAPALUA, Hawaii _ According to his girlfriend, David Duval has
been shopping for a new car. And whoever wins the Mercedes
Championships this weekend will be awarded a 1999 Mercedes-Benz SL
500 coupe-roadster.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Duval has been inspired.
</P>
<P>
   Tying the Plantation Course record with a 10-under-par 63 and
continuing a 14-month run of sensational golf, Duval roared to a
five-stroke lead after Friday's second round of the PGA Tour's
opening event.
</P>
<P>
   Pulling away from an elite 30-man field that includes eight of
the top 12 players in the world ranking, Duval had 10 birdies and
no bogeys. He matched the course record of 63 set by Steve Pate in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   After two rounds, Duval stood at 130, 16 under par and five
strokes ahead of Vijay Singh, Fred Funk and Billy Mayfair. But it
will take a lot to catch Duval, who has won seven times since
October 1997, and who enjoyed a superb 1998, when he won four
tournaments, captured the money title and led the tour in scoring
average.
</P>
<P>
   While Duval has been reluctant to accept the title of world's
best player, he believes he can beat anyone, any time, anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't think of myself, and probably never will, as a
superstar,'' said Duval, a native of Jacksonville, Fla., who turned
27 years old in November. ``Everybody wants to compare me with
Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara. I just don't think in those terms. I do
know how to play this game, though. I really feel I'm pretty good
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's performance moved Duval closer to the $468,000
first-place check and the new Mercedes. When asked about the
possibility that Duval would win the new car, his girlfriend, Julie
McArthur, smiled and said, ``He's been looking for a new car, and
winning a Mercedes would certainly make the decision a lot
easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval hit powerful drives and pinpoint approach shots Friday
that consistently left him with makable birdie putts. His longest
was 20 feet, as he made the only par-73 course on the PGA Tour
(7,263 yards) look much shorter.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the tournament has been a breeze for Duval, who also
shot 10 under par at Pebble Beach in 1997 and at Tucson in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Duval started the day six under par, one stroke behind Joe
Durant, Funk, Mayfair and Pate. Durant and Pate both shot 70s and
fell into a tie for fifth at 10 under par. Mayfair and Funk shot
69s to tie Singh, who also had a fine round, shooting a 65.
</P>
<P>
   But Duval was in a class by himself. He started with a 15-foot
putt for birdie at No. 1. At the par-5, 532-yard fifth hole, he
reached the green with a driver and a 2-iron, then two-putted from
about 30 feet for birdie. At the 398-yard No. 6, Duval drove to
just short of the green, chipped to within 10 feet and then made
the putt for birdie. Then, at the par-3, 203-yard eighth hole,
Duval hit a superb 5-iron to within two feet of the cup, then
tapped in for a birdie.
</P>
<P>
   On the back nine, Duval had a birdie at No. 10, hitting a sand
wedge approach shot to within six feet, then making the birdie
putt. He made a 12-foot putt for birdie at No. 12 and a 10-foot
putt for birdie at No. 14.
</P>
<P>
   At the par-5, 555-yard No. 15, Duval hit his second shot just
short of the green, chipped to within two feet and tapped in for a
birdie. Then, after making a 14-foot putt for birdie at No. 16,
Duval ended the day with a birdie at the longest hole on tour, the
par-5, 663-yard No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Duval showed his power on the final hole, reaching the downhill
green with a driver and a 3-wood, then two-putting from 50 feet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
