</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR KNICKS, ONLY WARD WILL DO TO START AS POINT GUARD
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ The New York Knicks will enter the season in
need of a compass. Amid the flurry and confusion of a
lockout-shortened schedule, the team will look to lean on simple
direction, solid guidance and a straight arrow.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Charlie Ward. Rather than chase a flashier name
who could be a misfit, the Knicks would feel more comfortable
starting their frantic season with Ward as their point guard.
</P>
<P>
   To re-sign Ward, a free agent, the Knicks will have to take what
Chris Childs made last year as the starter turned backup _ a
generous $3.12 million _ and raise that number until a smile cracks
Ward's steely facade. Although the competition for him is limited
because few teams have salary cap space, the Orlando Magic, the
Toronto Raptors and the Detroit Pistons have surfaced as
candidates. Acting as Ward's pitchman, Knicks Coach Jeff Van Gundy
expressed his concern over the possibility of losing Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried,'' Van Gundy said Friday at the Knicks' practice
facility at SUNY-Purchase. ``I think Charlie's abilities have been
vastly underrated by people outside our team. Within the NBA, he's
highly regarded. Here's a guy who each year has gotten better and
better and better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has continued to improve. He thinks pass first, which is
not a trait among a lot of point guards. And he has a presence on
the team in that people listen to him. He has respect from within.
We expect him to get better, and I want to make sure it's here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The quicker you can get everything done and have a roster in
place, the better chance you have to get off to a good start. I
think that's as equal to how good your guys come back in shape.
It's important, if we can, to get him done. I don't think it's a
foregone conclusion, though, because I think there is a serious
interest from teams out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Money may not be the overriding issue, either. Ward has said he
wants to return to New York, but one teammate said that Ward was
irritated with the Knicks because of all the trade speculation he
was linked to last year. Ward asked himself, if they want me, why
are they trying to trade me? If there is a player who would choose
another team on principle, it would be Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Although there were times when the Knicks were not so sold on
Ward, he came through on several critical occasions, like Game 5
against the Miami Heat in the Knicks' first-round playoff series.
That was the icing on a season of improvement. Despite his
defensive liabilities and unreliable decision-making, Ward made
enough progress to nudge Childs out of the starter's role last
season. Ward slipped into Childs' job and became a distributor
whose first priority was to deliver the ball to Patrick Ewing,
Allan Houston and Larry Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Only when those options were shut down did Ward look for his
shot. Often, he delivered with an ever improving repertory last
season. Comparing his 1997-1998 production with his numbers for the
1996-1997 season, Ward was better in every major area: field-goal
percentage (39 to 45), free-throw percentage (76 to 81) and 3-point
shooting percentage (31.2 to 37.7).
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie is our starter,'' Van Gundy said. ``There's no doubt
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, there had been speculation that the Knicks would
try to land a bigger name at point guard. But a deal to acquire
Milwaukee's Terrell Brandon never materialized. The only other name
that has been bandied about lately is that of Israel's Oded Katash,
a European league star. He had a workout with the Knicks just
before the lockout and had sparked their interest. But as the labor
dispute dragged into January, Katash left to return to the Maccabi
team in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a chance he could come back,'' his agent, Marc
Fleisher, said. ``Whether he wants to or not, that's up to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Katash's return may depend on how much pressure the Maccabi team
places on him to stay. Either way, Katash is certainly no threat to
Ward. At best, he is a reserve who could be signed by the Knicks
with one of the salary cap exceptions the team has.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a learning year for him, like for any rookie,''
Van Gundy said. ``If he is able to come over and we're able to sign
him, it's going to be hard for him. It's difficult to find playing
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Childs is traded, a move the Knicks have tried to make
for a year now, the backup minutes are going to be sewn up, too.
There is no question that if Ward returns, this will be his team.
With so much uncertainty about the coming season, the Knicks
believe they can rely on Ward to be their trusty guide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, if you lose a starter, especially through free
agency, it's hard,'' Van Gundy said. ``There are no point guards
you can replace Charlie with. I like Charlie and I believe in
Charlie.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
