<SLUG> BC-NY-SPRINKLER-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSH TO REQUIRE SPRINKLERS RAISES COMPLEX ISSUES
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fire safety breakthroughs are often born of terrible
losses of life that show the shortcomings of the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   But the surging emotions that survive such catastrophes, like
last month's fatal fire in a Manhattan high-rise, can also cloud an
issue as complex as New York City's push to require sprinklers in
all new homes.
</P>
<P>
   Few people on either side of the debate argue, however, with the
assertion that sprinklers are effective at stopping the spread of
fires. When activated in homes and apartments _ usually when the
temperature in a room reaches 160 degrees _ sprinkler heads
typically spray 15 to 25 gallons of water a minute on a fire, often
stopping it in its tracks, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The National Fire Prevention Association, a nonprofit group that
studies fire safety issues, said that no fire in a home, school or
institution with a working sprinkler system had ever killed more
than two people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Or perhaps a more useful comment is that, if you have
sprinklers and you have a fire, you will reduce your chance of
dying by half to two-thirds, and your loss from fire by a half to
two-thirds,'' said John Hall, the association's assistant vice
president for fire analysis. ``These are huge reductions.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of extensive new sprinkler regulations also marshal
facts to support their contention that sprinklers, while effective,
are an expensive and unsightly answer to a problem that has already
been largely solved.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinklers, said Steven Spinola, president of the Real Estate
Board of New York, only duplicate protections already in place in
the newly constructed high-rise buildings where many New Yorkers
live. These buildings employ fire-resistant construction, intended
to contain a fire with extra-thick walls and doors designed to
withstand flames for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is the degree of additional protection weighed
against the problems that sprinklers can cause,'' Spinola said.
``Sprinklers don't put out fires. They just slow it down _
hopefully until the firefighter can get there. Fire-resistant
construction can do that just as effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Spinola pointed out that there were only 107 fire fatalities in
the city last year, the lowest number in 42 years. That death rate
is comparable, sprinkler opponents contend, to the rate in many
other cities where expansive sprinkler laws are in effect.
</P>
<P>
   But a Manhattan high-rise fire last month on West 60th Street,
in which four people died, illuminated the limitations of
fire-resistant construction. In one panic-filled moment, all that
building's precautions were undone when someone left a fire door
ajar and allowed the smoke to billow into hallways.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the cost of installing sprinkler systems _ which
could add up to $360 to the yearly rent for a one-bedroom
apartment, the Real Estate Board says _ the real estate industry
argues that sprinklers are also subject to vandalism and a
potential lack of maintenance. The latter problem was cited in the
deaths of three firefighters last month in a Brooklyn high-rise
where a working sprinkler system that might have saved their lives
had been inexplicably turned off.
</P>
<P>
   Fire experts also acknowledge that sprinklers often do not work
well in fires where an explosion overwhelms the system. But they
discredit as myth the idea that sprinklers are always going off
accidentally and flooding homes and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that sprinkler systems are carefully designed to
activate early in a real fire but not to activate in a nonfire
situation,'' a report by the National Fire Protection Association
concluded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
