<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARCELLS TAILORED DRESS FOR SUCCESS 
GLENN STILL NOT STARTING   
 LINE, LIKE JETS, HAS GROWN   
 JETS ARE HOMEBODIES  
</HEADLINE>
 (bl)  
By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Over the summer, the New York Jets put on new
uniforms with an old logo, the one they wore as the surprising
winners of Super Bowl III. Now, 30 years later, they are in the
playoffs and thinking it can happen.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, positive history is catching up to the Jets, who are
wearing the logo for the first time since the playoffs after the
1969 season, when the Jets lost to the Kansas City Chiefs as the
defending Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   As coach Bill Parcells spent time this week analyzing Sunday's
playoff game against the Jacksonville Jaguars, he reflected on the
uniform the Jets will wear at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Initiating a uniform change was Parcells' first decision when he
took over the team 23 months ago. Within 24 hours, he put into
motion the return to the logo _ the one Joe Namath wore on his
helmet, the one with the word ``Jets'' against a background that of
``NY.' Below it is a football. In addition, the Jets reverted to
white helmets with a green logo.
</P>
<P>
   When the old logo was changed _ to one that simply read
``Jets,'' with a bit of a swept-wing design and green helmets _
many of the players who were on the Super Bowl team complained.
They thought that history had been tampered with.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, linebacker Ralph Baker, who later became a Jets
assistant coach, recalled: ``Some of the older players were
alienated when the team changed the logo back in the '70s. Changing
the logo was a slap.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there is a subtle difference between the 1960s design
and the new one. The green is darker now, and the laces of the
football under the word ``Jets'' are more distinct.
</P>
<P>
   As for Parcells, he actually wanted the change instituted in his
first season, 1997. But the National Football League's marketing
arm wanted to allow retailers to clear their shelves of the
merchandise on hand, so the change was put off until this season.
</P>
<P>
   Why Parcells did it is quite simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked the people here what their feelings were,'' he said.
``Their unanimous feeling was it shouldn't have changed originally.
I'm a traditionalist. I have no trouble identifying when the
Yankees are playing. The Brooklyn Dodgers, the Bears, the Cubs, the
Giants. Those teams have had the same appearance and a team needs
that identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Corwin Brown, the 28-year-old free safety, was not born when
Namath played for the Jets. But he watches Namath on old football
game films on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I see the uniform, I think of Joe Namath beating
the Colts,'' Brown said. ``That was the history. We thought of the
uniform as something new, time to make some new things happen. I
think it helps, plus other teams look at you differently. Look at
how people regarded Tampa Bay last year when they changed
uniforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The public has been gobbling up the new uniforms, not only
excited by the traditional design, but also by the club's success.
The Minnesota Vikings, the Jets and the San Francisco 49ers are the
three hottest-selling teams right now, said Chris Widmaier,
director of corporate communications for the NFL, which sells about
$3 billion worth of items at retail.
</P>
<P>
   Three factors, he said, drive any team's success in marketing:
``Wins on the field, personalities _ and the Jets have Vinny
Testaverde, Aaron Glenn, Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne Chrebet _ and
tradition. Those things combine in a cyclone force.''
</P>
<P>
   There is one factor that makes the Jets a bit different, though.
``Superstars on both sides of the ball move sales,'' said Widmaier.
``Who's the Jets' superstar? Parcells.''
</P>
<P>
   GLENN STILL NOT STARTING
</P>
<P>
   Except for Aaron Glenn, the Jets will start every first-stringer
who began the season. The Pro-Bowl cornerback will not start on
Sunday, Parcells said Friday, although he will dress after missing
three games with a sprained ankle. Ray Mickens continues in his
spot on the left side.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn will not return kickoffs, either, with that job being
handled by Kevin Williams. But Glenn is likely to play cornerback
during Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill and I have a very good relationship,'' said Glenn. ``He
trusts me to tell him the truth about whether I can play or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells has told injured players to let him know if they have
any doubts about their ability to perform. ``I don't want anyone to
have a built-in excuse,'' the coach said.
</P>
<P>
   LINE, LIKE JETS, HAS GROWN
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have won 10 of their last 11 games as the offensive
line has improved. Staying healthy helped the unit, which has The
performed together for nearly all the team's 1,000 offensive plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I missed one play all year,'' said the rookie right tackle
Jason Fabini. ``My shoe came off and I couldn't tie it. I had to go
off for a play.''
</P>
<P>
   And why couldn't he tie his shoe?
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't maneuver the laces because of the cast I had on my
broken hand.''
</P>
<P>
   JETS ARE HOMEBODIES
</P>
<P>
   The Jets captured their last seven home games, while the
Jaguars, Sunday's playoff opponent, dropped three of their final
four on the road. January has been the best month in Parcells'
career: his teams have a .750 winning percentage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0038EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
