u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GUN-CONTROL-NYT &LR;      01-09 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GUN-CONTROL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TRIALS OF GUN MANUFACTURERS, A MOTHER GIVES A STATISTIC A NAME
AND FACE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Pa., Mass.)   By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Brooklyn woman whose son was shot to death
personalized the human toll taken by illegally obtained handguns as
she testified Friday in a lawsuit that she helped bring against the
gun industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping there was some mistake, that he was still
alive,'' the woman, Freddie Hamilton, told a jury in U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn as she recalled her feelings while rushing to a
hospital on the night of July 27, 1993, after getting a phone call
about her son, Njuzi Ray, 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a shooting,'' she said, quoting the caller, a
friend of her son's. ``Njuzi didn't make it,'' she said the caller
added.
</P>
<P>
   At the hospital, Ms. Hamilton said, she lost hope. ``When I
walked into the hospital, I knew he was dead,'' she said in a calm,
steady tone. ``I insisted on seeing him, but they said they had to
clean him up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the potentially precedent-setting suit, Ms. Hamilton, 55, is
one of seven plaintiffs: relatives of six homicide victims in New
York City and Yonkers, N.Y. in recent years, and a teen-ager who
survived a shooting but who still carries a bullet in his brain. In
a trial in the case that opened on Monday, they contend that the
more than 40 firearms manufacturers and distributors named as
defendants are collectively liable for the deaths and injuries,
regardless of which companies actually made and distributed the
weapons legally before they fell into unauthorized hands.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs' lawyers argue that the companies have marketed
and distributed handguns so negligently that dealers in states with
weak gun-control laws are supplied with more new guns than can be
sold in the legitimate markets there.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the lawyers maintain, many of the excess weapons
move through an illegal gun-trafficking underground into states
with strong gun laws, like New York, and end up in the hands of
people like those who shot Njuzi Ray and the other victims in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   The companies being sued include some of the most prominent
firearms makers in the nation, like Smith &AMP; Wesson and the Colt's
Manufacturing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the companies say that their clients cannot control
what happens to the weapons after they are sold legally to licensed
dealers.
</P>
<P>
   The defense lawyers say that the companies adhere to tight
federal regulations. They deny that the companies oversupply
dealers in states with weak gun laws, particularly those in the
South. The lawyers say that many guns are shipped to those dealers
in the South because of a stronger demand there for guns for
legitimate uses like recreation and protection.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being widely followed by gun control advocates, the
firearms industry and lawyers for cities, like Chicago,
Philadelphia and Boston, that have sued or plan to sue the gun
manufacturers, much as states have sued the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the far-ranging issues in the Brooklyn suit are the
people on whose behalf it has been brought, like Ms. Hamilton and
the son she lost.
</P>
<P>
   Njuzi Ray, she recalled on the witness stand, had left high
school because of manic-depressive illness, but was striving to
build a life despite his problems. At the time of his death, she
said under questioning by a lawyer, Elisa Barnes, her son was
working in the family's vending machine business and, with a
friend, was producing background music that he hoped would be used
by rap artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had aspirations for himself, and I didn't see anything
limiting him,'' said Ms. Hamilton, the executive director of a
social services group in Brooklyn, the Child Development Support
Corp. After her son's slaying, she helped form a group called
Parents United to Rally for Gun Elimination, made up of women,
mostly from Brooklyn, who lobby for gun control.
</P>
<P>
   After stepping down from the witness stand, Ms. Hamilton said of
her son's killing and the killing of other victims with illegally
possessed handguns, ``Just say Njuzi was a personal tragedy of so
many other tragedies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0044EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
