<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS FIND RIGHT MAN IN HOLMGREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ It won't be long before everyone around the Pacific
Northwest knows how much Mike Holmgren loves to ride his
Harley-Davidsons.
</P>
<P>
   Or that the 50-year-old father of four daughters makes daily
phone calls to the three who no longer live at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is nice. He is moral. He is intelligent,'' said Seahawk
defensive end Matt LaBounty, who played for the new Seahawk
executive vice president of football operations/general manager and
coach during Holmgren's seven fruitful seasons in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Nice. Moral. Intelligent.
</P>
<P>
   And now, most important: King.
</P>
<P>
   How else can you describe a two-time Super Bowl coach with ties
to the Super Bowl-winning 49ers who, within hours, convinced Paul
Allen and Co. to turn nearly complete control of the Seahawks to
him?
</P>
<P>
   That is why it's time to say: Move over, Lou Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle has another big-name, big-time pro sports franchise
leader that is going to turn this town upside down. Like Piniella,
who used his blue blood Yankee pedigree, his Cincinnati Reds World
Series experience and a blustering, larger-than-life personality to
legitimize the Mariners, Holmgren is nothing short of instant
credibility for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   That is without doubt the impression Holmgren gave at Seahawk
headquarters Friday, when he was announced as the franchise's sixth
head coach.
</P>
<P>
   The minute Holmgren walked into the room, decked out in a navy
blue double-breasted suit and razor-sharp sea-blue eyes, you could
tell Holmgren was a man of persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think there was a fumble a few plays before (the
49ers' NFC playoff game-winning touchdown),'' Holmgren quipped.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Holmgren was describing how, before last Sunday, he
had no thoughts of another job except taking the Packers to their
third straight Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But when the 49ers' last-minute victory ousted Green Bay,
solidifying Steve Mariucci's status in San Francisco, it was clear
that Holmgren's next-best professional bet was to head to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, after an accelerated but exhilarating 24-hour round of
negotiations, the deal was done.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect fit declared by all parties. That much you could tell
when Holmgren described his first moments with Allen as ``awesome''
_ what else could it have been?
</P>
<P>
   Later, Seahawk president Bob Whitsitt showed his complete
satisfaction with Holmgren's authoritative and charismatic
personality. The chemistry was palpable and, it sure seemed,
genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which team is going to have to pay the fine?'' Whitsitt joked
about Holmgren's ``dispute'' of the non-call by game officials on
Jerry Rice's apparent fumble during Green Bay's 30-27 playoff loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get the lawyers in on that,'' Holmgren shot back, a
twinkle in his eye and an intensity in his voice as he took command
of the packed room.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing personal against former Hawks coaches Dennis Erickson or
Tom Flores, but there hasn't been that sort of snap, crackle and
pop around here since Mount St. Helens blew its stack 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   For more than $32 million over eight years, Holmgren has already
given pretty clear indication that he will be the name, the face,
the personality, and, with a formidable dose of stature about his
6-foot-5 frame, the overwhelming physical presence of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Where Flores and Erickson could never capture the public
imagination, either on the field or off, Holmgren should prove
180-degrees different _ with endorsements and public service
announcements galore.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, 275 season tickets were sold within the first three
hours of Holmgren's installation as Seahawk Kahuna.
</P>
<P>
   Next, Eagle Hardware will no doubt come calling soon. Holmgren
might be the only guy who fits in Randy Johnson's old blue
bathrobe.
</P>
<P>
   And the way Holmgren projects consumer confidence, there could
be a new ``Mike Burger'' at Dick's _ a half-pound whopper, hold the
cheese. Holmgren ate enough of the stuff during his seven years in
America's dairyland.
</P>
<P>
   Winchell's could soon offer a Holmgren Crueller; Ivar's a West
Coast Offense Shrimp Basket; Red Hook a Holmgren Pale Ale.
Possibilities soar, just as realistic Super Bowl expectations rise.
</P>
<P>
   And we thought linebacker Chad Brown and running back Ricky
Watters were big deals in the Allen regime.
</P>
<P>
   Huh-uh. Next to the Pioneer Square stadium that will be built to
house the new-era Hawks, nothing compares to the largesse that is
Holmgren ... except, perhaps, the mysterious Mr. Allen, who
continues to spend and amaze.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, after flying the Holmgrens in on his private
jet, Allen ushered Holmgren and his family to Allen's Mercer Island
estate. There, Allen served up a seven-course French dinner _ none
of which Holmgren said he could distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept bringing out all these plates but I didn't know what
they were. The menu was all in French,'' Holmgren said, apparently
unaware that Allen _ a well-traveled gourmand _ might be offended.
</P>
<P>
   However, French menus might be one of the rare things that slip
from Holmgren's legendary attention to detail. The word on Holmgren
was pretty much the same from whatever corner it came.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, he's a perfectionist. He demands excellence from everyone
around him and he doesn't have a lot of patience,'' Holmgren's
wife, Kathy, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's his work personality, but when he tries to
bring that home, we say: `We're not your secretaries. We don't work
for you. This is a democracy here.'''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   To the contrary, there is no such democracy on Holmgren's
football teams, although he does command the respect of his
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is fair. He is strict. He is very successful,'' LaBounty
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was there, there was no doubt he was in control. He
studied every inch of film. If he saw something he didn't like in
practice, he'd be hollering at the team. At first you'd think it
was nit-picking, but then you realize that's what it takes at this
level.''
</P>
<P>
   And Whitsitt said that within a matter of hours he came to view
Holmgren as an ``open, intelligent,'' questioning man upon whom
responsibility for the entire Seahawk organization can be safely,
enthusiastically placed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the stature and the presence and he is authoratitive,
but I don't mean in a dictatorial sense. He can build a
consensus,'' Whitsitt said.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Holmgren is indeed a Bill Parcells-type of
football guru _ only Holmgren comes without the bullying need to
manipulate, a la Parcells. And he comes without the sing-along
Tostitos ads, although that could change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
