<HEADER>
A5865 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-POLICE-SHOOTING     01-09 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-POLICE-SHOOTING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNANSWERED QUESTIONS IN FATAL POLICE SHOOTING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIVERSIDE, Calif. _ The last hour of Tyisha Miller's young life
in this ``all-American city'' began with a flat tire and a
stranger's act of kindness in the early morning darkness three days
after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   It ended in a burst of police bullets, Ms. Miller's death and a
blizzard of unanswered questions, not only about what happened and
why, but also about race and justice. Protesters have marched,
police officers have been put on leave, much of the city is shaken
and so far the investigation has mainly led to more questions.
</P>
<P>
   One development this week was a new, detailed account of the
events leading to the shooting, provided by a lawyer for Ms.
Miller's family, based on the accounts of a friend who was with Ms.
Miller that night and of a cousin who witnessed the shooting from
about 40 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   The police have not been able to interview the friend, leading
to frustration and perhaps some skepticism. The account also does
not explain what is perhaps the most important factor leading to
the police shooting _ a gun in Ms. Miller's lap.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 28, shortly before 1 a.m., Ms. Miller, a 19-year-old
black woman, was driving her aunt's Nissan Sentra home with a
15-year-old friend, when a tire went flat, said the lawyer, Andrew
Roth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller had spent the day partying and shopping with several
girlfriends. They went to a mall, a Taco Bell and an amusement
park. Earlier in the day, said Susan Taylor, the mother of one of
the girls, they also did some drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Initial toxicology tests made public by the Riverside County
coroner put Ms. Miller's blood-alcohol level at 0.13 percent. The
legal limit for driving in California is 0.08 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tyisha was at my house 45 minutes before she died,'' Mrs.
Taylor said, ``and the kids admitted that they had been doing some
drinking early in the day. But I didn't see any alcohol or smell
any alcohol on her breath. When she left here, she was not drunk.''
</P>
<P>
   When the tire went flat, neither Ms. Miller nor her passenger, a
girl whom Ms. Miller's family will identify only by her nickname,
Bug, was able to fix it, so they asked a white man coming out of a
store for help.
</P>
<P>
   Although the man was a stranger, Roth said, he rolled up his
sleeves and changed the tire. But the spare was almost flat. So,
driving his own car, the man led Ms. Miller and the girl, who
followed behind in the Nissan, to a gas station for air.
</P>
<P>
   At the station, the spare tire would not hold air and the man,
whom Roth refused to identify, was eager to go. Still, before
leaving, he agreed to drive Bug home to nearby Rubidoux, an
unincorporated area where both young women lived, across the Santa
Ana River from Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   The police have not been able to confirm this chain of events.
They also said they had not interviewed Bug or the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been unable to locate her,'' Sgt. Chris Manning of the
Riverside Police Department said, ``despite numerous attempts and
at least five public appeals for her to come forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth said both witnesses were afraid but had agreed to talk to
the FBI, which has begun a preliminary investigation into the
death.
</P>
<P>
   When Bug and the man drove away, Ms. Miller stayed behind. She
was not about to leave her aunt's car at a gas station a few miles
from home. So she locked the doors and rolled up the windows. She
turned up the heat and the radio, and reclined in the driver's
seat. Apparently she also put a pistol in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   When Bug got home, she called Ms. Miller's family.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost 2 a.m., and Ms. Miller's young life was almost
over.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller's 18-year-old cousin, Anthonete Joiner, and a
girlfriend, Chy King, headed for the gas station after Bug's call.
</P>
<P>
   Before they left, Ms. Miller's aunt gave them her AAA card and
some advice: ``Be careful.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Joiner said she had planned to pull up to
Ms. Miller's car and simply hand her the card through the window.
But when she arrived, she saw that something was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something was bubbling from her mouth,'' Ms. Joiner said. ``I
hurried out of my car and banged on the window. She wouldn't
respond. I banged on the door. She wouldn't respond. I banged on
the roof. She still wouldn't respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner's friend peered into the car. ``Anthonete,'' she
said, ``Tyisha has a gun!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner said she was on the edge of panic. Her cousin did not
own a gun. Sure, Tyisha was a tomboy, who played first base for
their church softball team, but she did not carry weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The police say that the gun did not belong to Ms. Miller and
that the owner is a woman they refused to identify. Manning did say
that the gun owner and Ms. Miller had no connection, and added that
how and why she had the gun is one of ``numerous unanswered
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner went back to her car and searched her purse for
change to call for help. ``Hurry up!'' Ms. Joiner shouted when
another cousin answered the phone. ``I can't get the door open!
Tyisha looks like something is wrong with her!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner and her friend then debated whether they should call
911. It seemed the best thing to do, the quickest way to get help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared out of my mind,'' Ms. Joiner said.
</P>
<P>
   Her friend dialed 911, and Ms. Joiner said she heard her tell
the dispatcher that they could not wake Ms. Miller and that there
was a gun on her lap.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrived within minutes. Ms. Joiner said she ran over
to a police officer and told him that something was wrong with her
cousin, that she would not wake up and once again she mentioned the
gun.
</P>
<P>
   Get back, the officer said, and he and three other officers
began screaming at Ms. Miller to open the door and get out of the
car.
</P>
<P>
   One officer pounded on the glass with a flashlight, she said,
while the others took positions around the car, their guns out.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of minutes later,'' Ms. Joiner said, ``they were
shooting at her. She was just lying there the whole time.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner said the police rushed into the station's lot ``like
something was going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller was struck at least 12 times, including four times in
the head and five times in the back. An autopsy showed the fatal
wounds were two shots to the head and one to the chest.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the police said the officers _ three of them white
and one Latino _ fired only after Ms. Miller had shot at them with
the .380-caliber semiautomatic pistol in her lap.
</P>
<P>
   But hours later, the police said it was unclear whether Ms.
Miller had ever fired the gun, and could find no evidence that she
had.
</P>
<P>
   As more information came in, the police said later that Ms.
Miller had reached for the gun after one of the officers broke a
window to get into the car and give medical assistance.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You get the notion that this is like a Greek tragedy,'' said
Ron Loveridge, the weary-sounding mayor of this city of 250,000
people, about 60 miles east of Los Angeles. Last year, Riverside _
a city of colleges, quiet streets and sunshine _ was named an
all-American city by the National Civic League.
</P>
<P>
   The four officers have been placed on paid leave as the
investigation continues. But that is not good enough for Ms.
Miller's family and the 300 black, white and Latino people who
marched through the city's streets a week after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want those police officers to be on paid vacation,''
said the Rev. Bernel Butler, Ms. Miller's cousin and a family
spokesman. ``We want them charged. We want them brought to trial.
Are they above the law?''
</P>
<P>
   The other day Ms. Joiner was in a grocery store, trying to
resume as normal a life as possible, when a stranger approached
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``You killed her!'' the woman shouted at Ms. Joiner. ``You
called 911!''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Joiner broke down in tears and ran. Later, she even changed
her hair style, hoping she would no longer be recognized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to help my cousin,'' Ms. Joiner said. ``I
was scared for her. That's why we called 911. She needed help.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Tyisha Miller will be buried, just outside this
all-American city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
