<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-FLAMES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' UNBEATEN STREAK ENDS AT 15
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ The littlest goalie in hockey cut down the
biggest team in the NHL last night in what appeared to be a lost
episode of ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Brathwaite, the 5-foot-7 journeyman who played his first
game in two seasons only because the Calgary Flames were down to
their eighth goalie, stopped the Stars' franchise-best 15-game
unbeaten streak in a 1-0 Flames victory at the Canadian Airlines
Saddledome.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first NHL shutout for Brathwaite and pushed his NHL
career record to 6-17-4. Not only did the Stars lose for the first
time since Dec. 4, 1998 _ ending the league's longest unbeaten
streak this season _ the Flames stopped an eight-game losing
streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars came in with the best road record in the NHL (11-4-4).
The Flames had the second-worst home record (now 6-12-2). The Stars
had the top power play, the Flames the worst penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, yeah, it did seem like a mismatch,'' Stars captain
Derian Hatcher said. `'I guess what's most disappointing is they
outworked us. They deserved this win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hatcher added the Stars didn't take Calgary lightly, and
that sentiment was echoed by winger Pat Verbeek.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not at all,'' Verbeek said. ``Look at their lineup, they
have a hard-working team.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the Flames did indeed work hard defensively, that's
not what killed the Stars. Both teams settled into a boring,
defensive game and each team waited for the other to make the first
move. That cautious style hurt the Stars as they didn't get in hard
on the forecheck, didn't force the Flames into mistakes and didn't
get many second shots on Brathwaite.
</P>
<P>
   And that caution blew up in the Stars' collective face at the
9:11 mark of the second period when the Flames finally broke
through. Jeff Shantz popped in the only goal of the night on a
simple backhand that somehow bounced off Ed Belfour's stick, over
his head and then eluded the grasp of defenseman Shawn Chambers as
it slowly tumbled over the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had missed on just such a scoring opportunity earlier
in the game when winger Grant Marshall drove hard to the net and
collided with Brathwaite. The puck squirted out of the pile, but
Brathwaite gloved it before it could go over the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   That was as close as the Stars would come. Brathwaite shut down
a strong scoring chance from Joe Nieuwendyk in the third period,
but even that shot wasn't truly dangerous as Brathwaite simply
covered it with his pads.
</P>
<P>
   That Brathwaite was even in the game was a miracle of sorts.
Injuries forced the Flames to go through seven previous goalies,
including one call-up from junior hockey and a call-up from the
East Coast Hockey League who had to borrow pads from the Flames. It
had become almost a laughing matter in Calgary, where the Flames
are 13-24-3.
</P>
<P>
   But Brathwaite turned the joke on the Stars, who fell to 25-6-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to keep \Rthe streak\S going, but that's not the big
deal,'' Verbeek said. ``We were more looking at getting a good
start to the \Rfive-game\S road trip. That's more disappointing
than anything.''  &LR; tagtop: Mike Heika, (817) 390-7760
</P>
</TEXT>
