r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOUGHBOY-HONORED-LADN     01-09 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGHBOY-HONORED-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD WAR I VET, 100, RECEIVES FRANCE'S TOP DECORATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Eighty years after William Zelnicker fought in
World War I, the French government remembered his service with its
highest honor Friday _ but the 100-year-old said he'd rather forget
war and recall the life he made in the years after.
</P>
<P>
   ``I raised a family. After my wife died, I did my own cooking,
dish-washing. I never complained to the U.S. government. I've lived
a good life,'' the former doughboy said during a ceremony at the
Veterans Affairs Sepulveda Ambulatory Care Center and Nursing Home.
There the French deputy consul general bestowed upon Zelnicker the
National Order of the Legion of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't forget what you did 80 years ago,'' said Deputy
Consul General Philippe Vinogradoff. ``You helped us reach victory.
You helped us make a peaceful Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   He leaned over and pinned on Zelnicker the crimson ribbon and
white cross first awarded by Napoleon, then kissed the aging
veteran on both cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   The French began a program of awarding their highest honor to
all surviving soldiers and nurses from Allied countries, in
recognition of the 80th anniversary of the war's end Nov. 11, 1918.
VA officials believe about 1,500 are still alive in the United
States, but only 80 have received their honors so far.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnicker ran away from home and enlisted in the Army's 26th
``Yankee'' Division at age 17, even before the United States had
entered World War I. He served as an ambulance driver and stretcher
bearer in the trenches that etched the French countryside, until
Sept. 24, 1918. Then, during an American offensive in St. Mihiel,
the Germans launched a mustard-gas attack that scarred his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   The noxious cloud that swept across the battle lines ``was just
as thick as mud,'' Zelnicker recalled. ``After it took effect on
me, it affects your lungs; my breathing is heavy.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years recovering in an Army hospital, and even 80
years later, he said, doctors believe the aftereffects are causing
him circulation problems.
</P>
<P>
   But sitting in his Van Nuys home, where he lived on his own
until moving to the VA hospital seven months ago, Zelnicker
preferred to recall a time after the war, when he could dance the
Charleston with his young bride, Anna, at a dance hall in his
hometown of Providence, R.I. She died 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The pair raised a daughter, Sylvia, and two sons _ Albert, who
fought in the Navy in World War II and Korea, and Harold, killed in
action at 18 with the Army in Korea. A trace of bitterness colors
Zelnicker's voice when he talks about the death, and about how he
quit his membership in veterans organizations afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnicker shrugged when asked the secret of his long life, but
his family believes it was the fruits, vegetables and other healthy
foods he prepared for himself while living on his own up to age 99.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled the string of jobs he held after the war _ washing
dishes; running a five-and-dime in Bristol, R.I.; selling balloons
during parades for 10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done everything _ everything you can do to make a
dollar,'' he said. ``I was very happy.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
