<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAYLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAYLE LIKELY TO SET UP EXPLORATORY 2000 PANEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Former Vice President Dan Quayle likely will form a presidential
exploratory committee next month, putting him in competition with
another Arizonan, Sen. John McCain, in the first test of the GOP
primary:
</P>
<P>
   A candidate's ability to raise up to $20 million this year is
crucial to be considered a serious contender in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle signaled his intentions to enter the race Thursday night,
when he told reporters after a speech in Tempe that he probably
will seek a ticket to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Knowledgeable sources said Friday that Quayle likely will first
file papers in February with the Federal Election Commission that
would create a presidential exploratory campaign committee. Such a
move would allow Quayle to begin raising funds and to travel to key
early primary states as a potential presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to make a formal announcement in April.
</P>
<P>
   McCain became the first Republican candidate to form a
presidential exploratory committee on Dec. 30. Since then, the
field has begun to fill out, with Elizabeth Dole strongly hinting
that she might run and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander
forming an exploratory committee on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Publisher Steve Forbes, who won Arizona's 1996 GOP presidential
primary, also is expected to form such a committee next month.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually early start of the next presidential contest puts
additional pressure on candidates to secure the limited number of
Republican contributors who can give the maximum of $1,000 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle, a prodigious fund-raiser, is prepared to raise $20
million to $25 million, according to his spokesman, Cameron Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not daunted by that task,'' Carter said. ``Vice
President Quayle has a national fund-raising base and he has
hundreds of thousands of supporters, active donors, around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he were to run for president, there are no concerns he
would raise the requisite amount of money to be competitive and
successful.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain said last week that he will try to raise $14 million to
$15 million this year, should he decide to run. He has $2 million
from his 1998 Senate re-election campaign that he can use.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is expected to further his presidential effort next week
by hiring a campaign manager and by increasing his fund-raising
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Quayle last year toured the nation campaigning for GOP
candidates through his Phoenix-based political action committee,
Campaign America. Federal rules, though, prohibit Quayle from
transfering the $200,000 to $300,000 in remaining PAC funds to a
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said a ``fire wall'' exists between Campaign America and
Quayle's presidential activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no commingling of activities or monies, no
cross-pollination whatsoever'' with Quayle's presidential effort,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Stuart Rothenberg said Quayle has a
fund-raising advantage over such lesser-known candidates as McCain
and House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich of Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any former vice president of the United States ought to be a
formidable fund-raiser, just in terms of connections made over the
years,'' Rothenberg said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that ``there is great skepticism about Quayle as
someone who could really win the nomination . . . I think it
undercuts his fund-raising ability.''
</P>
<P>
   State GOP Chairman Mike Hellon said McCain has the upper hand in
Arizona, but the state hardly could be considered a gold mine of
presidential funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Bush will raise as much money in Arizona as Dan
Quayle,'' Hellon said, referring to the Texas governor and likely
GOP presidential front-runner. ``Bush has personal ties and
political ties here.''
</P>
<P>
   Quayle has lived in Paradise Valley since 1996, but is expected
to make his formal announcement in Huntington, the Indiana town he
represented in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rothenberg said the expanding GOP field will make it even harder
to compete for funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more candidates you have, the more likely you're going to
freeze contributions for everyone, or the people who are less
well-known will stay less well-known,'' Rothenberg said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
