<HEADER>
A5876 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HAWKS-HOLMGREN-SP     01-09 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HAWKS-HOLMGREN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHIFTING GEARS: HOLMGREN MADE GRADE AS TEACHER AND COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tall and blessed with a strong arm, Mike Holmgren was a prize
quarterback recruit from San Francisco, a new-age player for the
option-minded '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Cal called him the next Craig Morton, a replica of the Bears'
All-American, only bigger. Stanford would sign Jim Plunkett, but
wanted Lincoln High's oversized prospect as much, if not more.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Holmgren chose USC and rarely got off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   He threw just 27 passes as a collegian, completing eight. He had
one attempt against Washington. Typical of his career, the ball was
intercepted and returned 23 yards. By a Husky defensive lineman, no
less.
</P>
<P>
   The man perceived to be an NFL genius, to have unfailing vision
regarding all matters pigskin, has not always made the soundest
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to discourage him from going to USC because they
weren't using an offense to feature his talents,'' said Vic Rowen,
a family friend and former San Francisco State University football
coach. ``But that's what happens with 17-year-olds; they get
dazzled by the big-time program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Jim Plunkett and Mike reversed schools, Mike would have
gone on and played for years in the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren the coach would take a long and circuitous route to the
pros. Twelve years on the high school level. Twenty-two consecutive
defeats with one team. It was a time for making ends meet, not
making things happen.
</P>
<P>
   He was the head coach at San Jose's Oak Grove High in 1980, the
third entry on his resume, when Rowen offered him a job as San
Francisco State offensive coordinator and quarterbacks coach. The
position paid $23,000, less than Holmgren was making at the time.
He initially balked at taking a paycut. He gave in to Rowen. Good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he hadn't taken the job, Mike might still be coaching at
Oak Grove right now,'' the 79-year-old Rowen said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren instead is the newly hired Seahawks coach and general
manager, hailed as a guy with all the answers after guiding Green
Bay to a pair of Super Bowls and, as an assistant, helping San
Francisco to two others. He was part of BYU's national championship
run in 1984, his last stop before drawing an NFL paycheck. The
persuasive Rowen got him that job, too.
</P>
<P>
   On the outside, Holmgren, 50, is a frumpy guy with a mustache
and a motorcycle. Inside, he's a veritable web site of football
knowledge, acquired from several mentors. Rowen, SFSU's leader for
37 years until 1989, taught him independence. USC's legendary John
McKay gave him toughness. BYU's LaVell Edwards passed along the
intricacies of the passing game. And Bill Walsh, the former 49ers
head man, showed him what it takes to win.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's travails at USC helped establish him as a coach, too.
He went from a 3,592-yard passer as a high school senior to
perennial bench-warmer. He never played enough to letter. He sat
and watched as smaller, quicker quarterbacks Steve Sogge, Toby Page
and Jimmy Jones ran the Trojans. Holmgren handled adversity by
paying attention. First to practice, first to meetings, last to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says Brett Favre has a gun on him, but in his heyday
Mike could whistle it, too,'' said Craig Fertig, the Trojans'
quarterback coach at the time. ``He was like the hard-luck guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fertig used to pull out an electric football game then popular
with youngsters, set up the figurines and demonstrate what was
desired on offense to kneeling USC players. Even in his idle state,
Holmgren always had a question.
</P>
<P>
   In the Trojan empire, this was almost blasphemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually when John McKay said something, it was gospel, but
Mike was the first person who asked why,'' said Fertig, now a
Fox-TV college football analyst. ``He was the first person I
coached who ever did that.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren thought he was good enough to force the Trojans to
change their Tailback U. offense. He didn't anticipate them
bringing in O.J. Simpson during his sophomore year to keep the
vaunted Student Body Right and Student Body Left approach firmly
intact. Nor did Holmgren count on a dislocated thumb, sprained
ankle and senior season-ending shoulder injury thwarting his every
move to become USC's chief hand-off guy.
</P>
<P>
   He tried playing in the pros. He was an eighth-round draft pick
of the St. Louis Cardinals and went to camp with the New York Jets.
But he had sat too long.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren, a likeable guy who did killer impersonations of his
coaches and others and was always good for a sit-down beer, turned
to Fertig for his first job. The coach got him hired as a bartender
at the Nightwatch, a onetime USC coaches' hangout in Pasadena. Not
exactly a direct route to an NFL headset. Or was it?
</P>
<P>
   ``People who have less than glamorous playing careers, to some
degree, have less ego and better adapt to a bigger workload,'' said
Randy Cross, former 49ers center. ``I think what he really excelled
at in Green Bay was his handling of people and handling of
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren effectively sees the whole picture, but has built a
reputation as an unparalleled quarterback coach. He has had a
direct hand in the maturation of Joe Montana, Steve Young, Brett
Favre, Mark Brunell, Steve Bono and Ty Detmer in the pros, and
polished Young and Robbie Bosco during his BYU stint. Seahawk
starter Jon Kitna will get the next makeover.
</P>
<P>
   The former Trojan sub uses what Walsh gave him as a quarterback
blueprint: Be specific when teaching your men behind center, never
general. Too much information, and no one will remember it during
the heat of battle. Walsh stresses the word ``decisive'' in his
teachings. He wants his quarterbacks to have instant recall and
reflexive action for any situation they encounter. Holmgren imparts
this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's organized, an excellent teacher, a communicator,'' said
Sam Wyche, former Cincinnati and Tampa Bay coach, and another Walsh
disciple. ``Which is coaching, not cheerleading, when your guy
makes a nice throw. It's teaching him how to make the right throw
every time. Mike does a good job of that. I don't think this guy
will ever be hurting for a job.''
</P>
<P>
   With quarterbacks, Holmgren is best described as a sculptor. He
thinks he can mold just about anyone into a productive quarterback.
Take Seahawk reject Rick Mirer, for instance. Holmgren brought the
shaken one to Green Bay this past season as a pet project. Mirer
was a lost cause to all but the Packer coach. Mirer was the car up
on the blocks, getting overhauled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was really excited about what he saw in Rick Mirer _ he
thought he had to completely reteach the guy the position, and he
was excited about doing it,'' Cross said. ``He had Steve Young and
Joe Montana at the same time, and that wasn't exactly a lovefest.
He had to be father, confessor, and disciplinarian and friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know anybody in my opinion in the league better at
developing a quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren wants to make everybody feel good. A happy player is a
productive player. When African-Americans on his team started
complaining about getting a decent haircut in predominantly white
Green Bay, their coach procured the services of a Milwaukee barber.
And when Packers voiced their dislike for the standard
training-table culinary offering, the coach had soul food catered
from Milwaukee twice a week.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to reward his players. At the same time, Holmgren
expects them to earn the extras, the frills. There's a certain
toughness beneath the fun-loving veneer. John McKay gave it to him.
That, and a mere 27 passes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Holmgren seems determined to never let another
quarterback die on the vine. Each player is him, waiting his turn,
hoping his chance will come. For Holmgren, he rode the Trojan
hearse, not horse, and made the best of it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
