<SLUG> BC-FBN-HAWKS-PLAYERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KITNA, SEAHAWKS VETERANS `JACKED' ABOUT HOLMGREN HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ For the past two seasons, Seahawks wide receiver Mike
Pritchard has been comparing blossoming quarterback Jon Kitna to a
young Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Kitna was face to face with the coach credited with
molding a young Favre into a three-time NFL MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Kitna came by the team's headquarters after hearing that former
Green Bay Packers coach Mike Holmgren had been hired to be the
executive vice president of football operations/general manager and
head coach of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Kitna said after exchanging handshakes and a
few words with Holmgren. ``They seem to use a lot of play-action.
They don't run a play without a complement. It reminds me a little
of what we did in college.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Brett Favre takes that to another level because of
the plays he can make. But hopefully I can go out and do the same
things.''
</P>
<P>
   With Holmgren come hopes and high expectations, not to mention
the West Coast offense that has helped make Favre a star and plays
into Kitna's strengths.
</P>
<P>
   If this Kitna-Favre comparison seems like too big a stretch,
Favre did play his college ball at Southern Mississippi and was
with the Atlanta Falcons for one season before being traded to the
Packers. Granted, Southern Miss is like Notre Dame when compared to
Central Washington, where Kitna played. But Kitna appears to have
the skills to shove Holmgren's offense into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Mike is probably at his best _ getting young
quarterbacks ready to be stars,'' said Seahawks running back Ricky
Watters, who played for Holmgren in 1991 when both were with the
49ers _ Watters as an injured rookie, Holmgren as the offensive
coordinator. ``Jon already has a lot of confidence. He already has
a lot of poise. He already has a field presence about him. But
anything that's missing, Mike will fill in all those gaps.''
</P>
<P>
   How?
</P>
<P>
   ``What Mike is not afraid to do, and what he does well, is he
gets on you and then he praises you,'' Watters said. ``Then he gets
on you and he praises you again. And that's what you need. It's
like having a parent. You want a little fear there, a little
respect there and a lot of love.''
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Robinson also sees this Kitna-Holmgren match having a
spark. Robinson was a Pro Bowl free safety with the Seahawks who
was traded to Green Bay in 1996 and became a Pro Bowl player. This
year, he is with Atlanta and again was voted to the Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most obvious thing is he really knows the game, especially
his execution of the West Coast offense _ the quick strike, the
distant reads, the most probable open receiver. And he's always had
the quarterbacks, receivers and backs to get it done,'' Robinson
said Thursday from his home near Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seahawks have a quarterback in Jon Kitna that reminds me
of a young Mark Brunell. If (Holmgren) goes to Seattle, you'll see
the offense change dramatically to the quick strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren is here, and Kitna is, as he put it, ``ecstatic.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna was not alone in his enthusiasm over Holmgren's hiring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does the same thing that coach (Bill) Parcells brings when
he goes to the Jets,'' Watters said. ``It's like instant respect in
knowing that this guy knows what it takes to win. He's going to do
what it takes to win. You don't have to guess or question anything
that he's doing because you know whatever he's doing is for that
reason _ to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very jacked.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Matt LaBounty was traded by the Packers to the
Seahawks for Robinson, but is looking forward to the reunion with
Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited because obviously he's an excellent coach,''
LaBounty said. ``It appears that the people upstairs, the powers to
be, went out and got the best coach available. ... A lot of the
guys are excited and already looking forward to next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren's background is offense, and he called the plays in
Green Bay. But the Packers also had strong defenses because
Holmgren hired strong coordinators _ first Ray Rhodes, then Fritz
Shurmur.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Mike Holmgren's record, you can't help but get
excited,'' cornerback Willie Williams said. ``Once I heard they
were trying to get him, I was hoping this would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great defense and I'm sure Mike Holmgren will find
the right guy to bring out the best in us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
