<SLUG> BC-WALKING-GRANNY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRANNY GETS LIFT ON LONG JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, resending for those needing) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe it's her age. Could be the sign around her
chest. Whatever draws attention is fine for ``Granny D'' Doris
Haddock on her trek for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive great-grandmother wearing a backpack, light pants
and long-sleeved shirts, and hiking boots is still on the road to
the nation's capital after leaving Pasadena on New Year's Day in
the wake of the Tournament of Roses parade.
</P>
<P>
   She's been urged on by motorists, given lodging by strangers and
accompanied every step of the way by the West Virginia secretary of
state.
</P>
<P>
   Haddock reached the low desert community of Cabazon on Friday
after a stop on the Morongo Indian Reservation outside of Banning.
</P>
<P>
   Before heading out from Banning, the New Hampshire activist said
she was drawing strength from fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hoped for it because I'm talking of creating a groundswell,
but I certainly didn't really expect it,'' said the 88-year-old
retired shoe company secretary from Dublin, N.H. ``As a matter of
fact, it gives you energy, there's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such energy won't house or feed the pilgrim for political
change. So she has been thankful for the legions of people who
learned of her trek and provided room and board.
</P>
<P>
   A good measure was generated by a letter mailed nationally by
the nonpartisan political reform group Common Cause urging members
to aid the crusade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pioneers came from the east to the west to find a better
way of life, and she's going from west to east to create a better
environment for the average citizen to run for public office,''
said Ralph Langley, a Common Cause member in Upland who housed
Haddock, organized a week's worth of lodging and provided rides at
the end of several legs of her walk.
</P>
<P>
   The 72-year-old retiree said the effort was both exhilarating
and exhausting. ``What makes it worthwhile is the satisfaction to
participate in what I think is a historic event.''
</P>
<P>
   Lending daily support has been Ken Hechler, the West Virginia
secretary of state, who has walked with Haddock from the start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do a lot of crazy things,'' said the 84-year-old nine-time
congressman and former speech writer for President Truman. ``I just
was excited about stirring up public support. It already has. It's
pretty obvious when three out of four cars going down the highway
honk and lots of them stop and say I want to sign your petition.''
</P>
<P>
   Many others along the route apparently share that sense of
history in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Upland presented her the key to the city, San Bernardino gave
her an official lapel pin, and the Yucca Valley Chamber of Commerce
plans a parade Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Walking some 10 miles a day and making numerous impromptu
speaking engagements, however, sapped enough strength to force
Haddock off the road for rest this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have an urge to press ahead. I didn't want to lose the
momentum, but my legs were starting to get a little heavy,'' she
said. ``Family and friends convinced me to take a little rest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Haddock figures this initial fatigue will pass. ``It's so
exciting. I'm very sure I'm going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
