<HEADLINE>
PERFECT MATCH: SEAHAWKS SATISFY HOLMGREN'S THIRST FOR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ It was almost 16 months ago that Green Bay coach Mike
Holmgren offered what he thought was an innocent answer to a
question about his future: Would he like to run an entire football
operation in the NFL?
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren said yes, and has been dogged by the response ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first question he was asked each day during news
conferences at the Super Bowl last January, when the speculation
was that Holmgren was headed to the Seahawks. It was a question he
couldn't dodge this season, and even ignited a regrettable incident
with a fan in Green Bay who suggested Holmgren was more concerned
with his next job than his current one.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Holmgren got that job when he was named executive vice
president of football operations/general manager and head coach of
the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks signed him to an eight-year contract _ not for the
$5 million a year that was widely reported, but for closer to $4
million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was never a slam dunk,'' Holmgren said. ``I wasn't going
to leave to leave. That was never going to happen. But if the right
situation, in our opinion, came forth then I wanted to try it. And
this is exactly the right situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Holmgren has his dream job, what will he do with it?
</P>
<P>
   He'll start by assembling a coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is my No. 1 priority, get my coaches hired, get them in
here and let's get to work,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren did not contact any of his Packers assistant coaches
Friday, but the most likely to follow him to Seattle are defensive
coordinator Fritz Shurmur, defensive line coach Larry Brooks, wide
receivers coach Nolan Cromwell, linebackers coach Jim Lind,
offensive line coach Tom Lovat, quarterbacks coach Andy Reid, tight
ends coach Mike Sherman and defensive backs coach Bob Valesente.
Reid and offensive coordinator Sherman Lewis have interviewed for
head-coaching positions in Chicago and Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren will interview the six Seahawks assistants who are
under contract for at least one more season. Those with the best
chances to be retained are special teams coach Pete Rodriguez and
linebackers coach Jim Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't complete the entire staff,'' Holmgren said of mixing
and matching former Packers and Seahawks assistants. ``I'm fairly
certain there are some other guys I'll have to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren wants to have his staff in place within a week, so he
will have to work quickly. He is scheduled to fly back to Green Bay
today and return to the team's headquarters early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Those assistants will then help in evaluating the roster and
deciding which players must be added in free agency and the draft.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren will have his hands in every aspect of the football
operation and perhaps beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The language of his contract is that he has everything,'' said
Bob LaMonte, Holmgren's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Everything? Marketing? Tickets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, he will oversee those things,'' LaMonte said.
``They have a quality organization and business people. Mike will
come in and assess that. One thing about Mike Holmgren, there will
be a singular purpose. There will not ever be a question about the
direction of this football team. That will be one way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgren way.
</P>
<P>
   It was a thirst for power that made Holmgren want to leave Green
Bay after coaching the Packers to an 84-42 record in seven seasons
and a victory over the New England Patriots in Super Bowl XXXI.
With the strong hand of general manager Ron Wolf controlling things
in Green Bay, the Packers were unable to give Holmgren the power he
sought.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks decided Holmgren was their man quickly, and did
everything possible to make sure he felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we feel a fit, we move,'' Seahawks president Bob Whitsitt
said. ``We felt a fit, and we moved.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holmgren did not come cheaply. In addition to his salary,
which makes Holmgren the highest-paid coach in the NFL, the
Seahawks must give the Packers their second-round pick in April's
draft as compensation for signing Holmgren.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren had one year remaining on his contract in Green Bay,
but was given a clause last February that allowed him a 21-day
window to accept a job as general manager and coach with another
team.
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore Ravens and Philadelphia Eagles also had contacted
Holmgren, but he canceled weekend trips after deciding the Seahawks
were offering what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became abundantly clear that they were not going to let
Mike go to Baltimore, no matter what,'' LaMonte said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day for smiles all around at the team's headquarters,
and even a little giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   When Holmgren complained about officiating in the Packers' loss
to the 49ers on Sunday, Whitsitt interrupted him and offered,
``Would that fine be a Packer fine or will it be a Seahawk fine?''
</P>
<P>
   Cracked Holmgren, ``I don't know. We've got to get the lawyers
involved in that one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
