<SLUG> BC-FBN-HAWKS-FAMILY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED-CARPET TREATMENT WOWS HOLMGREN FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND _ Without his wife's approval, Mike Holmgren would not
have been signing a $32 million-plus contract with the Seahawks
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the most input,'' Kathy Holmgren said. ``If I won't go,
he won't go. We work as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Football factors and control issues are important to Mike
Holmgren, but family is the foremost consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, when he was the 49ers' offensive coordinator, Holmgren
turned down head-coaching jobs with the Cardinals and Jets, fearing
disruption at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a great thing for me,'' Holmgren said at
the time. ``It wouldn't have been the greatest thing for my
family.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Super Bowl two years ago, he dropped his
weekly TV and radio shows and most of his speaking engagements to
free up time in his schedule to spend with his wife and kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, there are things you have to do, but if there's a
choice, I'm going to choose being with my family,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgrens have four daughters, three of whom are officially
grown-ups, and another who is about to be. In 1990, the twins were
juniors nearing the end of high school. Now Calla and Jenny are 25.
</P>
<P>
   Tracing her mom's history, 21-year-old Emily got married young
and is currently on a mission in Bolivia. Thirty years ago,
21-year-old Kathy Holmgren was in the Congo, beating the bush, a
nurse giving physicals and injections to the natives.
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgrens are one removed from an empty nest. Gretchen, 17,
is in her senior year at Ashwaubenon (Wis.) High School. She went
to Seattle Pacific University on Thursday to check out the campus,
marking it down as a potential candidate now that dad has
relocated.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen accompanied her parents to Seattle on Paul Allen's
private jet. Gretchen had a wow-like expression on her face when
asked about the flight in luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her: ``Don't get used to it,''' Kathy Holmgren said.
``Enjoy the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgrens enjoyed their Thursday night dinner at Allen's
estate, eating French fare they could not pronounce. Kathy Holmgren
said she felt honored that Allen would cut short his scuba diving
trip in Costa Rica to be the dinner host. She sat next to Allen's
mom and found her to be a ``delightful woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The description applies to Kathy Holmgren. As reporters hovered
around her, she politely answered questions. But you got the
feeling she would prefer anonymity. This is not as big of a deal to
her as it is to everyone else. She remembers when Mike Holmgren
used to be a teacher at a Catholic high school, Sacred Heart, in
San Francisco and was paid $600 a month, not $4-plus million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   She has been known to use her maiden name when working for
charity, wanting people to recognize her only as Kathy, not wife of
the Green Bay Packers coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to not be in a fishbowl,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren finds perspective at Paul's Pantry, a charity that
distributes food to the needy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really love going to the Pantry,'' she told the Milwaukee
Journal Sentinel. ``I love all the people. They're so genuine. It
keeps you grounded in what's important in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren is working toward her second master's degree, in social
work, at the University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee. She received her
first in oncology nursing when Mike was coaching quarterbacks like
Steve Young at BYU in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real important for each one of us to have our own life so
that I don't depend on him for my happiness,'' she said. ``I have
to be happy on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgrens met when they were both 13 at a church camp in
Santa Cruz, Calif. Two years later, before he was old enough to
drive, Mike Holmgren proposed marriage in a card to Kathy. They
would be married after college.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, in the game plan drawn up by his wife, Mike Holmgren
will be running a bookstore instead of an NFL franchise. Kathy
Holmgren will be upstairs doing social work.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Kathy Holmgren talked about how nice it was to leave the
wind chill behind, fully knowing, however, what to expect here _
rain and inevitable heat if her husband fails to produce.
</P>
<P>
   The Holmgrens are looking forward to sampling Seattle's
restaurants. Undoubtedly, they will find a new home somewhere in
Kirkland near the Seahawks headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A priority is the smallest commute possible,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At work, Mike Holmgren will be the man in charge. At home, he
still has a general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a perfectionist. He demands excellence from the people
around him,'' Kathy Holmgren said. ``But when he tries to bring
that stuff home, we go: `Whoa, we're not your secretaries. This is
a democracy here.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
