<HEADLINE>
FANS SHOULD APPRECIATE NBA DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You're a Denver Nuggets fan. What if your team had
been able to keep Antonio McDyess?
</P>
<P>
   You're a Minnesota Timberwolves fan. What if the Wolves hadn't
emptied the piggy bank for Kevin Garnett and had a few million left
to keep both Stephon Marbury and Tom Gugliotta?
</P>
<P>
   You're a Clippers fan. OK, that's a stretch, but maybe you would
be if they hadn't shipped out every talented player who ever asked
for a 50-cent raise.
</P>
<P>
   What if NBA teams could compete on equal ground, thriving only
on their basketball acumen and not by the financial portfolio of
the owner?
</P>
<P>
   What if the real winner in the NBA's nasty little labor war was
not the billionaires or the millionaires, but Joe Wage Earner?
</P>
<P>
   That might just be the case.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA's new labor deal includes maximum salaries for every
class of player and several wrinkles that should greatly inhibit
free agency, reduce players' bargaining leverage and generally
promote an even playing field for all 29 teams.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Major League Baseball, where stratification of
the classes has up to 18 teams already eliminated from the
postseason _ before spring training begins _ the NBA's future looks
bright indeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a deal where truly everyone wins,'' said
Lakers executive Jerry West, ``and I'm talking about the sports
fans from all the different cities that comprise the NBA, from the
small-market teams to the big market teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's why:
</P>
<P>
   Maximum salaries: The much-discussed Larry Bird exception
allowed teams to pay any amount to keep their free agents. Problem
was, if a player demanded too much of his cash-strapped team, the
Bird rule failed its purpose _ to keep stars with their teams.
</P>
<P>
   Now no player can earn more than $14 million in the first year
of a deal. The playing field is leveled, and teams' budgets will be
intact. If this were the case a year ago, maybe the Nuggets
wouldn't have shipped McDyess _ then presumed to be out of their
price range _ to the Phoenix Suns. And perhaps Karl Malone, who
threatened to go anywhere that would pay $20 million a year, won't
abandon the Jazz when he becomes a free agent this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Longer rookie deals: Starting with the class of '98, rookie
contracts will be four to five years, instead of three. That means
teams won't have to turn the franchise over to a prospect before
he's proven his worth (Garnett), or trade him away for fear of
overpaying and getting burned (McDyess, onetime Warrior Joe Smith).
</P>
<P>
   Cap exceptions: In a typical year, most teams are over the
salary cap, meaning they can only sign additional players to
minimum salaries and can't compete for free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The new middle-class exception, $1.75 million this season, is
available every year, and combined with the $1 million exception
(available once every two years), will allow capped-out teams like
the Lakers to pay veterans what they're worth. Last year, that
might have meant keeping Jerome Kersey, who left for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Opt-out clauses and timing rules: In some cases, players had
been able to option out of a contract after only three years. Now
they have to wait five years.
</P>
<P>
   The timing rules, which govern free agency, are more complicated
than calculus, but put it this way _ they've been altered to make
it more difficult for free agents to test their value on the open
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal kills free agency,'' said agent Marc Fleisher. ``The
only ones who benefit are the (players) under long-term guaranteed
contracts. Every other class of player out there is going to get
hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   But fans, who couldn't keep up with their own teams' rosters in
an era of bedouins and mercenaries, win. And the folks in
Vancouver, Toronto, Denver and Sacramento might have hope restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like players not to be moving because of economic
disparity between teams, and we think that this (deal) is going to
eliminate the movement because of economic disparity,''
commissioner David Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be different judgment by teams as to what a player
is worth,'' added deputy commissioner Russ Granik, ``so I think
you'll still see movement because a player can get a better offer
somewhere else. But we'd like it to be because one team values a
player more highly ... rather than just because that team has a
greater ability to pay by a wide margin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
