<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5895 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-HAWKS-Q&AMP;A-SPI &LR;      01-09 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HAWKS-Q&AMP;A-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUESTIONS, ANSWERS ON HOLMGREN'S HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: Will the hiring of Mike Holmgren get the Seahawks back
on ``Monday Night Football'' for the first time since 1992?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The NFL schedule won't be released until late March or
early April, but the Seahawks do play at Green Bay next season and
you know ABC will be lobbying to get Holmgren's return in prime
time. How about the Seahawks vs. the Packers on the first Monday
night of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Question: Does Holmgren's hiring set the table for the return of
quarterback Rick Mirer? Mirer, who the Seahawks drafted with the
No. 2 overall pick in the 1993 NFL draft, has been Holmgren's pet
project in Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: No. No. No. A thousand times, no.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Will Holmgren fill his staff with Packer assistants,
or retain some of the Seahawks assistants who remain under
contract?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Both. Holmgren definitely will bring some of his Packer
assistants with him. But it is likely that he also will retain at
least one or two of the Seahawk assistants. Also count on him
bringing in an assistant or two from other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Question: With Holmgren getting the dual title of executive vice
president/general manager and head coach, what does that mean for
Randy Mueller, the club's vice president of football operations who
has been handling the duties of a general manager without the
title?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: Nothing. As club president Bob Whitsitt put it:
``Randy's still Randy. Instead of reporting to Dennis (Erickson),
he reports to Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Question: What did Holmgren's hiring do for season-ticket sales?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The Seahawks ticket office sold 275 new season-ticket
packages in the first three hours after Holmgren was hired. The
total reached 848 by the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Thursday night's dinner at the Mercer Island estate of
owner Paul Allen was the piece de resistance in landing Holmgren.
Just what does a multi-billionaire serve for dinner?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: As Holmgen offered: ``As the dinner went along, each
course was described. But it was described in French, so I had no
idea what I was eating. It was pretty good, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0138EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0034 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5896 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-2NDLEDE-WRITE     01-09 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-2NDLEDE-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: pulled back.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   And so Friday began with a last attempt to reach across party
lines in the ceremonial room that served as the Senate chamber
between 1810 and 1859, when some of the great debates and
confrontations over slavery took place. The chamber was placed
under heavy security. Folding chairs supplemented the permanent
seats to accommodate the senators, whose number was greater than
that of their counterparts in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   A few Republicans assured Democrats that despite the House
prosecutors' insistence on witnesses, they too did not want a
sordid discussion of sex to take place in the Senate chamber.
``What was helpful in the room was for the Democrats to learn there
are a whole lot of Republicans who are not anxious to have a bunch
of witnesses either,'' McConnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators said the sense of the history of the room helped
foster an atmosphere where they could come together. ``Every
senator knows the level of oratory and the weight of the issues
discussed here,'' said Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J. ``It helped
all the senators put this in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodd reminded his colleagues that ``one of the saddest moments
in Senate history'' had taken place in the room _ the caning of
Sen. Charles Sumner of Massachusetts by Preston Brooks of South
Carolina. ``Many historians feel that was when the comity in the
Senate broke down, leading three and a half years later to the
commencement of the Civil War,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, said the breakthrough came
when an unusual pair _ Edward M. Kennedy, a Massachusetts liberal,
and Phil Gramm, a Texas conservative _ made back-to-back
statements. ``I describe it as the Kennedy-Gramm or the
Gramm-Kennedy proposal,'' Lott told reporters. He then stressed the
bizarre notion of these two ideological opposites working together,
by saying with relish, ``Did you hear what I said?''
</P>
<P>
   Other senators said Gramm pointed out that under Senate
impeachment rules a vote on witnesses could always be demanded by
any party _ there was no way around it. Kennedy agreed that the
Texan was right and started suggesting ways to make the witness
situation more palatable to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the Democrats who moved the most, to accept a
proposal much like the one the Republicans had originally drafted.
And some Senate Democrats expressed private annoyance that Kennedy
had been so quick to support Gramm because they thought he gave
away a tactical advantage stemming from the Republicans'
unwillingness to look as partisan as their House counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic official close to the developments said the White
House as well had been trying to get Democrats to forgo the display
of bipartisanship. But Senate Democrats said they felt they had won
the best deal they could so that Republicans would appear to be
promoting a partisan trial. Some made clear that they had more
allegiance to the Senate as an institution than to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too bad,'' Sen. Joseph Biden, said, when asked about White
House grumbling. ``They have no say.'' He added, ``We're not here
to defend either the White House or the House of Representatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle pointed to provisions in the agreement that his party
considered important. He noted that the impeachment trial would be
limited to evidence that was already in the public record and that
witnesses would be considered in a group.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of the House Republican prosecution team had argued
to bring forward an unsubstantiated allegation of an uncorroborated
sexual encounter between Clinton and a woman years ago. The woman
has denied the accusation in an affidavit. Although it was not a
part of the House proceedings, several undecided House members were
shown the information as they weighed how to vote on impeachment.
The Senate agreement will bar such matters since they are not part
of the House impeachment record.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the voting also mollified Democrats. Kennedy said
that in the afternoon of drafting, Gramm had originally wanted to
have the vote on witnesses come toward the beginning of the trial.
The Democrats rejected that idea, so the plan calls for the vote on
witnesses to take place after two weeks of presentations by the
House and the White House. Daschle said that he believed the case
against witnesses would be stronger at that point.
</P>
<P>
   The House has pressed for witnesses even though it did not call
any in its own inquiry. Hyde has said that the House's role was
simply to determine whether to bring charges against Clinton, not
to try him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers also said that unlike the House, the Senate had
structured a procedure under which the White House could win.
Senators, unlike members of the House, retain the option to censure
Clinton, rather than simply vote to convict or acquit him. That may
make it easier, White House aides believe, for a majority of
senators to vote to dismiss the charges against Clinton after
hearing the presentations.
</P>
<P>
   The White House remains fearful, though, that the Senate will
ultimately choose to call witnesses, with the result that the trial
could drag out.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the brokering that went on throughout the day,
Senators held to the idea that the impeachment trial was a historic
moment for the Senate and that they had to rise to the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still believe that the Senate can restore some order to the
anger which has overtaken the country and the chaos which threatens
this city,'' Sen. Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., told his colleagues in
the morning caucus. ``I believe in all of you. I believe that all
of the courage and conviction needed to handle any crisis is
present right in this room.''
</P>
<P>
   By day's end Lott, who has been trying for weeks to broker a
bipartisan agreement, said in satisfaction, ``I think today we have
acted in the very best tradition of the Senate, and it is an
appropriate approach for this historic, very solemn event.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
