<SLUG> BC-BKN-SEASON-1STLEDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOW TO REALITY, NBA ALLOWS TALKS WITH AGENTS
</HEADLINE>
 
(Subs to add 7 grafs to end. No other changes.)   (bl) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fearing a mad scramble for free agents three weeks before the
season is scheduled to begin, the National Basketball Association
agreed Friday to permit teams to negotiate with player agents
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   From Michael Jordan to Zan Tabak, the decision opens the
floodgates for nearly 200 players to negotiate new contracts
through their agents. No deals can be signed until the new
collective bargaining agreement is set in writing sometime next
week. And the moratorium for players having contact with teams
remains in effect until training camps are scheduled to begin Jan.
18.
</P>
<P>
   But the cloak-and-dagger methods of many agents and team
executives will end this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with the union, and aware that talks were
already secretly going on after Wednesday's settlement that saved
the season, the league sent memorandums to the 29 teams about 5
p.m. Friday advising them that negotiations could proceed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was obviously such pent-up demand that it wasn't worth
fighting about,'' one league official said on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has yet to decide whether he will retire, but a
free-agent class that includes Antonio McDyess, Scottie Pippen,
Dennis Rodman, Damon Stoudamire and Jayson Williams is about to
experience the NBA's version of Job Fair '99, replete with the
usual inducements and recruiting tactics from prospective
employers.
</P>
<P>
   One agent, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the Nets
were keenly interested in acquiring McDyess, the skywalking forward
whose youth and athleticism make him perhaps the No. 1 commodity.
Phoenix and Denver, teams McDyess has played for, were also in the
bidding, as was Houston. The Nets are planning to keep Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Sexton, Pippen's agent, said there was a possibility his
client would return to the Chicago Bulls when the 50-game,
lockout-delayed season is scheduled to open Feb. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scottie loves Chicago, loves the team and so, if we can work a
deal out that works for Scottie, I think he would like to stay
there,'' Sexton said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, Orlando Magic and Rockets have only four players
apiece under contract, while the Suns have five.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Kasten, the Atlanta Hawks president, told The Associated
Press that he was suspicious that other teams were getting a jump
on negotiations in violation of the rules. He said he had spoken
with Commissioner David Stern about the situation and vowed to turn
in any team that breaks the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing that teams and players were secretly negotiating for the
past 48 hours, the league deemed the moratorium as unrealistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got lesser guys that I need to get into camps,'' said
Eric Rudolph, an agent who represents the free agents Johnny
Newman, Kebu Stewart and Shawnelle Scott. ``It just makes sense to
lift the moratorium. I'd like to be able to negotiate. So now, when
the 18th comes, it's like a formality of cutting their deals. A lot
of GMs were pushing hard for it for no other reason than they
wanted to find out if a certain player was interested in their
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another agent, on condition of anonymity: ``Whether they
lifted it or not, I'm just telling you we've been going about
business. So have a lot of other people.''
</P>
<P>
   Golden State is said to be trying hard to trade Latrell
Sprewell, with Miami and San Antonio the most interested. The
controversial All-Star guard has not played since November 1997
after choking and punching his coach, P.J. Carlesimo, and
subsequently being suspended for the remainder of last season. His
contract was originally terminated as well, but an arbitrator
sharply reduced the penalty and allowed Sprewell to return to
Golden State contractually. The Warriors have been trying to deal
him since.
</P>
<P>
   The season is expected to start in four weeks, and the playoffs
could end in late June or early July. Leading up to that date, the
face of the league may change considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte is in the most trouble regarding free agents, with
both centers Vlade Divac and Matt Geiger fielding offers from
several teams.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bulls remain the most intriguing subplot, with nine
players on the open market. The feeling among most team officials
is that if Jordan and Pippen somehow are retained, the club will
try to sign Rodman, Steve Kerr, Bill Wennington and Luc Longley to
attempt a run for a fourth consecutive title. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the decision Friday, teams were, in theory, allowed to put
together deals Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It eliminates any need for investigation,'' the agent Keith
Glass said. ``Obviously, people have been sitting around for six
months doing nothing. So it's eliminated any hypocrisy. It puts
everybody on equal footing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I've been calling and wishing people a Happy New Year
just to get a conversation going, and I think they're questioning
my sincerity.''
</P>
<P>
   The collective bargaining agreement included salary maximums for
the game's highest-paid players, eliminating the glut of $100
million deals that the owners claimed had crippled NBA economics.
</P>
<P>
   A player with 10 years of experience can make no more than $14
million in the first year of his deal _ with the possibility for
annual 12 percent raises. With restrictions like those, some league
officials said they believed that the need for agents would be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Glass, for one, was not buying that theory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like city rats, we're very adaptable,'' he said. ``We
can live anywhere in any deal. We will survive. They can't
exterminate us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0151EST &QL; 
