<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEATTLE-HOLMGREN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS MAKE HOLMGREN TOP PAID 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maybe it was the seven-year itch. Maybe it was a chance to earn
the highest salary ever for a National Football League coach.
Maybe, as Mike Holmgren said, despite all his success he wanted to
achieve more.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the opportunity arrived Friday when
Holmgren, after seven winning seasons as the Green Bay Packers'
coach, signed as the executive vice president, general manager and
head coach of the Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren had a year left on a contract that paid him $2 million
this season. But he also had a clause that allowed him to pursue
another head coaching job until Jan. 25 if he also became the
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks wanted Holmgren, and they talked to him first. The
Baltimore Ravens and the Philadelphia Eagles expected to talk to
him within days. Instead, Holmgren signed an eight-year contract
with Seattle that is said to be worth $4 million a year. Holmgren's
contract with the Packers requires the Seahawks to send the Packers
a second-round draft choice.
</P>
<P>
   The 50-year-old Holmgren heads the National Football League's
coaching scale. The previous leader was George Seifert, who signed
on Monday with the Carolina Panthers for a reported $2.5 million a
year. Until then, the NFL's highest-paid coaches were also general
managers _ Bill Parcells of the Jets at $2.4 million a year and
Jimmy Johnson of the Miami Dolphins at $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren had said he would return to the Packers unless he found
a job that combined the head of football operations with the head
coach position. While thanking the Packers for giving him his first
head coaching job, Holmgren said: ``It's been a real honest
relationship the whole way. They knew at some point in my career I
would like to have the job I'm privileged to have now.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 28, the day after the regular season ended, the Seahawks
dismissed their coach, Dennis Erickson, after four seasons with
records of 8-8, 7-9, 8-8 and 8-8. The Seahawks have gone 10 years
without reaching the playoffs, the longest current drought in the
league. They were also troubled by poor talent decisions on rookies
and free agents.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Seahawks spent $15 million on signing bonuses
alone for such heralded free agents as running back Ricky Watters,
center Kevin Glover, offensive guard Brian Habib, linebacker Darrin
Smith and punter Jeff Feagles.
</P>
<P>
   Of those five, only Feagles, who averaged 44.1 yards a punt, had
a season that might have pleased Paul Allen, the team owner and
co-founder of Microsoft. Watters had an uneventful 1,000-yard
rushing season. Glover missed seven games because of injuries and
Smith missed four. Habib drew frequent penalties.
</P>
<P>
   While the Seahawks were foundering, the Packers were winning.
Holmgren, inheriting a losing team, posted records of 9-7, 9-7,
9-7, 11-5, 13-3, 13-3 and 11-5. His last six teams made the
playoffs, two reached the Super Bowl and one won it. This season,
the Packers lost to the San Francisco 49ers, 30-27, in a wild-card
game.
</P>
<P>
   At Green Bay, General Manager Ron Wolf said he had no timetable
for naming a new coach. He did say: ``This isn't going to be like
one of these little high school prom things where you are picking
the best looking or the most compatible. You have to get somebody
of championship caliber and championship quality.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0155EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
