A5908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MENTALLY-ILL-NYT &LR;      01-09 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MENTALLY-ILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COLUMN: STREET NAME FOR IMPASSE: HOMELESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Feinberg lives in a tiny room. He has a bed, a
dresser and a stand where his television shares space with a dozen
amber medicine bottles. Not much, but infinitely more than what he
had four years ago, when he drifted on the streets, marking the
change from summer to winter by migrating from breezy boardwalk in
Brooklyn to the subway stations of midtown. Back then he suffered
from infections, heart palpitations, anxiety attacks and seizures.
Sometimes, all he did was sob.
</P>
<P>
   His troubles began when he lost his job as a supermarket clerk.
Then his girlfriend died, and he ran through his savings to give
her a proper burial. With no money or prospects, he just left his
Brooklyn apartment one day.
</P>
<P>
   ``After six months, I didn't know what time it was,'' he said.
``I used to fall on the street. But I had nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent two years on the streets until some outreach workers
persuaded him to get help. He arrived a year and a half ago at
Euclid Hall, a single room occupancy hotel on the Upper West Side,
where he found a haven and people who make sure he takes his
medicine and keeps his appointments. He now boasts that he does a
lot for himself, and he no longer worries about wandering the
subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to walk the subways,'' he said. ``If I went to
the subway, I'd die. I don't think I would last two days on the
subways anymore. My doctor said I can't do that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that he has a doctor, as well as a room and counselors
to help him, was made possible through New York/New York, a city
and state partnership that built nearly 4,000 housing units for
mentally ill homeless people. City officials would like to build at
least 1,750 more apartments, but they have reached an impasse with
state officials over the state's part of the program. The city is
willing to spend $51 million and would like the state to provide
twice as much, as it did in the program's first phase. The state,
however, has stuck to its current commitment of $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   This has created uncertainty among those who advocate for and
care for the homeless mentally ill, who said that the disagreement
will only delay the construction of housing while the state moves
to release thousands of patients from its psychiatric hospitals.
They said that with little new housing in the pipeline, people may
have few options beyond living unsupervised on their own or moving
in with parents who are older and ill prepared to care for them.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Coe, the executive director of Community Access, an
advocacy and housing group, said this week's arrest of Andrew
Goldstein, who is charged with shoving a woman to her death in
front of a subway train, was an extreme example of what can happen
when people with psychiatric problems are left to live without
adequate support. Goldstein, a schizophrenic, was said to have
rented a room in a Queens home where he kept to himself and
sometimes did not take his medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you provide people with a decent place to live and people
who care about you, people are able to acquire skills and have some
sort of productive activity,'' he said. ``Somebody like Andrew,
living by himself in a room, he does not have access to those
resources to help him negotiate the system.''
</P>
<P>
   Coe belongs to a coalition that is urging public officials to
embark on a five-year program to build 10,000 more housing units,
an ambitious goal given the current deadlock. But supporters of the
movement said that while such an effort might sound expensive, it
was a worthwhile long-term investment, especially given current
budget surpluses. What was not as abundant, they said, was the
political will.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this frustrating mentality in the political sphere
where people want to make decisions that will have a quick impact
and generate political benefits to them,'' said the Rev. Alistair
Drummond, the moderator of the Presbytery of New York City. ``The
debate has degenerated into simple arguments about resources and
demands on a limited budget. People talk about budget surpluses,
yet there is not even a sense of moral obligation.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinberg prefers to talk about his new home, where the common
kitchen is spotless and his room is warm. He thinks it's a big
deal, considering the alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no other place for people to go,'' he said. ``You go
to the subway and the people are all mental cases. Not that they're
mental, but they get no nourishment and give up. You know what I'm
talking about? They give up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
