<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5910 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ROBITAILLE-LADN     01-09 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ROBITAILLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE'S RUN FOR 500 STARTED WITH RV TRIP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At campgrounds across America last summer, the
embarrassed-looking inline skater was a revitalized fitness
fanatic.
</P>
<P>
   At Big Sur, with weights draped around his neck, the star left
wing of the Los Angeles Kings was recognized by some vacationers,
and was the recipient of sidelong glances from others.
</P>
<P>
   And within the shadow of Mt. Rushmore, Luc Robitaille set up his
weight-lifting equipment a slap shot beneath the likeness of former
presidents George Washington, Thomas Jefferson, Abraham Lincoln and
Theodore Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   The motivation for Robitaille's summer of pain and gain was
simple: He wanted to better prepare for his final pursuit of
hockey's coveted 500-goal mark, which he reached by scoring twice
in Thursday night's 4-2 victory over the Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew he needed to play better,'' said Joe Horrigan, the
strength and conditioning specialist Robitaille turned to for help.
``And as his training progressed, so did his attitude. By July, he
was saying, `I'm going to score 40 or 50 goals.' ''
</P>
<P>
   As outlandish as that might have seemed at the time, Robitaille
_ the 27th player and sixth left wing to score 500 goals _ is well
on his way after scoring only 40 goals the previous two seasons
combined. Robitaille has scored 22 goals in 39 games, and enters
tonight's game at the Forum against the Edmonton Oilers with 12
goals in his past 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal was to make the NHL. I never thought, `I want to get
to 500 goals,' '' the 13-year veteran said. ``I think one day when
I retire, I'll look at a guy like Maurice Richard, to be in the
same numbers as him, it's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to Robitaille's success this season was his summer
workouts.
</P>
<P>
   On June 1, Horrigan performed baseline tests on Robitaille so
he'd be able to chart his client's progress over time.
</P>
<P>
   Horrigan had Robitaille skate from the goal line to the near
blue line _ a distance of 60 feet _ and clocked him at 3.0 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Horrigan _ who assumed Robitaille couldn't have lifted much more
than 135 pounds _ had Robitaille do a clean pull with an empty bar
(45 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   He started Robitaille at 55 pounds on a squat lift, assuming his
limit would have been less than 225.
</P>
<P>
   And he had Robitaille do three sets of sit-ups, 10 repetitions
each, holding a 10-pound weight. Robitaille never before had done
sit-ups holding a weight.
</P>
<P>
   How far has Robitaille progressed? According to Horrigan, in the
most recent testing, Robitaille skated from the goal line to the
near blue line in 2.67 seconds, did a clean pull of 315 pounds, was
close to 400 pounds in the squat, and did three sets of sit-ups, 10
repetitions each, holding a 70-pound weight.
</P>
<P>
   From the start of training camp in September, the difference in
Robitaille's performance was obvious. Robitaille _ who added 15
pounds of muscle to his 6-foot-1, 215-pound frame _ has been
quicker to reach loose pucks, and has looked stronger when he's had
to battle for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest difference I feel is, a year or even 10 years ago,
in 80 games, there probably would be 40 or 50 games where I felt
great, 100 percent,'' Robitaille said. ``And the other 30 games,
I'd feel sluggish or feel tired, and I'd get by somehow. Now, so
far this year, I can't say there's one game where I really felt
sluggish. Every game, I've felt strong physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Rob Blake _ Robitaille's workout partner on the road
_ added, ``If you watch him in the corners, instead of a guy being
beside him, the guy is behind him. Luc's gains are measured in
inches, but when you're as talented as he is, that's all you
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Horrigan's main concern as last summer began was the month-long
vacation Robitaille was planning with his wife, Stacia, and their
two sons, 10-year-old Steven and Jesse, 3. Robitaille was eager to
spend time with his family, crisscrossing the United States in a
rented motor home. For Horrigan, the trip represented potential
lost time.
</P>
<P>
   Robitaille's solution was simple: He purchased weight-lifting
equipment, packed his inline skates and hit the road. Each day,
Steven and Jesse would help their father set up his equipment
outside the motor home, and the workout would begin, lasting
anywhere from 60 to 90 minutes. As their father worked out, the
family sometimes would hide in the motor home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not coming out with you doing this stuff,'' they would
tell Robitaille.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little bit embarrassing at some of the campgrounds,''
Robitaille recalled. ``People were coming in with their tents and
they were looking at me with this big motor home and my big squat
rack outside. I was the only one doing that, that's for sure. A few
people would come up to me. They thought it was some kind of jack
to lift the motor home. They didn't know what the heck it was. It
was kind of funny, actually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were up north in Big Sur and there were people there from
L.A. and they recognized me. But mostly, I would get some funny
looks more than anything. We went all the way to Mt. Rushmore. Some
days were more embarrassing than others. But I knew it was
important. It's important for my career. It was something I had to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Robitaille had shunned lifting weights
once the season began, under the belief that conserving energy was
his most important task. Under Horrigan's direction, Robitaille has
learned not to exercise to the point of exhaustion, limiting
sessions to 25 minutes and riding the stationary bicycle daily, but
for no more than 20 minutes a day.
</P>
<P>
   He drains himself on the rink, not in the gym, and his efforts
on the ice already have netted Robitaille as many goals as some of
his friends thought him capable of scoring in an entire 82-game
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept saying, `The league has changed, the league is
faster,''' Robitaille recalled. ``And it's true. The league has
changed. The defensemen are better and the goalies are better. So I
said, `Well, I'm going to have to get better, too.'''
</P>
<P>
   After his struggles last season, and in light of the fact that
he hasn't scored more than 24 goals in a season since 1993-94,
there was something else prodding Robitaille last summer when he
motored around America with family and weight-lifting gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always felt I had to prove something,'' said Robitaille,
who is talking these days about playing five more years. ``But if
you look at all the great players, they always feel they have to
prove something. If you look at anybody who's had any kind of
success in their life, they always want to prove something.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it says in the paper that Luc played bad last night, my
first thing will be, `I'll prove that they were wrong,' and I'll
play harder. And if it says I played a great game or I'm a great
player, the first thing I want to do is prove that it's right, so
I'll go harder. That's the mentality I have for the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
