<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, Jan. 9.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-BOMBS (Washington) _ A close examination of events in
the year before the terrorist assault on the Kenya embassy, based
on interviews with officials throughout the U.S. government, shows
that concerns about embassy security were more intense, more
well-founded, more specific, and more forcefully expressed than has
previously been known. A special report. A short version has also
moved, as EMBASSY-BOMBS-ABR. By James Risen and Benjamin Weiser.
With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   EMBASSY-CROWE (Washington) _ Special panels set up by the State
Department to investigate the bombings of two U.S. embassies in
Africa called on the department Friday to consider closing a number
of embassies around the world that are vulnerable to terrorist
attack and replacing them with regional ``super-embassies.'' By
Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   POLLARD-SENTENCE (Washington) _ Law enforcement and intelligence
officials said Friday that they remain adamantly opposed to
shortening the life sentence of Jonathan Jay Pollard, a former Navy
intelligence analyst convicted of spying for Israel. By David
Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-DAMAGE (Washington) _ Almost three weeks after the bombing
stopped, the Pentagon's senior commanders claimed on Friday that
the American and British raids on Iraq had caused more damage than
initially reported. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-VATICAN (Rome) _ The new prime minister, an ex-Communist,
makes a formal visit to the pope as a sign of a new relationship
between the Roman Catholic Church and former Communists. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PIGEONS (Beijing) _ Recently 118 pigeons that made their
home in a public plaza outside a shopping mall suddenly died. The
shocking news was instant grist for front-page headlines in
Beijing's major newspapers. Ever since, generally fractious
Beijingers _ not known for their kindness to one another _ have
selflessly rallied in support of the birds in a period of outraged
mourning. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NY-READING-TEST (New York) _ A look at New York state's new
fourth-grade English exam, known in elementary schools simply as
The Test, which is to be given for the first time next week. Unlike
other standardized tests, this one requires students to take notes
on passages and write critiques and personal essays based on what
they heard. New York City may start using next year to determine
whether children should be held back a grade. By Randal C.
Archibold. With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HILLARY-POLITICS (New York) _ By most accounts, the prospect
of Mrs. Clinton seeking the Senate nomination is only the hopeful
figment of the imagination of Democrats contemplating the difficult
task of keeping Sen. Patrick Moynihan's seat under their party's
control. The first lady's associates say that Mrs. Clinton has
shown little interest in moving to New York and entering partisan
politics. It will probably be months before she offers a final word
on her political plans. By Adam Nagourney. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ For the first half of 1998,
religious leaders and theologians had a low profile in the national
debate over President Clinton's sexual and legal misdeeds. But
starting on Sept. 11, when Clinton chose a breakfast meeting with
religious leaders as the occasion for his fullest admission of
wrongdoing and expression of remorse, the situation began to
change. By Peter Steinfels. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Sioux City, Iowa) _ As the Senate debated how to conduct
an impeachment trial, the chamber's nominal president, Vice
President Al Gore, was 1,000 miles away Friday, talking about hogs,
methamphetamines and Social Security. Continuing an apparent White
House strategy to focus on policy as a way to divert attention from
events that could drive President Clinton from office, Gore spent
the day immersed in highly scripted appearances intended to reflect
an administration hard at work. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH (Washington) _ After an extraordinary bipartisan caucus
that lasted about three hours, the Senate voted unanimously Friday
to approve a plan for President Clinton's impeachment trial that
calls for opening arguments to begin on Thursday and defers a
decision on whether to summon witnesses until later in the month.
By Alison Mitchell. With photos and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-ASSESS (Washington) _ The road to a result the country
will consider adult, and fair, still has some rickety passages
ahead. And in the end, Republicans will cast all, or almost all, of
the votes to convict President Clinton and remove him from office,
while Democrats will cast most of the votes to acquit him and keep
him. If Friday's decision satisfied the Senate, it almost certainly
displeased the House managers and the White House. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CLINTON (Detroit) _ In the glow of more terrific
economic numbers, President Clinton proclaimed that all is well _
very well indeed _ showing once again just why he is popular, and
why removal from office is a very difficult goal for his opponents.
By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-SCENE (Washington) _ The Senate rallied on Friday around
its own need for dignity. Having sought sanctuary from the
maddening politics of impeachment in a hallowed gaslight-era
chamber of the Capitol, the senators emerged three hours later
exulting in the rarest of news: The clash of President Clinton and
his House Republican accusers was far from settled, but at least
the nation would be treated to a moment of bipartisan unanimity. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-CANING (Washington) _ Appealing for a sense of harmony,
Sen. Christopher J. Dodd, D-Conn., reminded colleagues gathered in
the Old Senate Chamber for a rare bipartisan caucus Friday that the
room was the scene of a ``tragic event'' in 1856: a brutal physical
assault by one member of Congress on another. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy added more jobs than
expected in December and the unemployment rate fell, tying a
28-year low. Payrolls increased by 378,000 jobs last month, well
above analysts' forecasts. The unemployment rate declined to 4.3
percent in December from 4.4 percent in November. By Sylvia Nasar.
With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   DOLLAR-DECLINE (Washington) _ Even while the stock market hits
new highs, a crucial indicator of foreign confidence in the U.S.
government and its economy _ the dollar _ has been falling. No one
can agree why. By David Sangar. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T-ACQUIRE (Undated) _ AT&AMP;T releases financial details of its
proposed acquisition of Tele-Communications Inc. Contrary to its
original plan, AT&AMP;T will not issue a tracking stock for its
consumer business or for any of its other operations, though it
will mount a 3-for-2 split of its common stock after the deal is
completed. Also, the company says its earnings this year will
exceed expectations and that it has agreed to form joint ventures
with five small cable operators. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS-ASIA (Hong Kong) _ The bulls finally stop stampeding
across Asia, but the recent sharp gains in stock prices from Seoul
to Singapore are worrying analysts, who are alarmed by the growing
disparity between the rising markets and Asia's still-sinking
economies. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RICH-COLUMN (Undated) _ Enough is enough. Move on. Let's get
back to the people's business. It's bad for the country. The
country is so bored it would rather watch ``Patch Adams.'' If
there's any consensus as we enter the last trial of the century, it
is this: Get it over with. By Frank Rich.
</P>
