<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 09:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5926 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-09 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: OF TANG AND THONGS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that impeachment has moved to the Senate, the
greatest deliberative body since Roman times, Peter and Dan and Tom
and Tim and Cokie and Greta keep telling me I should be awestruck
by the solemnity and majesty of the occasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``As moving as this was to watch on television,'' intoned Peter
Jennings, ``and it was moving ... .''
</P>
<P>
   They talked in sweeping terms about this moment in our lives we
would never forget, a day that would be recorded in bold print in
American history, about how the president's plight suddenly seemed
REAL.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know this is dead serious when you hear `Hear Ye, Hear
Ye,''' said NBC's Tim Russert. Well, Sue Me, Sue Me, but Hear Ye,
Hear Ye failed to send shivers down my spine.
</P>
<P>
   If I were describing the occasion, I would not use the words
moving, solemn, majestic, momentous, real, dead serious or bold.
</P>
<P>
   I would use the word OLD. I might use the word DEAD. I would not
talk about the extraordinary HUSH, but about the extraordinary
MUSH.
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Revenge of the Grumpy Old Men.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, during the Thomas-Hill hearings, the curtain parted on
the Senate to reveal a sight at once grotesque and hilarious: a
bunch of out-of-touch old white guys trying to fathom truth in sex.
</P>
<P>
   It had the quality Dickens called ``the attraction of
repulsion.'' America was riveted by that bawdy seminar on the
perils of sex in the federal workplace. We thought those wrenching
hearings would illuminate gender politics and modernize the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. Lo, these many years later, the curtain parts again. And,
LIKE HELLO, as Monica would say, what do we see but the grotesque
and hilarious sight of a bunch of out-of-touch white guys trying to
fathom truth in sex. That same old boys' club, once again slouching
toward C-Span to instruct America on the perils of sex in the
federal workplace.
</P>
<P>
   And who could believe that all these years later, Strom Thurmond
would still be center stage and Tang-colored? If Thurmond, who was
a boyish 88 during the Thomas-Hill hearings, and Ted Kennedy and
Joe Biden were uncomfortable with Long Dong Silver and X-rated
videos, imagine how they'll handle presidential phone sex and thong
underwear.
</P>
<P>
   We will have to do simultaneous translations with Thurmond
again, like the one the columnist Dave Barry did during the last
Senate sex seminar:
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thurmond: Deah wheah etn lonsh yep?
</P>
<P>
   Translator: He says, ``Did we eat lunch yet?''
</P>
<P>
   What a tableau. Henry Hyde lumbering across the marbled halls
from the House to the Senate, allegedly more in sorrow than in
anger, leading that pack of gray-haired, gray-faced, gray-suited
and gray-spirited fogies. These self-appointed Torquemadas of the
birds and the bees looked more like gouty Florida retirees hurrying
to get to that early-bird buffet.
</P>
<P>
   But the House managers were spring chickens compared with the
greeting party in the Senate, composed of Thurmond, 96, Sen. Robert
Byrd, 81, and Chief Justice William Rehnquist, 74, whose idea of a
wicked judicial jest is emblazoning his black robes with gold
Gilbert and Sullivan chevrons.
</P>
<P>
   It's a Mel Brooks routine. The Cicero-loving Bob Byrd, or
Quintus Robertus Byrdus, and his conclave of 2,000-year-old men
orating about those headlines in The Roman Tribune _ ``Ovid Ousted,
Augustus Disgusted.'' These are the sexual arbiters who are charged
with the solemn task of deposing the frisky Monica Lewinsky and
deciding who touched whom, where, when and with what degree of
arousal?
</P>
<P>
   Great Caesar's ghost!
</P>
<P>
   Last time it was a feminist liberal lynch mob trying to kill off
a conservative Supreme Court nominee over sex when the real reason
they wanted to get rid of him was politics.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's a reactionary lynch mob trying to kill off a
Democratic president over sex when the real reason they want to get
rid of him is politics.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the impeachment trial begin, it's hard to believe the
Senate, even with its sprinkling of post-Anita women, is any better
equipped to find justice in this politically poisoned muck than it
was the last time around.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that they Just Don't Get It. Maybe they should just
keep their noses out of it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 0935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
