</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WILL THE JETS' WIZARDS TRAP THE JAGUARS?  (JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their reputation precedes them, even when they are about to
propose the Jets' defensive game plan for Bill Parcells' approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' the Jets' coach has been known to greet them, ``what
have you wizards come up with this week?''
</P>
<P>
   The ordained Wizards are Bill Belichick (assistant head coach
and defensive secondary coach), Al Groh (linebackers coach) and
Romeo Crennel (defensive line coach). They are the Wizards of
Defense whose sorcery will be tested Sunday in the Jets' divisional
playoff game with the Jacksonville Jaguars in the expected wintry
wind chill of Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I don't like something, I'll say we've got to fix this and
they see the problem,'' Parcells said. ``But they'll also tell me,
`Don't make a mountain out of a molehill,' which I can do
sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   During the season, the Wizards' defensive designs contributed to
the Jets' limiting opponents to only 266 points, second in the
National Football League to the Miami Dolphins' 265. But in the
Super Bowl playoffs, when the stakes are higher and opposing
offenses are higher octane, determined defense is even more
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have not been in the playoffs since 1991, but two years
ago the Wizards, then on Parcells' staff in New England (after also
being on his Giants staff), were there when the Patriots stopped
the Jaguars, &QC; 20-6, in the American Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   So the Wizards have not only had two weeks to build a trap for
the Jaguars; they also remember how that title game turned on New
England safety Willie Clay's end-zone interception of Mark
Brunell's pass for what would have been the tying touchdown. Otis
Smith, then a Patriot cornerback, soon returned a fumble 47 yards
for the clinching touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is now the Jets' right cornerback, and with Aaron Glenn
apparently not completely recovered from a sprained ankle, Ray
Mickens is expected to start at left cornerback. Smith and Mickens
will be primarily responsible for covering the left-handed
Brunell's favorite targets, the wide receivers Jimmy Smith and
Keenan McCardell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches do a great job of breaking things down and
translating it to the players,'' Otis Smith said. ``They use the
right players for every situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not being able to use Glenn, their Pro Bowl cornerback, in every
situation would test the Wizards' ingenuity in devising the Jets'
pass coverage. But remember that Glenn, who missed the second half
of the victory over Seattle, was not available at all when the Jets
swept their last three games against Miami, Buffalo and New
England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belichick understands everything that goes on _ secondary,
linebackers, line,'' Glenn said. ``He puts his players where they
can make plays _ Mo Lewis rushing, Ray Mickens in the slot. He
taught me how to play zone.''
</P>
<P>
   The colder the weather, the stiffer Brunell's healing ankle
might be, especially on artificial turf. But with the rookie Fred
Taylor, who rushed for 1,223 yards and scored 17 touchdowns, the
Jaguars have a more explosive running attack than that of two years
ago, when the Wizards' game plan controlled Natrone Means and James
Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a lot will depend on how the coaches intend to play the
game,'' Parcells said. ``I can't tell until I see what kind of day
it is _ warm or cold, windy or no wind. How to generate the offense
if you couldn't do the entire scope effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells was talking about the Jets' offense, but the weather
will also dictate how Tom Coughlin, the Jaguar coach, will use his
offense and, in turn, it will dictate the Jets' defensive strategy.
Whatever develops, the Jets' defenders know that the Wizards will
be able to adjust to what's happening. Especially in the final
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know each other so well, they can read each other's
minds,'' defensive end Rick Lyle said. ``They're at their best at
the end of a close game. They know the other team's plays and
formations so well and they're able to communicate it to you so
well on the sidelines. You can anticipate what the other team is
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   During the game, Belichick and Crennel are on the sideline.
Groh, the linebackers' guru, is in the coaches' booth on the
press-box level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no game where we're not prepared,'' linebacker Chad
Cascadden said. ``The coaches always have a wrinkle in the game
plan, and they're able to adjust during the game. And they know how
to coach techniques. In pro football, there's more speed, more
formations than in college, but they know how to fine tune you to
that level.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Wizards' work is never done. If their defense makes the
difference for the Jets Sunday, they will need to be Wizards again
next Sunday in the AFC championship game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
