<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5938 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STATEOFUNION-     01-09 1219
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STATEOFUNION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
THE SPEECH, THE TRIAL AND THE STATE OF THE POLITICS  (The Week in
Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On Friday, the Senate finally settled on some basic
details for President Clinton's impeachment trial: when procedural
motions are due (Monday), when the prosecution will begin its case
(Thursday) and how long each side will have to present the
now-familiar evidence and arguments (a numbing 24 hours).
</P>
<P>
   But alongside the Senate's crisp, lawyerly schedule is another
timetable: when Clinton will deliver his State of the Union
address.
</P>
<P>
   The speech has long been scheduled, by agreement of the White
House and Congress, for Jan. 19. But already some Republican and
even some Democratic lawmakers have complained about the prospect
of a president extolling the union's state to House members who
impeached him and senators who are mulling his removal from office
on charges mired in Oval Office sex.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton might accommodate a congressional proposal to shift the
address by a few days, his advisers say, but he will not postpone
it indefinitely. To the administration, the speech is a golden
opportunity for Clinton to appear presidential before a national
television audience _ and to challenge his tormentors to improve
affairs of state even as they dicker over the state of his affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The question of when to deliver the speech represents one of
those Washington proxy fights over something bigger. Since Woodrow
Wilson revived the speech describing the State of the Union,
presidents have used it to make an implicit argument before the
upturned faces of their live audience: The three branches of
government may be equal, but one is more equal than others.
</P>
<P>
   Packed into the House chamber, representatives, senators and
justices of the Supreme Court are all listening to him as he
presents his agenda. He does not return the favor, at least not in
such a majestic setting. This year more than ever, some senators
seem uncomfortable with that unbalancing act.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be testing the command of his office,
challenging the widely discussed notion that his impeachment has
weakened the presidency. That is likely to work to Clinton's
advantage, the White House believes. In fact, aides said, the start
of the trial only made it more likely that he will deliver his
speech as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   They view the speech as a critical demonstration that the
government's business continues.
</P>
<P>
   The government's other branches might be reluctant to cheer
Clinton's view of a vibrant, healthy America after a year dominated
by sex talk and perjury charges. But would even the most
obstreperous opponents jeer the president of the United States?
</P>
<P>
   The conservative National Review editorialized last week that
Clinton should speak and that Congress should ``listen
courteously,'' giving the respect due the office. (It added that it
should later dispatch him to private life.)
</P>
<P>
   Along with the majesty of his office, Clinton has his own
political appeal to fall back on. As the president, in the camera's
tight focus, talks about his plans for education and health care,
the viewer is more likely to be impressed with him than with some
unseen member of congressman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else shows up,'' said a senior Clinton aide, ``but
when you look at it, the president is center stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does not have to give the speech at all. The
Constitution says nothing about an annual State of the Union
speech. It requires only that the president ``from time to time''
give Congress ``information of the State of the Union'' and policy
recommendations. From Jefferson until Wilson, presidents contented
themselves with annual, written reports.
</P>
<P>
   And an unspoken State of the Union would probably not
irreparably sadden the citizenry or enfeeble the Republic. Franklin
D. Roosevelt enunciated the Four Freedoms in his 1941 address.
Ronald Reagan added the dramatic touch of singling out heroes in
the gallery. But let's face it: There have not been many memorable
State of the Union speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can think of phrases from inaugurals or departure
speeches,'' said Todd Gitlin, professor of culture, journalism and
sociology at New York University. ``Can anyone remember a phrase
from a Reagan State of the Union or a Kennedy one? I can't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Clinton loves to give this speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the State of the Union is probably Bill Clinton's
favorite day of the year,'' said Paul Begala, the White House
counselor. ``It's the complete coalescence of politics and policy
and communications and one-on-one hand-clasping with members in the
aisles and leading the nation. It's everything.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be little doubt of Clinton's ability to give a
coherent, resolutely high-minded speech that addresses his
predicament obliquely, if at all. Last year, he delivered a smooth
State of the Union Message just six days into the furor over Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   More than other modern presidents, Clinton has used the State of
the Union to annually rewind the mainspring of his administration.
In the months leading up to his address, his top aides meet to plan
the programs he will announce in the speech. Those programs become
the framework for Clinton's entire year.
</P>
<P>
   It was a demonstration of the doggedness of this White House
strategy that meetings to plan the State of the Union were held the
same Saturday last month that Clinton was impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can define a lot of the history of the Clinton presidency
from his State of the Union addresses,'' said William E.
Leuchtenburg, a professor of history at the University of North
Carolina. He argues that Clinton has been given too little credit
on foreign policy and too much for the often small-bore domestic
initiatives that tend to stock his State of the Union messages.
</P>
<P>
   Using the speech to set an agenda is in itself an expansion of
presidential power that has reversed the intended dynamic of the
message. ``It was not an assertion of presidential authority,''
said Garry Wills, adjunct professor of history at Northwestern
University. ``The whole point was that Congress as the boss, the
legislator, is asking the subordinate who executes the laws,
`How're ya doin'?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But now, because of both its content and the surrounding
pageantry, the speech suggests the primacy of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The address also gives Clinton his best annual opportunity to
reach over the heads of Congress to tell Americans of his plans,
which are poll tested for approval. That's why Lyndon Johnson moved
the speech from mid-day to the evening, when the television
audience was larger.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows how Congress will respond? The speech could soften
members toward him. Wilson, in reviving the custom of appearing
before Congress, said he wanted to demonstrate that the president
``is a person'' and a ``human being trying to cooperate with other
human beings in a common service.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1058EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-STATEOFUNION-     01-09 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-STATEOFUNION-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
THE SPEECH, THE TRIAL AND THE STATE OF THE POLITICS  (The Week in
Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
