<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NY     01-09 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE NBA IS ALL ABOUT SPINNING  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's going to be tougher now. Rooting for local teams or
resenting individual players is no longer smart enough. Now that
political-style spin has engaged the arena, the National Basketball
Association spectator has to bring to the court an attitude worthy
of the disinfomercials that have emerged since the lockout ended.
``Love that game'' is a peeling bumper sticker.
</P>
<P>
   How will you greet the new season? As a rebirth after a racial
Armageddon, a labor-management fiasco, a triumph of small over
tall, a mockery of working-class values, a brilliant plan to bring
us more quickly to the playoffs? It really doesn't matter what you
choose, so long as you don't just sit there and moan when they
dunk. Find an angle. You'll win with a spin.
</P>
<P>
   Real fans can read the players' collapse in the signs in other
sports. The Jets' surge was credited to Bill Parcells' friendly
fascism; obviously, players need to be manipulated and ordered.
Then there is the widening scandal of the International Olympic
Committee; obviously, the real sport in sport is business, and you
can't beat the bosses at that.
</P>
<P>
   Most significantly, Yogi Berra finally rolled over for George
Steinbrenner. It was the sensible thing to do. First of all, Yogi
needed publicity for his new museum. More important, as men age,
there are few tighter bonds than those between old enemies. Who
knows you so well, has thought about you as often and as deeply?
Yogi and George, after all, are cartoon figures in the minds of
almost everyone but themselves. Yogi's refusal to set foot in the
Stadium while George was the owner was noble, and still is,
although it became stupid. Nobody cares anymore that Yogi was
crudely fired as Yankee manager. Since then, almost everyone in
America has been crudely fired, in one way or another. Yogi is not
stupid. George came to New Jersey last week. Yogi will go to the
Bronx next season. All will be right with that world.
</P>
<P>
   As one who admired Walt Frazier, Kareem Abdul-Jabbar and Isiah
Thomas above all others, the sight of Patrick Ewing, clogging the
Knicks' heart and fronting the players' association, was
disheartening. It was too easy for me to believe that he was a
puppet of David Falk, as he was once a puppet of the recently
resigned Georgetown coach, John Thompson. Actually, I do not
necessarily believe this, but I am not privy to accurate basketball
rumors, much less the truth, so I will enjoy the self-interested
takes on this past nonplaying season, including the following:
</P>
<P>
   1. It was just a battle between soft little white guys, David
Stern and David Falk, who couldn't make the varsity cut in high
school. The commissioner who created the modern sport and the super
agent who represented an aging corps of super players went
man-to-man for control of the game. This is an alluring spin for
most fans, who are soft little white guys. No matter which David
won, we won, too.
</P>
<P>
   2. The league won big. By dragging the players back on court
without ceding to their major demands, the NBA stuffed the greed
genie back in the bottle and capped it, giving inspiration to all
the beleaguered conglomerates struggling with ungrateful workers.
Most media outlets, owned by conglomerates and staffed by ingrates,
support this spin.
</P>
<P>
   3. The players really won. By delaying the season, making
reasonable demands (the Smith College economist and players union
consultant, Andrew Zimbalist, was best on this) and showing
themselves as a diverse group, in class, intelligence and financial
need, they transcended the living animated figures marketed by the
NBA and became people. Also, they were the ones who saved the
season.
</P>
<P>
   4. TV won. The length of the regular NBA season and the need to
carry it has always bothered television and advertising (same
thing) executives who have always preferred to cut to the chase,
where the audience and the rates are. Now, a truncated season will
feel as if it has the urgency of playoff time.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. The fans won. The idea of a backlash, that Joe Sixpack,
whoever the suits think that is, will not come back because he is
hurt, disgusted or discovered the Monet exhibit while the Celtics
were dark, is not only silly. It is also enormously pleasing to
Joe, his investment banker and his antique book dealer, because
they think there will be concessions. The game will find new ways
to entertain him, give him free trinkets for showing up, make his
seat warm.
</P>
<P>
   6. The gasbags won. Everyone with access to ink, air time or
cyberspace will have a chance to pontificate at length about the
meaning of all this until it is time to watch games, at which time
we will pontificate on the effect of all this on dunking, before we
go back to our real jobs, which is uncovering the love-that-game
billionaire owner who was raised in a log cabin without cable and
the power forward who manages to keep focus despite five criminal
indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Love that spin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
