<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5941 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CAPITAL-REVI     01-09 0603
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAPITAL-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURING FLOOR SPACE AND CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never in the history of modern business has there been a class
of companies that has spiraled so high, so fast and with so little
regard for convention as the Internet companies whose market values
have astonished Wall Street in recent months and caused even more
surprise last week.
</P>
<P>
   Some have shown profits, but many haven't. Some rent space in
office parks or old warehouses. They have relatively few employees,
no manufacturing plants and little inventory.
</P>
<P>
   By almost every traditional way of measuring a company's worth,
they don't add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that we live in a world where Wall Street can't explain
why these stocks are going up and where pundits can't explain why
Clinton is so popular,'' said Mark Pincus, the 32-year-old
president of Tioga Systems, a software company in Palo Alto,
Calif., who sold his Internet company, Freeloader, for $38 million
a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, the old world of building a lot of facilities is
going nowhere,'' Pincus said, ``while the value of doing things
that are idea-based on the Web is going up exponentially.''
</P>
<P>
   Under this theory of business, physical assets are liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's atoms you're trying to minimize,'' said Bill Gross, the
president of Idealab, a Pasadena, Calif., company that helps
Internet startups. ``The more neurons you have per dollar the
better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a ``zero-gravity'' view of commerce in which ``you don't
want molecules,'' he said. ``Knowledge moves at the speed of light;
molecules move at 600 miles per hour with Fed Ex.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts have a less exotic explanation for the
surge in interest in Internet businesses: the potential for
tremendous growth.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, there were about 5 million Internet users, but the
number is expected to rise to 115 million by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for this latest run is growth,'' said Larry
Wachtel, a market analyst for Prudential Securities. ``And Wall
Street loves growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com would be a textbook example of the new Internet
businesses, if a textbook existed. It was founded almost four years
ago by Todd Wagner and Mark Cuban, old college friends who were
then in their mid-30s. When it went public last year, it had one of
the fastest opening-day sprints in Wall Street history, rising
nearly 250 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company broadcasts live speeches, conferences, television
events and even professional wrestling over the Internet. It has
250 employees who work out of an old warehouse in Dallas that it
rents for $4,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, almost inexplicably, shares of Broadcast.com rose 50
percent and the company ended the day with a value of $3.4 billion,
more than the value of Wendy's International, which has 150,000
employees and 5,391 restaurants around the country.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. FOLLOWING SENTENCE SHOULD BE USED IF
</ANNOTATION>
GRAPHIC IS BEING USED.)
<P>
   Following is a comparison of Internet companies and more
traditional businesses with similar market values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1103EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5329 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CAPITAL-REVI     01-09 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CAPITAL-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEASURING FLOOR SPACE AND CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
