GRAPHIC IS BEING USED.)
<P>
   Following is a comparison of Internet companies and more
traditional businesses with similar market values.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5943 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-LIDDY-REVIEW-     01-09 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-LIDDY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO LOVE, HONOR AND RUN FOR HIGHER OFFICE
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It may be the ultimate slap at the boys in suits
who have long dominated U.S. politics: the hottest electoral
commodities, as of last week at least, are best known for the men
they married, and their last tries for elective office were in
student government.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hanford Dole commanded international attention when
she announced she was resigning as president of the American Red
Cross to ponder going after the Republican presidential nomination
next year. Hillary Rodham Clinton did not announce anything, and
there is no evidence that she will. But that has not tamped down a
persistent buzz in New York political circles _ one stoked happily
by the press _ that she might dive into the Democratic race to
succeed Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The boomlets for Mrs. Dole and Mrs. Clinton, both of whom were
at the top of Gallup Poll's survey of most admired women of 1998
(Mrs. Clinton placed first, followed by Oprah Winfrey and Mrs.
Dole), are surprising. Both women have formidable professional
accomplishments but are nonetheless most famous because of their
husbands. Mrs. Dole even overtook the early favorite, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, in a poll last week of Republican primary voters in
New Hampshire. (That may reflect little more than her name
recognition and the initial excitement over her announcement.)
</P>
<P>
   The enormous interest comes despite _ or maybe because of _ the
fact that their husbands have seen better days: President Clinton
faces an impeachment trial; former Sen. Bob Dole led his party to a
devastating defeat by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But their unusual circumstances have given both women rare
political appeal: While some ambitious, bright women threaten
voters, particularly men, Mrs. Clinton and Mrs. Dole ease such
qualms because they are also viewed as loyal, traditional wives.
</P>
<P>
   Besides enduring the cascade of revelations about her husband's
affairs, Mrs. Clinton aggressively defended him. And Mrs. Dole did
for her husband at the 1996 Republican convention what he could not
do for himself: She waded into the audience and tried to rescue his
candidacy by articulating a passionate case for his election.
</P>
<P>
   The positive reaction may be the latest example of voters who _
after the yearlong Lewinsky drama _ have lost confidence in the
political structure and see women as representing different values.
That happened in 1992, when voters elected four women to the Senate
in part out of bitterness over the Clarence Thomas hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``These women are not Jesse Ventura,'' said Rachel Gorlin, a
Democratic strategist, referring to the professional wrestler who
was elected governor of Minnesota in November. ``They are very
tested. They are very established. But they are kind of a hybrid:
they represent values that are not the traditional back-room guy
chomping the cigar but are not completely outside of the political
process.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Clinton and Mrs. Dole are devout Methodists who are
admired for their devotion to the church. Yet they are also driven,
Ivy League-trained lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In both cases, you're talking about women who rose
professionally because of who they were married to,'' said Ralph
Reed, a Republican strategist. ``In Elizabeth's case, when she was
named a Cabinet secretary, it didn't hurt that she was married to a
vice presidential candidate and a powerful senator. But what makes
these women figures of sympathy and desirable on a political level
is the perception that they are better politicians than their
husbands.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Mrs. Clinton, at 51, is 11 years younger than Mrs. Dole,
she has forged a more traditional path. She followed Clinton to
Little Rock, where they reared their daughter. By contrast, Mrs.
Dole did not have children and by the time she married late in
life, she was nearly a decade into her climb up the governmental
ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole and Mrs. Clinton do not necessarily signal any trend
because they are not ordinary politicians. Although Democrats enjoy
an advantage over Republicans in wooing female voters, women do not
reflexively flock to the polls to vote for women.
</P>
<P>
   For example, former Rep. Geraldine Ferraro, who made history as
the Democratic vice presidential nominee in 1984, did not do
particularly well among Democratic women last year when she lost
her party's nomination for U.S. senator from New York after a
lackluster campaign. And New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, a
Republican, drew fewer votes from women than did her male opponents
in 1997 and 1993. ``Christie Whitman's biggest problem is getting
women to vote for her,'' said Mike Murphy, an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mrs. Dole and Mrs. Clinton have emerged as possible
potent antidotes to what ails their parties: Mrs. Clinton had
reignited the fears people have of liberal Democrats by championing
national health care, and because of the perception that she would
be a co-president. But her image as a compassionate figure who was
wronged by her husband has quieted those misgivings.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, increasingly, have suffered a reputation as being
dominated by males who are not interested in issues like education
and health care. Mrs. Dole is in a position to neutralize that
perception, and she would stand out in the sea of men seeking the
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Yet timing is a factor: Before Ferraro's vice presidential
candidacy, most people probably would not have dared to advance a
Clinton or Dole candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see either Elizabeth Dole or Hillary Clinton springing
out of the head of Zeus,'' said Ruth Mandel, a political scientist
at Rutgers University. ``They emerged out of the last quarter of
the 20th century from a culture which makes it possible for people
to consider women as potential presidential candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   The danger is that if they began running in earnest, their
prominence might magnify any blunders they make. And they could not
expect to be embraced automatically by women. Referring to Mrs.
Dole's opposition to abortion, Murphy said, ``The pro-choice women
will turn on her.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be why it is far from assured that the names Dole and
Clinton will adorn bumper stickers again. Yet there is no question
that both women are drawn to political power. After starting a book
club in junior high school, Mrs. Dole writes, she took matters into
her own hands: ``I simply declared myself president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1107EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5336 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-LIDDY-REVIEW-     01-09 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-LIDDY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
