<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      01-09 1520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Jan. 10:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-UNBURDEN (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Countless
`unburdenings' are taking place among Cambodians today as the
country seems to be embarking, spontaneously, on a long-delayed
national conversation about its traumatic past. Interviews with a
score of people here and in Battambang, the country's
second-largest city _ from market vendors to professors _ suggest
that a common legacy of anger and pain is being shared in a way
that has not been evident in recent years. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CUBA-U.S. (Havana) _ A high-ranking Cuban official has denounced
President Clinton's proposal to ease some restrictions on the
United States' embargo of this communist-run island, calling them a
``deceptive maneuver'' intended to deflect growing opposition
around the world to the embargo. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   KAZAKH-CAPITAL (Astana, Kazakhstan) _ When President Nursultan
Nazarbayev unveiled his plans for this city of 300,000 people on
the Siberian steppe, he stubbornly rejected objections that the
move from the old capital of Almaty was unnecessary, unpopular and,
considering the cost in an oil-rich but still cash-poor nation,
even imprudent. On Sunday, the autocratic Nazarbayev is seeking
re-election to a new seven-year term; he is expected to win easily.
But the prognosis for his dreamchild, Kazakhstan's new capital, is
in doubt. By Steve LeVine.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-AXWORTHY (Toronto) _ As a graduate student at Princeton
University in the 1960s, Lloyd Axworthy spent many nights at the
old Madison Square Garden watching greats like Dave DeBusschere,
Walt Frazier and Bill Bradley outplay almost everyone in the
league. It did not help his studies, Axworthy concedes, but the New
York Knicks' approach to basketball did help him develop a game
plan that has made him the most successful Canadian foreign
minister in years, and also the one who has most antagonized
Washington. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-ANIMALRIGHTS (Oxford, England) _ Colin Blakemore,
Wayneflete Professor of Physiology at Oxford and director of the
university's Center for Cognitive Neuroscience, spends his days
like any academic, in an office with brimming in-trays and
bookshelves stacked high with research volumes. His work has won
him awards for advances in treating vision problems in infants and
young children. But it has also attracted the attention of a
violence-prone movement that says it wants to kill him because his
research depends on animal testing. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-HOLIDAYS (Moscow) _ In Russia, long holidays are a handy
excuse for not paying salaries for work that is not being done _ a
familiar practice in post-communist Russia even in the nonholiday
season. But there were stores, and offices _ all of them private _
that defied the Christmas holidays, because they could not afford
to stay shut for so long. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-POLITICS (Istanbul, Turkey) _ Turkey may soon have a
functioning government after six weeks without one, but its
new-found assertiveness in foreign policy is likely to continue no
matter who emerges as the next Prime Minister. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w' code)
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The Senate's agreement on how to
conduct the initial phase of President Clinton's impeachment trial
sent House prosecutors and the President's lawyers diving this
weekend back into the voluminous evidence collected by the
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. In the 7,000 pages of grand jury
testimony and boxes of supplementary evidence, Rep. Henry Hyde, the
leader of the House prosecution team, sees a clear and convincing
picture of perjury and obstruction of justice so grave that Clinton
should be removed from office. From that same pile of evidence, the
president's legal team is putting together a more aggressive
defense than the one they presented unsuccessfully to the House _
one they now say should lead to the president's exoneration. The
White House agreed to stipulate to the record amassed by the
independent counsel, although the president's lawyers profoundly
disagree with Starr and Hyde about what the evidence shows. By Jill
Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HYDE (Washington) _ When Clinton was impeached it was in
no small measure as a result of Rep. Henry Hyde's determination to
press forward even after Republican losses in the November
elections. Hyde is now throwing himself wholeheartedly into his new
role as Clinton's chief prosecutor in the Senate. Rep. David Dreier
of California, one of his closest friends on the Hill, said Hyde's
attitude was: ``If you're going to catch hell no matter what you
do, you might as well do what's right.'' By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Some now-familiar faces will be
presenting some now-familiar arguments on the Senate floor to
defend President Clinton as he goes on trial this week. Though
White House aides say they are still mapping out their strategy,
the core of the defense team and of its case are settled. The team
is to be led by Charles F.C. Ruff, the former Watergate special
prosecutor who is Clinton's fifth White House counsel. By James
Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-WINDFALL (Undated) _ As state legislatures nationwide
start new sessions, lawmakers are beginning to debate how to spend
their biggest windfall in recent years: tens of billions of dollars
from tobacco settlement deals. While some elected officials are
calling for the money to be spent on health care initiatives and
anti-smoking campaigns, others are urging that it be used on
projects unrelated to tobacco, including new schools or jails, and
even sidewalk repair. Still other lawmakers say the tobacco
windfall should be used to eliminate state debts or be given to
taxpayers as rebates. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   TEAMSTERS (Undated) _ Thomas R. O'Donnell, a newly elected vice
president-at-large of the teamsters, is in the infelicitous
position of obtaining the second largest vote total in last month's
union election _ only the new president, James P. Hoffa, received
more _ yet facing possible expulsion from the union. By Steven
Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   PAROLE-DEBATE (Undated) _ Fifteen states so far have taken the
politically popular step of abolishing parole boards, a vestige of
what most Americans regard as a failed system of penal
rehabilitation, and last week Gov. George Pataki of New York
proposed to make his state the 16th. But based on the experience of
the other states, there is no proof that eliminating parole boards
reduces crime, while it can lead to a further increase in the
already swelling prison population, criminologists and other
experts say. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   ASTRONOMY-NEWPLANETS (Austin, Texas) _ In a stunning run of
discoveries over the last three years, astronomers have observed 17
nearby stars that appear to be orbited by planets more or less the
size of Jupiter. But while astronomers continue the search for more
such objects, they have now seen enough to be puzzled by an
emerging pattern: None of these extrasolar planetary systems seems
to resemble the Sun's family of planets. Is this an observational
fluke? Or is the solar system a cosmic oddball? By John Noble
Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   DOCS-REBEL (New York) _ While 92 percent of doctors in New York
state accepted managed care last year, it seems a small rebellion
is on. Fed up with years of acrimonious relationships with
managed-care companies, doctors, particularly those serving upper
middle class patients, are quietly starting to fight back. Many are
dropping plans that have the lowest reimbursement rates, biggest
administrative headaches or represent the fewest number of their
patients. Others are washing their hands of the carriers, forcing
patients to pay up front and file claims the old-fashioned way, or
pay the fees themselves. By Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Herbert and Maureen Dowd (both have moved).
</P>
