<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5947 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-UCONN-LADYVOLS-NY     01-09 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-LADYVOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVYWEIGHTS OF WOMEN'S COLLEGE BASKETBALL SQUARE OFF  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CAVANAUGH    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To provide his starters with tougher competition, Geno Auriemma,
the women's coach at Connecticut, sent two assistants in search of
male practice players on the Storrs campus a few years ago. But
with 11 players capable of starting for most teams in the Big East,
Auriemma must no longer find men to practice against his front
liners.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, several players on the top-ranked and undefeated UConn
women's team, which meets No. 2 Tennessee in a showdown at Gampel
Pavilion Sunday afternoon, have said their toughest competition to
date has come from one another during practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Through its first 13 games, Connecticut has surpassed 100 points
nine times while beating its opponents by an average of 40 points.
``We do score pretty easily at times,'' Auriemma said after the
Huskies trounced Pittsburgh, 106-52, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They are unlikely to score so easily against Tennessee, which
has lost only once in 13 games _ to Purdue on Nov. 15 _ and has won
three consecutive national championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols have also won three of their last four games
against UConn, including a 15-point victory last January before a
crowd of 24,597 in Knoxville. Tennessee also knocked off the
Huskies in both the 1996 Final Four and the 1997 Midwest Regionals.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tennessee has lost both times it has played in
Connecticut _ at Storrs in 1995 and at Hartford in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to downplay the significance of Sunday's game, Auriemma
said: ``I realize that for a lot of people the world will come to
an end around 7 o'clock Sunday night when we will either have won
the national championship or wrapped up second place. It's like the
season ends on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not, of course, but the game could be a portent for this
season's Final Four. The outcome, no doubt, will instill confidence
in the victor and a certain doubt in the loser.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's depth could be decisive Sunday. Eight players are
averaging at least 17 minutes of play, including the sophomore Shea
Ralph, who has averaged 22 minutes though she has not started a
game since returning from a knee injury that caused her to miss all
of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Her playing time is second only to Amy Duran, the team captain
and lone senior on the starting five, who has played 23 minutes a
game. Reflecting the Huskies' balance, five players are averaging
in double figures _ Abrosimova (17.5 points), Ralph (16.7), and
three freshmen, Tamika Williams (12.4), Swin Cash (12) and Asjha
Jones (10.2). Cash, who is coming back from a stress fracture in
her right foot that kept her out of two games and limited her to
only seven minutes in the most recent game, is expected to see
significant playing time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee counters Connecticut's depth with its three ``Meeks''
_ the incomparable senior Chamique Holdsclaw from Queens, N.Y., and
the sophomores Tamika Catchings and Semeka Randall. They each were
chosen as preseason all-Americans and they average 20, 15 and 13
points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
