<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5948 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ANCHORS-BOOKS-REVI     01-09 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ANCHORS-BOOKS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TV NEWS, AN EPIDEMIC OF PENCIL ENVY 
</HEADLINE>
 (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   They have a weighty title _ anchor _ but an evanescent legacy.
Their faces are etched into the public eye by weightless electrons
30 times a second, but after 1,800 seconds, the music swells, the
screen changes to ``Jeopardy'' and they are gone until the next
evening, the next bulletin, the next interruption of that regularly
scheduled program.
</P>
<P>
   But where there is ink, there is permanence, and it is not
difficult to understand why the nation's television news anchors
are increasingly drawn across the boundary between media to the
solid ground of books on paper. Both Tom Brokaw of NBC and Peter
Jennings of ABC have books on the best-seller list (in fact, they
are currently numbers 1 and 2, respectively, on The New York Times
nonfiction list), and Dan Rather of CBS, who has written or edited
five books, has two more scheduled to come out in the next year or
so.
</P>
<P>
   The anchors are not shy about acknowledging their envy for the
one comfort of writers everywhere: the constancy of the written
word, the lasting victory of the printed page over videotape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're always frustrated by the abbreviated form we have,''
said Brokaw, author of ``The Greatest Generation'' (Random House),
a 352-page account of the World War II years. ``You spend a day on
a distinguished piece of work, and as the joke goes, it all goes
out to Venus at the end of the day. But after the book came out, I
had dinner with Jim Lehrer, who said to me, `Brokaw, you know, your
great-grandchildren won't see you on TV, but they'll read this
book.' '' (Lehrer, of the PBS NewsHour, has written 11 books.)
</P>
<P>
   Most older television journalists got their start in print and
never really lost the sense that it is first among equals as a
communications medium, the classic sense of pencil envy that
Jennings says is rapidly disappearing among younger workers who
came straight to video, as he did. Rather unabashedly admits that
over a late-night glass of wine, there is nothing quite so
satisfying as seeing one's name on the spine of a hard-cover book
on a well-populated shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound corny, but I like the writer's life, the way a
book looks and feels,'' he said. ``When you're thinking about your
life's dreams and trying to get past the ephemeral, writing a book
provides a unique satisfaction.'' Rather is completing a collection
of essays, ``Deadlines and Datelines,'' for publication by Morrow
this spring, and is working on a documentary film for PBS about his
native Texas that will also be spun off into a book.
</P>
<P>
   But even beyond the physical pleasure and vague sense of
immortality, there is also a sense that books confer a legitimacy
on a profession often derided for its absence of seriousness. ``All
these guys think of themselves primarily as journalists, and they
want to be recognized as more than just television personalities,''
said Peter Osnos, the publisher of Public Affairs books, who has
helped transform Sam Donaldson, Morley Safer, Ted Koppel and others
into authors. ``They don't need to cash in, but they like having
people acknowledge them as writers.''
</P>
<P>
   That may explain why their topics are so sweeping: centuries,
generations, epochs instead of the seconds usually used to measure
their work. Even Rather edited a book on the early years of the
20th Century.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings' book, written with Todd Brewster, was called ``The
Century'' (Doubleday). ``It was hard, because I'm used to writing
for sound,'' Jennings said. ``But the material was so broad it was
inescapable. The calendar told us to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1125EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0066 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
