<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-JAGUARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDAMENTAL ISSUES FOR THE JETS: WHO WILL RUN? WHO WILL STOP IT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to Bryan Cox, time bomb turned team spokesman, to break
down the essence of Sunday's Jets-Jacksonville Jaguars playoff
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know our guys will score some points,'' Cox, the linebacker
coerced out of retirement to become a Jet, said in the team's
locker room after a spirited Friday practice in the snow. ``Will
our defense make sure those points are enough?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe what all this comes down to is this: Who's still running
the ball at the end like they want to, and who's had to give up and
throw and throw and throw?''
</P>
<P>
   There are many variables in Sunday's game at Giants Stadium,
from the weather and the wind at game time to the health of
Jacksonville quarterback Mark Brunell's sore left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have a quarterback, Vinny Testaverde, whose last
playoff experience was four years ago, and that game ended with
Testaverde on the wrong end of a 20-point defeat. The Jets also
have an unpredictable kicker in John Hall while the Jaguars have
Mike Hollis, the most accurate place-kicker in National Football
League history.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, the matchup within the matchups that may matter most
could be: Which team can enforce its will on the ground?
</P>
<P>
   With the fourth-best offense in the league, the Jets have been
committed to a balanced attack, but the passing game has been
predicated on play-action passes made effective by a power running
game. And Jets Coach Bill Parcells has proven this season that he
will not abandon the running game, regardless of lackluster early
results.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Martin rushed 369 times in 1998, the third-highest number
of carries in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jacksonville's defense ranked 25th among the 30 teams,
there is general belief that the Jets will be able to move the ball
on the ground and eventually through the air. It follows that
Jacksonville's best shot at victory is a high-scoring game.
</P>
<P>
   The key, therefore, could be how the Jets' linebackers fare
against Fred Taylor, Jacksonville's rookie running back, and how
well Cox can contain the scrambling of Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who has averaged 112.5 rushing yards in his last five
starts, goes against a Jets team that has not allowed a 100-yard
rusher in its last 10 games. Taylor is fresh off a 162-yard rushing
performance in the Jaguars' first-round victory over the New
England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Brunell has reportedly exhibited no ill effects of the ankle
problem that kept him out of three games at the end of the regular
season. If he is healthy enough to bolt the pocket and run, the
Jets may have their hands full.
</P>
<P>
   In the Jaguars' playoff push to the verge of the 1997 Super
Bowl, Brunell rushed for 78 yards in two post-season games. Perhaps
significantly, when the Denver Broncos routed Jacksonville in the
first playoff round last season, Brunell rushed three times for
just four yards.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Bill Belichick, the Jets' defensive
coordinator, to devise a scheme that stops the explosive Taylor
while keeping an eye on the clever Brunell _ not mention the
two-time Pro Bowl wide receiver Jimmy Smith and his sidekick Keenan
McCardell, a former Pro Bowler who has caught six passes in each of
his last three playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big assignment,'' Parcells said Friday. ``Taylor can be
relentless, but like us, Jacksonville isn't totally reliant on one
dimension, which is why both teams are still playing this time of
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox has respect for Taylor and Brunell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taylor's probably the league m.v.p. if not for Randy Moss,''
Cox said. ``Like they say, Brunell can be the next Steve Young. You
can't let him roam. Historically, at playoff time, running the
football is how you win. Stopping the run is how you win.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows why he has thrust Cox into the role of run
stopper _ as well as named him the probable defensive ``spy'' who
will shadow Brunell all over the field Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brings explosive hitting ability,'' Parcells said of Cox.
``This guy has been running the defense, he can take on blockers,
he's not afraid to battle, he's not afraid to play one-on-one
football, and he never resorts to finesse.''
</P>
<P>
   Think Parcells is happy he made that July 31 call to Cox,
convincing him to come out of retirement?
</P>
<P>
   Cox knows he's happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think I'd feel like this again,'' he said. ``I didn't
know if football would ever be worth it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The role Cox and his fellow linebackers Mo Lewis and Pepper
Johnson play against the run may be especially significant because
of the work of Jacksonville's talented offensive tackles, Tony
Boselli and Leon Searcy. If that duo can control the line of
scrimmage, the Jets' linebackers will have to fill the gaps and
anticipate Taylor's cutback moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a gutsy bunch, but we're smart as a defense,'' Lewis
said. ``There's some kind of problem in almost every game, but we
go to the sideline and talk it over with Belichick. We adjust very
well. I'm sure there will be adjustments we'll have to make
again.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, as Cox has predicted, it's likely that one team
will still be running the football while the other is forced to
play catch-up through the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different time of the year now and the spirit of the
game is usually higher,'' Parcells said. ``Players get nervous,
their moods change. Emotions are going to be high. And at times
like those, I tell our people we have to rely on fundamental
techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust the fundamentals.''
</P>
<P>
   And nothing in football is more fundamental than establishing
the run and stopping the run. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
