   &UR; Off-lead: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-EVIDENCE (Washington) _ The Senate's agreement on how to
conduct the initial phase of President Clinton's impeachment trial
sent House prosecutors and the President's lawyers diving this
weekend back into the voluminous evidence collected by the
independent counsel Kenneth Starr. In the 7,000 pages of grand jury
testimony and boxes of supplementary evidence, Rep. Henry Hyde, the
leader of the House prosecution team, sees a clear and convincing
picture of perjury and obstruction of justice so grave that Clinton
should be removed from office. From that same pile of evidence, the
president's legal team is putting together a more aggressive
defense than the one they presented unsuccessfully to the House _
one they now say should lead to the president's exoneration. The
White House agreed to stipulate to the record amassed by the
independent counsel, although the president's lawyers profoundly
disagree with Starr and Hyde about what the evidence shows. By Jill
Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 1 p.m. ET in `w' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   2-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOLD: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-UNBURDEN (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ Countless
`unburdenings' are taking place among Cambodians today as the
country seems to be embarking, spontaneously, on a long-delayed
national conversation about its traumatic past. Interviews with a
score of people here and in Battambang, the country's
second-largest city _ from market vendors to professors _ suggest
that a common legacy of anger and pain is being shared in a way
that has not been evident in recent years. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 12 noon ET in `i' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   3-column hed.
</P>
<P>
   IMPEACH-HYDE (Washington) _ When Clinton was impeached it was in
no small measure as a result of Rep. Henry Hyde's determination to
press forward even after Republican losses in the November
elections. Hyde is now throwing himself wholeheartedly into his new
role as Clinton's chief prosecutor in the Senate. Rep. David Dreier
of California, one of his closest friends on the Hill, said Hyde's
attitude was: ``If you're going to catch hell no matter what you
do, you might as well do what's right.'' By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move this story by 12 noon ET in `w' news file.)
