<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE `DON'T DO' LIST
</P>
<P>
   Paul Quantrill, a Toronto pitcher, broke his right leg last week
driving a snowmobile. Thinking it would not sound as bad, he
initially said he had an accident on a toboggan. Neither pursuit is
barred in Quantrill's contract.
</P>
<P>
   However, the uniform player's contract has a paragraph, 5(b),
that prohibits players from engaging in other sports. Professional
boxing and wrestling are barred outright. The provision then lists
a series of sports that the player cannot play except with his
team's written consent: skiing, auto racing, motorcycle racing, sky
diving or any game or exhibition of football, soccer, professional
league basketball, ice hockey or other sports ``involving a
substantial risk of personal injury.'' At times a club, with the
player's assent, will add other specific sports to the list.
</P>
<P>
   THE TAX THAT DIDN'T WORK
</P>
<P>
   While the overwhelming consensus is that the National Basketball
Association owners got much the better of their labor agreement
with the players, the baseball owners have to continue to wonder
what they have to do to win one. They certainly didn't win the
234-day players strike in 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   If they didn't know it before, the owners, with the computation
of the 1998 luxury tax on the five highest payrolls, have to
realize they have been hornswoggled.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury tax was intended to inhibit mammoth payrolls. The
idea was the owners would not want to pay hefty taxes on top of a
large payroll. But all it takes is six large payrolls, and the
threshold that triggers the 35 percent tax becomes so high that it
keeps the taxes low.
</P>
<P>
   The threshold is the average between the fifth- and
sixth-highest payrolls, meaning the figure for 1998 was $70.5
million. The basic agreement, written two years ago, projected the
threshold as $55 million. The projected trigger level for 1999 is
$58.9 million, but it will be at least $75.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   What does the tax mean for 1998? The Baltimore Orioles, who,
under the formula for determining payrolls for luxury tax purposes,
had the No. 1 payroll, $79.5 million, will have to pay $3,138,621
as their tax. That's not much more than utility infielders make
these days.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Red Sox, at $2,184,734, have to pay the only other
tax that exceeds $685,000. The others: Yankees, $684,390; the
Braves, $495,625; the Dodgers, $49,593. Conclusion: The luxury tax,
which this year drops to 34 percent, has not been and never will be
a payroll deterrent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
