<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD MAKES IT HARD TO GET THE FEAST  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By NELSON BRYANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST TISBURY, Mass. _ For the past few years, bagging a brace of
ducks for a celebratory Christmas dinner and another pair for a New
Year's Day repast has been difficult for me on the island of
Martha's Vineyard, but this year it was different.
</P>
<P>
   It was different because in 1998 the weather turned around. Fall
and early winter were unusually mild, and it seemed as if a repeat
of the previous seasons was on its way, but in late December high
winds, cold and snow swept across New England with regularity. In
mild weather, so-called puddle ducks _ among them blacks, mallards,
teal and pintails _ tend to remain on broad expanses of open water,
safe from hunters' guns.
</P>
<P>
   Wind and ice get ducks moving; small ponds freeze, forcing them
to seek open water in lakes and salt ponds. If a fierce storm is
under way, they tend to lose their usual caution and instead of
carefully surveying a nimrod's spread of decoys from on high, they
come streaming in low over the water and often settle among the
bogus birds without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, a limit to the conditions under which ducks
choose to fly. More than 50 years ago, I went to my waterfowling
blind during a blizzard, and, enjoying the storm, remained in it
until after dark. Walking home across a plowed field, I suddenly
became aware of movement all about me. The field, raw frozen earth
covered with new snow, was alive with black ducks. Some took wing;
others simply scuttled away. They had been driven to earth by the
wind and swirling snow, less than a half mile from the sanctuary of
the swamp and salt pond where I had been waiting for them in vain.
</P>
<P>
   Until late in the just-ended duck season (Nov. 16-Jan. 9) in
coastal Massachusetts, there were few migratory birds from up north
on hand. The fall and early winter had been too mild. All the ducks
my son Jeff and I shot in several outings were mallards, and most
were resident birds. The crops of many of them were packed with
cracked corn that they had gobbled up while visiting various
private and public freshwater ponds where such handouts have become
a ritual on the Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   We shot six mallards on our Christmas Day dinner hunt and three
on the New Year's Day excursion. On the latter sortie, we would
have done better were it not for my ineptitude and bouts of
nostalgia. We had split up, Jeff going to the open marsh in Town
Cove on Tisbury Great Pond, I in a blind at the point where Mill
Brook enters the cove.
</P>
<P>
   Walking down the brook to the blind, past the cavern created by
the twisted roots of a still-living willow that had been blown over
in a hurricane decades before, I got to within 10 feet of a hen
mallard that was dozing on the shore. We saw each other at the same
instant. She sprang vertically into the air, while I _ deep in a
recollection of the time more than 65 years ago when I had caught
my first brook trout from the pool at my feet _ forgot that I was
hunting and watched her depart. Three seconds or more elapsed
before my shotgun was at my shoulder, and by then it was too late
to fire.
</P>
<P>
   Resolving to concentrate on my quest, I reached my wind-buffeted
blind, put out a few decoys and sat awaiting the arrival of
shelter-seeking ducks. The wind was out of the northwest, gusting
to 50 miles an hour, and the temperature, which was falling, was
about 15 degrees. I saw no ducks the first 30 minutes but was
visited by two curious catbirds that appeared to be eating the
bright red fruits of winterberries on the edge of the swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Near sundown, mallards began to fly. They came in from the
south, but always, when still far out of range, turned and headed
for the west side of the marsh where a tiny stream trickles in. An
occasional shot came from that direction, so I assumed that Jeff
was succeeding in his meal-gathering quest.
</P>
<P>
   A small duck _ at first I thought it was a leaf _ hurtled,
twisting and turning, past the bare, writhing, lichen-festooned
branches of an ancient willow on the opposite side of the brook and
plopped down among my decoys. A female wood duck, it swam up to one
of the decoys and whistled at it. Not getting any response, it
paddled a few feet to shore and sat on a rock.
</P>
<P>
   It was legal game, but I was not moved to shoot it. I wanted a
big, fat corn-fed mallard, not an unsuspecting little bird that
weighs about a pound and a half in full plumage. I later learned
that Jeff had made the same decision when a wood duck _ we assumed
that it was the same bird _ had visited him.
</P>
<P>
   My fingers, in lined, leather gloves, were getting numb, but
because light was failing and because there would only be a few
seconds in which to spot and shoot a low-flying duck, I resisted
putting my hands in my jacket pockets. A lone mallard, the only one
that was to come to me that night, flew in low, headed up the brook
and made slow progress against the violent gusts of wind. It was an
easy shot. I swung on it, but my half-frozen thumb slipped off the
safety. By the time I did manage to fire I missed with both
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's shadowy figure materialized through the cattails a few
minutes later. He had three mallards in hand and my brother Danny's
affable and affectionate Labrador retriever Duchess trailing
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny was on my side of the marsh,'' Jeff said, ``and Duchess
joined me after I shot the first time. She saved me a lot of work.
She retrieved two of my birds.'' Jeff's gain, however, proved to be
Danny's loss. He later dropped two mallards that he couldn't reach,
but Duchess ignored his whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Duchess became increasingly subdued on our ride to Danny's house
to return her. She clearly comprehended her breach of allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Danny pulled into the yard behind us, sans ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has happened before,'' he said, ignoring his dog's
tentative show of apology. ``She can't resist guns going off and
ducks falling.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
