u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMBODIA-UNBURDEN-2TA     01-09 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-UNBURDEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
20 YEARS ON, ANGER IGNITES AGAINST KHMER ROUGE
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: also see CAMBODIA-PROFESSIONS-REVIEW) 
(bl) 
By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ ``I'm just a small person,'' said Un
Samath, a customs inspector, using a common phrase among
Cambodians, ``so I dare not say.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he got angry, and he said it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate them,'' he said of the defecting Khmer Rouge leaders
who recently flaunted their impunity in a tourist trip around
Cambodia. ``So long as it doesn't cause a war, I want to see them
on trial. Cambodians cannot be happy as long as they are happy.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, like a man who has decided that the time has come to
speak, Un Samath, 46, described the pain he shares with almost
every other Cambodian of his generation _ the killings of family
members, the years of fear and hunger, the loss of youth and
education, the continuing harshness of life.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of countless unburdenings that are taking place
among Cambodians today as the country seems to be embarking,
spontaneously, on a long-delayed national conversation about its
traumatic past.
</P>
<P>
   In Phnom Penh, the capital, and in Battambang, the country's
second-largest city, interviews with a score of people from market
vendors to professors suggest that a common legacy of anger and
pain is being shared in a new way.
</P>
<P>
   As Cambodia struggles to break with its feudal past, the
comments also suggest an emerging political assertiveness among
people better informed and more aware of their rights. Recently,
several political parties and labor unions have formed, and people
are coming forward to seek redress for land seizure or the dumping
of toxic waste _ evils that in the past they might simply have
accepted as their fate.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly near-unanimous view is that Khmer Rouge leaders
should be put on trial, if only to determine who is really to blame
for the country's suffering _ and even if any convictions are
followed by an amnesty.
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, it offers a response to those who fear that
international pressure for a trial amounts to a new burden imposed
on an already traumatized people. It is also a response to the
defectors' assertion that pressure for a trial comes from a foreign
intervention against the will of the people.
</P>
<P>
   There has still been no real assessment of the national will.
Prime Minister Hun Sen has asserted that people do not want a
trial, while King Norodom Sihanouk has stated that they do.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1975 and 1979, more than a million Cambodians died from
malnutrition, overwork, untreated diseases or executions. After a
wave of anger and mourning in the early 1980s, Cambodia settled
into a state of stunned and sluggish denial, its psychic wounds
unacknowledged and festering.
</P>
<P>
   The surrender of the two Khmer Rouge leaders _ Khieu Samphan and
Nuon Chea _ and their welcome by the government have apparently,
without anyone having intended or foreseen it, aroused these buried
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, the defections have ignited the feelings of the
people,'' said Kao Kim Hourn, who heads a private office studying
regional policy, the Cambodian Institute for Cooperation and Peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the major topic now that people talk about,'' he said.
``People from all walks of life have begun to question what
happened in that period. They share a common past, a common
suffering and therefore a common outrage when they see these mass
killers returning to the mainstream of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Researchers say that even as international pressure grows to put
Khmer Rouge leaders on trial for crimes against humanity, a dozen
of them are living freely now in Cambodia, following the collapse
of their guerrilla movement in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   If public pressure built, it could affect the fate of these
figures in a country where the voice of the ``small people'' has
not generally been heard by the ``big people'' in power.
</P>
<P>
   After Hun Sen welcomed the defectors two weeks ago, saying, ``We
should dig a hole and bury the past,'' he found it politically
necessary to issue what he called a clarification a few days later
and declare that he was all for justice.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has not yet said whether it will seek to
arrest the defectors, who are now in Pailin, a remote town near the
Thai border where they are protected by armed former guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is becoming difficult for the government to just dictate to
the people and ignore public opinion,'' Kao Kim Hourn said.
``People have reached a certain level of maturity. They have more
access to information, they don't have to be so much concerned
about food and security and another war.''
</P>
<P>
   With popular emotions stirring, he said, ``internal pressure on
the government has begun to build up.'' He added: ``National
reconciliation at all costs? Bury the past? Forgive and forget? No.
I don't think that is the case now.''
</P>
<P>
   If indeed a new, more politically demanding society is emerging,
it may be one positive legacy of the huge international effort at
democratization organized by the United Nations at the start of the
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the violent power politics that has persistently stunted
the establishment of democracy and human rights, a fledgling civil
society has begun to emerge, addressing everything from education
to flood control. This society is led by some 200 local
nongovernmental agencies, most with foreign funding.
</P>
<P>
   The country's nascent discussion also offers a remembrance of
the dead as people recount their losses.
</P>
<P>
   When they talk about the past, Cambodians commonly offer lists
of family members who died at the hands of the Khmer Rouge. Two
decades have passed, and this may be the last chance the country
has to seek an accounting on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   King Sihanouk himself, in a statement Thursday, published a list
of victims that included 5 children, 14 grandchildren, 2 cousins, a
half-uncle and a son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Kao Kim Hourn, 32, lost a younger brother and sister. He said he
still dreamed about them. When he was a college student in the
United States, he said, his roommate called him ``the wall beater''
because of his violent nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   Chhour Sokheang, 44, a university instructor, lost his father,
an uncle, an aunt, a cousin and about 25 other family members.
``Everybody is talking about it now,'' he said, ``my friends, my
students _ many, many people. Everybody says that now the Khmer
Rouge leaders are very lucky. When they had their forces, they
fought and killed Cambodian people. But when they lost, they came
back and the government welcomed them.''
</P>
<P>
   Lim Navy, 39, who sells construction material, says she lost an
uncle, two uncles-in-law and more cousins than she can count. ``If
we start thinking about what the Khmer Rouge did,'' she said, ``we
just want to chop them up like minced pork.''
</P>
<P>
   Life then was filled with miseries both big and small, she said,
some of which can only be recalled with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   She recited a ditty that people shared secretly in the Khmer
Rouge years: ``Democratic woman with fleas on her head, democratic
woman with ringworms on her body.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We even had fleas in our eyebrows,'' Mrs. Lim Navy said.
</P>
<P>
   People's lingering traumas assert themselves in unpredictable
ways.
</P>
<P>
   Kao Kim Hourn said he could not overcome a fear of starvation.
``All Cambodians who have been through this experience share
this,'' he said. ``At a restaurant we order much more food than we
can finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lim Navy said she could not shake off a rumor that had
circulated among her friends at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to hear a truck at nighttime,'' she said, ``and people
said it was carrying bile from corpses to China. Ever since then I
haven't been able to drink wine from China. I'm afraid it's made
out of the bile of dead Cambodians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1140EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5961 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-ART-2TAK     01-09 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-HYDE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW HENRY HYDE'S RESOLVE WAS SHAPED AGAINST CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., Wis., N.J., Conn., Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo of XXXXXXXXX is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See also IMPEACH-DEFENSE, IMPEACH-EVIDENCE) 
(lb) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A year ago, after the first reports of the
president's affair with Monica Lewinsky, Rep. Henry Hyde reacted
predictably enough, tamping down what he clearly saw as a lot of
loose, hotheaded talk about impeachment: ``You don't impeach him
for a peccadillo,'' he said then.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde also said the president would not be impeached without
bipartisan agreement. He said public support was important, too.
And he promised that under his leadership, the House Judiciary
Committee proceedings would be marked by comity and bring honor to
the Congress. ``If we fall into partisan bickering, we will
disgrace this institution,'' he said in September. ``And we're not
about to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Good old Henry, whispered the Democrats, confident that the
famously fair-minded and genteel gentleman from Illinois would keep
the real partisans in check. Let the hard-liners howl at the moon,
the thinking went. Rep. Bob Barr of Georgia could hold his breath
until he turned purple but, thank God, Henry Hyde was the man in
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in yet another twist in the labyrinthian Lewinsky scandal,
good old Henry surprised everyone. He opposed a Democratic proposal
that would have limited the inquiry and instead toyed with
expanding it. He argued against a censure option. And he presided
over hearings dominated by partisan attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Was this the same Henry Hyde who once had Democrats cheering his
opposition to Republican proposals on term limits? Yes, friends
said, but it was also a man whose position had hardened
considerably over the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Angered by what he came to see as President Clinton's cavalier
attitude toward the law, the investigation and the committee, and
boxed in by Democrats who he felt had no intention of working with
him, the friends said, Hyde became convinced that he had no choice
but to push forward and impeach the president without them.
</P>
<P>
   As with some others who have gone up against Clinton, these
friends said, Hyde's reluctance gradually turned to resolve and his
hesitation to absolute certainty.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton was impeached _ without either bipartisan support
or popular approval, for behavior that did stem from what many
people dismissed as a peccadillo _ it was in no small measure as a
result of Hyde's determination to press forward.
</P>
<P>
   And now Hyde, who has lately been listening to the original
Broadway cast's recording of ``Man of La Mancha,'' is throwing
himself wholeheartedly into his new role as Clinton's chief
prosecutor in the Senate. Rep. David Dreier of California, one of
Hyde's closest friends on Capitol Hill, said the Judiciary
Committee chairman's attitude was ``If you're going to catch hell
no matter what you do, you might as well do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   After appointing a conservative team of prosecutors, Hyde was
pushing for a full trial with witnesses and fighting any effort to
truncate that process. Last week, some senators began grumbling
that they did not know who had died and made him ``Senator'' Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's resolve has been nearly unwavering from the start of his
committee's deliberations in October. Contrary to expectations that
he might be dissuaded by the Republicans' poor showing in the
November elections, his friends said, that drubbing, coupled with
persistent criticism from colleagues, had exactly the opposite
effect. If anything, it only emboldened Hyde to proceed without
worrying about the fallout, since both he and his party were
already taking some hits.
</P>
<P>
   Neither was Hyde in any way deterred by the disclosure, in the
fall, of an extramarital affair he had decades ago. A devout Roman
Catholic, Hyde spoke on the House floor of his great shame over the
relationship, but believed, too, that there is a clear difference
between a sin and a crime. ``To liken violations of the vows to
perjury,'' Dreier said, ``is just their attempt to bring about
similarities.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., said Hyde had recovered from
the disclosure of his affair far more quickly than he had from a
recent incident involving the actor Alec Baldwin. On late night
television, Baldwin said, ``If we were in other countries ... all
of us together would go down to Washington and we would stone Henry
Hyde to death! We would stone him to death and we would go to their
homes and we'd kill their wives and their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin later apologized and said the bit was intended as
satire, but Sensenbrenner said Hyde, who has received death threats
and travels with four security guards, has been worried about his
family's safety ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Dreier, who had lunch with Hyde on Thursday after he
presented the articles of impeachment in the Senate, said his
friend was in good spirits that day, joking, enjoying some ``real
crab cakes,'' and chatting about movies. (Hyde had already seen
``You've Got Mail,'' dismissing it as ``a chick flick,'' Dreier
said, and had tried to coax him into seeing the Adam Sandler
goofathon ``The Waterboy,'' with him this weekend.)
</P>
<P>
   Hyde is not plagued by doubts about whether he is doing the
right thing, Dreier said. ``He's just rolling with it now.''
</P>
<P>
   But for others, the transformation has been jarring _
``breathtaking,'' said the Congress-watcher Tom Mann of the
Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   Almost no one thinks pressure from the party's conservative base
was much of a factor. This is Henry Hyde, they said, author of the
Hyde amendment, a hero to opponents of abortion and, at 74, a man
with nothing to prove.
</P>
<P>
   His friends insist that politics is not driving Hyde at all: As
one friend said, ``What's the political benefit to doing what he's
doing? If we find one more Jane Doe, Clinton's approval rating will
be at 100 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Smith, R-N.J., said: ``The conventional wisdom
was that it was not in our interest to proceed, so why would we
want to? To enhance Al Gore's chances? Censure would have been much
more politically expedient, but he went the other way.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor was Hyde under any obvious pressure from party leaders. ``I
don't think he was under orders here,'' said Rep. Jerrold Nadler,
D-N.Y. ``I think he just got more determined as time went on.''
</P>
<P>
   And friends say Nadler and other Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee are partly responsible for that evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde's attitude shifted as he began to despair of being able to
work across the aisle as he had originally hoped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt he wasn't getting cooperation from the other side of
the aisle, so in kind he decided he had to get the job done with
Republicans,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn. ``It was a
polarized committee, and he thought in the end that the Democrats
had a strategy that didn't allow for much common ground. Henry was
ultimately the leader of this polarized and partisan outcome, but
he didn't want it that way.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner, who sat next to Hyde on the committee and on a
couple of occasions sat in for him when the chairman ducked out for
a moment to cool down, said: ``Henry can get his back up when he
thinks he's being used. Everything he did the partisan pit bulls
sharply criticized.''
</P>
<P>
   Nadler seemed happy to acknowledge getting under the chairman's
skin. ``Henry is a very determined guy and I think he was getting
exasperated at Democrats' not playing along,'' Nadler said,
laughing. ``We were not going to make his job any easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats on the committee said they felt Hyde was
influenced by his counsel, David Schippers, who also began his work
with an aura of bipartisanship as a lifelong Democrat but soon
adopted a hard line regarding the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank of Massachusetts, another Democrat on the
committee, said he thought he saw signs of what he called the
``bridge over the River Kwai syndrome.'' ``After a while, pride of
craft takes over,'' Frank said, ``and you just want to build the
bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   At a number of junctures, Hyde's associates said, he was
frustrated by what he came to see as Clinton's disrespect for the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is deeply offended by the president's conduct during this
entire matter'' in ways that have ``nothing to do with his
relationship with Monica Lewinsky,'' Sensenbrenner said.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, colleagues said, Hyde became convinced that he
had no choice but to protect the court system that he felt would be
seriously undermined if every citizen with a skeleton in his closet
decided under which circumstances it might be permissible to lie
under oath.
</P>
<P>
   And after Hyde saw Clinton's answers to the 81 questions the
committee had put to him, several people close to him said Hyde
felt there was no turning back.
</P>
<P>
   One person familiar with Hyde's thinking over the last few
months said that ``after the nonresponsive answers on the 81
questions, he said in a meeting of fellow Republicans, `Boys, I
don't see what choice we have now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly underestimated by the White House, Hyde was, in the
end, ``critical in convincing Republicans to impeach him anyway
after the election,'' Mann said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They mistook a teddy-bear exterior for a soft core,'' said
Ralph Reed, the Republican strategist, who knows Hyde well. ``If he
feels strongly about something, he'll fight harder than anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   And no one can doubt that Hyde now feels strongly about the case
against Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
