 The Week in Review 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Admits Using Spies In Arms Inspection Team
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials acknowledged that U.S. intelligence officers
worked undercover on teams of United Nations Special Commission
inspectors ferreting out secret Iraqi weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   They said U.S. intelligence agencies provided
electronic-eavesdropping equipment and secret information to the
special commission.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, they said, the United States received information on
Iraqi weapons programs that the inspectors uncovered. Iraq has long
accused the commission of being riddled with ``American spies and
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Weiner
</P>
<P>
   Ed, Formerly Known As Prince, to Wed
</P>
<P>
   The last child of Britain's Queen Elizabeth, Prince Edward, 34,
has decided to marry his longtime girlfriend, Sophie Rhys-Jones,
33, this summer, and the public well-wishing at the engagement
announcement was mixed with expressions of anxiety over whether he
could do better than his three siblings, all of whose youthful
marriages ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Things are promisingly different this time. The couple has been
together for five years, they are not in their 20s, they both have
jobs, and they shun publicity.
</P>
<P>
   She runs her own public-relations firm in London, and he is a
film producer. He may be her prince, but he prefers to be known as
Edward Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Hoge
</P>
<P>
   Hello. Anyone Alive Here?
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for extraterrestrial life picked up speed as NASA
launched the second of two new spacecraft toward Mars.
</P>
<P>
   The pair are part of a fleet of more than a dozen probes that
over 16 years are to help the agency answer the Martian riddle once
and for all.
</P>
<P>
   Mars Climate Orbiter was launched from Florida on Dec. 11, now
joined by Mars Polar Lander. The latter craft is to look deep
beneath the Martian surface in search of water, which is considered
the key ingredient for life.
</P>
<P>
   The new lander also carries a tiny microphone, paid for by the
Planetary Society, a private group in Pasadena, Calif., that backs
space exploration. The experiment's goal is to beam back sounds of
winds, lightning and any aliens that happen to amble by, though
that is considered unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave of craft left for Mars in 1996 and the series, if
money holds up, is to continue at least through 2012.
</P>
<P>
   The effort is to culminate in the return to Earth of rocks from
Mars that will be examined for signs of microscopic life, either
fossil or extant.
</P>
<P>
   _ William J. Broad
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Becomes The Body Politic
</P>
<P>
   So he didn't begin his inauguration ceremony by rappelling into
the Capitol from a helicopter. The mere fact that Jesse ``the
Body'' Ventura became governor of Minnesota was enough of a
curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   The former professional wrestler, elected on the Reform Party
ticket in a stunning upset of the two major parties, had already
demonstrated his flair for the unconventional _ licensing Jesse
Ventura action figures and T-shirts to replenish his campaign
treasury, giving few hints of his policies and suggesting that his
wife, Terry, merits a state salary.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ventura, for her part, wasn't asking for compensation; she
was expressing shell shock about the whole first lady gig. ``The
last time I gave a speech I was at my sister's wedding,'' she said.
``I was the maid of honor and I said: `Congratulations. Have a
great life.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _ Pam Belluck
</P>
<P>
   A Small Break For Black Farmers
</P>
<P>
   The farm life is a life of struggle.
</P>
<P>
   To make a profit, farmers must overcome weather, pests,
temperamental markets and intense competition. Black farmers
maintain that they have had to battle an additional obstacle in
recent decades _ racism _ and now the U.S. Department of
Agriculture has acknowledged that complaint. It settled a
class-action lawsuit filed by black farmers who maintained that
department officials discriminated in the processing of federal
farm loans.
</P>
<P>
   While not admitting bias, the department offered to pay $50,000
to black farmers claiming discrimination and to forgive their
outstanding federal debt. Noting that only 1 percent of today's
farmers are black, down from 14 percent in 1920, many black farmers
said the settlement came far too late.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kevin Sack
</P>
<P>
   A Tiny Opening to Cuba With Little Political Risk
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration took steps to allow more U.S. money,
air planes, food and mail flow into Cuba, with an eye toward the
day when Fidel Castro no longer rules the isolated island. But the
White House, which is wary of the political power of anti-Castro
Cuban-Americans, rejected calls for creating a national commission
that would study the 37-year-old American economic embargo that has
stifled Cuba's economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Weiner
</P>
<P>
   A British Scandal Claims Another Victim
</P>
<P>
   A third official has fallen from the British government of Prime
Minister Tony Blair, which came into office 20 months ago pledging
an end to the kind of behavior that led 12 ministers in the
previous Conservative government of John Major to depart in
disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   Quitting just before Christmas were Paymaster General Geoffrey
Robinson, 60, a millionaire industrialist and politician who had
given Trade and Industry Minister Peter Mandelson, 45, a $620,000
home loan, and Mandelson, Blair's closest confidant, who kept the
loan a secret even after Robinson's financial affairs came under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The latest victim was Charlie Whelan, the press secretary to
Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, the second most powerful
man in the government.
</P>
<P>
   Whelan's crime was to have conducted a negative campaign against
Mandelson.
</P>
<P>
   It was viewed as disruptive to the image-conscious government's
mission to portray itself as unified.
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Hoge
</P>
<P>
   A Plan for Tax Relief
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed a program of $6 billion in tax
credits and other assistance to people providing long-term care for
relatives with chronic illnesses and disabilities. The proposal
amounts to a tax cut for the middle class. People with relatively
high incomes would be ineligible, as would people with incomes so
low that they do not have to pay income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Deets, executive director of the American Association of
Retired Persons, said the tax credit of $1,000 a year would provide
``long-overdue recognition'' to families caring for relatives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Pear
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
