<HEADLINE>
UNDATED: ROBERT PEAR
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Together Again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you reach the fork in the road, take it, Yogi Berra is said
to have once told a friend who was coming to visit. Last week, when
George Steinbrenner, the New York Yankees' principal owner, made
his way to Berra's home turf to ask that they bury their 14-year
feud, the Hall of Fame catcher decided it was time for both men to
take the high road. ``Fourteen years,'' his son, Dale, told him,
``is long enough.''
</P>
<P>
   So Berra opened his arms _ and the museum bearing his name on
the Montclair State University campus in New Jersey _ to the man
who dismissed him as Yankee manager through an intermediary in
1985. The Boss told Berra that failing to deliver the bad news in
person was ``the worst mistake I ever made in baseball'' and
pleaded with him to return to Yankee Stadium next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Berra said, unwilling to firmly commit himself to
taking this latest fork. But his smile gave him away. Yogi, it
seems, is finally going home.
</P>
<P>
   _ Harvey Araton
</P>
<P>
   The Happiest Michael Jordan &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one was happier with the salvation of the National Basketball
Association season last week than Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   No, not the world's greatest hoopster. The Michael Jordan who
averages 17 points per game for the University of Pennsylvania, a
very mortal No. 23 who, in the absence of the NBA, became fodder
for America's sports announcers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe they'll stop killing me with the jokes,'' Jordan said on
the telephone before Penn played Yale in an Ivy League game Friday.
``One night I hear about a guy on ESPN starting his highlights,
`Jordan . . . from the top of the key . . . . airball.' With no
