603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By STEVE LeVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASTANA, Kazakhstan _ The government has tried almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   It has supplied heat to most homes and offices in the new
national capital of this Central Asian nation, taking the sting out
of temperatures now at 10 below zero. It has revved up drab Astana
with brightly decorated buildings and restaurants and a delightful
playground of ice sculptures and slides that lights up at night.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a year after Astana's showy debut, many bureaucrats are
miserable. An anticipated corps of foreign diplomats and business
people has simply not shown up, with conspicuous exceptions like
the occupants of a smart red storefront on Astana's wide main
avenue. They work for Saudi Binladen Group, the contracting company
that is creating Astana's master plan. It is run by the estranged
family of the terrorism suspect Osama bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather is fine for us,'' said Ashraf Khallad, a Binladen
manager, who had snow piled up outside his office window. ``We work
here. The apartment is upstairs. And, when we need to go somewhere,
the car is just outside.''
</P>
<P>
   When President Nursultan Nazarbayev unveiled his plans for this
city of 300,000 people on the Siberian steppe, he stubbornly
rejected objections that the move from the old capital of Almaty
was unnecessary, unpopular and, considering the cost in an oil-rich
but still cash-poor nation, even imprudent.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the autocratic Nazarbayev is seeking re-election to a
new seven-year term; he is expected to win easily. But the
prognosis for his dreamchild, Kazakhstan's new capital, is in
doubt. After some $1 billion in spending, officials are starting to
voice the previously unspeakable: Further plans for Astana must be
curtailed, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is not that Astana is situated on a mosquito-ridden
swamp and that in winter, said a Foreign Ministry official who
requested anonymity, it ``is tolerable only when the wind isn't
blowing.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, it is that the global economic slump has finally reached
Kazakhstan. After two years of expansion, experts say, Kazakhstan's
economy shrank last year and will probably contract further in
1999. A plunge in world oil prices has cut state income by a third,
producing budget deficits that, if not somehow reduced, ``over the
long term are going to become a crushing burden,'' said Stephen
Lewarne, who runs the Almaty office of Global Securities.
</P>
<P>
   State officials are examining a drastic reduction in 1999
spending on Astana _ to $25 million from $100 million, say Western
diplomats. Foreign investment in the new capital is unlikely to
meet government projections of $300 million this year, said a
senior Kazakh official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that although a few projects will begin in Astana
``because it is high on the president's political agenda,'' the
official said, the new city center that Nazarbayev envisions on the
left bank of the Irtysh River will probably remain in the planning
stages.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Few residents of this republic of 15.5 million, the
second-largest in the former Soviet Union, are likely to be
troubled. And the thousands of foreign business people who have
taken up residence because of an expected oil boom clearly prefer
Almaty, 750 miles south, with its nearby skiing, and plentiful bars
and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than two dozen foreign countries with embassies in
Kazakhstan, just one, Uzbekistan, has begun building a permanent
mission in Astana, a city official said.
</P>
<P>
   For disgruntled government officials, the suspension of
construction comes too late _ their ministries have already
permanently shifted here, and quality of life has declined.
</P>
<P>
   The one consolation is financial. On the edge of Astana are
1,000 colorful apartments, which several government officials said
had been sold to them for $7,000 to $8,000 each. If an official
stays in Astana for three years, he or she is entitled to sell the
apartment at the going market price, which some estimate as high as
$50,000, and keep the profit.
</P>
<P>
   When Nazarbayev chose the new capital's site, he also changed
its name. At its founding as a Cossack fortress in 1832, this spot
was called Akmola, or White Grave in Kazakh. After much snickering,
Nazarbayev selected its current name, which means simply
``capital.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
