<HEADER>
A5976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-ART-N     01-09 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-DEFENSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO FIELD A MUCH-PRACTICED LEGAL TEAM
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV 13 : Photo is being sent to NYT 14  photo clients.
Non-subscribers 15  can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By JAMES BENNET   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Some now-familiar faces will be presenting some
now-familiar arguments on the Senate floor to defend President
Clinton as he goes on trial.
</P>
<P>
   Though White House aides say they are still mapping out their
strategy, the core of the defense team and of its case are settled.
The team is to be led by Charles Ruff, the former Watergate special
prosecutor who is Clinton's fifth White House counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff anchored the president's defense before the House Judiciary
Committee a month ago. The White House was very pleased with his
sardonic, at times theatrical, dissection of the case presented by
Kenneth Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The defense was not terribly effective but the White House
attributes that, in part, to the news media. The Republicans
released the text of their proposed articles of impeachment
immediately after Ruff's appearance, overwhelming news of his
presentation on television and in some newspaper reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conventional wisdom is that we never argued the facts or
the evidence, and the conventional wisdom is wrong,'' said Joe
Lockhart, the White House press secretary. ``We argued them
forcefully and in a compelling way, but it was drowned out by the
release of the draft articles.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers' chief immediate goal is to present such a
convincing argument over the 24 hours available to them that a
majority of senators will vote to dismiss the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they hope for a quick resolution, the president's
lawyers are preparing for an extended trial with witnesses called
and new evidence admitted. Such a trial could last months, some
aides fear, and obliterate Clinton's hopes for a history-making
overhaul of the Social Security system.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing along with Ruff in the Senate will be Gregory Craig,
the White House special counsel hired by Clinton to help manage his
impeachment defense. A relative newcomer to the team, Craig still
does not have the detailed knowledge that his colleagues have of
the case, White House aides say. But as a former aide to Sen.
Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., he has close ties to the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Craig led off the president's defense before the House Judiciary
Committee and has functioned as the official spokesman for the
legal team.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being an experienced criminal lawyer, Craig comes
off well on television, the White House believes, and he carries
none of the political baggage of some of the longer-serving members
of the team.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff and Craig are backed up by numerous lawyers, both in
private practice and in the White House. Two among them _ David
Kendall, the president's longtime private lawyer, and Lanny Breuer,
a member of the counsel's office _ are likely to play significant
roles during the trial, White House advisers say.
</P>
<P>
   In public, Kendall has taken a lower-profile role since his
efforts to defend Clinton on television last year were panned as
hairsplitting even at the White House. He sat silently behind Craig
and Ruff as they defended the president in the House. But he
remains the foremost expert on Clinton's legal travails, White
House aides say, and he is trusted by both the president and his
wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer has been at the center of the president's damage-control
operation since last January. He has operated mostly out of sight,
processing subpoenas, gathering documents and contacting witnesses.
But he came to the attention of Starr, who subpoenaed him to
testify last year. The president tried but failed to invoke
attorney-client privilege to block his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment before reporters as he left the courthouse
after testifying, Breuer offered only two words when asked his
reaction to the hubbub surrounding his appearance: ``I'm honored.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
