<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5979 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-DOCS-REBEL-ART-2TAK     01-09 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-DOCS-REBEL-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY AT MANAGED CARE, DOCTORS START FIGHTING BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note)  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Calif., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For Dr. Clement Barone, a radiologist on the Upper
East Side, the final straw came when Blue Cross Blue Shield told
him it was cutting reimbursements for mammograms to $42 each. (He
charges $200.) He dropped the plan, and said he might stop
accepting all managed care soon.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barney Softness, a pediatrician on West End Avenue, said he
decided he could take no more when Oxford Health Plans suggested
that he cut costs by getting rid of the registered nurses in his
office. Instead, he told Oxford goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Byron Thomashow, a pulmonary specialist in Washington
Heights, recalled how he fought with one company for three hours to
get permission to do a procedure on a woman who was coughing up
life-threatening amounts of blood. He said the dispute underscored
why he no longer was in a managed care plan.
</P>
<P>
   While 92 percent of doctors in New York state accepted managed
care last year, it seems that a small rebellion is on. Fed up with
years of acrimonious relationships with managed care companies,
doctors, particularly those serving upper-middle-class patients,
are starting to fight back.
</P>
<P>
   Many are dropping plans that have the lowest reimbursement
rates, biggest administrative headaches or represent the fewest
number of their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Others are washing their hands of the carriers, forcing patients
to pay up front and file claims the old-fashioned way, or pay the
fees themselves. Still others are looking for alternative ways to
negotiate with the companies, like forming group practices or other
professional associations that have more leverage to seek better
reimbursement rates. And hospitals are trying to fight back by
asking the New York state attorney general's office to look into
managed care company practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that a growing number of doctors are
disassociating themselves from managed care,'' said Dr. Charles
Aswad, executive vice president of the Medical Society of the State
of New York. Still more, he said, ``are being much more judicious
about looking at managed care contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is too early to quantify much of the activity, some
numbers are startling: 10 percent of the doctors affiliated with
New York Presbyterian Hospital have dropped out of managed care in
the last three months, and 50 percent have whittled the plans they
accept, said Dr. Myron Weisfeldt, chairman of the hospital's
department of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a tremendous number of physicians that to one degree
or another are beginning to separate themselves from managed care
at some financial risk to themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there are signs that the movement extends past New York
City's borders: the Summit Medical Group, a 100-doctor practice in
Summit, N.J., for instance, recently dropped Blue Cross, and others
are expected to follow suit, said Dr. Greg Sachs, president of the
Medical Society of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors' opposition to managed care is on the increase
elsewhere, as well. In California, doctors have formed a group to
push their opposition, and in Texas, some are also forswearing
managed care. But experts say New York is particularly interesting
because doctors here are rejecting a system that is still quite new
and that rolled into the region at a breakneck speed in the last
few years. Chief among their complaints have been reduced fees and
more restrictions from the insurance companies on referrals and
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``California had an evolution toward managed care, and we have
had a revolution,'' said Aswad. ``And that is why you hear about
these disruptions and large groups suddenly getting out.''
</P>
<P>
   This movement raises difficult questions about whether doctors
can and should expect to make the same good living they did before
the managed care movement, and whether a decision among some of the
brightest and best to drop managed care plans simply re-creates the
caste system of care that health maintenance organizations were
meant to eliminate by providing preventive care and a variety of
services.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, New York is not leaving the managed care business. The
HMO Trade Conference, a trade group, said it has not yet heard of
managed care companies worrying about a mass exodus.
</P>
<P>
   But it is just as clear that in the last few months many
doctors, who have been unhappy about managed care almost since its
introduction to the New York area, seem to be dropping out
entirely, for several reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, consolidation among the managed care companies
has increased, underscored by the announcement that Aetna U.S.
Healthcare _ whose tough bargaining on rates makes it one of the
least popular insurance carriers among doctors _ would acquire
Prudential Health Care. As the companies grow larger, their ability
to dictate rates and policies is likely to increase.
</P>
<P>
   Further, many companies have cut reimbursement rates
significantly in recent months, causing many doctors to conclude
that they cannot make any money by accepting them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't stand it,'' said Thomashow, the pulmonary
specialist in Washington Heights. ``The thought of being put on
hold lines by people who don't know a quarter of what you are doing
to get permission for patients to go to the bathroom was
distasteful to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The revolt tends be led by doctors who have affluent patients
who are both demanding and willing to pay for the services if they
must. But some doctors, whose patient population is more diverse,
are trying to form groups to challenge the companies.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Mount Kisco Medical Group in Mount Kisco, N.Y.,
has started to take advantage of its size _ 64 doctors under one
roof _ to negotiate with managed care companies. It has dropped
some plans that were demanding too much paperwork, said Dr. Scott
Hayworth, the group's chief executive officer. But it negotiated a
more favorable contract with others, including Oxford and Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are 64 doctors,'' Hayworth said, ``so we are lucky because
we have better negotiating power. Does that mean if you could wave
a magic wand and make managed care go away, would we? We would want
that for sure. But we make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Experts predict that more large groups will come together _
perhaps in the form of unions. But forming groups does not always
assure power.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1994 Dr. Jonas Goldstone and Dr. Saul Kaplan
formed Mid-Manhattan Medical Associates, an association of 26
doctors from various specialties who organized as a group to
arrange better ancillary services, like laboratories, and to deal
with managed care through a central business office.
</P>
<P>
   While many of their goals as a group have been met, they have
not won better reimbursement rates from insurance carriers, they
said. ``We are finding out that the projected income we expected in
dealing with managed care has not materialized,'' Goldstone said.
At this point, he added, ``A number of us are seriously considering
exiting managed care.''
</P>
<P>
   If someone's doctor informs her he will no longer accept her
insurance plan, the options are clear: She finds another doctor or
she pays up. And if she is in a plan that partially reimburses for
visits to doctors out of the network, she files a claim.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals, too, are bridling at managed care. The biggest
complaint is that companies are refusing to reimburse for the full
number of days that patients spend in the hospital, arguing that
certain illnesses can be treated in shorter stays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot overstate enough the sense of frustration within the
hospitals,'' said Kenneth Raske, president of the Greater New York
Hospital Association, a trade group for local hospitals. ``We have
gone from tolerance to feverish pitch, and we are seeking help from
the authorities as well as lawmakers so HMOs stop abusing
hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   The association has asked the state attorney general's office to
pursue the matter of trimming days, and the association is
contemplating lawsuits against individual companies, Raske said.
</P>
<P>
   Most doctors say that quality of care, not their own earnings,
is driving their decisions. They argue, for instance, that when
managed care companies push for high-volume practices, it reduces
the time they can devote to each patient, teaching, reading medical
journals and working in clinics.
</P>
<P>
   They also recognize the painful reality that only middle-class
and wealthier patients are likely to have insurance plans that
allow them to choose their own doctor in exchange for a lower
reimbursement rate, typically 80 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want a practice just for rich people,'' said Softness,
the pediatrician. ``That was never my plan. But I also want to be
able to give the kind of care that I think people deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   But some health care experts argue that a tiered health care
system is in the offing with a movement like this one. ``I think we
are moving toward a two-tiered or three-tiered structure of health
care,'' said Michael Lichman, senior vice president of Willis
Corroon of New York, one of the country's largest insurance
brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Others, too, argue that despite a glut of doctors in the 1980s,
doctors' incomes rose higher than that of other professionals. They
contend that in a supply and demand economy, lower salaries would
have been expectable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If doctors say that quality will fall as reimbursements fall,
they are insulting themselves,'' said Uwe Reinhardt, a health
economist at Princeton University. ``The truth of the matter is
that when a group of laborers are in surplus, wages fall. They are
the only group that is unwilling to accept that.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors who serve the poor, doctors fresh out of school who have
no established patient base, and doctors working in towns where one
employer dominates the market simply cannot refuse managed care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't drop HMOs if you have a family to feed and a dog who
depends on you,'' said Lichman. ``Patients have become used to
walking into a doctor's office and paying $10, and you can't say,
`OK, I'm back in the fee-for-service business.'''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as employers continue to offer plans that give
employees a chance to go to doctors outside their networks _ which
is likely in a strong economy _ and HMOs continue to push for
doctors to cut costs, more are likely to leave the HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear every day about other groups of doctors who are
dropping managed care,'' said Dr. Barry Chaiken, who founded the
Association of Independent Physicians in New York, a new and
growing group of doctors free of managed care. ``As managed care
comes in and insists on fee discounts of 30 percent or more,
physicians have to change their practices to survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
