<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5983 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-HOLIDAYS-455&AMP;A     01-09 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-HOLIDAYS-455&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIA, EVEN HOLIDAYS ARE LONG AND PERPLEXING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It has been a long haul. Russians are confused,
exhausted and hung over, their resources and emotions spent. But
now at last they can see an end in sight _ not to Russia's
open-ended economic crisis, but to the year-end holidays, which
like the local winter seem to go on forever.
</P>
<P>
   By Monday, when something approaching a normal work schedule
starts again, most Russians will have had seven of the last nine
days off, and that is only counting the official holidays: four
over New Year's weekend and another three following Russian
Orthodox Christmas, which falls on Jan. 7. Unofficially, many a
factory and office simply shut down for the duration, in part
because it was too difficult to figure out which days were
workdays.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason, of course, is that long holidays are a handy
excuse for not paying salaries for work that is not being done _ a
familiar practice in postcommunist Russia even in the nonholiday
season.
</P>
<P>
   But then there were stores, and offices _ all of them private _
that defied the Christmas holidays, because they could not afford
to stay shut for so long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not profitable to be closed yet another day,'' said
Valery Bazunov, whose Dial Electronics Store, on Moscow's busy
Garden Ring Road, stayed open Jan. 7 and 8. ``Christmas is not such
a holiday yet,'' said Bazunov, the store director, referring to
Soviet times when the atheist communist regime did not celebrate
Christmas. ``It is just like another day off.''
</P>
<P>
   Given this year's unusually perplexing calendar, many stores and
offices had to post schedules on their doors advising customers and
clients who might otherwise not be aware that Sunday, Jan. 10, is a
regular working day, filling in for Friday, Jan. 8, technically a
day off.
</P>
<P>
   At the local American Express office, the listing took up a full
page. Closely spaced explanations were aimed to guide the
uninitiated foreign tourist through the maze of two interlocking
Russian traditions _ one anchored by the Russian Orthodox Church's
calendar, the other a Soviet bureaucratic habit of moving holidays
around like pawns on a chessboard.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Sunday periodically pops up as a regular working day
_ in spite of the postcommunist government's low bow to the Russian
Orthodox Church, hailed by President Boris Yeltsin in his Christmas
Day message as an irreplaceable pillar of Russian nationhood. After
74 years of state atheism, the church has regained its place of
honor, with both Easter and Christmas celebrated as national
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the church raised a ruckus a few years ago when Pentecost
Sunday _ one of the holiest days in the church year _ turned up as
a workday in a swap for a weekday secular holiday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There were no protests this year when Sunday, Jan. 10, was
offered in exchange for Jan. 8, the day after Christmas. In fact,
the Christmas holiday began on Jan. 6, Christmas Eve, when churches
around the country opened their doors for services that lasted
until the early hours.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jan. 4 was made part of the New Year's holiday
(compensating for Jan. 2, which is normally a holiday in Russia but
this year it fell on a Saturday), that left Jan. 5 as virtually the
only day between Dec. 31 and Jan. 10 when Russians on the
government payroll could reasonably be expected to put in a full
day of work.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian shopper, who since Soviet times has given presents
on New Year's, is also caught these days in a clash of calendars.
Western Christmas is not celebrated here, yet it has crept into the
commercial cycle, along with Santa Claus and ``Jingle Bells.'' Some
Moscow stores were even offering post-Christmas discounts before
New Year's, one week before Russians even get around to thinking
about their own Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the return of religion in the postcommunist period, many
Russians have only a vague idea of what Christmas is. The annual
televised transmission of the Christmas Eve service led by the head
of the Russian Orthodox Church, Patriarch Alexy II, is still
accompanied by a hushed explanation of the old Slavonic texts. For
those who do not attend church services, Jan. 7 and 8 are simply
new holidays, not unlike Russia's Constitution Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be honest, we haven't even been able to get around to
thinking about Christmas,'' said Andrei, a 27-year-old former
bartender who lost his job this fall when Russia's financial crisis
swept through Moscow. ``It was hard enough to get what we needed to
celebrate New Year's.''
</P>
<P>
   New Year's Eve remains the main day of festivity, when Russian
families gather around tables covered with food, and children wait
for Grandfather Frost to leave presents under their decorated fir
trees.
</P>
<P>
   This year, despite the financial crisis, Moscow stores reported
a hefty surge in sales. The aisles, even in expensive shops, were
full, and the streets, decked out in holiday lights, were jammed
with cars in the days before New Year's Eve. Big-ticket items like
cars were in demand as shoppers tried to sneak in ahead of new tax
regulations that will require an income declaration for purchases
worth more than $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   But for the most part, the presents this year were the small
souvenirs that Russians especially treasure. Many of these trinkets
featured rabbits in one form or another, as 1999, according to the
Chinese calendar, is the year of the rabbit _ a friendlier mascot
than the tiger of 1998, which is not regarded as one of Russia's
best years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1219EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
