<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6000 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-STATES-NYT &LR;      01-09 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-STATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLLARS AND CENTS OF SETTLEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Colo., La., Minn., N.Y., Texas)   (Eds: This sidebar replaces the graphic with TOBACCO-WINDFALL.) 
(jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the next 25 years, cigarette makers will pay almost $246
billion to all 50 states to settle lawsuits. Here are some
proposals for spending the money in six states.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Alabama: $3.2 billion settlement. Legislature has approved $85
million for youth programs, including health coverage, new
detention centers and added probation officers; $500,000 to tobacco
control. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Colorado: $2.7 billion settlement. Panel recently recommended that
35 percent be spent on tobacco control and 44 percent on children's
health programs. Not binding on Legislature. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Louisiana: $4.4 billion settlement. Gov. Mike Foster has proposed
selling future tobacco payments now and using the money to pay off
state debt. It could then use the money to raise teachers'
salaries. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Minnesota: $6.1 billion settlement. Set aside $202 million for
anti-smoking efforts. Some have recommended an added $650 million,
but businesses and Gov. Jesse Ventura oppose the effort. &QL; 
 &QL; 
New York: $25 billion settlement. Both Gov. George Pataki and Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani have yet to make recommendations. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Texas: $17.3 billion settlement. Some lawmakers have suggested
using the money for programs like lowering tobacco use, researching
cancer and implementing health programs for those living along the
Mexican border. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Source: National Conference of State Legislatures &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
