<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6004 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT     01-09 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICALLY WEAK AT HOME, TURKS FLEX MUSCLES ABROAD
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Turkey may soon have a functioning government
after six weeks without one, but its new-found assertiveness in
foreign policy is likely to continue no matter who emerges as the
next prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Once a bashful actor on the world stage, Turkey has begun
flexing its muscles whenever it feels the need.
</P>
<P>
   Through blunt warnings of economic pressure and even military
strikes, Turkish leaders are using their growing power as masters
of the 18th-largest economy to achieve what they consider vital
policy goals.
</P>
<P>
   Benefiting in part from the new weakness of Russia, Iran and
Iraq and regional rivals once backed by Soviet power, the Turks
have achieved surprisingly good results.
</P>
<P>
   This success is all the more remarkable in light of the
country's deep political problems.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz, faced with allegations of
corruption, lost a confidence vote in Parliament on Nov. 25.
</P>
<P>
   He has been serving as a caretaker during weeks of political
maneuvering that may finally produce a government led by a veteran,
the former Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, who hopes to put together
a Cabinet by Monday and win a Parliamentary confidence vote Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Turkey has not had a stable government since the 1995
election, Turkish foreign policy has become tougher and more
forceful than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Its most recent success came on the tense island of Cyprus,
which is divided between Turkish and Greek sectors: The
Greek-backed Cypriot government had planned to deploy Russian
anti-aircraft missiles; Turkey responded by promising to bomb them.
The week before last, the Cypriots backed down.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey cannot claim full credit for staring down the Cypriots,
because the United States and several European countries had also
urged that the deployment be canceled to avoid dangerous friction
between two NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   But in other areas, Turkish leaders have won important battles
on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Turkish generals and political leaders demanded that
Syria expel a Kurdish rebel leader, Abdullah Ocalan, who has
directed a 14-year guerrilla war in southeastern Turkey. They
strongly hinted that Turkey would attack Syria if it did not
comply. To reinforce their message, they massed soldiers along the
Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
   With an alacrity that some in the region found astonishing,
Syria quickly knuckled under and expelled Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously Syria was feeling weak,'' said a European diplomat
with long experience in the Middle East. ``It couldn't have
resisted an attack by Turkey and it didn't want to be humiliated,
especially with Israel watching.''
</P>
<P>
   From Syria Ocalan flew to Russia. Turkish officials warned
Russia that if he was allowed to stay there, they would demand
instant repayment of Russian debts and force the scores of Turkish
companies operating in Russia to cease operations immediately.
Within days, Ocalan was in the air again, this time headed to
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish leaders demanded that Italy send him home to face trial.
But Italy, which is governed by a left-leaning coalition that
includes some who sympathize with Kurdish rebels, proved less
pliant and refused.
</P>
<P>
   Outraged Turks have threatened to ban Italian imports, which are
worth many millions of dollars to Italian companies, and to reject
Italian bids for huge Turkish military contracts. Newspapers here
predict that Italy will soon see the error of its ways and send
Ocalan away.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is also using high-pressure tactics to persuade foreign
oil companies that they should build their main export pipeline for
Caspian crude oil through Turkey. The companies want to build a
shorter and cheaper pipeline to Georgia, then ship the crude in
tankers across the Black Sea and through the Bosporus, the narrow
strait that bisects Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   But Foreign Minister Ismail Cem replied that the Bosporus is
already full and that Turkey will no longer ``grant any priority to
oil tankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the Turks went even further: They told the two main
partners in the Caspian oil consortium, Amoco and British
Petroleum, that if they continue to support the Georgia route,
Turkey will revoke their permits to explore for oil in Turkish
waters. Turkish officials also said they would disqualify Amoco's
bid to build a new $500 million liquid natural gas terminal here.
</P>
<P>
   By some standards, Turkey is well positioned to use such tough
tactics. Despite its debilitated political system it has a strong
economy, a population of 65 million and 370,000 soldiers under
arms, more than any other NATO country except the United States.
Partly due to its old alliance with the United States and its new
partnership with Israel, its military is well trained, disciplined
and equipped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as recently as 1990, the Turkish state was largely Third
World militarily and economically,'' said Alan Makovsky, a
specialist in Turkish affairs at the Washington Institute for Near
East Policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had no modern weaponry, it faced countries that were well
armed and backed by the Soviets and it was basically inward
looking. Now all of that has changed.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 1,000 M-60 tanks and 200 F-16 fighters, Makovsky
said, the Turks ``can stir the pot in a way they couldn't five
years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When they threaten economic or even military retaliation,'' he
added, ``it's not something that's easy to dismiss.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1253EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6005 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERU-PADRE-ART-NYT     01-09 1171
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-PADRE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERUVIAN PRIEST, HIS CHILDREN AND AN ANGRY BISHOP
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
 (bl) 
By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORROPE, Peru _ Catholics cannot be baptized or married in
Morrope anymore. The graceful colonial church is locked shut. And
the Roman Catholic Church hierarchy has threatened to suspend all
charitable donations to this desert town of 39,000 souls, who are
still reeling from the floods brought by El Nino.
</P>
<P>
   Morrope's problem, at least as far as the local bishop is
concerned, is that its Catholic priest has two teen-age children
whom he fathered years after he entered the priesthood.
</P>
<P>
   The priest, the Rev. Jorge Arbanil Rico, 44, is unrepentant.
</P>
<P>
   Every day he offers Mass in the town cemetery and in the streets
accompanied by a jaunty New Orleans-style band of drummers and
saxophone and trumpet players, against the orders of the church
hierarchy. He has become a cause celebre for a movement of retired
Peruvian priests who say he should be considered a model for the
Roman Catholic priest of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first time anyone can remember, at least in modern
Peruvian history, that a priest has defied the Roman Catholic
hierarchy by continuing to practice priestly functions _ with the
exceptions of marriages and baptisms _ while openly admitting to
having broken his vow of celibacy. He will not identify the boys'
mother.
</P>
<P>
   But Arbanil Rico's case is not unique. One Peruvian priest in
Yurimaguas is openly married. Another from a settlement just
outside Huancayo reportedly lives with a 12-year-old son and has
defied the hierarchy by giving press interviews. But these other
would-be rebels have received the quiet acquiescence of their local
bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The blooming controversy comes at a time when as many as one in
every four priests in Latin America leaves the priesthood before
retirement age, often to marry. And while rural Latin America
remains deeply Catholic, a shortage of priests has helped
Protestant evangelicals make deep inroads.
</P>
<P>
   In this context the religious rebellion in Morrope has become
the top story in many Peruvian newspapers and news broadcasts since
Sunday, when townspeople showed a newly appointed priest, the Rev.
Pedro Vasquez Reano, to a mule _ a not too subtle hint that they
wanted him to go away. The standoff devolved into a rock and
brick-throwing fight between supporters of the two priests that was
broadcast across Peru.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only sin,'' Arbanil Rico said in an interview, ``is to
recognize my children and support them. The rule of celibacy is a
rule of the hierarchy, not a rule of the people of God. The
hierarchy is not the church; the church is the people of God.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico is a soft-spoken, pudgy man who, at least at first
meeting, does not appear to be ready to fill Martin Luther's shoes.
He does not express particularly deep thoughts, and his only
pastimes _ walking and reading magazines and newspapers _ mark him
as a simple man.
</P>
<P>
   But his words are revolutionary. ``The pope,'' he said, ``is a
member of the faith like any other Catholic. He just has an
administrative function.'' Nevertheless, Arbanil Rico said he was
thinking about making a personal appeal to Pope John Paul II to
review his case.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Guillermo Rouillon, national coordinator of the National
Movement for Dialogue and Life, an organization of 100 mostly
retired priests, estimated that as many as 40 percent of Peru's
3,700 priests ``have children, but they can't talk about it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Priests have had children since the Spanish came here four
centuries ago but nobody wanted to talk about it until now,'' said
Rouillon, 62, who left the priesthood 30 years ago and has been
living with the same woman for 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Jesus Moline Labarta of Chiclayo, who stripped Father
Arbanil Rico of his parochial duties, refused to discuss the case.
But the Bishop's private secretary, the Rev. Rolando Monteza, said
the matter of priests having children ``is not a big problem for
the church.'' He predicted that ``eventually the people of Morrope
will accept their new priest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Peruvian Episcopal Conference, the highest governing body of
the church in Peru, supports the bishop's position. The Vatican has
not commented.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that this dusty town of adobe and straw 400 miles
northwest of Lima is deeply divided, despite a history of rebellion
and labor strife that goes back to colonial times, when the Mochica
Indians successfully resisted efforts by the Conquistadores to
build a church over their religious altar in what is still the town
square.
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico received only tepid applause from a crowd assembled
in front of the church last week when he defiantly cradled a
religious statuette on the steps during a procession recreating a
medieval pageant in which ancient Indian deities are transformed
into the Wise Men. Still, on the same day, he was warmly received
by more than 50 people in a shantytown when he said Mass under a
makeshift hut decorated with colorful plastic flowers, a Nativity
scene and Peruvian flags.
</P>
<P>
   ``According to the Bible, it is never a sin to have children,''
said Melchor Valdera, a 30-year-old fisherman who attended the
street Mass. ``We support our priest.''
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico has not had a textbook career.
</P>
<P>
   He was persuaded to study for the priesthood at age 17 by a
high-school religion teacher, the Rev. Carlos Flores Pajares, who,
Arbanil Rico said, lived with a woman and had two children. ``At
the seminary,'' he said, ``for us, celibacy meant not marrying.
They did not speak of virginity.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arbanil Rico said he remained a virgin through the first few
years of his priesthood. Then he met a distant cousin at her
mother's birthday party, and he said there was an instant
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico would not identify the woman nor his two sons, age
15 and 17, who he said lived in Lima. But he said that he has not
had sexual relations with the woman for many years, and that he has
never slept with any other woman.
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico said he had told his bishop, the Most Rev. Ignacio
Maria de Orbejozo y Goicochea, of his children through another
priest, who served as an intermediary. He said he was ordered not
to sign the birth certificates of his sons after each was born, but
he disobeyed orders.
</P>
<P>
   Through the intermediary, Arbanil Rico said, the bishop told him
he could continue working in his parish as long as he kept his
fatherhood a secret. But last May, de Orbejozo y Goicochea died,
and was replaced by a less forgiving bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Arbanil Rico said the new cleric, Bishop Moline Labarta,
discovered his secret in private personnel files.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't care about the several priests in his files who
have children but don't recognize them,'' he said. ``My sin is that
I am willing to say that I have children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
