<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6006 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-AXWORTHY-550&AMP;A     01-09 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-AXWORTHY-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANADIAN ROUSTS DIPLOMACY (AND RUFFLES THE U.S.) 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ As a graduate student at Princeton University in the
1960s, Lloyd Axworthy spent many nights at the old Madison Square
Garden in New York watching greats like Dave DeBusschere, Walt
Frazier and Bill Bradley outplay almost everyone in the league.
</P>
<P>
   It did not help his studies, Axworthy concedes, but the New York
Knicks' approach to basketball did help him develop a game plan
that has made him the most successful Canadian foreign minister in
years, and also the one who has most antagonized Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody asks me to define Canadian foreign policy, I say,
`Take a look at the Knicks of the DeBusschere, Frazier, Bill
Bradley era,''' Axworthy said. ``They were a bit slower than other
teams, and they were not as big, but they were crafty.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada has been a small, poky player on the international scene,
but in his three years as head of Canada's foreign ministry,
Axworthy, a former college professor, has made waves, often by
running up against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He was instrumental in getting the international treaty to ban
land mines signed in Ottawa in 1997, even though the United States
opposed it. Canada was center court on the push to establish an
international criminal court, once more against the wishes of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   He does not support NATO's use of nuclear weapons, he does not
want Canada to increase military spending substantially, and last
week he visited Cuba again to embrace Fidel Castro's Communist
government despite continuing U.S. efforts to isolate Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Canada has a leadership seat on the U.N. Security
Council, Axworthy has made it clear he intends to use the position
to try to limit the veto powers of the United States and the
council's other four permanent members.
</P>
<P>
   But what upsets Washington most about Axworthy is the way his
policies often ignore the different responsibilities that Canada
and the United States have in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The United States objected to the international criminal court,
for example, because there were no controls to insure that it would
not be used maliciously against American officials involved in
missions like the one in Iraq, again something of little concern to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we have greater responsibilities, we have to look at
other aspects than do the Canadians,'' a senior American diplomat
said, ``and sometimes we would appreciate more understanding from
Axworthy of the different relationships we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy bristles at the suggestion that he or his initiatives
are anti-American. ``Look at the record,'' he said during an
interview in Toronto, where he had stopped recently to tape two
television appearances. ``There's no question that there are
differences. But they're not differences that are designed to be
anti-American.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Axworthy made clear that while it might seem he
is out to poke a stick in America's eye, he is not. But still, he
refuses to consider the United States ``the indispensable nation''
that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright has declared it to be.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful nation, for sure, he said, and probably the
most influential, too. ``But I think we can show from time to time
that things can happen without the United States being a
participant,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   However many his critics in Washington, and in Canada, Axworthy
has unquestionably put the diplomatic corps through its paces in a
way not seen since Lester Pearson, the Canadian diplomat and
foreign minister and a personal hero of Axworthy, won the Nobel
Peace Prize in 1957 for proposing the use of peacekeeping forces to
settle the Suez crisis.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada's government, ministries like foreign affairs are
headed by members of Parliament. Axworthy, a Liberal, just
celebrated his 25th year as an elected politician from Winnipeg,
Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   For Canadian politicians, taking a stand that is independent of
the United States has long been a way to win support at home.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy, 59, says he played the anti-American card himself,
earlier this decade, when he was free trade critic for the Liberal
opposition. ``I might have done that in the past, but I don't do it
now,'' he said. ``If anything, I really try to bend over backward
not to be critical of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in the north end of Winnipeg, in the Canadian plains,
and said that doing so helped him develop an affinity for and
understanding of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But as a liberal whose approach to politics was formed in the
1960s, he believes the world has changed more since the Cold War
ended than the United States is willing to accept.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, most conflicts now occur within nations, rather
than between them. Casualties increasingly are civilians rather
than soldiers. As a result, traditional diplomacy has also been
transformed from the aloof maneuvering of statesmen to protect
national sovereignty to the concerted efforts of individuals and
organizations to care for people.
</P>
<P>
   It was such a coalition, with the aid of small countries like
Canada and Norway, that successfully pressed more than 120 nations
to sign the land mines treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy believes that Canada and other small nations can lend
moral authority to help solve such problems. ``It's not a position
that makes me very popular with the striped pants crowd,'' Axworthy
said, ``but I think it has a resonance with the public.''
</P>
<P>
   The striped pants crowd of traditional diplomats, backed by
academics and conservative columnists, indeed has trouble
swallowing Axworthy's brand of pulpit diplomacy. ``He has a
romantic progressivist vision of Canada as a multicultural
coalition against the rich and greedy West,'' wrote The National
Post. But ``he has forgotten that Canada is a part of the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Axworthy clearly believes that even though the United States is
the world's only superpower, countries like Canada can set the
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States is a player it makes it so much easier,''
he said, ``but we can still do it without them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
