u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEAMSTERS-ART-NYT &LR;      01-09 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEAMSTERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAMSTERS LEADER KNOWN FOR HONESTY MAY BE EXPELLED
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thomas O'Donnell, a newly elected vice president at large of the
Teamsters, obtained the second-largest vote total in last month's
union election _ only the new president, James Hoffa, received more
_ yet faces possible expulsion from the union.
</P>
<P>
   Long considered one of the most honest leaders in a union never
known for probity, O'Donnell, the president of a New York Teamsters
local since 1961, insists that he is being railroaded over
accusations of filing false campaign reports. He says his career is
being jeopardized.
</P>
<P>
   A court-appointed review board has charged O'Donnell with filing
false campaign finance reports in 1996, when he ran on Hoffa's
slate in Hoffa's unsuccessful campaign for union president.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, the board said, sought to hide that Kevin Currie,
Hoffa's New York campaign manager that year, was a convicted felon.
Specifically, O'Donnell, who hired Currie, is accused of not
reporting that Currie received a salary and of concealing $12,700
in salary payments by making them to the campaign manager's wife.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against O'Donnell have assumed unusual importance
because they are an embarrassing blow to Hoffa, son of the famous
Teamsters leader, and because Hoffa and his chief of staff, Tom
Pazzi, may face similar charges. The two approved separate campaign
finance reports that listed payments for Currie that went to his
wife, Mary Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa has repeatedly denied making false statements about this
and other campaign finance matters.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffa lost the 1996 race to Ron Carey, but a new election was
ordered last year because three Carey aides siphoned money from the
union treasury into the Carey campaign. Hoffa _ and O'Donnell _
easily won the rerun race.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell is one of three vice presidents elected on the Hoffa
slate who face board charges that could lead to anything from
acquittal to expulsion from the union. O'Donnell is accused of
``bringing reproach'' upon the union _ an elastic term that allows
the review board, set up to oversee the union under a federal
consent decree, to punish those accused of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell, president of a 270-member local made up of drivers
for filmmakers, television stations and concert halls, does not try
to hide his frustration about the charges. They are the first
charges he has faced since joining the Teamsters union 48 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried hard to avoid this type of stuff,'' O'Donnell said
in an interview at his office in Lake Success, N.Y. ``It's
embarrassing to me and my family. It's embarrassing to my
members.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell insisted that he did not want to hire Currie, even
though there was no union ban on employing convicted felons in the
campaign. He explained that Pazzi, previously Hoffa's national
campaign manager, pressed him to hire Currie.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell said that he interviewed Currie before hiring him and
that Currie said he had never been convicted of a crime. Soon
after, O'Donnell said, he learned that Currie had been convicted of
grand larceny, and he again told Pazzi that he did not want to hire
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   But because Pazzi insisted, O'Donnell said, he hired Currie.
O'Donnell vowed not to pay Currie directly because he had lied
about the conviction. Instead, O'Donnell gave Currie's $700 weekly
check to Mrs. Currie, who was a part-time campaign worker. The
checks were made out to her.
</P>
<P>
   But the review board's charges state that O'Donnell told federal
monitors that one reason he decided to give the payments to Mrs.
Currie rather than Currie was to disguise that a felon was on the
campaign payroll. That, the board said, was not an innocent reason
for hiding Currie's role.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell insisted that he in no way hid Currie's role. He noted
that Currie maintained a pro-Hoffa Web site, had business cards
printed listing himself as the New York campaign manager and was
often listed on campaign finance reports when he was reimbursed for
campaign expenses.
</P>
<P>
   The review board will soon hold a hearing on the charges,
brought by the board's in-house prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell sounded pessimistic, saying the board unfailingly
finds against accused officials. O'Donnell's many supporters insist
that expelling him would cause the Teamsters' executive board to
lose one of its most honest officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
