<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-GOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAP AMONG REPUBLICANS OVER TRIAL WASN'T TOO WIDE TO BRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the privacy of the Senate Republican cloakroom,
a gaggle of senators was furiously working on ground rules for
President Clinton's impeachment trial when Majority Leader Trent
Lott suddenly appeared on television with his Democratic
counterpart, Tom Daschle.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican senators, including Slade Gorton of Washington,
Mike DeWine of Ohio, John Ashcroft of Missouri and Fred Thompson of
Tennessee, stopped what they were doing Thursday afternoon to watch
the announcement of a rare bipartisan meeting of the full Senate
set for the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Within moments, the senators were alternately cheering and
criticizing Lott, applauding his leadership one moment and groaning
over a poor choice of words the next. ``It was like being in the
parents' section at a high-school football game,'' said one aide
who watched the spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The plan that Democrats and Republicans unanimously approved
Friday, allowing the Senate to start an impeachment trial in
earnest this week, emerged from the unusual joint meeting in the
Old Senate Chamber. But the contours of that plan were hammered out
last week by a fractious Republican caucus that often pulled Lott
in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans control the Senate, by 55 to 45, and on Thursday
they could have imposed their will on the Democratic minority. At
the last minute, mainly because of objections raised by Olympia
Snowe of Maine, Republicans pulled back from the brink of a strict
party-line vote on competing plans, fearing that would brand them
as partisan as House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But even before engaging the Democrats, Republicans had to reach
accord among themselves, senators said, bridging ideological,
generational and institutional divides.
</P>
<P>
   Lott stood in the middle of this political maelstrom and
suffered sniping from colleagues. But he let senators vent their
feelings and assigned deputies to hash out details with Democrats.
And Wednesday, Lott presented Republicans with a plan that tried to
be fair to all parties without bogging the Senate down for months.
It became the basis for Friday's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in uncharted waters, and Trent Lott has had a
responsibility that would weigh heavy on St. Peter,'' said Sen.
Chuck Hagel, R-Neb.
</P>
<P>
   In seven hours of closed meetings over two days that led to
Friday's momentous joint conference in the Old Senate Chamber,
Senate Republicans veered from solemnity and sadness to passionate
pleas and an occasional jibe.
</P>
<P>
   Even as senators approached their task with grave purpose, an
edginess crept into many of the discussions. At one point, Lott
mulled aloud whether the caucus should hire a strong outside
counsel to help guide senators through the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a former federal prosecutor and counsel on the
Watergate committee, shot back with a suggestion that some senators
took as a barbed joke. ``I got just the guy for you: Dickie
Scruggs,'' Thompson said, referring to the Mississippi lawyer who
is Lott's brother-in-law and who helped negotiate last year's
tobacco settlement that later collapsed in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a damn low blow, Fred,'' Lott replied, senators said.
</P>
<P>
   The question of calling witnesses at the trial divided Senate
Republicans from Democrats. But Republicans were divided among
themselves, as well.
</P>
<P>
   Allies of Lott, including Gorton, Thad Cochran of Mississippi
and Mitch McConnell of Kentucky, backed a bipartisan plan to avoid
witnesses by holding early test votes on the two articles of
impeachment. But several Republicans, many of them conservatives,
refused to support that approach, which they said would
short-circuit a credible trial with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The witness debate boiled over in one of two meetings on
Thursday, senators said, when Sen. Ted Stevens of Alaska said that
with crises brewing in the Balkans and North Korea, the Senate
should move quickly to a bipartisan resolution, even if that meant
jettisoning witnesses the House managers wanted. Sen. John
Ashcroft, a conservative from Missouri, immediately challenged
Stevens, a Senate fixture, saying, ``What do we stand for if we're
willing to throw witnesses overboard?''
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over witnesses also revealed a generational rift
between old-guard senators like Stevens and Sen. Pete Domenici of
New Mexico, who feared that calling witnesses like Monica Lewinsky
could demean the Senate's institutional integrity, and younger,
conservative firebrands like Jeff Sessions of Alabama, Tim
Hutchinson of Arkansas and James Inhofe of Oklahoma, who said a
trial with witnesses was the only way to render justice.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal for witnesses on the part of the House managers who
will present the case against the president got mixed reviews from
senators, depending in part on whether Senate Republicans had first
served in the House themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those senators who are former House members feel strongly that
we should let the House managers present their case,'' said Sen.
Susan Collins of Maine. ``Those of us with no ties to the House are
more concerned about our roles as jurors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideology was not always a good indicator of a senator's
position. Ms. Collins and Sen. John Chafee of Rhode Island, both
moderates, nonetheless voiced arguments for calling a limited
number of witnesses to help untangle conflicting testimony.
</P>
<P>
   For many back-benchers, the caucus meetings were a chance to
offer emotional speeches that tapped personal experiences.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Conrad Burns of Montana, a former marine, invoked vivid
images of Omaha Beach to underscore that senators, too, sometimes
have to fulfill painful and unpopular responsibilities. ``This is
an issue that lives in the back of your mind and gnaws at you,''
Burns said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The meetings did have their lighter moments. When Sen. Frank
Murkowski of Alaska stood up to speak, Sen. Phil Gramm of Texas,
who was sitting in front of Murkowski, piped up in his Texas twang:
``Go up to the microphone, Frank. I want to see your face.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dutifully, Murkowski walked up to the front and started to
speak, only to be interrupted by Gramm: ``Well, gosh, Frank, on
second thought, come on back and sit down.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1257EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAROLE-DEBATE-ART-NYT     01-09 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAROLE-DEBATE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIMINATING PAROLE BOARDS ISN'T A CURE-ALL, EXPERTS SAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By FOX BUTTERFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifteen states so far have taken the politically popular step of
abolishing parole boards, a vestige of what most Americans regard
as a failed system of penal rehabilitation, and last week New York
Gov. George Pataki proposed to make his state the 16th.
</P>
<P>
   But based on the experience of the other states, there is no
proof that eliminating parole boards reduces crime, while it can
lead to a further increase in the already swelling prison
population, criminologists and other experts say.
</P>
<P>
   For politicians promoting tough-on-crime platforms, it can have
an unintended consequence: Connecticut, Colorado and Florida
reinstituted parole boards after eliminating them because the
resulting increase in inmates crowded prisons so much that the
states were forced to release many of them early.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a number of prison experts, including some who warn that
eliminating parole boards could lead to shorter time served for
less serious crimes, say the parole system is such a failure that
abolishing it does not make much difference. Scrapping parole
boards, they say, could save money that might be used on more
effective anti-crime programs.
</P>
<P>
   The parole system, like the modern prison, was an American
invention in the 19th century. It consists of two parts, parole
boards that have the authority to decide when to release prisoners,
and parole officers who supervise convicts after their release.
</P>
<P>
   Under Pataki's proposal, New York would follow other states by
eliminating the authority of the state parole board while keeping
released prisoners subject to supervision by parole officers.
</P>
<P>
   One argument against eliminating parole boards is that an
inmate's release then becomes automatic, at the end of a set term.
</P>
<P>
   ``You decrease the ability to keep very dangerous offenders in
prison,'' said Joan Petersilia, a leading authority on parole who
is a professor of criminology at the University of California at
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In California, Prof. Petersilia pointed out, the convicted
kidnapper Richard Allen Davis was rejected six times by the parole
board, but after the state passed a law ending parole, he was
released automatically because he had served a sufficient amount of
time; a few months later he murdered 13-year-old Polly Klaas.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts caution that the public's discontent with the
parole system has also led to a change in the role of parole
officers that is contributing to more ex-convicts being returned to
prisons, swelling their populations.
</P>
<P>
   As the penal system has moved away from rehabilitation, parole
officers have been transformed from social workers who helped
offenders find jobs or get drug treatment to law-enforcement agents
who are more concerned with surveillance, from electronic
monitoring and curfews to drug tests.
</P>
<P>
   In California, 80 percent of parolees are failing to complete
parole successfully. In 1997, 57 percent of the people entering the
state's prisons were parole violators, not criminals convicted of
new crimes, Professor Petersilia said.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the parole system is so flawed that parole
boards may as well be eliminated, but they caution that politicians
should be honest with the public about the cost of lengthening
prison sentences.
</P>
<P>
   If all inmates serve longer terms, ``you will break the bank,''
said Martin Horn, Pennsylvania's secretary of corrections and a
former executive director of New York's Division of Parole. One way
to avoid that, he said, is to sentence less serious criminals to
shorter terms.
</P>
<P>
   As for parole officers, Horn said, past efforts in New York have
shown that when more money is spent on them, reducing their case
loads, they tend to find more violations among their parolees,
leading them to send more back to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Horn suggested that New York could achieve a more cost effective
crime policy by taking the $260 million it spent on its 60,000
parolees last year and spending some of it on vouchers that would
enable parolees to get drug treatment and job training, and the
rest on anti-poverty programs that would help reduce crime.
</P>
<P>
   New York's chief criminal justice official, Katie Lapp, said
Pataki's proposal to end parole had been carefully studied to
insure that the public knew how long criminals would actually spend
in prison, and that she did not expect a jump in the number of
inmates as California has experienced.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast with California, Ms. Lapp said, only 20 percent to
25 percent of the offenders sent to prison in New York are parole
violators, a sign that parole officers in New York are more
thoughtful about their approach.
</P>
<P>
   The movement to abolish parole began in the late 1970s after
academic studies suggested that rehabilitative efforts in prison
and early release on parole for good conduct had no measurable
effect on reducing repeat offenses. Among the states that have
eliminated parole boards are Arizona, California, Delaware,
Illinois, Indiana, Kansas, Maine, Minnesota, Mississippi, Ohio,
Oregon, New Mexico, North Carolina, Virginia, Washington.
California counts itself among these states, although its parole
board still considers a handful of cases of inmates who are serving
life sentences. The federal prison system has also gotten rid of
the boards.
</P>
<P>
   Only one state, Maine, has taken the additional step of dropping
its system of parole agents to supervise inmates after their
release.
</P>
<P>
   As the nation has embraced harsher punishment for violent
criminals, those states that still have boards have moved to
restrict their authority to less serious criminals. And parole
boards have become more hesitant to grant release. In Texas, the
proportion of eligible inmates approved for parole in 1998 dropped
to just 20 percent, from 57 percent in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   But the three states that eliminated parole and subsequently
re-established the equivalent of parole boards did so after finding
that abolition did not increase actual time served, because prisons
became so crowded that some inmates had to be released early.
</P>
<P>
   There is no statistical evidence that abolishing parole boards
has lowered crime rates in any state, the experts say. But they
acknowledge that keeping serious criminals in prison longer
undoubtedly prevents some crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Allen Beck, chief of corrections statistics at the Bureau of
Justice Statistics, a branch of the Justice Department, said that
ending parole by itself ``has had no real impact on time served.''
Time served is going up everywhere, in states that still have
discretionary parole boards and states that have abolished them, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1258EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
