</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATIVE COMPETITION BETWEEN HOUSE AND SENATE HEATS UP
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It was a slip of the tongue, and not necessarily
Freudian. But after Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott referred to
Rep. Henry Hyde, the Republican chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, as a senator Thursday, a careful observer could
practically see the steam rising from other senators' heads.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry Hyde did not get elected over here,'' fumed Sen. Bob
Kerrey, D-Neb., drawing a sharp distinction between the House of
Representatives and the smaller, more exclusive club to which he
and Lott belong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do a deal across the aisle,'' Kerrey said, referring to
the quest of Senate Democrats and Republicans for a bipartisan plan
for the trial of President Clinton. ``But we can't do a deal across
the Capitol.''
</P>
<P>
   As the trial of President Clinton opened last week, it laid bare
yet another rivalry and set of resentments, revealing that while
members of the House and Senate work in tandem and in sequence to
pass the nation's laws, they do not always work in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many House members, senators can be an aloof,
arrogant lot, too cavalier about foiling the House's best-laid
plans, too distracted by an inflated sense of themselves and their
responsibilities to roll up their starched sleeves and get anything
done.
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of many senators, House members can be impulsive,
intemperate adolescents desperately in need of the adult
supervision that the Senate so patiently provides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The House of Representatives was intended to be a raucous,
undisciplined reflection of public passions,'' said Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., on Friday. ``It's certainly fulfilled the
Founding Fathers' expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   As senators struggled through the week to come up with a plan to
avert a lengthy trial that would rummage anew through the details
of Clinton's relationship with Monica Lewinsky, it became clear
that some of them saw their task as mopping up the partisan mess
that they felt the House had left them.
</P>
<P>
   It also became clear that part of their investment in doing so
was the preservation of their image of themselves as a more
cool-headed convention. In speeches during the Senate meeting
Friday morning that led to an initial trial plan, senators said
that their body could not afford to let its reputation be dirtied
the way the House's had.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many Republican members of the House saw the
situation differently, and had already made clear that they
distrusted the Senate to focus on the charges against the president
as thoroughly as the House had.
</P>
<P>
   ``A senator's attention span is probably less than an average
juror's, so we'll have to simplify, simplify, simplify,'' said Rep.
Bob Barr, R-Ga., a member of the House Judiciary Committee, in an
interview about a week and a half ago.
</P>
<P>
   Parliamentary rules laid down by Thomas Jefferson two centuries
ago, when he was vice president, forbid members of the two chambers
from sniping at each other, but that has never stopped them.
</P>
<P>
   They are simply too different to see eye to eye. Because the 435
members of the House represent smaller, narrower constituencies and
their two-year terms guarantee faster turnover, they form a more
diverse, flamboyant cast of characters than do the 100 senators,
with their six-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that comparison flatters the House or the Senate depends
on the vantage point of the person doing the comparing.
</P>
<P>
   Leon Panetta, a former congressman from California, recalled
that he had a very different view of the House of Representatives
when he first came to Washington as a legislative assistant in the
Senate in the late 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole attitude of the Senate at that time was to look at
the House and consider them an unruly lynch mob,'' Panetta said in
a telephone interview Friday, adding that he shared that
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you're a member of the House,'' Panetta continued,
``you think: `I'm closer to the people, I know what people think,
I'm much more in touch with their concerns, and the Senate is the
high-minded body that's not really in touch.' Your mentality
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Panetta said that sometimes, when colleagues from the House left
to become senators, they suddenly upgraded their wardrobes and
shortened the circumferences of their social circles. ``It's the
difference between the East Side and the West Side of New York,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the rivalry between House members and senators can be
traced to the envy that many members of the former group feel.
Senators have bigger offices and more individual power.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other sources of animosity as well. Because House
members serve on fewer committees and have smaller staffs, they
often develop a more thorough mastery of a given subject than their
colleagues in the Senate, who can nonetheless scuttle their
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   But while the rivalry can be bitter, it can also be friendly,
and many lawmakers have a sense of humor about it, admitting to
aspects of the caricatures their rivals paint of them.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that senators, who would be constrained from making
statements during many phases of a trial, might not like ceding the
spotlight to prosecutors from the House, Sen. Christopher Dodd,
D-Conn., said Friday, ``This may have the most salutatory effect on
moving the process expeditiously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
