<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REVIVES PROPOSAL TO EXPAND MEDICARE
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MEDICARE-REVIEW)  
 (bl)  
By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his new budget request, President Clinton will
again ask Congress to open Medicare to people 55 to 64 years old,
administration officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the proposal died in Congress last year, Clinton will
resubmit it, in part because he is concerned about the erosion of
private insurance coverage among people 55 to 64, the officials
said. Medicare now covers people who are 65 and older or who are
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   The number of people without health insurance rose by 4 percent
in 1997, to 43.4 million, the Census Bureau said. The number of
uninsured people age 55 to 64 rose more sharply, by 7 percent, to
3.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said they also intended to propose
cutbacks in Medicare payments to hospitals. The cuts, in the range
of $5 billion to $10 billion over five years, would reduce spending
by 1 percent to 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said such cutbacks were justified
because a federal advisory panel had found that hospitals were
making relatively high profits on their Medicare business. The
panel, the Medicare Payment Advisory Commission, said last month
that hospital profit margins averaged nearly 16 percent on patients
admitted overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives said the figures were misleading because
one-fourth of all hospitals were losing money on their Medicare
inpatient business. And hospitals of all sizes said that they had
much lower profit margins on Medicare payments for outpatient
services.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., introduced a bill to carry
out Clinton's proposal to expand Medicare last year. Under that
proposal, people ages 55 to 64 could have bought Medicare coverage
by paying premiums of $300 to $400 a month. People 62 to 64 who
chose this option would also have had to pay surcharges on their
premiums after they reached the standard eligibility age of 65.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says the proposal is needed because
commercial insurance is often unavailable or unaffordable for
people age 55 to 64.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says its new proposal would cost $1.4 billion
over five years, and the Congressional Budget Office has made a
similar estimate. But some insurance experts said last year the
plan would not work in the long run because it would attract sicker
patients. As premiums were raised to cover the cost of such
patients, they said, healthier people under 65 would drop out, and
the program would lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, who control Congress, have shown little interest in
Clinton's plan. But the idea of allowing more people to purchase
Medicare coverage will be seriously considered this year as
Congress weighs proposals to increase the eligibility age and
redesign Medicare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1301EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6014 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PA-PRISONER-ABORTION-     01-09 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PA-PRISONER-ABORTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRISONER IS THE FOCUS OF AN ABORTION DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILKES-BARRE, Pa. _ Five months pregnant, her belly just
beginning to show through the orange prison jumpsuit, Karen
Ptaschnik has become an unlikely lightning rod for the abortion
debate here.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ptaschnik, a 30-year-old single mother of three young
children, is serving a 15-to-24-month sentence in the Luzerne
County jail for selling cocaine and driving with a suspended
license. This fall, when she told the prison authorities that she
was pregnant and wanted an abortion, they said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw it as an elective procedure, not the emergency or
necessary medical care we pay for,'' said Thomas Makowski, the
Luzerne County commissioner. ``Even though she said she would pay
for it herself, we weren't certain she could. We're elected to
represent a constituency, and this boils down to how you use
taxpayer money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ptaschnik went to court, with the help of New York
abortion-rights lawyers, and, in November a federal judge said that
the county must pay for abortions as a necessary medical procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Although the case broke no new legal ground _ the federal
appeals court had previously upheld inmates' right to publicly
financed abortions _ here in this staunchly Catholic area it has
become a tangled saga of how abortion politics can play out far
from big-city clinics and Washington policy debates.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear precisely how Ms. Ptaschnik's request for an
abortion became public knowledge, but as word spread, it became
headline news, covered so extensively here and in Hazleton, her
hometown, that everyone in town seemed aware of the situation.
Bishop James Timlin of the Scranton diocese formally denounced the
court order.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, an abortion doctor seeking to practice here was kept
out after anti-abortion groups collected 100,000 signatures against
him. Anti-abortion sentiment runs just as strong in this old mining
center today: Ms. Ptaschnik's request brought taunts from fellow
inmates and harassment to her children.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ptaschnik never had the abortion. At the Allentown Women's
Center, awaiting the procedure, she changed her mind, worn down by
months of harassment, she said, and beginning to feel the life
stirring within her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I began asking for an abortion at four weeks,'' she said. ``At
that point it's not so real. But when you feel the baby move, it's
very real.''
</P>
<P>
   In prison and out, she and her children _ especially the eldest,
7-year-old Jayme _ were hounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone came up to Jayme and told her I was going to kill her
unborn baby brother or sister, and maybe I would kill her next,''
said Ms. Ptaschnik, who has been in prison for a year. ``There was
a baby doll with a knife in it left on our porch. And in my bunk,
someone left a baby-name book with a note saying `Choose a name for
your baby's grave.' People left me pictures of aborted fetuses.
There are no secrets in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not announce that she was still pregnant when she
returned to prison from the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in, one of the girls got down on her knees, in
the middle of the kitchen, and said she prays for all the unborn
children,'' said Ms. Ptaschnik, who grew up in New York in a Jewish
family. ``The girls and the prison officials said that I don't
deserve to have babies, that I'm a good excuse for court-ordered
sterilization.''
</P>
<P>
   While the public debate is framed in terms of tax expenditures,
anti-abortion beliefs play a role: Makowski told one newspaper that
Ms. Ptaschnik's change of heart answered his prayers, and another
commissioner described himself and his colleagues as ``pretty
adamant pro-life supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ms. Ptaschnik's court order nor the fact that she is
having the baby, has entirely resolved the issue. Makowski says he
will still take inmate requests for an abortion to a judge. ``I'm a
lawyer, so I would never violate a court order,'' he said. ``But
every case is a different fact situation, and there are enough
nuances so I think we'd take each one back to court.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is it really over for Ms. Ptaschnik. ``My children will
never have a fair chance here,'' she said. ``Parents tell their
kids things about me, and the kids aren't so nice to Jayme. She'd
just about cut off a limb for a friend right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ptaschnik said she agonized before deciding that an abortion
would be the best thing for her, her children and her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids need more attention from me, not less, and my mother
is having to take care of them, at a time of life when she should
be off doing whatever she wants,'' she said. ``I don't think
abortion is right or wrong. It's whatever a woman can live with. I
think it's important that I showed you don't lose your
constitutional rights just because you're in prison, but it all
should have been private.''
</P>
<P>
   The children live with Ms. Ptaschnik's mother, but on a recent
snowy day they were staying with Maureen Rousseau, who lives in the
other half of Ms. Ptaschnik's modest twin house and often cares for
the three children.
</P>
<P>
   Starting last August, because of good behavior, Ms. Ptaschnik
was allowed to go home each weekday to care for her children,
feeding them dinner before returning to the halfway house where she
and others on child-care or work release were allowed to do their
own cooking and laundry.
</P>
<P>
   But on Dec. 14, at a hearing attended by her children and Ms.
Rousseau, Ms. Ptaschnik's child-care leave was revoked and she was
returned to the restrictions of the main prison building. She was
denied Christmas furlough, too, and has not seen her children since
the hearing, which she is convinced came in retribution for her
abortion battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a popular person around here,'' Ms. Ptaschnik said.
``They're furious that I took them to court on the abortion, and I
heard people say they were going to get me one way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Bernard Brominski said he revoked the child-care leave
because the circumstances surrounding Ms. Ptaschnik's pregnancy had
not been satisfactorily explained.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 18, three days after Ms. Ptaschnik won child-care leave,
the father of her youngest child, himself in and out of jail,
appeared at her home, drunk. Unscheduled visits to a prisoner on
child-care leave are prohibited. But the man _ whom she describes
as the love of her life, although his beatings have landed her in
the hospital _ has visitation rights for his 2-year-old son, Jason.
</P>
<P>
   When he threatened violence, she said, she sent the children to
Ms. Rousseau. Ms. Rousseau said that Ms. Ptaschnik had not expected
the visit and had tried to keep the man out. He left only when the
police arrived and charged him with public drunkenness _ and only
after the sexual encounter that left Ms. Ptaschnik pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made a big deal about how I didn't file rape charges,''
Ms. Ptaschnik said. ``But this is Jason's father. And when he's not
drunk, he's a wonderful man.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ptaschnik objected when prison officials sent Catholic
social services to counsel her about her pregnancy; she perceived
it as governmental meddling, not counseling. But she is now
gratefully accepting Catholic social services' aid with her legal
and medical bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say I should put the baby up for adoption, but I
could never do that,'' said Ms. Ptaschnik, whose earliest release
date is in May, right before the baby is due. ``I was adopted
myself, and you feel that if you're not good enough for your own
mother to keep, how can you be good enough for anything else in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   For some who oppose abortion, Ms. Ptaschnik's continuing
pregnancy seems a sort of victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased she's having the baby,'' said Betty Caffrey
of Pennsylvanians for Life, adding that she still does not
understand the court ruling. ``I don't see why we as taxpayers
should be forced to be part of something we don't want. I don't
know where in Roe vs. Wade it says a prisoner can break her
sentence and go off and get an abortion.''
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights supporters have asked the county for a policy on
handling future inmate abortion requests. And Makowski said the
prison board's lawyer is researching how state and federal prisons
handle the situation, looking for a way to keep from paying for
abortions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which covers
Pennsylvania, ruled in a New Jersey case that inmates had a
constitutional right to an abortion. While a few other courts have
issued similar rulings, it is impossible to say how prisons
actually handle the situation, because so few cases come to light,
said Simon Heller, of the Center for Reproductive Law and Policy, a
New York advocacy group that represented Ms. Ptaschnik.
</P>
<P>
   But, Heller said, a Nov. 20 order by Judge Edwin Kosik of U.S.
District Court, that future requests for abortion be ``honored as a
necessary medical procedure,'' leaves no legal wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   Legal issues aside, Ms. Ptaschnik said, the whole mess has taken
a toll on her already messy life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm left in a worse situation,'' she said, ``and so are my
kids.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
