<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE ODDEST COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To watch Jets receivers Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne
Chrebet play off each other, to watch them block for one another,
it seems apparent that they have a unique relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, they have been close all season, forming the most
prolific receiving tandem in the National Football League with a
total of 158 catches. Johnson made 83 of those receptions for 10
touchdowns and Chrebet made 75 for eight touchdowns. Each gained
more than 1,000 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they have been at the forefront of the Jets' evolution
from a 1-15 team two seasons ago into the 12-4 team that will play
the Jaguars in an American Football Conference Divisional Playoff
game Sunday at the Meadowlands in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship is indeed unique, but these two are not
joined at the hip, or anyplace else. Their common denominator is
quality play. They do their jobs, congratulate each other with a
tap _ never a hug _ dress silently at their adjacent lockers and go
their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the odd couple. It is the oddest couple.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson even declined to discuss his relationship with Chrebet.
Chrebet has no qualms talking about their football connection, and
dismisses as irrelevant the fact that they never talk about any
other part of their lives, nor see each other once the pads are
off.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that way since Johnson's rookie season in 1996 when
he joined the team as the NFL's top draft choice, instantly
declaring himself the team's top receiver.
</P>
<P>
   But it was after that season, when Johnson published his
breathless book _ ``Just Give Me the Damn Ball!'' _ that tension
between the two became apparent. The book was devoted to the
frustrations of playing for a 1-15 team and, in addition to
speaking of the failings of quarterback Neil O'Donnell, coach Rich
Kotite and the offensive coordinator Ron Erhardt, it labeled
Chrebet as the team's ``mascot.'' In fact, Chrebet is listed 17
times in the book's index, prompting Chrebet to once say, ``I'm
flattered that he's so obsessed with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the book's publication widened the distance
between the pair. And yet, somehow, it does not seem to have
affected the team when the two are out on the field together.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, something has happened in recent weeks that makes it
seem as if these fellows aren't as far apart as some people think _
or as they think.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, Chrebet has begun talking as a confident,
I-want-the-ball kind of player. And Johnson, with steamrolling
success that includes his first Pro Bowl selection, has joined
Chrebet as the consummate team player.
</P>
<P>
   Don't invite them to the same party just yet. Here is Chrebet,
short _ he likes to think of himself as standing 5 feet 10 inches _
and muscular, wearing T-shirts and jeans and his old college cap.
Who even knew about this guy when he showed up in 1995 out of
Hofstra, whose national acclaim as a football power was somewhat
less than Southern Cal's?
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets' depth chart had gone that deep, Chrebet would have
been listed as the No. 10 receiver. But with his extraordinary
ability to hold on to the ball, to run exquisitely precise routes,
to be fearless over the middle, Chrebet blossomed into a big-league
receiver with 66 catches in his first season, the second-most among
NFL rookies.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, along came Johnson. He made his own depth chart.
He was the first player chosen in the entire draft, the all-America
out of USC, whose team he had led to a Rose Bowl victory with 12
catches.
</P>
<P>
   Before he had even signed a Jets contract, he donated his USC
jersey to the Official All Star Cafe in Times Square. He came
equipped with an Adidas contract, as well as the book deal, and
knew who Giorgio Armani was.
</P>
<P>
   As the Jets' fate would have it, the pair was squeezed together
in a corner of the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   There would sit Chrebet, usually dressing quietly, face down
toward his open locker. Alongside, towering over everyone at 6 feet
3 inches, Johnson would be holding court for the news media. Camera
operators, photographers and reporters of all kinds would push past
Chrebet to surround Johnson, the loudest _ and probably most
talented _ rookie the Jets had seen since the days of Joe Namath.
</P>
<P>
   The differences between the two go well beyond football. While
Chrebet was raised in the suburbs in Garfield, N.J., the son of a
Vietnam veteran, Johnson grew up in Los Angeles amid troubled
circumstances. He once spent a few nights with his mother sleeping
in a car when there was a family dispute over the ownership of an
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   He spent time in a correctional facility as a teen-ager after
committing a series of street crimes. But he not only went to USC,
he graduated. He is proud of that degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always told me I wouldn't be able to do certain
things,'' Johnson said. ``I keep doing them.''
</P>
<P>
   People have forgotten about his criminal infractions. It took
longer to make others forget about his book.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Chrebet was asked this week about his relationship
with Johnson, he said: ``I'm always surprised when people ask
whether I block for him or he blocks for me. Of course we do.
There's not even a question about it. I compliment him when he does
something well and he does the same for me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Glenn Foley, who began this season as the Jets starting
quarterback and has regularly worked out in the off-season with
Chrebet, is certain that it would show if either player carried
negative feelings about the other onto the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything negative on the field,'' Foley said.
``It would be obvious, believe me. I saw it in college. But
whatever their problems are, if any, they're both professional. You
never see it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hayes, a defensive back and special teams' star who rooms
with Johnson on the road, said Johnson never talks badly about
Chrebet. He said Johnson is high-strung before a game, getting only
four or five hours' sleep, and sometimes wakes up Hayes to discuss
plays with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, Keyshawn's style is to be the go-to guy,'' Hayes said.
``But anything happens on the field, he compliments Wayne. I never
heard Keyshawn say anything bad about Wayne. He thinks Wayne's a
good player. I think they'll both be remembered for what they've
done with the Jets. Keyshawn's a tough big guy, Wayne's a tough
little guy. Both love the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while this season, Chrebet's jersey was the best-selling
item in the National Football League catalog. In recent weeks,
Johnson's has overtaken it, perhaps because of his Pro Bowl
selection.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is taking some receivers to Hawaii as guests for the
game; Chrebet is going at Vinny Testaverde's invitation. But
Chrebet said that is merely because he and the quarterback had made
a pact: If either one was selected to play in the Pro Bowl, the
other would go as his guest.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Chrebet and Johnson will be together after all when
the season ends. They simply will be making separate reservations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
