<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MARLINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLINS: ON THE WAY BACK UP?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   These names are known little, if at all, beyond their own
households, but they have something in common: Armando Almanza,
A.J. Burnett, Joe Fontenot, Braden Looper, Rafael Medina, Jesus
Sanchez, Ramon Castro, Derrek Lee.
</P>
<P>
   This group has something in common, too: Jorge Fabregas,
Guillermo Garcia, Preston Wilson. So do these two: Justin Speier,
Kevin Orie.
</P>
<P>
   The first group is players the Florida Marlins acquired in
trades for players who were on their 1997 World Series championship
team. The second group is players the Marlins obtained for other
players they had received in deals for players who were on their
1997 world championship team.
</P>
<P>
   The last two players? The Marlins got them in a swap for one
player who was on their 1997 World Series championship team and one
player they acquired for a player who was on their 1997 World
Series championship team.
</P>
<P>
   All 13 of these players have one more thing in common: They are
on the Marlins' 40-man major league roster that this week will
become the property of John Henry, the man on whose watch the
Marlins will rise to the heights they enjoyed for a split second 15
months ago, or fall _ well, they can't really fall any farther than
they have.
</P>
<P>
   When Henry is approved by the major league owners at their
meeting in Carlsbad, Calif., this week, he will replace the
expansion franchise's original owner, H. Wayne Huizenga, who played
havoc with the Marlins' fans' emotions.
</P>
<P>
   No sooner had Craig Counsell crossed home plate with the
Series-winning run in the 11th inning of the seventh game in 1997
than Huizenga was plotting the dismantling of the championship
team. He didn't do the dirty work himself. That's what he was
paying Dave Dombrowski, his general manager, to do.
</P>
<P>
   He also had paid Dombrowski to build an instant winner, and
Dombrowski did an admirable job, hiring Jim Leyland to manage, and
signing in the space of a year Moises Alou, Bobby Bonilla, Devon
White, Al Leiter, Alex Fernandez, Kevin Brown and Livan Hernandez
as free agents.
</P>
<P>
   The returns are not in on the job Dombrowski has done in
demolishing Huizenga's team. He got rid of all of the high-priced
players, which is what his boss directed him to do, but it is
premature to judge the value of the players the Marlins received in
return.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski has traded 17 of the 25 members of the World Series
team, the most recent, shortstop Edgar Renteria, just four weeks
ago, a few weeks after the Marlins learned he was eligible for
salary arbitration. In return for those 17 players, the Marlins
received 27 young and inexperienced players.
</P>
<P>
   Dombrowski turned around and traded 7 of those 27 for 10 other
players. After selling one player and losing another in last
month's minor league draft, the Marlins have a net of 28 players
from the largest-scale destruction of a championship team since
Pharaoh's soldiers drowned in the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of the 28 players, seven of them pitchers, are on the
Marlins' 40-man roster. Three are expected to be in the 1999
starting lineup: first baseman Lee (one of three players acquired
for Brown), third baseman Orie (one of three players obtained for
Felix Heredia and Steve Hoff, who had also been in the Brown trade)
and catcher Fabregas (swapped for Oscar Henriquez, who was one of
three in the Alou deal).
</P>
<P>
   Two are expected to be in the starting pitching rotation:
Sanchez (one of three received for Leiter) and Medina (the third
player in the Brown swap).
</P>
<P>
   How good are these or any of the other young substitutes?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to assess some of those guys,'' a personnel expert
with another club said. ``Some of those players they got in trades
were rushed to the majors because of the void left by the trades.
Derrek Lee is a perfect example. If he was in Triple-A last year,
people would be saying he's a superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who had a solid but not spectacular season in Class A the
year before, batted only .233 for the Marlins, 60 points below his
cumulative minor league average.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez was another player who was in the major leagues last
season because the Marlins needed him. Bypassing the Class AAA
level of the minors, Sanchez had a 7-9 record for the Marlins. He
could have used the year to better advantage at AAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not everyone they got is a great player,'' the executive said.
``I'm sure there will be some who will be legitimate everyday
players, maybe a couple of star-type players. They have guys who
were highly thought of in other organizations.''
</P>
<P>
   Five of the organization's top 10 prospects, as rated by the
publication Baseball America, are players the Marlins received in
those trades. That's a good sign if the Marlins are viewed as
having a strong organization otherwise, and they are.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the top four prospects are trade acquisitions, led by
Burnett, another pitcher the Marlins got in the Leiter deal.
Burnett, who just turned 22, had a 10-4 record and a 1.97 earned
run average in Class A last season.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, in a two-week span, the Marlins traded away
the two pitchers they got from Houston for Alou, Henriquez and
Manuel Barrios. They actually traded Barrios a second time, having
sent him to Los Angeles in the Mike Piazza deal, then claimed him
off the waiver wire.
</P>
<P>
   When the Marlins got Henriquez, they thought the big
right-hander would someday be their closer, but he gained too much
weight and lost too much velocity on his fastball, a deadly
combination.
</P>
<P>
   It is this type of unpredictability with young players that
Henry, the new owner, is inheriting. He has been reluctant to talk
about the Marlins until he is approved as the owner, but he has
acknowledged some of the problems he faces, including the team's
credibility with fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, it's going to be a major undertaking, a
very big challenge, to try to win back the fans,'' said Henry, a
49-year-old commodities trader, who must sell his slightly more
than 1 percent share of the Yankees. ``They've been angered.
They've been upset, first by the dismantling of the team and then
the loss of the All-Star Game. I have a lot of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins were supposed to be host to the All-Star Game in
2000, but Major League Baseball felt uneasy about circumstances in
south Florida and put the Marlins further back in line, giving them
time to get a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's a necessity,'' Henry said, ``and it's going to
determine whether or not the Marlins will be able to compete. There
will be other things, but that will be a primary factor.''
</P>
<P>
   A new stadium will be one of Henry's first priorities, right
there with building a winner and winning back the fans. Those fans
may want to note that unlike H.Wayne, the initial in Henry's name,
W., comes after John, not before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
