<HEADER>
A6027 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-SENATE-N     01-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IMPEACH-SENATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAPITOL COUPLES
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Jan. 10:
</P>
<P>
   Think of ``Profiles in Courage'' or ``Mr. Smith Goes to
Washington,'' and you have a popular image of the Senate: a place
where principled individualism and collective deliberation reign.
The daily reality usually falls short of the idealized images. But
Friday's accord on the rules for the impeachment trial of President
Clinton did offer a stirring picture of divergent ideologies
blending together for the greater good. The odd-couple cliche got a
heavy workout in news stories about the sudden flowering of
bipartisan comity.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is the Senate was guided to its goal by the forming
of several striking partnerships: Trent Lott and Tom Daschle, Slade
Gorton and Joseph Lieberman, Phil Gramm and Edward Kennedy. It is
worth pondering how and why these tandems formed around the common
goal of saving a political institution from itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today we have acted in the very best tradition of the
Senate,'' said Lott, the majority leader, in announcing a plan to
finesse the witness issue, which will move the Senate toward its
proper goal of censuring Clinton for lying under oath. Lott
credited Robert Byrd, the keeper of the lares, with a timely
invocation of the burden of Senate history.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Lott and the minority leader, Tom Daschle, who mixed
the glue. They made a striking pair, Lott looking starched, pressed
and polished, yet with an unmistakable glint of anxiety in his eye.
He had opened himself to intramural attack by saying he wanted the
Senate trial to be short and credible.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Daschle looked like a rumpled survivor of an
all-night poker game. He was, in fact, playing the only hand he
could, the threat to withdraw the bipartisan approach Lott craved,
and he won a bigger pot than the White House had any right to
expect. The Lott-Daschle rules will make it extremely hard for the
House prosecutors to put on live testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Lott nominated Gramm and Kennedy as the most unlikely team. A
rock-hard critic of Clinton and an early exponent of a full trial,
Gramm is also a stickler for Senate rules. He probably liked the
fact that these rules allow the GOP to look generous while leaving
room to ram through witness summonses if war breaks out. As a
Senate veteran, Kennedy had the experience to recognize the best
possible deal when it came. As a liberal icon, he could provide
cover for other Democrats to grab it.
</P>
<P>
   On the House side and in the most conservative corner of the
Senate, Republican partisans still hope that a parade of witnesses
will at last break the spell of the president's popularity and
convince the public that he should be tossed instead of
reprimanded. Among some Democrats, there lingered the belief that
Clinton could survive a vote on removal and escape without any of
the punishment he deserves. Managing these delusions has been the
job of the pioneer odd couple, Gorton and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Gorton has a hard-knuckle reputation that forced other
Republicans to take him seriously as a conciliator and as an
in-house envoy on behalf of Lott's plan to avoid a long, detailed
trial. Lieberman brought an interlocking credibility as the first
important Democrat to voice stinging, moral criticism of the
president's personal conduct and betrayal of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a set of such formidable pairings, certain conditions
were required. Given its history, there is one force that always
trumps partisanship in the Senate. That is the desire to make both
the White House and the House look shortsighted and craven.
</P>
<P>
   The next election also played a big role. The Democrats are
willing to defend a presidency they regard as a burden in order to
get calmer seas before 2000. Among Republicans, 13 of the 19
senators up for re-election in the year 2000 come from states
carried by Clinton in 1996. Lott clearly fears he could lose the
Senate if a trial became a free-for-all.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, everyone who rallied to history and to duty also
harbored dreams of victory and dreams of defeat. Such dreams are
the stuff that deals are made of.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
