<HEADLINE>
SPECULATING ON AMERICA'S CUP CHALLENGER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Md., Hawaii)  (jw) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's Cup yacht racing has taken on an immediacy with the
beginning of the new year. Challengers are scrambling to get their
sailboats built in time for autumn trial races in New Zealand. But
observers are speculating on which teams will make it at all.
</P>
<P>
   Two national yachting magazines, one English, the other
American, recently published predictions of which teams would
prevail. But already the reshuffling has begun.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dennis Conner announced that his America's Cup
program was taking over Team Caribbean, the yachting syndicate that
Peter Holmberg founded in the U.S. Virgin Islands. The Caribbean
team was unable to raise enough money to support a viable America's
Cup effort.
</P>
<P>
   Holmberg, meanwhile, will compete with Conner aboard his new
Stars &AMP; Stripes, the traditional boat name for Conner's cup
contender. Sailing as helmsman on Stars &AMP; Stripes will be Ken Read,
a two-time national yachtsman of the year. As with his cup campaign
of 1995, Conner will manage the team, but still sail.
</P>
<P>
   Conner's cup merger leaves 15 teams of the original 16 that each
invested $350,000 in performance bonds to compete in the Louis
Vuitton Challenge Selection Series.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of that four-month set of trials, which begins Oct.
18 in Auckland, will sail against Team New Zealand, defender of the
America's Cup. The cup match between the final two boats _
challenger and defender _ begins Feb. 19, 2000. In the meantime,
more campaigns are likely to falter _ even before the challengers'
trials begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a couple of side bets with people,'' said Dyer Jones,
president of the America's Cup Challengers' Association, during a
recent trip to New York. ``The numbers range from 9 or 10 through
12. I'd be very happy if we had 12 in the Louis Vuitton Cup. I
certainly see weaknesses with some of the teams, as many others
do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the February issue of Sailing World magazine, to be mailed to
subscribers this week, the cup challenge teams are broken into
three tiers.
</P>
<P>
   The first set, the ones considered most likely to succeed at
becoming challenger, are listed in order: first, Prada, the team
from Italy; second, Young America, the New York Yacht Club group;
third, Nippon, the Japanese team, and fourth, America One, the
campaign founded in San Francisco by Paul Cayard.
</P>
<P>
   The projections were made by Gary Jobson, a veteran of five cup
campaigns who is now ESPN's America's Cup commentator. ``New
Zealand is for sure the favorite to win the America's Cup series,''
Jobson said in a telephone interview last week from Annapolis, Md.
``They have the funding, and they are testing like crazy, both off
and on the water.''
</P>
<P>
   In his assessment of the six (now five) U.S. teams, Jobson
wrote: ``At the minimum, the Americans should freely scrimmage with
each other, for at the moment, American prospects are not strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Seahorse, a British magazine, came out with an article in
December by Rod Davis, a former America's Cup helmsman who is now a
coach for Prada.
</P>
<P>
   Davis omitted his own group from the assessment to avoid a
conflict of interest, but said, ``I would not be with a team that I
did not think would be in the hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   Evaluating each of the other 15 challenge entries, he assigned
points based on sailing ability, funding, design work and the
x-factor, his gut feeling about potential.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, like Jobson, gave Team New Zealand the best chance of
ultimately winning the America's Cup races. As the sole defense
team, he gave the Kiwis 19 points.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Among challengers, he ranked Cayard's America One team next,
with 17 points. Third was the New York Yacht Club's team, with 16
points, and in a tie for fourth, with 14 points each, were America
True, the team of men and women founded by Dawn Riley in San
Francisco, and Team Aloha Racing, the Hawaiian syndicate founded by
John Kolius.
</P>
<P>
   Conner scoffed last week at the rankings, noting that boat
design would make the final difference. ``Rod Davis can have all
the conjecture in the world,'' Conner said. ``But it will all come
down to who has the fastest boat.''
</P>
<P>
   Being the underdog, in fact, has worked well in the past. Ed
Baird, skipper for New York's Young America team, pointed out
recently that Team New Zealand was considered a dark horse before
the 1995 cup races, then won. Baird should know; he was the Kiwi
team's coach then.
</P>
<P>
   ``They loved it, because it took the attention off them and the
pressure off them,'' Baird said. ``Now they're in a very different
position.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
