<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-VOTE-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIANS VOTE IN 2ND STEP TO CIVILIAN RULE
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAGOS, Nigeria _ Casting ballots on sidewalks, under trees, at
construction sites, next to a man selling yams, in garages and
countless other neighborhood spots, Nigerians elected governors and
state legislators Saturday in voting that is the second step in the
military government's plan to restore civilian rule by May.
</P>
<P>
   The streets in this city of 7 million people were deserted of
cars, as drivers were kept off roads and people walked to voting
areas. Nigeria's borders were sealed during voting hours, the most
dramatic of many steps taken to prevent ``magomago,'' or
vote-rigging in Nigerian slang.
</P>
<P>
   The vote in 35 of Nigeria's 36 states should give foreign
monitors further evidence of how fair next month's presidential
elections will be. Furthermore, the results should provide clues to
whether an emerging alliance between two of the three parties can
check the seemingly inevitable rise of Gen. Olusegun Obasanjo to
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Elections were canceled in Bayelsa state in the Niger Delta
region in the South after more than 20 people were killed in recent
riots. The Delta produces Nigeria's oil, but the country's Northern
military rulers have left the region desperately poor.
</P>
<P>
   It was too early to estimate voter turnout in this country of
108 million, although visits to several polling places in Lagos
suggested that turnout was low. Results in the races were not
expected until Sunday at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
   In Lagos, under a sky made hazy by the harmattan winds that have
been blowing down sands from the Sahara, voting appeared largely
peaceful. Violence erupted in at least one neighborhood, however,
when a group of men brandishing bottles and knives invaded a
polling place in Isale Eko, broke open four ballot boxes and
destroyed the cards, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, officials at polling places seemed better organized
than in December's municipal elections, when many showed up late
and did not have enough voting materials. Officials seemed to have
addressed one of the chief criticisms of last month's process: lack
of privacy. On Saturday, voters entered makeshift booths or ducked
under curtains hanging over tables.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any cause to complain about the process,'' said
Peter Olusegun, who was monitoring a site for the All People's
Party, a right-of-center grouping that is one of three parties to
have emerged strongly from December's elections. ``I have not
recorded any cases of cheating or malpractice. Things appear to be
better organized this time around.''
</P>
<P>
   The West African nation has experienced a bewildering six-month
period, which began with the unexpected deaths of its longtime
dictator, Gen. Sani Abacha, and its most revered opposition leader,
Moshood K.O. Abiola. It also has included sweeping political
reforms, ruinous unrest in the Delta region and the collapse of
worldwide oil prices.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Saturday, even typically skeptical residents of Lagos expressed
optimism about Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you vote and elect the person you want,'' said Idris
Elegushi, 18, at a polling place in Lagos, ``Nigeria will change.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting clearer in their minds about what they
want, and it's also getting clearer in people's minds that the
military will really hand over power,'' said Sinatu Ojikutu, a
former lieutenant governor of Lagos state and a member of the
centrist People's Democratic Party, which won 60 percent of votes
cast in December's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians voted six months after the death of Gen. Abacha, who
ruled Nigeria for five years, stole billions of dollars in oil
revenues and turned the country into an international pariah for
abusing human rights. The military has ruled Nigeria, the world's
sixth-biggest oil producer, for all but 10 years since gaining
independence from Britain in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Abacha's successor, Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar, carried out
a series of well-received political and economic reforms, including
municipal elections last month.
</P>
<P>
   Election monitors from the West described last month's municipal
elections as generally free and fair. Nevertheless, they warned
that the independent agency holding the elections needed to improve
how ballots were cast and collected in Saturday's vote and, most
importantly, in the Feb. 27 presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent National Electoral Commission warned in a
statement that the primaries leading up to Saturday's statewide
elections had been ``beset by all forms of irregularities,
intimidation and in some instances violence.'' Local and foreign
monitors who dispatched observers throughout the country are
expected to issue reports early next week.
</P>
<P>
   After last month's elections, three parties survived to present
candidates in the statewide and national races.
</P>
<P>
   Many leaders of the People's Democratic Party, which emerged
strongest in December's vote, include former political opponents of
Abacha. Chief among them is Obasanjo, who spent three years in jail
until Abubakar freed him in August.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo, who ruled Nigeria from 1976 to 1979 and gained lasting
esteem for being the only military ruler to hand over power to a
civilian government, is considered the leading presidential
candidate. He is the only one with nationwide recognition; even
though he is a Yoruba from the South, he is said to be trusted by
the Hausa-speaking military rulers from the North.
</P>
<P>
   The two other weaker parties, which occupy opposite ends of the
political spectrum, announced last week that they would present a
common candidate against Obasanjo in the Feb. 27 election.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Democracy, considered left-of-center and
strongest in the Yoruba southwest, includes former supporters of
Abiola, a Yoruba billionaire businessman who had appeared set to
win a presidential election in 1993 before the military annulled it
and imprisoned him. He died unexpectedly in prison last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The third party, the right-of-center All People's Party, has
been nicknamed ``Abacha People's Party'' for the presence of many
of the late general's allies. But its base in the North and East
means that a partnership with the Alliance for Democracy would make
strategic sense.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the two ideologically opposed parties have grown closer,
some members of Alliance for Democracy have tried to play down the
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now looking at ways to cooperate,'' said Kofoworola
Bucknor-Skerele, the Alliance for Democracy's candidate for
lieutenant governor in Lagos state, as she waited at a polling
place under an almond tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're not forming an alliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
