<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-FRANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLIES ARE COOL TO FRENCH PLAN FOR MONITORING IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ France and Britain conferred last week on the next steps
to take in Iraq, but French officials said on Friday that wide
differences still separated them.
</P>
<P>
   France would like Britain and the United States to agree in the
U.N. Security Council to lift the oil embargo against Iraq if
President Saddam Hussein consents to a new system of international
arms monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   The French proposal has met with little success with the allies
so far, and as a high-ranking French official said on Friday, there
was not yet any certainty that Saddam would agree to a permanent
control system.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China, also permanent members of the Security
Council, would have to approve as well.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Britain bombed Iraq last month after
Baghdad stopped cooperating with U.N. arms inspectors that the
Iraqis said were spies for the United States. Since then, the
United States has acknowledged getting information for the bomb
strikes from equipment the inspection teams used.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Hubert Vedrine of France discussed Iraq here
over breakfast on Friday with Britain's foreign secretary, Robin
Cook, but they made no statement afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``The British and the Americans at this point are insisting that
Iraq will be subject to continued bombing unless it agrees again to
inspections by United Nations Special Commission teams,'' a French
official said, referring to the arms inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe Iraq no longer has any nuclear capability, and
large quantities of chemical and biological stocks, we know, have
been found and destroyed by the United Nations teams,'' the French
official said. ``We do not believe there is any point in going back
in and continuing to look for the last test tube, because we'll
never find it. What we need is a new system of continuous
monitoring that allows us to make sure Iraq does not try to build
new facilities to acquire these things again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the French view, such a system would include both television
cameras and expert inspections to keep an eye on suspected sites.
But the French believe that the special U.N. inspection commission,
which has been led by an Australian diplomat, Richard Butler, will
never again be acceptable to Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   As an incentive to get Iraq to permit a new inspection system,
French officials said, the United Nations would lift the remaining
embargo against Iraqi oil exports but set up controls to make sure
Saddam did not spend any of the revenues on acquiring new weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But at this point, according to French officials, the United
States is unwilling to consider such ideas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
