<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GRAHAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: BILLY GRAHAM, AND US, THEN AND NOW
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (bl)  
By DUDLEY CLENDINEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aunt Carolyn was my godmother, and one November night she phoned
to ask if I would go with her to hear the Rev. Billy Graham in
crusade on a day three months away. I couldn't say no. I was 16. My
calendar was clear for 1961. And Aunt Carolyn's determination was
well known.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, to people in Tampa, Fla., Graham had the fame of a
local boy. He had graduated from Florida Bible Institute, just
north of town. Aunt Carolyn adored him. She was a Southern
fundamentalist, an Alabama country Christian. The Bible was her
law, and his, and she liked the way he strode around, showering
damnation and redemption, calling people to come to Christ.
</P>
<P>
   My father, however, had become a city man in the years after
World War II, an Episcopalian like my mother. When the night came
for Graham to preach, in an old stadium on the river where my
high-school football team played championship games, and stock cars
races threw up dirt and thunder on summer nights, Dad went too. He
sat between us, to block me from the impulse to run down the
bleachers to answer Graham's altar call. Liking stock cars more
than preachers, I was relieved. But Aunt Carolyn looked
disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Graham headed on to Fort Lauderdale, and larger places. He
preached in Madison Square Garden and Moscow, and almost 100
countries around the world, to more than 100 million people. He
spent too much time in Richard Nixon's White House, but regretted
it. This past year he turned 80, and two months ago he came back to
Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   He and the city had changed. The new stadium was huge, with
video screens and commercial promenades to entertain the
professional-football fans, and separate them from their money. Up
and down the road were other stadiums where George Steinbrenner's
Yankees and other teams play, new car dealerships, television
stations, strip bars. Country Christians like Carolyn are now
mainly dead and gone. The shores of Tampa Bay swarm with new
suburbanites, many of them just as fervent, more of them
Republicans, leading tanned but fragmented, modern lives. Some of
my schoolmates, pillars of the city now, who had gone down to the
altar in 1961, did not attend this time. But in four nights, more
than 280,000 people did, filling the stadium and its infield.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people, boomers in their early 50s like me _ Carolyn's
age in 1961, Bill Clinton's now _ are feeling mortal these days .
Exhausted by the harsh judgmental combat in Washington, we yearn
for love and reassurance, some source of faith, wisdom and sweet
reason. And there, at the pulpit, still at center stage, is Billy
Graham. In the time he has been preaching, mega-preaching in the
form of televangelism has come of age, and some would say,
overreached its place. The public record of its preachers _
Southerners, mainly, like Graham _ has been stained by grapples
with sex, power and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   But not Graham. He has never been involved in a scandal like
Jimmy Swaggart, or convicted of cheating his flock like Jim Bakker.
He has never played the moral autocrat like Jerry Falwell, run for
president or sold out his Family Channel audience to Rupert Murdoch
like Pat Robertson, or bullied Republican politicians like James
Dobson. It is partly in contrast that he looks so good.
</P>
<P>
   He is no Puritan. He simply preaches faith, and so people seek
him out. Thirty-eight years ago, in a stadium for 15,000 people, he
seemed big to me. Now, from the high seats in a stadium where the
Tampa Bay Bucs play Detroit, or Dallas or Denver, Graham seems an
old man, weakened by a decade of Parkinson's. Yet thousands of
people watched him on the video screens, straining to connect with
him, to be filled by his words.
</P>
<P>
   It may be that despite the physical work of the years, Graham
has stayed the same, and it is the need for his love and integrity
that has grown. It may be, in this splintered culture, that no one
can fill the pulpit he will leave whenever he goes.
</P>
<P>
   But other preachers and politicians should take note of the
qualities in him that people seem to reach for _ the tolerance, the
moral support rather than condemnation, the plainness, the
non-judgmental love. They are in very short supply right now, and
are sorely missed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
