<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GOP set to convene with contributors in Florida
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Top Congressional leaders and governors
are coming here next week for three days of private meetings and
golf with six-figure contributors to the national Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   While the Senate trial of President Clinton gets under way,
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., is scheduled to be the keynote
speaker at a ``Team 100'' dinner Friday night at the Four Seasons
Resort, according to a Dec. 9 invitation letter from the Republican
National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Team 100 are part of an exclusive club of
$100,000-plus contributors to the Republican Party. Members also
must contribute an additional $75,000 over a three-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the meetings took place at The Breakers hotel at
the same time that Congress was investigating questionable campaign
contributions to the Democratic Party. At the time, House Speaker
Newt Gingrich of Georgia cancelled his appearance because of the
controversy. Then he changed his mind, slipping in through a back
door and leaving the same way.
</P>
<P>
   Lott is a staunch defender of big contributors. Lott says there
should be no limits on how much money someone can give a candidate.
He also opposes public financing of campaigns, calling it ``food
stamps for politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   The event begins Thursday evening with a dinner at a private
home featuring Gov. Jeb Bush, who spoke to the crowd two years ago,
and other GOP governors. Friday morning begins with meetings with
Gov. John Rowland of Connecticut and U.S. Rep. John Kasich of Ohio,
who is considering a run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Reed, who heads the political consulting firm Century
Strategies, and Mike Deaver, a media strategist in the Reagan White
House, will discuss the outlook for the 2000 campaign. U.S. Rep.
Porter Goss of Sanibel, a member of the Intelligence Committee, and
William Kristol, editor of The Weekly Standard, will discuss
national security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson and Mel
Sembler, a Tampa businessman and the RNC's finance chairman will
also privately brief the contributors on campaign strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's luncheon speakers will be Sens. Connie Mack of Florida
and Fred Thompson of Tennessee, who also is considering a campaign
for president. He chaired the Senate committee that investigated
campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Most GOP members of the Florida delegation are expected to
attend at least part of the three-day event, which ends Saturday
with a golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   While the big money givers are at the Four Seasons Resort,
Republican Eagles, those who give $15,000, will be at the Breakers
Wednesday. Former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander, who is a
candidate for president will speak to the Eagles during a welcoming
reception at the Breakers.
</P>
<P>
   Schedules for both groups were still being modified and the list
of speakers could change depending on what is happening in Congress
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
