</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIE-DETECTOR10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Controversial lie detector a `tremendous' help in Ohio
 &HT;    By Lou Grieco
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Law enforcement agencies across the country _ and
across the Miami Valley _ have nothing but praise for Computerized
Voice Stress Analyzer, a new type of lie detector: The innocent are
cleared. The guilty confess. Cases are closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tremendous investigative tool,'' said Joseph Mahan,
chief deputy with the Miami County Sheriff's Office. ``It's been
quite effective for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also controversial. The FBI won't use the CVSA. Nor will
the Defense Department. Government scientists compare it to
flipping a coin.
</P>
<P>
   Manufactured by a former police officer who calls his 10-person
firm the National Institute for Truth Verification, the CVSA is
purported to be 98 percent accurate, according to company
literature.
</P>
<P>
   The company says the device is cheaper and easier to use than
traditional polygraph machines, can be used over the telephone or
television and even with tape recordings of people living or dead.
Drugs and medical factors that can throw off a polygraph don't
affect CVSA results, according to the institute.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 law enforcement agencies across the nation have
bought the lie detectors and use them to interview suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of criminals, convinced that the machine would detect
their lies, have confessed to crimes of every description, the
manufacturer says. Other suspects reportedly have been cleared in
part because the CVSA concluded they were blameless.
</P>
<P>
   In Cincinnati, a woman recanted her claim that she was raped. In
San Diego, detectives elicited a murder confession from teen-agers
in the death of a young girl. In Florida, a murderer confessed his
crime and implicated an accomplice.
</P>
<P>
   But government scientists say the CVSA doesn't work. They
concluded: You'd not only get better results with a polygraph, you
could do better flipping a coin.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Department, which considered the CVSA a potential
godsend in intelligence and international diplomacy, found in
laboratory studies an overall accuracy rate of 49.8 percent, or
slightly less than pure chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found no credible evidence ... that voice stress
analysis is an effective investigative tool for determining
deception,'' concluded Michael Capps, director of the Defense
Department's Polygraph Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But neither Mahan nor Lt. Jerry Mays of the Warren County
Sheriff's Office have had problems with the machines. Both said
they have on occasion backed up the CVSA with a polygraph. Every
time, they say, where the CVSA has shown deception, the polygraph
has as well.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the polygraph nor the CVSA are admissible as evidence in
Ohio courts. Mahan noted that neither test can be forced on a
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps lead us in the right direction,'' said Mahan. ``It is
nothing more than a mere investigative tool.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
