A6061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDLIFE-AGENCY-CASH1     01-09 0653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDLIFE-AGENCY-CASH10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refuge land buy hampered by U.S. cash shortfall
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Eight months ago, Jon Starnes and several
partners agreed to sell 200 acres of hunting land in northwestern
Travis County to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
</P>
<P>
   They are still waiting for the agency to come up with the cash.
And now it looks like they could be waiting a lot longer.
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife service, part of the Interior Department, is
getting nearly $4 million less from Congress this year for land
acquisition at the Balcones Canyonlands National Wildlife Refuge
than the agency had requested and anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The refuge, which is in northwestern Travis, eastern Burnet and
southwestern Williamson counties, was established in 1992 to
protect the nesting habitat of two endangered songbirds, the
black-capped vireo and the golden-cheeked warbler. The government
has acquired 16,000 acres toward its 46,000-acre goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the same position as a lot of people out there,''
said Starnes, a financial consultant who lives in Austin. ``They've
convinced us to sell, but where's the money?''
</P>
<P>
   The wildlife service is getting $3.5 million this year for land
acquisition for the Balcones refuge. It had requested $7.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Conservationists are charging that Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison
(R-Texas), a longtime critic of the Endangered Species Act,
exercised an unwritten rule of privilege and reduced the request.
Lisette Mondello, a spokeswoman for Hutchison, said the senator did
nothing of the sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do anything on this,'' Mondello said. ``We didn't
get contacted by the local community people about this, like the
chamber and other groups.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, business leaders and conservationists in South
Texas have advocated aggressively for the Lower Rio Grande National
Wildlife Refuge. That refuge, extending upstream from the mouth of
the Rio Grande, protects brushland for rare cats and migratory
birds. It is receiving $7.4 million this year for land acquisition,
the amount the wildlife service requested.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Rieff, senior director in Austin for the National Wildlife
Federation, a conservation group, criticized Hutchison for not
pressing to secure the Balcones refuge's fair share. Hutchison once
secured a moratorium on the addition of species to the endangered
list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vocal critics of the Endangered Species Act are always
saying that if the federal government wants to protect endangered
species it ought to buy the land,'' said Rieff, a former deputy
chief of staff for Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt. ``Here you
have a situation where a federal agency wants to buy it and someone
is intervening to say no.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has appropriated $21.2 million for the refuge, but
outlays have varied widely from year to year. For example, $5
million was appropriated in 1995, zero in 1997. The wildlife
service could spend $10 million a year on land acquisition for the
refuge if it had the money, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Holle, manager of the refuge, said the agency buys only
from willing sellers and does not condemn property.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have more willing sellers than we have money to buy land,''
Holle said. ``We have people on a waiting list. Some people are
going to have to make a decision: Do I wait for the refuge to get
money or do I sell it to someone else who wants to subdivide and
develop? Some people don't want their ranches developed.''
</P>
<P>
   Starnes and his partners were initially inclined not to sell.
But when they learned that their tract would be an important link
between other refuge parcels, they changed their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two hundred years from now, it'd be nice to have a big chunk
of public land like that that people could use and relate to,''
Starnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
