u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SINGH-NYT &LR;      01-09 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SINGH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH STARTS '99 WHERE HE LEFT OFF IN '98 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAPALUA, Hawaii _ Coming off the most successful year of his
career, Vijay Singh does not sound complacent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you've got to forget about what happened last year,''
said Singh, who won his first major at the 1998 PGA Championship,
and finished second on the PGA Tour's money list. ``Last year is
gone. You've got to focus on the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``My focus on every tournament is a little bit more this year.
Last year, a few tournaments at the beginning of the year, I just
tried to get through the first two rounds, see how you finish. This
year I'm more focused on playing solid all four days.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. Singh started Saturday in contention to win the
tour's season-opening Mercedes Championships. Standing at 11 under
par for the tournament (135, 70-65), Singh was in a three-way tie
for second with Fred Funk and Billy Mayfair, five strokes behind
David Duval (130), who tied the Kapalua Plantation course record
Friday with a 10-under 63.
</P>
<P>
   Catching Duval will be difficult, but Singh is the kind of
player who can do it. The 7,263-yard Plantation Course favors long
hitters, and with the wind expect to pick up Saturday, Singh's
power should give him an advantage over many players in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Singh's confidence is also an advantage. He was recognized as a
very good player before he won a major, but winning the PGA
Championship has changed the way people view Singh, and it has
slightly changed the way Singh views himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I won a major, I thought if I didn't win, it wouldn't
make any difference,'' said Singh, a native of Fiji who will turn
36 next month. ``But it does make a lot of difference to your
confidence. If you win a major, it boosts your confidence so much
higher than before. That's what it has done to me. You can go out
and win any golf tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh, one of the game's hardest workers, looked sharp during
the first two rounds of the tournament, and his consistency has
long been a trademark. From August 1995 through March 1998, Singh
made 53 consecutive cuts, and he has learned the importance of
being ready to play each week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've prepared for this year very well, and I've got a lot of
confidence coming in from finishing second on the money list last
year,'' Singh said. ``I'm looking forward to this year, and my goal
is to play solid in every tournament. If I can go out there and hit
solid shots, the result is going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh entered 26 PGA Tour events last season, and with three new
World Golf Championship tournaments on this year's schedule, he
expects to be busy again. Singh will qualify for all three World
Golf Championship events, as a member of last year's international
Presidents Cup team, ranked No. 9 in the world ranking. The world
events will each carry a $5 million purse, and Singh is looking
forward to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rewards are always good if you play well,'' Singh said.
``I'm going to play a lot of tournaments, probably 10 out of the
first 12 events. I feel like playing, I want to play, I feel fit to
play. I'm going to have a pretty full season until August. After
August, I'm going to take it easy. I've always done that, and
that's pretty much what I'm going to do this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Since adopting a cross-handed putting style last year, Singh has
been a consistent contender. He has always been known for his
ball-striking ability, but Singh struggled with his short game and
putting for most of his career. His improved putting has turned
potential pars into birdies, and potential bogeys into pars. And
knowing he has the ability to make putts has only increased Singh's
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't putt, you can't play,'' Singh said. ``It's as
simple as that. You can't win golf tournaments having 32, 33 putts.
You've got to have one or two rounds in the 20s. I've worked a lot
on my putting, and I'm beginning to get a lot more confident.''
</P>
<P>
   So if Duval slipped this weekend, Singh would be more than happy
to take the $468,000 first-place check, and the new car that will
be awarded to the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Singh enjoyed a special year in 1998. This year, he would like
to do even better. ``I think whoever putts well is going to have a
good chance,'' Singh said. ``I'm looking forward to this year. I've
got a lot of confidence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
