<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Chante LaGon, 404 526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Art Dalglish, 301 460-6176.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-BANANAS _ MIAMI _ A taste of the tropics, nearly everyone
loves potassium-rich bananas. But this delicate fruit has split the
United States and Europe in a nasty trans-Atlantic tug-of-war that
could soon spell trouble for American consumers. This week, the
Clinton administration is expected to announce that it will go
ahead with plans to slap 100 percent tariffs on $590 million worth
of European goods as soon as Feb. 1. The move is designed to force
the European Union -- which gives preferences to banana growers in
former colonies, particularly those in the Caribbean -- to open its
markets to bananas produced in Latin America by U.S. companies. For
U.S. consumers, the retaliatory measure could double prices on
everything from cheese to linens to candles to cashmere sweaters.
But even more is at stake than higher prices. Experts fear that one
retaliation could spark another, igniting a real trade war between
the United States and the European Union that could threaten
two-way trade estimated at
</P>
<P>
   more than $400 billion a year. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BANANAS-BOX _ MIAMI _ The imposition of increased tariffs as a
result of a banana trade dispute between the United States and
European Union would affect a number of European imports. The
following consumer goods are expected to increase in price if a
proposed U.S. tariff increase holds. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Thurs., Jan. 7, in the International and Financial
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   LEGACY _ Newt Gingrich leaves office after having accumulated
and exercised more power than any speaker since Joe Cannon. He
ignored the seniority system, gave his troops a short work week so
they could spend more time at home and took authority away from
committee chairmen. Some of those moves may not long survive. But
he also brought the House into the computer age, brought Congress
under many laws it previously could ignore and brought a
sophisticated media operation to the speaker's office. These
changes likely will last. (Sherman, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ A halftime report from the Microsoft
trial. With the federal case against the software giant now
complete, how effective has it been and what lines of defense
appear most promising? (Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Friday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   GA-INAUG _ Mainbar on Roy Barne's road to the governor's mansion
with smart treatment of how he expects to accomplish his agenda and
the obstacles he will have to overcome. This will be the session
where Barnes tests his power and displays his leadership abilities
for the first time. What are his priorities? HMO reform, tax
relief, regional growth/transportation solutions? What can he hope
to accomplish this session? Barnes will be sworn in on Monday.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL _ The 14th annual Stellar Awards, gospel music's premier
award show, plays out at Atlanta's Civic Center this afternoon and
early evening (Saturday), and features a parade of celebrities,
including Kirk Franklin, Fred Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ choir;
Lynn Whitfield, who starred in the 1997 film ``Eve's Bayou''; and
comedian Steve Harvey, star of the WB sitcom ``The Steve Harvey
Show.'' (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12-15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   DUANE-OWEN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Jury selection started this
week in the murder trial of Duane Owen, a chronic liar who has
confessed to murders in Florida and Colorado. This story chronicles
game of cat and mouse with detectives who have investigated his
stories. ( Stapleton, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Mug of Owens available.
</P>
<P>
   NEWDEAL _ Black farmers who were once promised 40 acres and a
mule when most of the blacks in the nation were on farms now have a
genuine New Deal. For some, a consent agreement reached with the
USDA that offers $50,000 cash and repayment of debts will give them
a new lease on life, but for others, including leaders of the black
farm movement, the proposal falls short and will be challenged anew
when federal Judge Paul Friedman calls them back into court in
February and March. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NEWDEAL-SIDE _ Interview with someone who will accept the offer
- a farmer from South Georgia named Willie Head, and some who will
reject it. Head, who has seen his wife and father die while he has
battled the USDA, says he has no choice. He needs the money to keep
his farm from being foreclosed and he will accept it, pay off his
debts and tell the USDA to go to hell. Those who will reject
include an Oklahoma farmer who feels he has been hit by
discrimination twice. When schools were desegregated his in the
1950s, he lost his job teaching. He got into farming with his dad
and became a millionaire, but lost it all after a bad spell put him
in the pocket of the USDA. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
40. WITH PHOTO (of Head).
</P>
<P>
   STAMPS _ Cost of mailing a standard first-class letter goes to
33 cents from 32 cents on Sunday. Are people lining up to buy penny
stamps? How will the postal authorities deal with letters mailed
after Sunday that have 32-cent stamps affixed? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WALLYS-WORLD _ The story of a sexual predator and how he landed
a job at Palm Beach Community College with only phone calls toi
references as background checks. The college is reviewing its
hiring practices and the former professor is somewhere doing
something and the worry is with whom and what. ( Peltz/Moffett,
Palm Beach Post). 50-60.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With mug shot of the professor.
</P>
<P>
   ARABS-JEWELS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How do you persuade a
Midwestern businessman, to whom you're trying to sell millions of
dollars worth of allegedly fake jewels, that you're a world-class
wheeler and dealer with a pipeline to the world's richest man?
Dress up a 340-pound bearded mechanic in silk sheets, put Arafat
headgear and sunglasses on a couple of employees, hire two hookers
as harem girls and strip the logos off your own private plane.
That's what witnesses say jeweler Jack Hasson did to fool Detroit
broadcasting tycoon Aben Johnson into thinking he was meeting with
``Prince Akhmed,'' nephew of the Sultan of Brunei, at Palm Beach
International Airport. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post). 40-50.
</P>
<P>
   LYONS _ Rev. Henry Lyons, embattled leader of the nation's
largest black Baptist group, goes on trial (Jan. 11) Monday in St.
Petersburg on charges that he and a one-time paramour siphoned
millions of dollars from the National Baptist Convention's accounts
to finance a lavish lifestyle. Lyons has managed to hold onto his
post as president of the convention, but may not be so successful
in court. Among the charges against him are that he took nearly
$200,000 intended to help burned-out black churches across the
South; swindled $3 million from corporations doing business with
the convention and spent money intended for black colleges on
himself and friends. We advance the trial, which is expected to
last a month. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WEALTH-GAP _ NELSONVILLE, Ohio _ This southeastern Ohio town on
the edge of Appalachia has become an outpost in a 1990s version of
class warfare. The Rev. Jesse Jackson and others are using its
poverty-scarred face to rally support for measures to bridge the
widening gap between wealthy suburbia and poorer inner cities and
rural areas. Next Thursday and Friday, Jackson takes will take the
story of Nelsonville to the epicenter of wealth, Wall Street, for a
two-day rally. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   COX-WEALTH-DATA _ Material for graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Cox photos for this story will be placed in the National folder
on the Cox server.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-GOP-MEETINGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Top Congressional
leaders and governors are coming here next week for three days of
private meetings and golf with six-figure contributors to the
national Republican Party. What's happened here in the past, and
what this gathering may hold. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIE-DETECTOR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Law enforcement agencies across
the country _ and across the Miami Valley _ have nothing but praise
for Computerized Voice Stress Analyzer, a new type of lie detector:
The innocent are cleared. The guilty confess. Cases are closed. But
it's also controversial. A look at its use in Ohio. (Grieco, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WILDLIFE-AGENCY-CASH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Eight months ago, Jon
Starnes and several partners agreed to sell 200 acres of hunting
land in northwestern Travis County to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. They are still waiting for the agency to come up with the
cash. And now it looks like they could be waiting a lot longer. The
agency wasn't granted the money it requested, and now others are
paying the price. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
