<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-YALE-GENES-NYT     01-09 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-YALE-GENES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: YALE GENE POOL SEEN AS ROUTE TO BETTER BABY
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Young women scanning The Yale Daily News over
the last year have found their eyes straying to advertisements
offering up payments of $7,500 _ not quite for them but for their
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperately Seeking Smart, Sensitive, Sunny Samaritan,'' went
one such ad. ``We are alumni looking for a donor match: A lovely
light-eyed lady with a quick, sharp laugh. Wit and warmth a must.''
</P>
<P>
   Egg donation is not news, of course. Through the process,
thousands of couples have healed the void of childlessness and
profoundly enriched their lives. But what takes the ads that have
appeared at Yale, Princeton, Harvard and other Ivy League schools
into an unsettling dimension is that the couples placing them are
insisting on a striking specificity _ going beyond requests for
blue eyes to demand Ivy League pedigree or 1,300 SAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   These couples seem to assume that if a young woman goes to Yale,
chances are her egg will end up at Yale, or the equivalent. That
not only ignores the alma mater of the sperm, but such things as
upbringing and the general capriciousness of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anything so smart about me,'' says
Isaiah Wilner, a Yale male who is the editor in chief of the campus
newspaper. ``What an Ivy League student is is someone who works
hard, whose parents pushed them to do their school work. That's not
genes.''
</P>
<P>
   Some chuckle when they read how frantic parents drag 4-year-olds
barely out of diapers to IQ tests for private schools, hoping they
will launch their toddlers on trajectories toward Harvard. Is it
any different to read of people plotting a Harvard future with a
microscopic cell?
</P>
<P>
   There's a related problem, notes Daniel Callahan of the Hastings
Center, a bioethics research institute in Garrison, N.Y. ``The risk
with these boutique babies is that parents will be unhappy with the
actual child,'' he said. ``You want children to have certain
traits, but a good parent accepts the child for who he or she
happens to be.''
</P>
<P>
   In a miraculous fertility business, many people assume they can
control everything. That's why some students boning up for another
semester beneath the Gothic grandeur of Sterling Library say the
ads make them squeamish. Egg donation is a remarkable innovation,
they say, but they are uneasy with the idea of ordering up a child
like a car, where pricey options like high SAT scores can be
specified as if they were anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some reservations about what seems to be modern-day
eugenics,'' said Elizabeth Manwell, a graduate student in classics.
``One can understand the desire of a couple to have a child that
resembles them. But it seems kind of fantastic to try to obtain
some kind of perfect child.''
</P>
<P>
   She and others squirm at advertisers who pointedly mention being
Yale alumni, as if a woman could be persuaded to undergo painful
egg harvesting just for old Eli.
</P>
<P>
   ``As someone who did not attend an Ivy League school as an
undergraduate,'' said Ms. Manwell, who graduated from the
University of Chicago, ``I'd wonder what's wrong with my egg.''
</P>
<P>
   The ads here are placed through Options National Fertility
Registry of Los Angeles, whose Web site allows a password-armed
couple to scroll through photographs and resumes of willing donors.
Yet some prospective recipients are not satisfied with the pool,
said Teri Royal, the director of Options, and want donors from the
same Ivy League schools they've attended.
</P>
<P>
   They advertise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to offer their child something that reflects who
they are as a person,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable, but there is also something of a whiff of
too much calculation, and a reluctance to accept that some things
in life may not be entirely fixable.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Royal estimates that 18 to 20 Ivy League women have donated
eggs. Perhaps that number suggests that Ivy Leaguers are too well
off to be seduced by $7,500. But possibly it's because Ivy Leaguers
like Maria Fruglio, a graduate student, realize that demanding such
precision from the crap-shoot process of reproduction may not be
that smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a child doesn't end up the way the parents envision,'' she
wondered, ``how will they treat that child?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1412EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
