<HEADER>
A6066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT &LR;      01-09 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following text accompanies the weather map for Sunday,
Jan. 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York Times
News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Dry air will spread over the Atlantic seaboard in the wake of a
cold front. Ample sunshine will prevail in most areas east of the
Appalachians. Afternoon temperatures will be several degrees below
the seasonal average.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, a cold front marking the leading edge of a surge
of Arctic air will move across the Great Lakes states. Snow showers
and squalls will be common as the frigid air gathers moisture in
passing across the warmer water. Intense snow squalls are expected
to reduce visibility to near zero in some areas east of Lakes Erie
and Ontario later Sunday and Sunday night as a jet stream
disturbance enhances the moist updrafts in the narrow roiling cloud
bands. Clouds and lighter snow showers will accompany the cold
front from the Ohio Valley to the west slopes of the central and
northern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine will prevail over most of the Southeast and southern
Plains. A band of thundershowers will move south over central and
southern Florida as drier air arrives behind a cold front.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, patchy light snow will occur near a front in the
northern Rockies and northern Plains. A moist air flow from the
Pacific will bring rain to the Washington coast and some showers in
the interior. Snow will fall in the northern Cascades and
Bitterroots of Montana and Idaho. Farther east, strong winds will
buffet some areas along the east slopes of the central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure will keep most of the Southwest mild and dry.
Offshore winds will bring unseasonable warmth to the southern
California coast. Dense fog will plague the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: The End of Chill
</P>
<P>
   While residents from the northern Plains to the Northeast will
be shivering in another Arctic onslaught early this week, the bout
with wintry weather that began around Christmas will soon end. The
Arctic chill that reaches the United States forms over the Canadian
tundra when clear skies and calm winds allow the ground to rapidly
lose energy. These conditions are found in zones of high pressure.
Now, pressures are falling across western Canada which will limit
the production of cold air. By late this week, the current supply
of Arctic air over the United States will be depleted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1413EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHURCH-BANKLOAN-AR     01-09 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHURCH-BANKLOAN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKS PUT THEIR FAITH IN BUILDING CHURCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LESLIE EATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The storefront was plain, the street unprepossessing,
and the skies sent down torrents of rain. But inside last Sunday,
more than 100 members of the New Jerusalem Church were rejoicing _
singing and dancing, swaying and shouting _ as their minister
thanked God, ``who makes us sit together in heavenly places.''
</P>
<P>
   As Bishop Altamont Blackwood said, ``there is no more heavenly
place than the church.'' And the congregation's new church,
complete with a bell tower and steeple, is rising on Springfield
Boulevard in Queens, just a few blocks from the commercial strip
that has been New Jerusalem's home for more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Though the congregation gives God most of the credit for the new
building, He does have a worldly partner _ the Chase Manhattan
Bank, which has lent the congregation more than $1 million for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   The bank is doing this not merely out of the goodness of its
corporate heart. Under the Federal Community Reinvestment Act of
1977, banks are required to lend money to help struggling
neighborhoods in which they do business. And at a time when
governments seem to have neither the will nor the power to help
with community redevelopment projects, Chase and other banks are
turning to God _ or at least, to some of his servants on earth _ to
do such work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided that these institutions are critical to the
communities we care about,'' said Carol Parry, the bank's executive
vice president for community development. ``Our ultimate objective
is to make those communities better places to live.''
</P>
<P>
   The theory behind the Chase program is fairly simple: If
churches are bigger and have more seats, they can attract more
parishioners, who will finance and work on more community projects.
It is mostly black churches that have received loans, though the
program is open to all types of congregations and faiths. The bank
also provides grants and technical assistance to religious
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Banks have a long history of lending money for church-sponsored
programs, like low-income housing. But financing church buildings
as a way to help communities is something new. (Chase made its
first such loan, for just $150,000, in 1994.) Other large banks,
like First Union in Charlotte, N.C., are also trying to increase
their involvement with churches, and the approach was featured at a
conference on community redevelopment in October organized by the
American Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   Churches across the United States have occasionally borrowed
from banks before, though often only with the help of wealthy
members willing to cosign the loans or to put up a lot of cash as
security.
</P>
<P>
   Black churches have had particular trouble getting loans, said
Albert Tew, a former commercial banker who as a consultant to
churches has helped arrange some loans, including New Jerusalem's.
``There aren't too many lenders who are aware of how
African-American churches actually operate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, however, banks are becoming aware of the critical
role churches play in poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church is the foundation of everything we do, in housing,
health care, and for senior citizens,'' said Edwin Reed, chief
financial officer of the Allen African Methodist Episcopal Church
in Queens. ``Seats mean revenue to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen's history serves as a sort of parable for those who
support lending to religious institutions. Membership in the
church, which was founded in 1834, has soared since the Rev. Floyd
Flake became pastor in 1976, when the church had 1,400 members and
a building that could seat 200.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the church has a congregation of about 10,000 and offers
three Sunday services at a new building that seats 2,500. The
congregation raised $10 million of the $25 million cost; the rest
was financed by a group of banks put together by Chase last year.
</P>
<P>
   The church has also become a major employer in Queens, running a
dizzying array of social programs. Even for such a powerhouse of a
church, getting a loan was not easy, for reasons Reed said he
understood. Not only can it be hard to figure out where a church
will get the money to repay a loan, he noted, but there is also the
question of collateral. No bank would want to repossess a church.
</P>
<P>
   If lending $15 million to Allen took an act of faith, lending $1
million to New Jerusalem took a real leap. After all, the church
has just 250 members, almost all immigrants from the West Indies,
and they are by no means rich.
</P>
<P>
   But what their leader does have is a financial track record. Now
52, Blackwood has been preaching since he was a teen-ager in
Queens, and he came to the United States in 1970. Within seven
years, he had scraped together enough money to make a down payment
on a little building where he started his church, whose full name
is the New Jerusalem Church of God in Christ Jesus (Apostolic) Inc.
The $57,000 building was paid for in three years.
</P>
<P>
   When it was started, his congregation had only five members _
all related to him and living in the small apartment over the
church, Blackwood recalled. He remodeled the building himself,
moving the bathrooms, finishing the basement, painting the tiny
office.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the sanctuary has wood-paneled walls, a dropped ceiling
and wall-to-wall carpeting; the wooden pews are supplemented with
folding chairs when the crowd gets too big, as it often does.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Blackwood found a vacant lot for sale; he raised and
borrowed enough money for the down payment and got a five-year
mortgage from the owner. Within three years, he and the
congregation had paid off the $127,500 cost of the land.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation has also raised hundreds of thousands of
dollars for the new church, one of the reasons Chase was
comfortable making such a large loan to such a small group, said
Earlene Hampton, vice president of Chase Community Development
Corp., the unit of the bank that made the loan last spring.
</P>
<P>
   How has the congregation come up with so much cash? And how will
it cover the roughly $150,000 annual mortgage payment?
</P>
<P>
   The church does some fund raising. It sells oranges from Florida
and sponsors bus trips to family-oriented spots like the theme park
Sesame Place in Langhorne, Pa., said Maria Angus, the church's
secretary. Elfreda Moore, a 78-year-old matriarch of the church,
sells hats outside the doors on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the money comes out of church members' pockets. Many
of them tithe, giving a tenth of their incomes to the church, and
they also contribute to special fund-raising campaigns, Blackwood
said. ``Some folks that give it, give their last mite,'' he said.
``but they find such favor and love in what we are doing that they
give what they have to give.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Certainly they seem to be giving with joy. At last week's noon
service, the plate was not passed; rather, members filed to the
front of the church to contribute money and checks. Once the
offering was completed, Clara Pettigrew led the choir dancing down
the aisle and then back up to the front, as everyone sang that they
would ``Walk and Talk in the New Jerusalem Way.''
</P>
<P>
   It does not hurt the fund-raising effort that neither Blackwood
nor the assistant ministers receive a salary from the church.
Blackwood owns a small hardware store, and his wife works at
Jamaica Hospital Medical Center. Although he supervises almost a
dozen Apostolic churches in and around New York, he continues to
live simply and to spend the church's money very carefully, said
Tew, the consultant.
</P>
<P>
   The people who give the most will get the best seats in the new
church _ and those seats will be grand. Pews for 650 people will
fill the floor and balcony under a soaring wooden ceiling. Glass
blocks in the stone walls will form stylized crosses in the front
and back of the huge room. There will be enough space on the dais
up front for all the ministers and elders, the senior and junior
choirs, and even a baptismal pool.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement, there will be room to serve hot lunches to 270
needy people, and to expand the church's free food distribution
program. These programs are now run out of the old church's cramped
basement, which does not have a kitchen or enough exits to
accommodate much of a crowd. That old building will be turned into
a church-sponsored day-care center.
</P>
<P>
   These plans were crucial in Chase's decision to give the church
a loan, Ms. Parry said. And so was confidence that the church's
congregation would grow to fill the new church.
</P>
<P>
   The median household income in the mostly black neighborhood is
about $58,700, according to projections by the Queens College
sociology department. The mostly single-family homes in the
neighborhood are small but neat; many of the commercial areas,
however, are far less prosperous-looking.
</P>
<P>
   The new church is replacing decrepit buildings on land that was
being used as an illegal dump, church members say; it sits between
two open lots, their fences festooned with signs advertising
everything from used cars to goat meat.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwood hopes to acquire these lots someday, to add more
parking, perhaps even to build a school. But for now, he is just
trying to restrain his impatience to see the church completed, and
to plan a ceremony for the grand opening, which he hopes will be in
March.
</P>
<P>
   And, along with his congregation, he is counting his blessings.
The list last Sunday was long _ the service lasted almost three
hours _ and included all kinds of things, spiritual and physical,
including the new church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't dream he would lend us more than $1 million to build
a church, just a small group of people as we are,'' Blackwood said,
referring to God, as exclamations of ``Jesus!'' and ``Hallelujah!''
rose from the congregation. ``He made a way where there was no
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
