<SLUG> BC-NY-CONEDISON-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CON ED WORKERS PROTEST UNION'S TAKEOVER OF LOCAL AND LEADER'S
OUSTER
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Thousands of Con Ed workers are angry at their
Washington-based parent union for taking direct control of their
10,000-member local in July and ousting their popular leader, who
plans to ask a federal judge to reinstate him.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 members of Local 1-2 of the Utility Workers
Union of America have signed a petition protesting the decision to
remove their leader, Joseph Flaherty, and put the union into
trusteeship. Flaherty's supporters, who say he was a forceful
leader who had obtained improved pensions and unusual job security
guarantees for them, asserted that the president of the national
union had engineered a crude power play to push aside an outspoken
critic and potential challenger for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the folks from the national union as terrorists who
took over the local for no reason whatsoever,'' said Harry Farrell,
a troubleshooter on high-voltage problems for Con Ed. ``They know
Joe Flaherty was a powerful union leader. His integrity was
impeccable. In my 34 years in the union, we never had a leader like
Joe Flaherty.''
</P>
<P>
   But Donald Wightman, president of the parent union, the
45,000-member Utility Workers Union, said the union took over its
largest local and removed Flaherty to rescue it from insolvency and
from a leader who was stifling dissent and democracy. Wightman also
said the local had wasted hundreds of thousands of dollars on
excessive legal fees and a bloated payroll. He said allegations
that Flaherty was being punished for his outspoken opposition were
absolutely false.
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty had repeatedly accused Wightman of violating federal
law by accepting utility industry money to set up forums against
deregulation of the electric industry. Both the union and the
utilities fear deregulation will mean competition and layoffs. But
Wightman said his lawyers advised him it was legal to use the money
for that purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have furiously swapped charges and countercharges.
Judge Loretta Preska of U.S. District Court in Manhattan has been
sifting through the conflicting accounts but so far has upheld the
trusteeship. This month, Flaherty plans to file new court papers
asking the judge to reinstate him as the local's chief executive _
his formal title was business manager _ or to order a new election
for the local's officers. Since his ouster, Flaherty, who had
headed the local since 1991, has returned to his work in a manhole,
splicing cables.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of who wins the court battle, both sides agree that
this has been an ugly, painful episode not only for a respected
union local, but also for New York City's labor movement, which has
been scarred by a corruption scandal at District Council 37, the
giant municipal union.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has also hurt Consolidated Edison. The utility
negotiated a two-year contract extension with James Keller, the
trustee running the local, but Flaherty turned the ratification
vote into a referendum on the trusteeship, and the extension was
overwhelmingly defeated, by a more than 2 to 1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   Wightman said he had acted courageously in removing Flaherty.
``If you put a local into trusteeship, you're hated,'' he said.
``It's not the most popular thing to do. Whether the members knew
it or not, there was financial malpractice. If I didn't act, that
local was as close to being insolvent as you can be.''
</P>
<P>
   Wightman said that under Flaherty, the local's net assets fell
to $1 million from $3.5 million. And that, he said, was before
Flaherty projected a $500,000 deficit for last year. Wightman cited
examples of wasteful spending _ a $4,000 weekly retainer to the
local's general counsel, more than $2 million a year for wages and
benefits for the local's 20 full-time officers and more than
$200,000 a year for leased cars and auto insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Wightman said it was wasteful to have 20 full-time officers. And
he faulted Flaherty for not reducing the union's staff when
membership fell to 10,000 from 13,000, after reductions in the Con
Ed work force because of automation. He also attacked Flaherty for
paying legal fees with money from the fund meant to support members
during a strike, without first getting members' approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``The local was for all practical purposes bankrupt,'' Keller,
the trustee, said. ``Unfortunately, for years the members were
informed only by what he told them.''
</P>
<P>
   Flaherty acknowledged the local's finances were in bad shape,
but he said they were no worse than when he was elected as its
leader. The main reasons for the local's financial woes, he said,
were the drop in membership and the million dollars a year in dues
sent to the national union.
</P>
<P>
   He said he acted frugally, noting that he cut his salary to
$95,000 from $100,000 and had officers give up leased luxury cars
in favor of Ford Tauruses. He insisted that the local's staff was
smaller than when he took the local's helm. Flaherty said that when
he had the bylaws amended to allow him to reduce the number of
officers to save money, the national union attacked him for trying
to force out officers who disagreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This trusteeship is an outrage,'' Flaherty said. ``It's purely
political. They could have trusteed me any time, but they only did
it after I criticized the national president. If I was a good boy
and kept my mouth shut, I'd still be there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
