u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TV-SPORTS-NYT     01-09 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FIESTA BOWL BECOMES JACKSON'S LONG GOODBYE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 12:05 a.m. Tuesday, Eastern standard time, the Fiesta Bowl
mercifully ended. The Tostitos were soggy, the Diet Coke flat.
After 3 hours 50 minutes _ not counting a 15-minute pre-game show _
Tennessee won. The Christmas yule log burned faster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had everything in this game,'' ABC's Bob Griese said
late in the Vols' 23-16 victory over Florida State. ``We've had
missed extra points, missed field goals, defensive scores.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' Keith Jackson said, ``but beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauty might have revved up matters (and might have saved us the
pathetic sight of a Frito-Lay executive trying to hand the
victorious Tennessee coach, Phillip Fulmer, a bag of Tostitos;
here, Coach, bet you can't eat just one!)
</P>
<P>
   But in college football, games rarely end in less time than
``Lawrence of Arabia.'' They may be exciting, but they are not
quick. If they could rush along like Lou Holtz's mouth, victory
could be declared. But college games are slowed by first-down clock
stoppages and 20-minute halftime shows; throw in a sloppy one with
21 penalties, like the Fiesta, and you're not in Hallelujah Land.
</P>
<P>
   The Fiesta's lugubrious pace led viewers to abandon it before
the final gun. When nothing much happens, even the national
championship can induce surfing.
</P>
<P>
   After peaking at a 19.1 rating from 10-10:30 p.m., the game
concluded with a 16.2 thud from 11:30 to midnight _ a loss of 2.6
million households in 60 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 17.2 final Nielsen rating routed ABC's competition _
CBS rated a 10.9 from 8-11 p.m., with ``Sleepless in Seattle'' as
its prime attraction _ and finished 27 percent above last year's
Nebraska-Tennessee Orange Bowl, which matched the two top teams
available to the former bowl alliance. Last year's Rose Bowl, which
made Michigan the co-national champion, rated a 17.6.
</P>
<P>
   But the Fiesta was not a fittingly glorious game for Jackson to
retire on. His finale merited a classic. He got a boring clunker.
But his rich voice, singular verbal skills and personal grace
provided the reasons to hang in.
</P>
<P>
   As the day darkened in Tempe, Ariz., Jackson said: ``Nighttime
in the land where the Chirakawa used to hunt.'' Few announcers
could get away with a reference to Apaches. Fewer still would know
enough to refer to them.
</P>
<P>
   After a Florida State 5-yard penalty, Jackson said: ``Oh, it's a
little thing. It's 5 yards. It's a nickel. But if you get enough
nickels, first thing you know, you've got a quarter, then a heavy
sack, and then you ain't going nowhere.'' From any other announcer,
such words might seem excessive, but they emerged from Jackson as
naturally as anything from Red Barber.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson will be missed because he defined his sport. When a
defender rocks a receiver, we'll want to hear the old hoss say, ``I
mean to tell you, he put some lumber on him.'' Or, ``That was some
licking.'' Or when the Big Uglies have put in a hard day, no one
will say, ``Griese, the boys who played all game in the trenches
won't be so nimble at the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson and Griese _ perhaps an unlikely pairing because Griese
can seem stiff _ had more than bonded by this, their 12th year
together. Jackson's goading for Griese to be more emotional last
season in calling Michigan games featuring his son, Brian, brought
a sense of on-air friendship to their partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the moon, wondering why you didn't call it a
possum-hunting moon,'' Griese said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's not possum-hunting time,'' Jackson said. ``Snow's
too deep.''
</P>
<P>
   After a fumbled handoff by Tennessee with 1:29 left in the game,
Griese asked, ``At a critical time in the game, how can you miss
the exchange?''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder, when that happens, why does someone want to
coach?'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, Jackson turned misty when Griese informed him that
a $100,000 scholarship in his name had been endowed at his alma
mater, Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``My cup will always be half full because of people like you,''
Jackson said. Despite his protests, Jackson survived the myriad
tributes paid to him during his last season. Although flattered
that Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper, wanted to visit
him off camera in the booth Monday night, Jackson fretted that
there might not be enough time between halves, when he wanted to
prepare for the third period. Jackson relented, and they chatted
briefly.
</P>
<P>
   At night's end, the 70-year-old Jackson thanked the ABC crew,
and concluded his career by saying: ``And so, Phillip Fulmer has
been validated. He's now one of the legends that have spent time at
the foot of the Smokies. And so it is done. I say goodbye to all of
you. God bless and keep you. Good night.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
