<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NC-MARKET-REAL-2TAKES     01-09 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-MARKET-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: ASHEVILLE, N.C., PUBLIC MARKET HOPING TO BLOOM
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
By LYN RIDDLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ The Grove Arcade began life in 1929 as a
public market, but housed federal offices for nearly half a
century. By year's end, the mammoth building in the heart of this
city's downtown will recapture its birthright.
</P>
<P>
   In January, workers moved into the 269,000-square-foot building,
one of the nation's first indoor malls, to begin the $10 million
transformation. Asheville officials hope a public market will do
for their city what similar enterprises have done for others.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, public markets, with locally owned small
businesses that focus on selling local products, have breathed life
back into downtowns or renewed long-neglected sections across the
nation. Dozens of cities are building or planning new markets,
including the Portland Public Market in Portland, Maine, which
opened in November. In other cities like Atlanta and Buffalo,
millions of dollars have been invested in long-standing markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``As institutions, they're so ancient, one of the things that we
all share cross-culturally,'' said David K. O'Neil, the former
manager of the Reading Market in Philadelphia, who is now a market
consultant. ``It's nice to have a center of your community where
everything connects.''
</P>
<P>
   Markets, he said, touch people at an emotional level.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are attracted to people,'' he said. ``They love to buy
from people who know the product.'' Markets, he added, create an
environment of conviviality.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil estimates 100 markets exist today. Best known perhaps is
Pike Place Market in Seattle, founded in 1907, which noticeably
declined in the 1970's.
</P>
<P>
   After $55 million was invested in the market, it turned around.
Today, the market spills across 22 acres on Puget Sound and
attracts 11 million people each year. It also generated a total
investment of $650 million from private developers of stores,
hotels and 1,800 apartment units.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Zaretsky, the executive director of the Asheville effort,
was a director at Pike Place for 15 years before moving here three
years ago. Zaretsky heads the Grove Arcade Public Market
Foundation, a nonprofit organization that has leased the building
from the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Grove Arcade was built by E.W. Grove, who made a fortune
selling tonics that were said to cure all manner of ills. His
slogan was ``makes children and adults as fat as pigs.'' Grove also
built the Grove Park Inn, a luxury resort still operating about
five miles away from the arcade.
</P>
<P>
   Grove had planned for a high-rise tower on top of the
marketplace, but he died before the building was finished. The work
stopped at just two stories. In 1942, the federal government,
looking for space outside Washington to house agencies not
essential to the war effort, bought the Grove Arcade. Until three
years ago when a new federal building was built a block away, all
the nation's weather data were stored at the National Climatic Data
Center in the Grove Arcade.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, the largest computer in the region _ an 8-foot-tall
UNIVAC used to store weather data that filled an 80- by 150-foot
room _ was housed in the building. It was such a novelty that a
small platform was built outside the office so residents could
watch it work. The platform still exists in the arcade walkway.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather center and other smaller federal agencies moved
into the new federal building, the government deeded the property
to the city. The foundation that has leased the building from the
city is responsible for the renovation of the basement and first
floor of the building, while a private developer will refurbish the
upper two floors and a mezzanine for offices and residences.
</P>
<P>
   On the first floor, foundation planners hope to lease space to
an eclectic mix of businesses, everything from a Thai restaurant to
a bicycle shop, a fish market to a craft store. To keep the flavor
of a public market, all the stores will be locally owned and will
cater to a local clientele. Generally, public markets provide
opportunity to small businesses, giving them an edge on larger,
nationally known chains.
</P>
<P>
   And some nationally known businesses have started out at public
markets. Starbucks Coffee began as a small coffeehouse in Pike
Place.
</P>
<P>
   Public markets are not to be confused with festival markets,
which H. Christopher Slusher, Zaretsky's assistant, describes as
shopping districts filled with upscale national chains catering to
tourists. Fanueil Hall in Boston and Inner Harbor in Baltimore
would be considered festival markets, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Public markets are more down-home, as in a fish store in Pike
Place where a worker is apt to throw a salmon across the shop to
have it wrapped for a customer. ``The stores showcase the best
products of a region,'' said Slusher, an architect who worked for
the National Trust for Historic Preservation before coming here in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Appalachian crafts and handmade furniture will be
spotlighted, as will smoked salmon and ramp, a garlicky onion that
grows wild in the southern Appalachians and is considered a
delicacy. Slusher hopes stores will feature baskets, weaving and
quilting as well as the basic needs: groceries, banks, photo
developing, garden supply, ice cream shop, a mailing service.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, 450 people have expressed a desire to open a shop in the
public market area, which ultimately will have 60 spaces plus about
15 stalls for fresh food vendors. Financing comes from a $1 million
grant from the U.S. Economic Development Administration, $1 million
in contributions and $2.5 million in financing. A parking lot _ for
cars and bicycles _ will be constructed in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation has leased the top three floors of the building
to Rick Skelton, an Atlanta developer who intends to renovate the
space for an undetermined number of offices and 52 apartments that
will be converted to condominiums in a few years. In addition, a
band shell in the tower overlooking the rooftop will be renovated
and the roof will be used for public gatherings, meetings,
receptions and dancing.
</P>
<P>
   The residences and the rooftop overlook downtown Asheville and
the Blue Ridge Mountains, which ring this city of 60,000 in western
North Carolina. The marketplace will serve to foster an already
reviving downtown, said City Manager James Westbrook. He hopes the
city will be able to attract a medium-priced hotel chain to the
block between the marketplace and Asheville Civic Center to enable
the city to play host to bigger conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some larger and more famous Southern cities like Atlanta
and Charlotte, Asheville has not leveled its historic buildings in
favor of new development. City leaders say it has the nation's
second largest number of Art Deco buildings after Miami. City Hall
itself is an Art Deco tower whose renovation has just been
completed with a $1 million yearlong replacement of its distinctive
red tile roof.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away is the First Baptist Church, whose Art Deco
design sets it apart from its Baptist cousins of staid brick, high
white steeples and white columns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a conscious decision to retain these buildings,''
Westbrook said.
</P>
<P>
   The city has worked, too, to develop and enhance its artistic
side. Shops that were long empty now house art galleries, jewelry
stores, crafts, even a shop that features items from expeditions.
Pack Square features a number of museums, including one that
features minerals and gemstones, for which North Carolina is
famous. Sculpture dresses up many street corners and yards outside
buildings. One notable piece _ by Albert Paley, the metal sculptor
_ stands outside the new federal building. Some locals consider it
brilliant; others say it looks like a plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Slusher says planners hope the Arcade Marketplace will further
revitalize life in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This building was beautifully designed and is in remarkable
condition,'' he said. ``This city has a heart and soul as an urban
center and can reclaim itself as the center for commerce in the
region. We're well on our way to doing that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
