<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-SNOWBOARDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERMONT SNOWBOARDER IS A NATURAL AT 18
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt.)   (jw) 
 By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was about six years ago that snowboarders in central Vermont
began hearing stories about the little dude with the big black
helmet who was taking the mountain apart.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when few snowboarders wore headgear, the helmet was
one of the things that set Adam Petraska of Andover, Vt., then 12
years old, apart from the hordes of young riders on the slopes. But
it soon became apparent that the helmet was not the only thing
different about him.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer verve with which Petraska rode the halfpipe made him
unique at an early age, almost from the moment he first received a
snowboard for Christmas at age 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would come at 1 p.m. on Thursday afternoons to Okemo with
the rest of the schoolchildren from Chester and Andover,'' said
Gordon Robbins, a member of the board of directors of the
International Snowboard Federation, referring to the Okemo Mountain
School, where he still trains and studies. ``He was always the best
rider _ he was totally natural on the board _ but he was such a
ball of fun, too, and that's what made him different.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always looking for something to jump, spin, bonk or hit
off of,'' Robbins recalled. ``He'd hurl himself in the air and come
down in a complete splat and get up with a huge grin on his face.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, however, the splats have been few.
</P>
<P>
   In February 1995, when an international federation event was
canceled in Canada and restaged at Okemo, Vt., with the condition
that some local riders could participate, Petraska, then 13,
finished 23rd among some of the best riders in the world.
</P>
<P>
   At 15, he won his first national competition; in 1997, he
attended his first junior worlds, and last year at 17 he won the
junior world championship with a pair of runs through the halfpipe
that had people rubbing their eyes in disbelief.
</P>
<P>
   Now 18, Petraska is challenging the adults as well, finishing
third in the season's first Grand Prix in December at Mount
Bachelor, Ore., and headed into this weekend's Grand Prix at Copper
Mountain, Colo., ranked No. 2 in the U.S. Amateur Snowboarder
Association behind Todd Richards in halfpipe and No. 12 in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I try to do is push myself constantly to higher
levels, whether it's a certain trick or anything else,'' said the
5-foot-10-inch, 165-pound Petraska, who wears his blond hair
shoulder-length. ``I try to focus on that one thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Petraska's regimen as a senior at Okemo combines a basic high
school curriculum with a decidedly unbasic emphasis on winter
sports training. With his close friend and fellow rider, Abe Teter,
20, acting as his personal fitness expert and nutritionist,
Petraska is on the mountain from 8 to 11:30 a.m. Weight-lifting and
more training in the halfpipe come later. He fits in academics as
time and tutors permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not one thing he does differently or better than anyone
else; it's that he is a total competitor: He sees the top and he
says, `I'm gonna be there,' '' said Teter of Belmont, Vt. ``For
instance, at the junior worlds last year, he said beforehand, `I'm
going to win it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Having skied from age 2, Petraska easily transferred his summer
skateboarding skills to snowboarding. He asked for a board for
Christmas when he was 9 (``I was really disappointed when I didn't
get it,'' he said). The following Christmas, Petraska was on the
mountain the next day, teaching himself how to ride. Competition
was a natural next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end of the day I was making turns,'' he said. ``The
next day I went up with a bunch of friends, and I guess I caught on
real quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Petraska found he enjoyed the competition as
much as anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competition is cool,'' he said. ``Not only are you with your
friends, you get to travel, and it pushes your snowboarding to a
higher level. I'm definitely better than I was a year ago, and as
the season goes on I hope that progression will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
