<HEADER>
A6089 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRESAFETY-REAL-NYT     01-09 1180
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESAFETY-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE SAFETY: PLANNING IS KEY
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What would you do _ what specific action would you
take right now _ if you just learned there was a fire in your
building?
</P>
<P>
   Those who try to answer that question might argue that it is
difficult to do so without some additional information _ such as
the severity and location of the fire, for example, or whether
there is smoke in the hallways or exit stairs.
</P>
<P>
   But such information, fire-safety experts say, is rarely
available during a real fire and, when information is available, it
is often unreliable and at times irrelevant. This became painfully
clear late last month when four residents of a high rise on West
60th street died while doing something most would consider
reasonable _ leaving their burning building via the fire stairs.
Even seemingly reasonable actions can result in tragedy in the
chaos and confusion that accompany a fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``In high-rise fires people tend to panic and leave their
apartments,'' said Barbara Strauss, senior vice president of the
Owens Group, an insurance broker in Englewood Cliffs, N.J. ``In
most cases, they would be much better off if they would just stay
where they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Strauss, whose company offers seminars on fire safety to
residents and boards in client buildings, said that while
residential buildings in New York City are not required to have
sprinkler systems, most high-rise structures have safety features
like self-closing, fire-rated doors designed to minimize the spread
of fire in the building. In such buildings, she said, it is
generally safer for residents to stay in their apartments and wait
for help or instructions than to attempt to exit the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, the fire department will use loudspeakers from
outside the building to tell the people inside what to do,'' Ms.
Strauss said, adding that about the only time residents should
leave their apartments during a fire is when they are instructed to
do so by the fire department or when the fire is inside the
apartment itself.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Lanza, a New York City firefighter and president of the
board of Boulevard Gardens, a 966-unit co-op in Woodside, Queens,
agreed. ``In a high rise, you're usually better off staying put,''
Lanza said. ``And if people in their apartments are getting nervous
or scared, they can call 911, tell the operator what apartment
they're in, and the chief on the scene will usually send in some
firefighters to check on them.''
</P>
<P>
   David Kuperberg, president of Cooper Square Realty, a management
company, said that his company provided residents in client
buildings with fire-safety strategies in an operations and
procedures manual that the company prepares. Since every building
is different, Kuperberg said, each should have an individualized
plan.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, in buildings that have an intercom system
tied to the concierge desk it is possible for someone at the desk
to use the system to provide emergency instructions to residents on
specific floors or apartments.
</P>
<P>
   An even better way to keep residents informed or alert them of
an emergency, Kuperberg said, would be to install a building-wide
public address system with speakers installed in the hallway on
each floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most residential buildings don't have a PA system,'' he said.
``But it would be a huge benefit to have one and probably wouldn't
cost more than a few thousand dollars to install.'' Kuperberg, who
is a lieutenant with the volunteer fire department in Scarsdale,
N.Y., also recommends the installation of ``hard-wired'' smoke
detectors whenever an apartment is being altered or renovated. Such
devices, he explained, use the electrical wiring in a building _
instead of batteries _ as their primary power source.
</P>
<P>
   Kuperberg also pointed out that the ``stay put'' strategy
commonly given to residents in concrete and steel high-rise
buildings would not necessarily apply to inhabitants of other kinds
of buildings. ``People in a five-story brownstone with a fire
escape should probably use the fire escape,'' said Kuperberg.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, it is generally advisable for those
responsible for management of a multiple dwelling to contact fire
officials in the area and ask for help in developing a specific
plan for residents to use in the event of a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Marolyn Davenport, senior vice president of the Real Estate
Board of New York, an industry organization, said that the board
plans a ``major effort to educate occupants of high-rise apartment
buildings about what to do in the event of a fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Davenport said that over the next few weeks, residents of
member buildings, which include co-ops, condominiums and rental
buildings, would receive pamphlets on fire safety prepared by the
board with and the New York City Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Cholst, a Manhattan co-op lawyer, said that he advises
boards he represents to develop a plan of ``panic management'' to
cover various emergency situations. ``I think it is imperative to
provide residents with a written protocol for dealing with each and
every scenario that might occur,'' Cholst said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was important for boards to rigorously enforce
all house rules that relate to safety. He pointed, for example, to
rules regarding apartment alterations, noting that faulty design or
construction could result in a fire hazard.
</P>
<P>
   Matters relating to building security and maintenance should be
closely monitored as well, Cholst said. ``Members of the building
staff often succumb to the temptation to tinker with complicated
equipment and end up making a bad situation worse,'' he said. ``And
all areas with equipment and machinery should be off-limits to
residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after seven fatalities in fires in Manhattan and
Brooklyn _ including three city firefighters _ Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Fire Commissioner Thomas Von Essen held a news
conference to offer fire safety tips to New Yorkers living in
high-rise apartment buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Among the tips are the following:
</P>
<P>
   _ When there is a fire in your apartment, leave immediately,
making sure to shut the door behind you. Alert as many other
residents on the floor as possible, and leave the building using
the nearest stairwell. Under no circumstances should an elevator be
used during a fire or a suspected fire. Upon reaching the lobby or
street, immediately notify the Fire Department by calling 911.
</P>
<P>
   _ If there is a fire elsewhere in the building, remain in your
apartment. Call 911 and provide the operator with your name,
address, the location of your apartment and other pertinent
information like loss of electric power or conditions requiring
special medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep the apartment door closed and block the bottom with a wet
towel or blanket. Turn off air-conditioners and close the windows
if smoke is entering the apartment. If you are unable to escape,
seek refuge in the room farthest from the point of smoke entry and
notify the 911 operator that you are trapped.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
