<SLUG> BC-MEGA-CINEMAS-REAL-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE MOVIES ARE THE NEW STARS OF THE MALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass, Mich., N.Y., Tenn.)  (js) 
 By DIANA SHAMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STONY BROOK, N.Y. _ The 15-screen Loews movie theater that
opened here on Route 347 on Dec. 23 is _ for the moment _ the
biggest, plushest and most elaborate on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   But others equally elaborate are in the planning stages as
theater circuit companies, aglow in record attendance numbers, seek
additional sites in what is considered one of the hottest markets
in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The United Artists Theater Circuit of Englewood, Colo., plans to
break ground in the spring for a 12-screen theater on Brush Hollow
Road in Westbury. And, according to Kurt C. Hall, the chief
executive, the company is considering building another complex of
up to 14 screens to replace an existing theater at the Sunrise Mall
in Massapequa.
</P>
<P>
   Regal Cinemas of Knoxville, Tenn., one of the largest theater
operators in the nation, has selected Route 58 in Riverhead for a
16-screen theater that would be its first on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Association of Theater Owners, a trade
group based in North Hollywood, Calif., 1.39 billion movie tickets
were sold in 1997 compared with 1.34 billion in 1996; gross revenue
rose to $6.4 billion from $5.9 billion and the net number of
screens rose to 31,865 in 1997 from 29,731 in 1996, the largest
one-year increase on record. Figures for 1998 are not yet
available. Industry spokespeople say that rising movie attendance
reflects the popularity of films like ``Titanic'' but also has
everything to do with making theaters exciting places to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marcus Loew (the theater owner and film producer) once said,
`I sell tickets to theaters, not movies,' '' said Barrie Lawson
Loeks, the newly elected chairwoman of the theater owners
association, and the president and co-owner with her husband, Jim,
of the Loeks Star-Theaters chain, based in Grand Rapids, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have tried to bring back to the business is a sense of
excitement, a higher level of service and the idea that you should
feel the price of the ticket was worth it just to be in the
lobby,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the appeal of the new theaters is a relatively recent
development in theater design. The arrangement, called stadium
seating, allows all moviegoers to have unobstructed views of the
screen by placing each row about a foot higher than the row in
front. Seats themselves are plush and high-backed. They rock and
come with retractable arm rests that have cup holders and trays to
hold snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple screens under one roof _ as many as 30 in some
complexes _ not only offer a huge variety of fare but also allow
big hits to be scheduled on several screens, virtually guaranteeing
seating and providing a choice of show times.
</P>
<P>
   Also, huge curved screens extending wall to wall and floor to
ceiling and the latest sound technology give theatergoers an
illusion of being participants in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you saw `Titanic' in a theater that had stadium seating, it
was like being on the boat, almost to the point of being
disconcerting when it sank,'' said Edgar A. Knudson, senior vice
president for advertising at National Amusements, based in Dedham,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The privately held company owns theaters on Long Island in
Commack, Hicksville, Brookhaven, Valley Stream and East
Farmingdale. National is renovating its 14-screen theater at the
Airport Plaza Shopping Center on Route 110 in East Farmingdale,
even though the theater is only two years old. Stadium seating is
being installed throughout, and expansion to 23 screens is also
under discussion, Knudson said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that construction was expected to begin next summer on
an 18-screen theater with stadium seating in central Suffolk, but
said he could not disclose the location because the deal had not
yet been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The first theater on Long Island with stadium seating was Hoyts
Ronkonkoma Cinema 9, which opened in October. The Australian-based
Hoyts Cinemas Corp., whose U.S. headquarters is in Boston, has
built 17 theaters with stadium seating throughout the country the
last two and a half years, said Joanne Berberan, director of
marketing for Hoyts. ``We conducted a survey and found people all
wanted the four S's _ stadium seating, high-backed seats,
wall-to-wall screens and good sound,'' she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Long Island already has several theaters with 14 or
more screens _ known as megaplexes _ the density of the region and
its excellent demographics ``make it a very strong market for
theater development,'' said Dan Zelson, a principal of Charter
Realty and Development in Greenwich, Conn., which brokered the
Regal deal in Riverhead. The theater is scheduled to go into the
431,000-square-foot Riverhead Centre shopping center, but
construction has been delayed until the settlement of litigation
initiated by local merchants who are challenging a zoning change
for the shopping center developers.
</P>
<P>
   Zelson predicted that Regal, which has 3,563 screens at 404
sites, will build five to 10 more theaters on Long Island the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   Loews Cineplex Entertainment Corp. also expects to add more
theaters. The Manhattan-based company, formed last May with the
merger of Loews/Sony Theatres and Cineplex Odeon Corp., operates
425 moviehouses with 2,750 screens in the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   On Long Island, its 15 complexes include an eight-screen theater
at Roosevelt Field in Garden City and 10 screens at the site of the
former Roosevelt Raceway in Westbury. Several additional sites are
under consideration, said Kenneth B. Benjamin, Loews' senior vice
president for real estate.
</P>
<P>
   The new Stony Brook theater, which is expected to draw 1.5
million patrons a year, is the first Loews on Long Island with the
lavish lobby and stadium seating typical of the newest moviehouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept is to bring the elegance and glamour of theaters
built in the 1920s and 1930s back and to bring these elements to
the current theaters so they become special places to go,'' said
Eric J. Hugger, a principal of Fishbeck, Thompson, Carr &AMP; Huber of
Grand Rapids, the architect of the Stony Brook theater. Half the
firm's design work now involves movie theaters, Hugger said, noting
that ``architecture and design have become as much a part of the
moviegoing experience as the movie itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The Art Deco theater in Stony Brook has a 160-foot-long lobby
that is topped by a 48-foot atrium. Two 150-foot-long corridors,
each with a concession stand, lead from the central core to
individual theaters ranging from 112 to 467 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The lobby contains a concession stand with its own kitchen.
Customers can munch on freshly prepared chicken wings, French
fries, tacos and other treats. They can also watch previews of
upcoming features in the lobby while waiting for their show to
start. It even has a concierge.
</P>
<P>
   The theater, which is in the Brooktown Plaza shopping center,
replaced a 25-year-old theater that had only three screens. When an
adjoining bowling alley relocated last year, Loews seized the
opportunity to expand, said Daniel H. Serota, vice president for
construction at Nathan Serota &AMP; Sons of Valley Stream, which owns
the 30-acre shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Serota said the new theater would bolster traffic for his other
tenants, a Waldbaum's supermarket and a Marshalls department store,
which until now have been the draw for other retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the new moviehouses are increasingly becoming the anchor
tenants for shopping centers, taking on a role traditionally held
by department stores and supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a shopping center to be successful, it has to give people
more reasons to come, and you do that by offering them
entertainment,'' said Peter L. Levine, a shopping center developer.
</P>
<P>
   His company, Levcom of West Paterson, N.J., is building the
800,000-square-foot Airport Plaza in East Farmingdale, where the
14-screen National Amusements theater occupies 20 of the center's
91 acres. The theater opened in October 1996. A Staples
office-supply store and a Modells Sporting Goods store opened late
last year. A Home Depot will be completed by June.
</P>
<P>
   Levine said he was also negotiating with tenants that specialize
in building so-called entertainment centers, which combine a
restaurant, a sports bar and game rooms. By adding theme
restaurants and other family entertainment, ``we can appeal not
only to shoppers, but to everyone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AMC Entertainment, a theater operator based in Kansas City, Mo.,
carries that idea a step further by building what it calls
``entertainment-themed retail centers,'' where large-store
retailers like Home Depot and Marshalls are not even wanted.
Satellite stores include only entertainment-oriented outlets like
book and record stores and restaurants. ``And the megaplex is the
anchor,'' said Brenda Nolte, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
