<HEADER>
A6092 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-INAUG10-COX     01-09 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-INAUG10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia's Roy Barnes ready to govern
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roy Eugene Barnes takes over as Georgia's 80th
governor Monday with a nod to the century that's ending and an eye
on the one to come.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney and veteran state lawmaker, Barnes brings a
knowledge and appreciation of history to his new job, but at age
50, he'll also be Georgia's first baby boom governor. He grew up in
the south Cobb County town of Mableton when it was still largely
rural, but his views were largely shaped by the explosive growth of
the Atlanta suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' priorities for his first legislative session as governor
will include some traditional political issues _ a tax cut and
education improvements _ as well as a problem that could dominate
state government in the early part of the 21st century: managing
traffic and growth in the Atlanta region.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see quality of life, and how we deal with congestion and
growth, being a dominant issue that will continue more than one
year,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   He has a tough act to follow in Zell Miller, who leaves office
as one of the most popular governors in state history. In fact,
Barnes might not even be governor if Pierre Howard, who is stepping
down as lieutenant governor, had chosen to seek higher office last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Howard decided to quit politics, and Barnes, who had
finished a distant third in the 1990 Democratic gubernatorial
primary, won his party's nomination last summer and then defeated
Republican Guy Millner in the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has no single item on his agenda this year that is likely
to capture the public imagination the way Miller did in 1990 with
his promise to start a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a high-profile issue, but it's a solid list of
political goals to try to achieve,'' said Georgia State University
political scientist Michael Binford.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Barnes' proposals will probably be easy to implement,
such as his campaign promise to cut property taxes. He will ask the
Legislature this year to double the existing homestead exemption,
and wants to increase it to $50,000 over the next six years.
</P>
<P>
   To shore up school discipline, another of his campaign themes,
Barnes will seek funding this year to open more alternative schools
for disruptive pupils, and to offer after-school programs for
middle school students whose parents want their child to
participate. Barnes also is expected to begin a study to determine
the best way to give teachers more authority to boot troublemakers
out of class.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' campaign promise to reform managed health care will
probably take a tough political fight. Doctors and hospitals
generally support his view that patients should have a wider choice
of physicians, but insurance companies and some business groups are
opposed.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal likely to have the greatest long-term impact,
though, will be Barnes' effort to establish a regional
transportation authority aimed at reducing traffic and air
pollution in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Poor air quality has caused a freeze on most federal highway
money for the area, and business leaders fear that access to
inexpensive land for development, which has spurred suburban
growth, is being threatened by nightmarish traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes' commitment to address these problems comes in part from
his experiences growing up in Mableton, and from his days in the
state House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Barnes' family had diary cows and ran a general store
where local folks did much of their shopping for everything from
groceries to shotguns. Barnes would hop on a Greyhound bus in
Mableton and ride to downtown Atlanta to watch the Legislature in
action.
</P>
<P>
   His father told him about the trains that used to run from
Mableton to Atlanta every hour, and other Cobb residents described
riding a trolley downtown from the Marietta Square.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the things I heard about, that folks talked about, I
draw on those experiences and those times in forming what I think
ought to be the role of urban Georgia,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   As a state senator in the 1980s he served on the Growth
Strategies Commission, which tried to plot a course for the state
to avoid many of the pitfalls of suburban sprawl. Most of the
panel's recommendations have been ignored over the last decade, but
Barnes hasn't forgotten them. Today he cites the state of Maryland,
with its ``Smart Growth'' guidelines to contain sprawl, as a model
of good planning.
</P>
<P>
   Also during the 1980s, Barnes sponsored legislation to protect
the state's lakes and rivers. His environmental record was
considered so strong that he was endorsed by the Georgia Sierra
Club in 1990, the first time he ran for governor, and again last
year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to setting up a regional transportation authority,
Barnes is asking the Legislature for $1.9 million this year to
study a rail line that would run from Marietta to Lawrenceville,
connecting communities across the northern suburbs to one another
and to Atlanta via the MARTA north line. He also wants $3 million
in state funds to help start a bus system in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   In order to establish a regional transportation authority,
Barnes will need cooperation from many local governments. ``It goes
beyond jurisdictions and neighborhoods, and counties can't do it,''
Binford said. ``It's going to take statewide leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   If Barnes can convince local leaders to cooperate, he could set
a precedent for them to work together on other regional issues such
as water and sewers, managing growth, and consolidation of
government services, Binford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you build up those relationships, it's easier to tackle
additional problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond untangling traffic, Barnes believes better public
transportation would help knit the Atlanta region back together.
When he was young, he said, people in Mableton and other towns
around Atlanta felt connected to the city as the destination for
major shopping trips, business and entertainment. Today, people in
Mableton and other suburbs don't have to go to Atlanta if they
don't want to _ and many don't want to because of traffic and other
hassles.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring that regional connection is ``good from the
transportation viewpoint, and it's also good from the social and
policy viewpoint,'' Barnes said. ``We have common problems, and the
days when we could go to the suburbs and leave all the urban
problems behind are gone.''
</P>
<P>
   By tackling the problems of growth, traffic and pollution,
Barnes is focusing on matters that are less sexy than, say, a
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being the environmental governor is not initially as
appealing,'' said Charles Bullock, a political science professor at
the University of Georgia. ``It takes a while to pay its
dividends.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes acknowledged that some problems are too big to be solved
in four years _ or even eight years if he wins a second term.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even taken office yet, and it's too early to worry
about my legacy,'' Barnes said. ``But there are several thorny
problems I anticipate we're going to address while I'm governor. I
hope that's what I'm remembered for.''
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Roy Eugene Barnes
</P>
<P>
   Age: 50
</P>
<P>
   Party affiliation: Democrat
</P>
<P>
   Residence: Mableton
</P>
<P>
   Education: Bachelor's and law degrees, University of Georgia
</P>
<P>
   Profession: Lawyer
</P>
<P>
   Political experience: State representative 1993-present; state
senator 1975-1991; ran for governor in 1990; elected governor 1998
</P>
<P>
   Personal: Wife, Marie; three children
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1448EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
