<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-NYT     01-09 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS LOOK TO FUTURE, AND SEE A GOALIE THERE
</HEADLINE>
  (bl)  
By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Far from Long Island, where for the fifth straight season the
New York Islanders are nowhere close to making the playoffs, there
is help in Canada for the struggling franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Roberto Luongo, the Islanders' first-round selection in the 1997
National Hockey League draft, is biding his time in the small towns
of the Quebec Major Junior Hockey League. Widely considered to be
the best goalie in juniors, the 19-year-old Luongo led a moderately
talented Canadian junior national team to a world championship
silver medal last week and was named outstanding goaltender of the
tournament. In a few years, the Islanders expect him to be leading
them to the Stanley Cup playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a reason he was the highest drafted goalie ever,''
said Mike Milbury, the Islanders' coach and general manager. ``In
time, we believe that he can be an elite goaltender. His
performance in the world juniors last week proved that.''
</P>
<P>
   Luongo, who was picked fourth over all in the draft, was invited
to the Islanders' training camp last September and played in
several preseason games. He flashed a deft glove hand, had
lightning-quick feet for a 6-foot-3-inch, 190-pounder and showed
intense concentration. But there were technical aspects he had to
improve.
</P>
<P>
   So after an inconsistent month in camp with the Islanders, a
disappointed Luongo was sent back to the juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``For sure, I was disappointed not to make the team,'' Luongo
said by telephone from his home near Montreal on Friday. ``I
thought I might have had a chance to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   If Luongo were a little older, he would be closer to Long
Island, with the Islanders' minor league team in Lowell, Mass. But
players must be 20 to play in the American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Luongo took an ordinary Val d'Or team to the Quebec
Major Junior Hockey League title and a berth in the Canadian junior
championship, the Memorial Cup. Named the league's top prospect,
Luongo posted a 27-20-5 record and a 3.09 goals against average in
54 games last season, respectable numbers considering the defense
in front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo would have preferred to have made the NHL this year, but
he now agrees that returning to the juniors was the right decision.
He was not ready for the NHL. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the issue of a contract standing between Luongo
and the Islanders. Luongo's agent, Gilles Lupien, and the Islanders
failed to work out a deal by Oct. 1, the deadline to sign with a
junior team and still be eligible to be called up to the NHL during
the season. Several people close to Luongo said the sides had
reached an agreement in principle since then, though many details
remain open. Lupien met with Milbury on Friday in Montreal, and it
is expected that Luongo will sign a three-year deal worth about
$2.25 million later this month.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Luongo has been having a season he will not
soon forget.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Luongo lay flat on his back on the ice in
Winnipeg, Manitoba, as the Russian junior national team piled up in
front of him, celebrating the overtime goal that gave it a 3-2
victory over Canada in the championship game. The disappointment
overwhelmed Luongo. Reaching the final was a proud moment for him
and for the Canadian team, which had been embarrassed the year
before. But for the ultracompetitive Luongo, second was not good
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best experience of my life,'' Luongo said. ``It was
high pressure, playing against the best players. But even though we
won the silver, I was very disappointed. I wanted to win a gold
medal. That's why you go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordie Clark, the Islanders' director of player personnel, who
deserves much of the credit for selecting Luongo, attended the
tournament. ``He made several key saves at key times,'' Clark said.
``He was their best player. Roberto took an average Canadian team
and gave them a chance to win a gold medal.''
</P>
<P>
   When Luongo returns to the juniors this week, the pressure will
again be on him. During the two-week world championship tournament,
he was traded from the struggling Val d'Or to a contending team,
Acadie-Bathurst of New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an Italian immigrant father and an Irish-Canadian
mother, Luongo speaks English, Italian and French. He grew up in
St. Leonard, a town north of Montreal known as Little Italy, and
began playing hockey at the age of 8. He always wanted to be a
goalie, but his parents, Lina and Tony Luongo, insisted that he
first learn to skate. A few years later, when Luongo was cut from
his peewee team, he became a goalie. His idol is Grant Fuhr, the
St. Louis Blues goalie, ``because of his spectacular glove saves,''
Luongo said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many future NHL goaltenders from Quebec, at 15 Luongo
joined Montreal-Bourassa, a midget team that has produced the
Devils' Martin Brodeur, the Toronto Maple Leafs' Felix Potvin, the
Los Angeles Kings' Stephane Fiset and the former Islander Eric
Fichaud, among many others. Under the direction of the goalie
coaches Mario Baril and Francois Allaire, a longtime assistant
coach with the Canadiens and most recently the Mighty Ducks of
Anaheim, Luongo began showing signs of potential greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaching in Montreal for goaltending is excellent,'' said
Allaire, who coached the Colorado Avalanche star Patrick Roy when
he played for the Canadiens. ``The athletes have never been so
good, too. The best players in Quebec, when they are young, want to
be goaltenders. Not many players can say, `I'm as good or better
than any goalie in the world at my age.' Roberto can.''
</P>
<P>
   One look at Luongo's gangly frame and his size-15 feet, and it
is obvious that he possesses the physical attributes. But all of
his coaches agree that it is his intelligence that sets him apart.
While playing for Acadie-Bathurst, Luongo plans to take
correspondence courses from a college in New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders have no plans to rush Luongo, but even the most
conservative predictions have him playing some, if not most, of
next season with them as Tommy Salo's backup, though he may start
the season in the American Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting drafted so high, yeah, there's pressure on me,''
Luongo said. ``But if you're going to play the game at this level,
you have to deal with that. I haven't proven anything in the NHL
yet, but hopefully I will.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
