<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-WELLSTONE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WELLSTONE SAYS HE'S 'SKEPTICAL' OF CLINTON CHARGES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., says he is
``skeptical'' that the impeachment charges against President
Clinton warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone's comment, one of the strongest indications of a
probable vote since the senators swore Thursday to ``do impartial
justice'' at Clinton's trial starting this week, was made on CNN's
``Larry King Live'' Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still would argue that what the president's done is not a
threat to the freedom and the liberty of people in the country,''
Wellstone said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the question of whether he should be removed is another
question. I'm skeptical about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone predicted that a ``number of us'' will move to dismiss
the case as soon as both sides have presented arguments and before
any witnesses are called.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he's an impartial juror in the Clinton impeachment
case, Wellstone said, ``I certainly will listen to everybody make
their case and I will make a judgment as to whether they've
marshaled evidence for their point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, this is a political process as well,'' he said.
``I mean, we're jurors, but this ... is a political thicket.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone also urged that the Senate conduct all trial business
in public, not behind closed doors. That issue was not covered in
Friday's bipartisan agreement on procedures for the trial's opening
phase.
</P>
<P>
   Wellstone said he is sponsoring a motion to require a public
deliberation on whether to convict or acquit. Rules dating to the
impeachment of President Andrew Johnson in 1868 call for the
senators to reach their verdict behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
