<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INTACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE CHAMPIONSHIP YANKEES REMAINED INTACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bernie Williams will be back with the Yankees when they open
spring training next month, and the team that won 125 games and a
World Series title last season will remain virtually intact. For
about five minutes on the morning of Nov. 25, however, Albert Belle
was a Yankee and Williams' career with the team was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' lineup for 1999 would have looked much differently
if Belle hadn't suddenly backed out of an oral agreement, those
involved in the contract negotiations say. If Belle hadn't changed
his mind, Williams likely would have signed with the Boston Red
Sox. If Belle hadn't changed his mind, the Yankees never would have
given Williams the sort of huge offer they had refused to extend
for years.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-paid players in the game have been the likes of Ken
Griffey Jr. of Seattle and Belle _ players whose skills are
quantified easily with statistics. Griffey already has 350 career
home runs at age 29, and if he remains healthy, almost certainly
will challenge Henry Aaron's record of 755 and eventually be voted
into the Hall of Fame. Belle has 30 or more home runs and more than
100 runs batted in for seven consecutive seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, 30, has never produced such numbers: He has never hit
30 home runs in any single season, never driven in more than 102
runs. When he turned 27 in 1995, his career high in RBIs was 82;
when Griffey was 27, he had averaged nearly 100 RBIs for nine
seasons. Griffey is a dominant player; Belle is, too. Williams
wanted to be paid like a dominant player, and as the Yankees tried
attaching a dollar value to his ability over the last four years,
they didn't think of him in that way. After Bob Watson, the
Yankees' former general manager, offered Williams a four-year, $24
million contract in 1996, Watson said Williams was ``a good player,
but not a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, Williams' agent, would argue to the Yankees or
anyone that he spoke with that Williams was, in fact, an elite
player who was improving.
</P>
<P>
   Williams has batted better than .300 for four consecutive
seasons, winning the American League batting title in 1998 with a
.339 average, played a crucial part for championship teams in two
of the last three years _ and, Boras noted, Williams is a center
fielder and a switch-hitter. There are many good run-producers
playing left field or right field, but few center fielders capable
of driving in 100 runs.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the consensus within the Yankees' organization was
nearly unanimous when Williams applied for free agency in October:
There was no way George Steinbrenner, the principal owner, would
give Williams a seven-year contract. Brian Cashman, the Yankees'
general manager, sought possible options as Williams talked to
other teams.
</P>
<P>
   After Williams met with the Arizona Diamondbacks on Nov. 11,
Boras reached an understanding with Jerry Colangelo, the
Diamondbacks' managing general partner, of what it would take to
sign Williams without any formal offer being made; later, the
Yankees were told by the owners' labor relations committee that
Arizona had been willing to give Williams an eight-year, $100
million contract, with much of that money deferred. Boston offered
a $91.5 million package 12 days later.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had refused to alter their offer of $60 million to
Williams and became comfortable with the notion of signing Belle,
in spite of his volatile history. Yankees Manager Joe Torre played
golf with Belle on Nov. 16, and Torre and Cashman liked what they
heard and saw. Belle assured them he would be more fan friendly,
that he would not disrupt their clubhouse. Riding in Belle's
Mercedes-Benz, Cashman noticed that the car was spotless. ``He is a
very structured individual, locked into his routine,'' Cashman
said.
</P>
<P>
   For instance? ``October is dessert month for Albert,'' Cashman
explained. ``It's the only month he eats desserts. He's working out
all the time _ he had hand flexors in the Mercedes.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras advised Williams that the time to make a decision was at
hand and arranged a meeting with Steinbrenner and other club
officials for the afternoon of Nov. 24. It was during that
conversation that Cashman's beeper activated; returning a message,
he learned that the Baltimore Orioles had joined the bidding for
Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Angelos, the Orioles owner, had read of the Yankees'
interest in Belle. ``If the Yankees signed Belle,'' said Angelos,
``I thought that was going to be a serious, serious problem. I
didn't relish the idea of him batting in the middle of that
Yankees' lineup _ with those other hitters around him, he would've
been a destructive force. Not that Williams isn't a first-rate
ballplayer, but offensively, I don't think there's any
comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Angelos' strategy was offensive and defensive: Lure Belle to
Camden Yards, where the slugger could exploit the cozy confines,
``where he might hit 60 home runs for us,'' and keep him away from
the Yankees. ``I figured that if we signed Belle, the Yankees would
probably re-sign Bernie. Or Boston would sign Bernie, and the
Yankees don't get either guy. But I didn't want them getting
Belle.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between Williams and Steinbrenner ended well, with
the owner saying, ``Bernie, you came here, you talked to me, and I
really have to think about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras walked into the room believing the Yankees would not
increase their offer. ``But when George said that, I felt there was
a chance,'' Boras recalled.
</P>
<P>
   But Steinbrenner wasn't ready to increase his offer to Williams
by 50 percent, and at around midnight, Cashman called Belle's
agent, to extend a five-year, $60-million offer. Cashman and Belle
spoke directly at about 11 a.m. on Nov. 25, and according to
Cashman, Belle said he would be willing to reach an agreement if
the Yankees made an adjustment to their offer: Rather than an
annual salary of $12 million over five years, how about an annual
salary of $13 million _ which, at that time, would've matched the
highest in baseball _ over a four-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   Cashman, fearful about losing both Williams and Belle to
division rivals, was thrilled. He told Belle he thought this
proposal was workable, that all he needed was Steinbrenner's rubber
stamp on the agreement. Steinbrenner quickly gave his approval, and
Cashman called Arn Tellem, Belle's agent, to complete the details.
</P>
<P>
   But Tellem's voice sounded stilted to Cashman: Something had
gone wrong. Belle was having second thoughts, Tellem explained.
Cashman exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, Cashman would learn the Orioles had offered a
five-year, $65 million contract _ $13 million a year _ with $15
million deferred. Cashman had to call Steinbrenner and tell him
Belle had changed his mind. ``It made me look like a fool with
George,'' Cashman said, ``and he wasn't happy.'' Later, Belle
explained to Cashman that he had reservations about being the focal
point of the New York news media.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, left without a viable cleanup hitter, determined to
sign Williams. Steinbrenner called Boras later in the afternoon and
hammered out a new contract in 20 minutes of negotiations. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
