<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6122 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWDEAL10-COX     01-09 1199
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWDEAL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Black farmers may reap cash for injustice claims, but some fear
it comes too late
 &HT;    By Peter Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Instead of the usual crops of soybeans and peas,
thousands of black farmers, mainly in the South, may soon reap a
harvest of greenbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But for many of the farmers, who say they were victims of 15
years of discrimination in federal farm programs, it may be too
little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Paul L. Friedman of Washington, D.C., gave
tentative approval last week to a consent agreement that will pay
about 5,000 black farmers nationwide an estimated average of
$200,000 apiece, including $50,000 in cash, said Alexander Pires,
an attorney for the farmers. He said the settlement in the
race-discrimination lawsuit also includes tax payments and
reimbursement for unfairly assessed U.S. Department of Agriculture
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Black farmers not included in the decision could end up
receiving as much, or more, as they take their claims to an
independent arbitrator or file separate lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman has set a March 2 hearing for a final decision on the
settlement, and has ordered the farmers to come to court so he can
hear from them firsthand regarding the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   He can expect plenty of feedback from the farmers, many of whom
claim the damage to them goes far beyond what the settlement would
provide.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The proposed settlement) is a shock to the American sense of
fairness,'' said Eddie Slaughter, a South Georgia farmer who is
vice president of the national Black Farmers and Agriculturalist
Association. ``They are telling black farmers that for all the
suffering they have endured at the hands of the government, it is
worth about $3,572 a year, or $150 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Taylor, a national spokesman for black farmers, cites
examples like the black farmer in Mississippi who lost his leg in a
farming accident and, despite developing a prosthesis that allowed
him to operate his tractor, found himself labeled handicapped and
inelligible for federal loans. He is now facing foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   And in Georgia, Taylor said, a dairyman undergoing dialysis was
denied loans, so he sold some cows in order to have enough cash to
get by. Now he's facing criminal charges because the USDA claims it
held title to the cows as collateral for previous loans.
</P>
<P>
   Other farmers were so far in debt they could see no way out,
said Taylor. He said he knows of three black farmers who committed
suicide because they lost their land.
</P>
<P>
   Some 600 black farmers from Georgia and 14 other states filed
the $2.5 billion lawsuit in 1997 against U.S. Secretary of
Agriculture Dan Glickman and the USDA. The farmers allege that
since 1983, the agency has discriminated against them in the denial
of farm loans, crop subsidies and other farm program benefits
administered by the Farm Service Agency and its predecessors, the
Farmers Home Administration.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the farmers contend, they lost potential farm
income, and sometimes, their farms.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers charged that the USDA was part of an effort to
systematically erase them from the agricultural landscape. The
number of black farmers has declined from 925,710 in 1920 to fewer
than 18,000 today. The black-owned farm acreage has dropped from
15.6 million acres to less than 1million.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman has acknowledged that black farmers were treated
differently than white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Breckenridge of Oklahoma is among those who says he
suffered from unfair treatment. When he began dealing with the USDA
in 1986, he had a gross worth of $2.5 million. Since that time, the
61-year-old former vocational agriculture teacher and member of the
Oklahoma Board of Regents has seen his wealth diminish. His family
once farmed 3,000 acres, but now has less than 200 acres. He once
had 1,300 head of cattle. He now has just 160.
</P>
<P>
   He said the USDA wouldn't give him the kind of support it gave
other farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I signed up with the USDA, I could borrow little or no
money from the banks,'' said Breckenridge, who began farming in
1964 shortly after schools were desegregated in Oklahoma and many
black teachers lost their jobs as all-black schools shut down.
``The USDA had my equipment and land as collateral. Our area had
four or five bad crop years. Up until this day, I've never received
operating funds from USDA.''
</P>
<P>
   Willie Head of Georgia is among farmers who have spent years
trying to hang on despite their inability to get the same kind of
loans available to white farmers. ``I may be able to save my land,
but I won't be able to put my farm in full production. The
agreement will allow me to secure my land,'' said the 44-year-old,
third-generation farmer in Pavo, just south of Thomasville.
</P>
<P>
   Head faces foreclosure on a 150-acre farm that has been in his
family for 100 years. He hopes the agreement will help convince his
local creditor to delay a $6,500 payment that is due on part of his
$42,000 debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lay down crying and we wake up crying. We are trying to
hold on,'' said Head's 71-year-old mother, Jessie Mae.
</P>
<P>
   Head has always wanted to farm and learned by the side of his
late father, Willie Sr. He bolstered his skills with a degree in
business administration and economics from Albany State University.
</P>
<P>
   But Head has gotten so far in the hole that when his wife and
father died within two weeks of each other last September, he had
no insurance to bury them. His wife was in intensive care with
pneumonia when he was told his farm was about to be foreclosed.
Friends and supporters helped raise more than $11,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (settlement) will help keep us around, but we won't be
productive. It's almost like being comatose _ you are breathing but
not living,'' said Head.
</P>
<P>
   He said he fears many black farmers challenging alleged racial
discrimination will face retaliation from whites in the farming
community who are struggling, but for different reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Commissioner of Agriculture Tommy Irwin said he will not
tolerate acts of discrimination. If such acts are committed, he
said, ``Heads will roll.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that it is very difficult to make up for
past unfairness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing that can be paid to overcome the existence of
discrimination in the past,'' Irwin said. ``I suspect farmers who
have lost their land, (by now) it's in somebody else's name and
there is no way you correct that misjustice.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Sherrod, executive director of the Albany field office
of the Federation of Southern Cooperatives, an ombudsman agency for
small and minority farmers, worries that despite the settlement,
the same problems for black farmers will eventually resurface. Many
of the USDA officials who were the targets of the black farmers'
complaints remain in the positions they held before the suit was
settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a moral or just conclusion to what black farmers and
their families have endured over the past 50 to 60 years,'' said
Gary Grant, a Virginia farmer who is president of the national
Black Farmers and Agriculturalists Association.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
