</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-INVEST-REAL-4TAKES     01-09 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INVEST-REAL-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 REAL ESTATE: AFTER A ROLLER-COASTER YEAR, OPTIMISM 
</HEADLINE>
 (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Real estate executives used words like ``frothy,''
``giddy'' and ``frenzy'' to describe the investment market in the
New York area during the first half of last year. Fueled by a
seemingly unlimited amount of capital from Wall Street, real estate
investment trusts and private operators bid against one another for
available properties, driving up prices.
</P>
<P>
   Today the froth has flattened and nobody is feeling very giddy.
At the same time there is little gloom.
</P>
<P>
   Although the capital markets took the industry on a
roller-coaster ride last year, the fundamentals of the commercial
real estate business remain strong and most executives are
optimistic about the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the top end of a real estate cycle, so 1999 should
be a good year, but not a spectacularly good one,'' said Dennis
Yeskey, managing director of the real estate services group at
Deloitte &AMP; Touche, the accounting and consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Cohen, president of Williams Real Estate, said, ``What
we saw last year was a historic disconnect between the rental and
sales markets.'' Cohen said that commercial rents remained strong
even as the prices of properties fluctuated in response to activity
in financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news,'' said Raymond Torto, a principal in Torto
Wheaton Research, an econometric analysis firm specializing in real
estate, ``is that real estate has made it in capital markets,''
allowing financing to be raised by public stock and bond offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is also the bad news,'' he added, noting that events in
foreign countries can affect projects and prices in the United
States, regardless of local market conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate investment trusts, known as REITs, were the first to
feel the market's sting, as disenchanted investors drove the prices
of their shares down, preventing the REITs from selling more shares
to finance a continuation of their buying binge. The overall stock
market also took a sharp lurch downward in August, raising fears of
layoffs in financial services companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those worries have not entirely evaporated despite the market's
strong showing in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw that public markets for real estate are quick to go
down and slow to recover,'' said John Bralower, the president of
Sonnenblick-Goldman, a real estate finance company. ``The
underlying market for the properties did not go down as much as the
stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, recessions in Asia, currency problems in Russia and
the near-collapse of a huge American hedge fund shook up the bond
market in the United States, leaving Wall Street firms unable to
convert into securities the mortgage loans they had already bought.
</P>
<P>
   With widespread uncertainty about the future pricing of
mortgage-backed securities, liquidity dried up and sales ground to
a halt.
</P>
<P>
   Properties that had been for sale were withdrawn from the market
because of uncertainty and declining bids. According to
Insignia/ESG, a real estate brokerage and services company,
properties that were pulled off the market included the 1.5
million-square-foot building at 450 West 33rd St., the 1.1
million-square-foot structure at 237 Park Ave., at 45th Street, and
the million-square-foot building at 450 Lexington Ave., at 45th
Street.
</P>
<P>
   One transaction that did close reflected the abrupt drop in
pricing. Witkoff Group acquired the Woolworth Building, at 233
Broadway, for $133 million after having successfully reduced its
original _ and accepted _ bid of $157 million. The seller was
Venator Group, the successor to the old Woolworth Corp.
</P>
<P>
   All the time the capital markets were churning, most of the real
estate fundamentals were strong, with office vacancies low and
rents stable or climbing. According to a year-end report prepared
by CB Richard Ellis, a brokerage company, the overall office
vacancy rate for Manhattan was 5 percent, with the Midtown North
subdistrict, generally defined as 32nd to 59th Street, river to
river, down to 3.2 percent availability.
</P>
<P>
   Asking annual rents for all classes of multitenanted commercial
buildings in Manhattan reached $36.60 a square foot in the fourth
quarter, according to the report, compared with $29.96 at the end
of 1997. Brokers reported that some prime buildings in key
locations, such as 9 West 57th St. and the General Motors building
at 767 Fifth Ave., were fetching as much as $70 to $75 a square
foot.
</P>
<P>
   Because of these strong fundamentals, most real estate leaders
say they are cautiously optimistic as they head into 1999. The
relative lack of new construction in Manhattan will keep office
rents high, they say, although builders in New Jersey are betting
those rates will drive some companies to their developments along
the Hudson River waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   The big layoffs that were feared in the financial services
industry have not materialized, reducing the chances that a lot of
office space will be dumped back on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, new industries, most of them computer-related, are
growing in Manhattan and injecting new life into what had been
declining postindustrial neighborhoods, such as the garment
manufacturing buildings in the teens between Fifth and Sixth
avenues and the old printing buildings near Hudson Square on the
west side.
</P>
<P>
   The companies in these new industries are contributing to the
numbers and pace at which new leases are being signed. ``Leasing
velocity over the last two years has been 25 to 30 percent better
that the best years in the past,'' said Stephen Siegel, the
president of Insignia/ESG.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said he expected the pace to decline somewhat in 1999,
but added that some large space users, including the NASDAQ stock
trading operation and the German-based publishing company
Bertelsmann, are actively looking for new quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Liquidity will return to the market, real estate executives say,
as Wall Street firms sell their portfolios of existing loans and
start looking for new business. ``People talked about a capital
crisis, but it was really a pricing crisis,'' said John Lyons,
chief executive of Granite Partners, a real estate financing firm.
``People were not lending, because they did not know what price to
lend at.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that one result of the crunch is that money is more
expensive for acquirers and developers than it was. He said that
interest rates are 2 percent to 2.5 percent above Treasury
securities with a similar maturity, compared with 0.8 percent to
1.0 percent above during the summer. But he said that was still
more favorable than the 3 percent to 3.5 percent premiums that
prevailed three years ago as the market was developing.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the height of the crunch in October, he said, lenders were
demanding rates of up to 7.50 percent, regardless of how low the
rates on Treasury securities fell.
</P>
<P>
   Higher interest rates and the need for buyers to put up more
equity capital means that the prices paid for property are expected
to be somewhat lower than in the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return on equity is higher than debt,'' said Barry Gosin,
the chief executive of Newmark &AMP; Company Real Estate, explaining
that stockholders want more income for their greater risk than the
relatively more secure bondholders.
</P>
<P>
   Gosin said if a purchaser has to put up 30 percent to 40 percent
equity _ rather than the 5 percent or 10 percent that was
sufficient when money was flowing out of Wall Street _ it limits
the ability to bid. ``You have to pay less for properties,'' he
said. ``It's that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Gosin said that prices appeared to be down 10 percent to 20
percent, although not many transactions have closed since the bond
market crunch began in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate executives say the markets have functioned as
they are supposed to, cutting off funding before too many people
joined the party. ``The capital markets exerted discipline and
prevented overbuilding,'' said Mitchell Hersh, the president of
Mack-Cali Realty, a New Jersey-based REIT. ``It is usually supply
that puts markets out of balance.''
</P>
<P>
   The furious pace of the first half of 1998 many have contributed
to the slowdown in the later months, said Thomas Benneville,
managing director of LaSalle Partners' investment banking group.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys in my business had the year in the bag by
July,'' he said. ``So when the markets got hit, they had no reason
to move quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted that sales activity would pick up quickly this
year. ``The real estate fundamentals are still good,'' he said,
``and you have to eat in '99, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Others agreed. Darcy Stacom, an investment sales specialist at
the Cushman &AMP; Wakefield brokerage company, said that the Wall
Street firms started getting back in the market late last year and
that she expected sales to be brisk early in the year. ``We are
going to see a lot of product for sale in the first quarter,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   One sale that closed late in the year was that of Exchange Place
Center, a 700,000-square-foot waterfront office tower in Jersey
City, for $175 million. The building was bought by BBV U.S. Real
Estate Fund III, a German investment group, from Prudential Real
Estate Investors.
</P>
<P>
   In the leasing market, brokers say they expect the landlords in
New York to continue to have the upper hand, but few are predicting
sharp increases in rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been better times to be a tenant,'' said James
Meiskin, the president of Plymouth Partners, a tenants'
representative. ``Rents will go up marginally, but you will see
less free rent, less work and tougher lease terms,'' he said,
referring to provisions that give tenants a period of no rent and
require landlords to contribute to renovation costs.
</P>
<P>
   But some brokers say the summer's dips in the stock market have
cooled the demand for space. ``During the summer there was an
intense frenzy for every piece of space,'' said Mitchell Steir, an
executive vice president of the Julien J. Studley brokerage
company. ``That has leveled off. Now the landlords do not have two
backup deals for every bit of space.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the decline in the price of REIT shares sharply slowed
their pace of acquisition, it did not prevent Reckson Associates
Realty Corp. from becoming the second of the suburban-based REITs
to enter the Manhattan office market. The first was Vornado Realty
Trust, which acquired Mendik Co.'s midtown portfolio in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Reckson reached agreement to acquire Tower Realty, a
Manhattan-based REIT with seven buildings totaling 2.3 million
square feet, including Tower 45 at 120 West 45th St.
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was for Reckson to be an equal partner with
Crescent Real Estate in an acquisition vehicle called Metropolitan
Partners. But when Crescent pulled back, Reckson went ahead with
the acquisition for a total of $680 million in cash, stock and
assumption of debt, with Crescent remaining as a passive investor.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Rechler, the president of Reckson, described the
acquisition as a strategic one for the company, which already has
properties on Long Island, in New Jersey and in the area north of
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A report by CIBC Oppenheimer, a securities brokerage and
research firm, on the deal said that ``With Reckson having
established a dominant position as an owner/operator of office and
industrial real estate in the suburban New York market, the Tower
acquisition appears to be a natural extension to fill a geographic
void in its portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   But it warned that Reckson needed to find managers for the Tower
properties who are both savvy about the Manhattan market and able
to participate smoothly in a suburban-oriented company.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The following is a look at markets in the metropolitan area:
</P>
<P>
   Midtown
</P>
<P>
   Prime Office Space Is Scarce
</P>
<P>
   Space in modern buildings in good locations is all but
unavailable, real estate executives report. ``In the top 65
buildings north of 42nd Street, the vacancy rate is about 2
percent, which is something that we have not seen since 1980,''
said Steven Swerdlow, senior managing director of CB Richard Ellis'
metropolitan area office.
</P>
<P>
   With prime space scarce, some tenants are even leasing space
they do not currently need in anticipation of even higher rents and
stiffer terms in the future. ``We are seeing a mentality of taking
an extra 10,000 square feet of space and warehousing it,'' said
Robert Emden, an executive managing director of Grubb &AMP; Ellis, a
brokerage company. ``Tenants are concerned about protecting
themselves down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the last office-market peak in the 1980s, there is very
little building going on in Manhattan, and the few projects under
way or announced are largely preleased. The Reuters news and
financial information company will occupy most of the
856,000-square-foot building, designated 3 Times Square, being
constructed at the northwest corner of Seventh Avenue and 42nd
Street.
</P>
<P>
   The largely complete 1.6 million-square-foot building at
Broadway and 42nd Street, designated 4 Times Square by its
developer, the Durst Organization, will be divided between the
Conde Nast publishing company and the Skadden Arps Slate Meagher &AMP;
Flom law firm.
</P>
<P>
   The financial services company Bear Stearns will be the
principal tenant of a 1.1 million-square-foot building under way on
Madison Avenue between 46th and 47th streets.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter will be the principal tenant and
co-developer of a million-square-foot building to be built on what
is now a parking lot on Seventh Avenue between 49th and 50th
streets. The co-developer is Rockefeller Group, the former
proprietor of the landmarked Rockefeller Center and still the part
owner and manager of four buildings along the west side of Avenue
of the Americas facing the center.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown
</P>
<P>
   High-Tech Firms Keep on Arriving
</P>
<P>
   Because the midtown market has reached saturation, ``the
overflow tenants will have to flow downtown,'' said Cohen of
Williams Real Estate. ``Because that is where the double-digit
vacancies remain.''
</P>
<P>
   During the year, Guardian Life Insurance Company of America said
it would move from the Union Square area to 7 Hanover Square near
the lower tip of Manhattan, while Empire Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield
decided to leave midtown for 461,000 square feet at One World Trade
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing for downtown was that there was no
disaster in financial services,'' said Siegel of Insignia/ESG. He
said that the developing infrastructure of what was once canyons of
office buildings _ new stores, hotels and other amenities _ was
making the area attractive for people who like to live near where
they work.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city-subsidized Plug 'n' Go program and other
incentives have attracted computer-based companies to downtown
buildings that have been rewired and outfitted for tenants who need
robust telecommunications, power and cooling services.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this activity has accelerated the relocation of numerous
small high-technology companies from places like Vancouver,
Cambridge, Mass., and New Hampshire to downtown,'' said a report by
CB Richard Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Suburbs
</P>
<P>
   The Action Is in New Jersey
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is where the commercial development action is, both
along the west bank of the Hudson and in the middle of the state in
Morris and Somerset counties. Private developers are leading the
way, with REITs _ even those with development sites _ holding back
because of uncertainty about how financial analysts will value
projects that have no current income.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street does not know how to handle development projects,
so the REITs will not build on speculation,'' said Donald Eisen,
executive managing director for the suburban market at Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield. Eisen said that between 2 million and 3 million square
feet of office space was under construction in the state, which he
said was not a major addition to a 140 million-square-foot market.
</P>
<P>
   SJP Properties is building three speculative office projects in
Morris, Somerset and Mercer counties totaling 900,000 square feet
and has an agreement with the Port Authority of New York and New
Jersey to build a 1.2 million-square-foot office building on the
waterfront in Hoboken.
</P>
<P>
   Although he will not start the Hoboken project without an anchor
tenant, Steven Pozycki, the company's president, said his
relationship with pension funds insulated him from the ups and
downs of capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The funds followed us in the early 1990s when we were doing
acquisitions and since 1994 when we resumed development,'' he said.
``Our investors know we will take reasonable risks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pozycki said that with Class A office buildings replacing
abandoned industrial plants on the Hudson, the west bank of the
river should be regarded as part of the Manhattan market. But it is
a place that is cheaper and where it is possible to erect buildings
with large floors suitable for trading floors.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel Stern of Hartz Mountain Industries is developing
projects as varied as an office building at 90 Hudson St. in Jersey
City, the TriBeCa Grand Hotel at Sixth Avenue and White streets in
Manhattan and an 1,100-car parking deck in Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   He said the problems in the credit markets actually helped
established developers like himself, who can finance their own
projects if necessary. ``It's the new guys who get hurt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speculative building is also under way on Long Island, where
Greenway Plaza Office Park, a Melville developer, started a
100,000-square-foot office building on Pinelawn Road in Melville in
July. Fortunato Development of Bohemia followed in October with a
60,000-square-foot building at Airport Corporate Center in Bohemia.
And in December, Tilles Cos. began a 100,000-square-foot building
at Gateway Office Park in Woodbury.
</P>
<P>
   In Westchester County, a rising vacancy rate, caused by the
relocation of large companies such as IBM and Nynex, is squelching
any plans to build. The country's overall vacancy rate stood at 18
percent in 1998, compared with 16.5 percent the year earlier. In
the business hub of the county, White Plains, vacancies were 30
percent, up from 28.3 percent in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The small amount of building that is under way in Connecticut is
not taking place in the traditional office center of Stamford, but
in places like Shelton, Norwalk and suburban New Haven. One of the
most ambitious projects is under way in Bridgeport, where the city
is embarked on a $1 billion, 3-million-square-foot waterfront
commercial and retail development.
</P>
<P>
   Retail
</P>
<P>
   Low Vacancy Rates and Higher Prices
</P>
<P>
   A low vacancy rate _ under 5 percent, according to some reports
_ and strong demand for prime locations has driven up rental rates
for retail space in Manhattan, with parts of Madison Avenue among
the most expensive in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``A store with 4,000 square feet on the ground on Madison Avenue
commands in excess of $500 a square foot,'' said Faith Consolo, a
senior managing director of Garrick-Aug Associates, retail real
estate specialists.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Consolo said that the strong economy and the appeal of New
York were behind the demand. ``New York is where retailers want to
be,'' she said. And the appeal is not just glamour. Sales at a
Manhattan store can be as much as those of five or six suburban
mall stores combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is competition for every location that comes on the
market,'' said Alan Victor, an executive vice president of Lansco
Corp., a retail brokerage company. He said the demand came from
stores already in Manhattan, such as the Gap, Old Navy and Coach,
which added locations, and from newcomers such as Restoration
Hardware that are opening their first stores.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to high-fashion stores that cluster on Madison and
Fifth avenues and are slipping into areas like SoHo and the
Flatiron District, chains that deal in more mundane items and have
been successful across the country are looking to New York for
expansion, brokers report. They say that Wal-Mart and Target are
particularly interested in breaking into this market.
</P>
<P>
   Hotels
</P>
<P>
   Room Rates and Occupancy Rise
</P>
<P>
   The city's hotels continue to be essentially full, with profits
rising as operators raise room rates and developers scour the city
for sites to build new hotels or convert existing buildings for use
as hotels.
</P>
<P>
   According to a report by E&AMP;Y Kenneth Leventhal Real Estate
Group, occupancy last year was 83.0 percent compared with 81.5
percent in 1987. The average room rate in the city reached an
all-time high of $192 a night, which was a 9.5 percent increase
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue per available rooms, a key indicator of financial
performance, also reached an all-time high of $159, according to
the report, which was a 11.5 percent increase over 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The financial performance of hotels in New York far outstrips
the rest of the nation, said Sean Hennessey, head of the new York
hospitality practice of PricewaterhouseCoopers, an accounting and
consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   Hennessey said that in 1991 annual income per room after
expenses in New York was $9,179, compared with $4,977 for the rest
of the country. In 1997, the figure for New York was $32,008
compared with $10,100 elsewhere. ``New York is three times more
profitable than the average for the United States,'' Hennessey
said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, there are 16 hotels with a total of 3,256 rooms
under construction or renovation, or considered likely to go
forward, according to a PricewaterhouseCoopers survey. Nine more
hotels, with 3,540 rooms, are in the planning process, and 17 more,
with as many as 6,480 rooms, are in the proposal stage.
</P>
<P>
   But rapidly rising room rates may be too much of a good thing,
Leventhal said. ``With the average daily rate for Manhattan
approaching $200 a night,'' he said, ``Manhattan could be pricing
itself out of some market segments such as wholesale and leisure
travel as well as lower-rated corporate travel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
