<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6137 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-MAFIA-CONSTRUCTION     01-09 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAFIA-CONSTRUCTION-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTORTION CASES EXPOSE MOB TIES TO ROGUE WORKERS' COALITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SELWYN RAAB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For three decades, construction companies in New York
City have been bedeviled by groups claiming to represent minority
workers battling racial bias in the billion-dollar industry. The
groups, dubbing themselves ``community coalitions,'' have often
staged stormy protests that forced contractors to offer them jobs
in return for labor peace.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, the convictions of six coalition leaders in two
separate extortion cases exposed a new aspect of some of the
groups: secret deals between three rogue coalitions and the Mafia
to extract payoffs from contractors.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, William Marshall, a Mafia defector, testified that
the Gambino crime family and two major coalitions joined forces to
shake down contractors in the mid-1990s. The mobsters, he
explained, encouraged coalition leaders to stage disruptions at
construction sites. Gambino family members then stepped in,
Marshall said, promising the contractors that they had the muscle
to end harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The mobsters and the coalition chiefs got thousands of dollars
in payoffs from each collaboration, according to testimony by
Marshall and several contractors who were government witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Although they were paying both sides, Marshall said, the
contractors apparently did not know that the coalition leaders and
mobsters were allies.
</P>
<P>
   The Gambino family, Marshall said, took protection money for
supposedly helping the contractors reduce demands by coalitions.
And prosecutors charged that coalition bosses, in exchange for
canceling protests, were given no-show jobs as ``community
coordinators'' that paid up to $900 a week. Prosecutors asserted
that the coalition leaders did little to find jobs for black and
Hispanic workers. Lawyers for those leaders, however, insisted that
they had found jobs for many minority workers.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall claimed, without citing proof, that two other Mafia
factions in the New York area, the Genovese and Lucchese families,
obtained similar payoffs by using minority coalitions ``to stir up
trouble'' with contractors.
</P>
<P>
   That case, tried in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, also
provided a partial preview of testimony about construction rackets
that may be offered later this year against John A. Gotti, 34, who
is accused of being the acting boss of the Gambino family. Marshall
said that Gotti, son of the imprisoned Gambino boss, John J. Gotti,
got a $50,000 protection payoff in 1995 from a company that was
being extorted simultaneously by a coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A decision that every contractor in New York City has to make
is whether or not to seek protection by employing people from the
coalitions,'' said Joel Aurnow, acting president of DeFoe
Construction Co., whose officials acknowledged at a trial and in
interviews that the company hired representatives of coalitions and
employed a reputed Gambino mobster to deal with the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't arm your employees, and you can't rely on the police
to provide all the protection you need,'' Aurnow said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   Aurnow and other contractors said the coalition disruptions
occurred mainly at construction sites in the city and rarely in the
suburbs or upstate. But six construction companies involved in the
two cases denied paying mobsters for protection.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 16, a federal jury in Manhattan convicted four coalition
leaders on charges of extortion conspiracy: Trevor Johnson, 58,
whom prosecutors described as the leader of Brooklyn Fight Back;
two of his top aides, Robert Carnes, 29, and Daniel Hunter, 27; and
Dennis McCall, 33, of United Construction Labor Coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors charged that the two groups had worked in concert
and with mobsters on extortion plots.
</P>
<P>
   Payroll records and testimony revealed that Johnson was paid
$800 to $900 a week for almost a decade by Tully Construction Co.
of Flushing, Queens; McCall was paid $140,000 in recent years by
HHM Construction Co. of Maspeth, Queens; Carnes was paid $65,000
from 1995 to 1997 by DeFoe Co. of Mount Vernon, and Hunter was paid
$4,500 in 1997 by Sullivan and McGrath Construction Co. of
Amityville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   In a related case in U.S. District Court in White Plains, on the
same day as the guilty verdicts in Manhattan, Michael Sims, 32, and
James Sims, 28, who together ran the Black and Latin Economic
Survival Coalitions, known as BLES, pleaded guilty to extorting an
unspecified amount of money from a company that had a $25 million
state contract for repairs on the Grand Central Parkway in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said they obtained evidence against Michael and
James Sims, who are stepbrothers, after they were heard on
court-authorized telephone taps discussing deals with Gambino
mobsters. No testimony was presented at hearings when the Sims
brothers pleaded guilty, and prosecutors declined to give further
details of the evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The six defendants in the two cases had jobs as community
coordinators or were seeking them from contractors. Each defendant
faces up to 20 years in prison and a fine of $250,000 when
sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   None of the defendants in Manhattan testified. Through
cross-examinations of government witnesses and in summations,
defense lawyers argued that their clients legally earned their
salaries from construction companies by resolving disputes among
rival coalitions and by obtaining jobs for black and Hispanic
construction workers in an industry they described as entrenched in
racism.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers contended that the defendants were recruited for
help in publicly financed projects that require companies to
include minority employees on their work force. Stephen Scaring, a
defense lawyer, maintained in closing arguments that mobsters, not
the coalitions, extorted payoffs only for themselves and that the
Mafia had no influence on the labor organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement and government officials say that since the
1960s, legitimate and questionable coalitions have sprung up in the
city, advocating greater employment of minority construction
workers.
</P>
<P>
   James McNamara, who helped draft city and state regulations on
the hiring of minority workers for public construction jobs, said
that about a dozen loosely organized coalitions exist in the city.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders of most of these groups are out to feather their
own nests and do very little to increase job opportunities for
minorities,'' said McNamara, a former consultant to law enforcement
agencies on labor racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   But he cited two long-established coalitions, Harlem Fight Back,
which is not affiliated with Brooklyn Fight Back, and the Chinese
Construction Workers Association, for unblemished records in
helping minority workers.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Haughton, director of Harlem Fight Back, said the ``teaming
up of these convicted coalition people with organized crime has
discredited legitimate efforts to bring about fair play for blacks,
Latinos and Asians in this industry.''
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, contractors created much of the problem by
inventing the position of community coordinator. ``The real
criminals,'' Haughton said, ``are contractors who pay off phony
coordinators even if they have to use strong-arm methods to keep
legitimate folks away from construction sites and to undermine our
efforts against racism in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   For more than 50 years, criminal and civil cases have shown that
five Mafia families based in the New York area have engaged in
construction corruption, mainly through influence in labor unions.
Before the recent extortion cases, the authorities suspected that
the Mafia cooperated with several coalitions, but found no
substantial evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state investigators say they had been hampered in
uncovering shakedowns by spurious coalitions primarily because
contractors and their employees feared retaliation if they
cooperated with law enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   But an investigation by state and federal agencies that began in
1995 with a look at Gambino family gambling and loan-sharking rings
uncovered evidence involving Brooklyn Fight Back, the United
Coalitions and BLES. In telephone taps and bugs on Gambino members,
investigators heard about meetings and alliances being arranged
with coalitions.
</P>
<P>
   Those leads helped implicate the three coalitions and allowed
investigators to track down the construction companies that were
being victimized.
</P>
<P>
   At the Manhattan trial, Marshall admitted that in the early
1990s, he became an associate, or worker, for a Gambino crew in
Westchester County that prosecutors say was run by Gregory DePalma,
an acting capo, or captain.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, 33, a ruggedly built man who is a former Westchester
County jail guard, said that in 1996 he accompanied DePalma, 66,
his son, Craig DePalma, 32, whom prosecutors have identified as a
Gambino soldier, and other Gambino mobsters to three or four
meetings with Johnson and members of his coalition at the
Baychester Diner in the northeast Bronx. The purpose of the
meetings, he said, was to discuss payoffs from DeFoe Co.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after being indicted with John A. Gotti and both
DePalmas in a broad federal racketeering case, Marshall pleaded
guilty and agreed to testify for the government in return for a
reduced sentence. He is now in the Federal Witness Protection
Program, awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Sarita Kedia, a lawyer for the younger Gotti, characterized
Marshall as a perjurer. ``Marshall did not have any direct
relations with Gotti,'' Ms. Kedia said. ``His testimony is
unreliable and cannot be believed.''
</P>
<P>
   In final arguments at the Manhattan trial, Mylan Denerstein and
Mark Godsey, the federal prosecutors in charge of the case,
maintained that the term ``community coordinator'' was a
construction industry code word for extortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coalitions have created an environment where a contractor
can't do business in New York City without paying for protection,''
Godsey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
