<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6160 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GAY-SENATOR-ART-65     01-09 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GAY-SENATOR-ART-650(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GAY STATE SENATOR JOINS THE CLUB
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Ill., Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ In the first roll call of the 222nd session of
the New York state Legislature, the clerk had to call Thomas
Duane's name three times before he responded, ``Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Duane, the first openly gay member elected to the conservative,
clubby fraternity that is the state Senate, had his back to the
podium. His leather chair sat empty on the Democratic side of the
gilded chamber. He was across the aisle, shaking hands with
Republicans, introducing himself to the powerful majority leader,
Joseph Bruno, in one breath, and in the next, urging him to
reconsider his denial of domestic-partner benefits to employees of
the upper house.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We'll talk,' and I take him at his word,'' Duane
said a few minutes later on Wednesday, after the ceremonial votes
starting the legislative session had been taken and the senators
awaited the call to the Assembly chamber for Gov. George Pataki's
State of the State address.
</P>
<P>
   ``We WILL talk about it,'' Duane added, ``because I won't let
up.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven years of representing the heavily gay neighborhoods
of Chelsea and Greenwich Village on New York City's
Democratic-dominated City Council, Duane, 43, is now firmly in the
minority. He is one of just 25 Democrats in the 61-member Senate, a
body not known for its diversity, where all but 10 members are
white and all but eight are men.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Assemblywoman Deborah Glick of Greenwich Village,
Duane constitutes an ad hoc caucus of two openly homosexual state
legislators. He is the only state lawmaker who identifies himself
as carrying HIV, the virus that causes AIDS, and has just become
the nation's highest-ranking openly HIV-positive elected official
(others include a New York city councilman and a member of the
Illinois Assembly).
</P>
<P>
   It is a distinction Duane dons with delight, responding to
cracks that Bruno and other colleagues are reluctant to shake his
hand with a joke about planting kisses on conservative cheeks. A
big teddy bear of a man with a honeysuckle voice, Duane has a list
of legislative priorities likely to be non-starters in the
Republican-controlled Senate, like civil rights for homosexuals and
privacy protections for people with HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno, who in 1995 derided homosexuality as an ``abnormal life
style,'' offered a ``very hearty welcome'' to Duane in his opening
remarks to the Senate on Wednesday. He declined to discuss the new
senator's arrival in an interview, though his aides have privately
grimaced about the prospect of a gay legislator waving rainbow
flags around the room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's free to express his opinions as he pleases,'' said Sen.
Dale Volker, the Republican chairman of the Senate Codes Committee,
which handles criminal justice issues. ``Will it have a major
impact? I doubt it.''
</P>
<P>
   Wary of being perceived as a one-note politician, Duane said he
also planned to lobby for campaign finance reform, aiming to
increase disclosure requirements and lower contribution limits. He
also wants to relax the stiff penalties of certain drug laws,
televise Senate debates and protect access to abortion clinics.
Those issues have been raised before by others, without success.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Duane relishes the role of the renegade, and he is
prepared to speak up whenever _ and even whether or not _ he is
asked to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it, but it's not the first time I've ever been in
this position. I have some experience being the only one,'' said
Duane, recalling his years at Lehigh University in Pennsylvania,
where, he jokes, there were ``four and a half'' gay people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a minority voice can be very powerful,'' he added,
acknowledging his limited potential as a Democrat in the Republican
Senate but focusing on the importance of being a live example of a
gay person with HIV within the halls of power. ``I don't expect
things to change overnight, but over time.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For now, there is the matter of introducing himself to Capitol
staff members, like the security guard who tried to send Duane
through the metal detector with hoi polloi on Wednesday rather than
let him stream into the Assembly chamber with his fellow senators.
And setting up his office, now barren except for a pair of New York
and United States flags and a broken bookshelf holding some old
budget briefings. Truth is, nobody has yet told him which office he
will get, but Duane is hoping to keep his temporary digs _ which
belonged to his predecessor, Catherine Abate _ because he thrives
on the sunlight streaming through the south-facing windows and
enjoys the view of the skating rink outside.
</P>
<P>
   There is little formal orientation in the Capitol, where Duane,
a former stockbroker, was one of five new senators who arrived last
week (there are two other New York City Democrats, Dan Hevesi of
Queens and Eric Schneiderman of Manhattan, and two Republicans,
John J. Bonacic of Mount Hope in Orange County and Patricia K.
McGee of Franklinville in western New York, both of whom came over
from the Assembly).
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Glick warned Duane that the cafeteria closed at 2 p.m.,
meaning that lunch after the governor's speech would be a crispy
chicken sandwich and fries at McDonald's. Last month, Duane filled
out paperwork for his health insurance and pension, and hired two
staff members who had worked for former senators. Soon he plans to
look for a studio apartment, ``a place with my own bed, a
coffeepot, cable television,'' to cut the dreariness of the Howard
Johnson's motel where he stayed last week. And he has heard that
there are a few gay bars here, though he has yet to check them out.
</P>
<P>
   He is angling for a spot on the Codes Committee, and also wants
a seat on panels dealing with health care, the environment and arts
financing. When the work begins in earnest this week, Duane's top
task will be meeting his colleagues, who were sworn in Wednesday in
a huddle of back slapping that looked like a football team before a
big game. Some Democrats already have their arms open: Sen. Nellie
Santiago of Brooklyn, whom Duane thanked upon their meeting for
casting one of a handful of votes against identifying people who
test positive for HIV by name, saved him a front-row seat Wednesday
for the State of the State.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will give him an opportunity to confront a fair amount of
homophobia,'' Ms. Glick said of Duane's new job. When she asked to
meet with all the Republican senators in 1991 to discuss civil
rights for homosexuals, Ms. Glick recalled, only three agreed; last
year, seven sat down with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably will be some people who would not want to have
any personal contact with him,'' Ms. Glick said.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen DeBold, political director of the Victory Fund, which
raises money for gay and lesbian candidates nationally, said that
when Texas elected its first openly gay state lawmaker in 1992,
people switched seats so they would not be near him. Now there are
about 160 openly gay elected officials nationally, she said, which
sounds like a lot until you realize that there are almost 500,000
positions on numerous public bodies, from library boards to
sanitation commissions.
</P>
<P>
   The old-boy bastion of the state Senate was not Duane's first
choice. He ran, unsuccessfully, for the House of Representatives in
1992. But he faced term limits on the City Council in 2001, and Ms.
Glick, who represents his neighborhood in the Assembly, had no
plans to abandon her perch in the Democrat-controlled lower house.
So when Ms. Abate ran unsuccessfully for attorney general last
year, her open Senate seat provided an opportunity Duane said he
could not pass up.
</P>
<P>
   For a politician who was sometimes criticized at New York City
Hall for representing only his gay constituents, the new post
presents many challenges. The Senate district is about twice the
size of the council district Duane represented, stretching from
Wall Street through Central Park. Even as he fulfills his destiny
as a kind of gay gadfly, constantly raising the HIV-positive
perspective in the conservative Senate, Duane will also have to
scramble to set up a constituent services system, which is the
chief task of the minority Democrats, who can rarely get
legislation passed or even amended.
</P>
<P>
   Duane remains healthy and robust and says his openness has lent
force to his arguments on HIV and AIDS-related issues.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a hematite pinkie ring that binds him to his partner,
Louis Webre, Duane is not hiding. But neither is he reckless: While
many senators had their spouses by their sides during the
swearing-in, Webre was 150 miles away in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might have been a part of me that didn't want to
overwhelm them,'' Duane acknowledged. ``Let them get to know me
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
