<HEADER>
A6174 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-RESEARCHER-NYT &LR;      01-09 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-RESEARCHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESEARCHER FINDS AND OFFERS TREASURE AT LIBRARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ David Shulman's blue eyes glistened as he showed off
his most topical prize: an unused ticket to the impeachment trial
of President Andrew Johnson dated April 21, 1868.
</P>
<P>
   He picked it up at an auction in 1960 for $13 and thinks it
might be one of the few unused tickets remaining. He thinks it
might now be worth a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   But after suffering a heart attack five years ago, Shulman, 86,
gave it away to the place he loves the most, the New York Public
Library. He gave away almost everything else he valued to the same
institution _ a spelling primer from Colonial America, 20,000 old
postcards, and Bowery Boys novels the library did not have.
Thousands upon thousands of things.
</P>
<P>
   Years before, he gave the library his cryptography collection,
which included a book about secret writing published in 1518 and
comic books from World War II.
</P>
<P>
   These are only possessions. What Shulman, who wears blue jeans
and sneakers, lives for is the mental adventure the library
represents. It was there he ferreted out the earliest use of more
than 5,000 words and phrases for the Oxford English Dictionary,
which paid him when they printed the additions or modifications.
</P>
<P>
   It was also at the library that he built a plausible case that
baseball's first game was played in Manhattan, not in New Jersey _
and certainly not in Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of one of the city's most inclusive and
distinguished clubs: regular readers in the Brooke Russell Astor
Reading Room for Rare Books and Manuscripts, at the library's main
branch on Fifth Avenue at 42nd Street. The price of admission is
filling out an application attesting to a serious purpose. Users
range from people designing coffee-table books to poets seeking
inspiration in fraying Latin tomes.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Bartow, curator of rare books, says Shulman is both an
important contributor of material and one of the library's most
frequent users. ``David is what we're all about,'' she said. ``He
collects books, he researches endlessly and he writes for
publication.''
</P>
<P>
   His current campaign is to revive the reputation of Steve
Brodie, the man who declared he was the first to jump from the
Brooklyn Bridge and live. The New York Times, in its 1901 obituary,
told of how Brodie, ``on the strength of this imaginary feat,''
went on to become a saloon owner on the Bowery and start an acting
career.
</P>
<P>
   But Shulman believes that Brodie's feat was not imaginary at
all.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, Shulman spread out scores of old newspaper
stories on a library table to make the case. He had arrived by
subway from the St. Nicholas Adult Care Center in Brooklyn, where
he now lives.
</P>
<P>
   His motivation is to nail down another phrase for the Oxford
dictionary. ``To do a Brodie'' has long meant to take a dive, a
phrase sometimes applied to the stock market. But Shulman insists
that if the man did not dive, the phrase must go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in running everything down to primary sources,'' he
said. ``In other words, if you pursue the truth as far as you can,
you'll find out many times that it ain't so.''
</P>
<P>
   Painstakingly, through The National Police Gazette, The Brooklyn
Eagle and other sources, he sifted evidence against the assertion
that Brodie, a newsboy, conned reporters into believing him. He
noted that witnesses, including a police officer, testified that
they saw Brodie leap in 1886. Shulman asked, ``If he was carrying a
dummy, wouldn't anybody have noticed it? A dummy's a big thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He concluded: ``Everything is alleged. No concrete evidence. I
think he did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until he retired in 1956, this self-described ``Sherlock Holmes
of rare books'' designed puzzles for newspapers. In World War II,
he deciphered Japanese codes. He was long one of the world's top
Scrabble players. He never married, saying he never had the time.
He said his only relatives are two nieces whom he has had no time
for since they tried to stop him from giving his treasures to the
library.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it, but your relatives can be predators,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The library is different. There he can show friends his
impeachment ticket, or have millions of potentially fascinating
intellectual treats delivered to him. He can time-travel in the
manner of his mentor, Norbert Pearlroth, the chief researcher for
``Ripley's Believe It or Not,'' who pored through hundreds of books
virtually at random in search of odd facts.
</P>
<P>
   But Shulman, who carries myriad scribblings on index cards in a
plastic bag, came to see his mentor as less than rigorous.
``Instead of believing it,'' he said, ``I believed it not.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he bubbled happily off on a kaleidoscope of things. Did you
know there is no difference between a split finger fastball and a
forkball? Or that the marquess of Queensberry did not personally
write the rules of boxing that are named after him?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
