<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 15:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6175 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DNA-DEBATE-ART-430     01-09 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DNA-DEBATE-ART-430&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARPTON AND ACLU ASSAIL NEW YORK GOVERNOR'S DNA PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jw) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rev. Al Sharpton and Norman Siegel, executive
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, pledged Saturday to
fight together against Gov. George Pataki's proposal for a
statewide database containing information on the DNA of all felons.
</P>
<P>
   They said the plan, outlined in the governor's State of the
State message last week, threatened privacy, exceeded any
legitimate law enforcement needs and could ultimately be used to
discriminate against those who fit a general genetic profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a major mistake to equate DNA samples with fingerprints
and to say they are used solely for identification purposes,''
Siegel said at a news conference at Sharpton's National Action
Network in Harlem. ``DNA is that, but it is also much, much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, who has maintained that the criminal justice system is
racially biased, added that the proposal posed a particular threat
to black and Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't become just numbered, medically identified pawns of
the state,'' he said. ``We must have the right to live our lives,
but not as suspects.''
</P>
<P>
   The joint appearance by the city's most flamboyant black
advocate and its most visible white civil libertarian, was
sprinkled with sentimental references to similar alliances that
blossomed during the civil rights movement of the 1960s but have
infrequently surfaced since.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel raised rainbow visions, declaring that with ``black,
white, brown and yellow together,'' this year would be ``a defining
moment in the history of civil liberties in the city and state.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Sharpton told his supporters in the audience that
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. would be proud of his alliance with
Siegel and the civil liberties group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the same lineage,'' he said. ``We fought governors in
the South before and we'll fight governors in the North now.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said the availability of DNA testing and technology had
spurred attacks on individual rights in New York from several
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir suggested last month that DNA
samples be taken from every person arrested and fingerprinted.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani backed him and went further, saying he would
not object to DNA testing and fingerprinting of all newborns.
</P>
<P>
   On a state level, DNA samples have been taken for the last three
years from people convicted of sexual and violent crimes. In those
narrowly defined categories, Siegel said, law enforcement
authorities can make a case for DNA sampling because saliva and
blood, the sources of the DNA samples, are likely to be found at
crime scenes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sharpton and Siegel have fought on the same side of the
barricades frequently in the recent past, particularly in
protesting police brutality and Giuliani's policies. Last month,
both Siegel and Sharpton shared the microphone at an AIDS
activists' rally at City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   But their motivations have sometimes been at odds. Siegel, for
example, defended a white police officer who was disciplined for
riding on a Labor Day parade float that parodied a racial murder.
The defense argument focused on free speech. Sharpton appeared as a
witness for the same officer at a police hearing, but he said the
punishment was the mayor's attempt to curry favor with blacks.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of DNA testing, the two expressed willingness not
only to join forces but to merge their styles.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Siegel tried to engage the crowd of Sharpton's
supporters by getting them to repeat his slogan, ``DNA is d.o.a.''
The audience didn't catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel tried again, with a bit more zest. ``DNA is d.o.a.'' he
called out, nodding toward the silent audience of a few dozen
people in encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton got to his feet and grabbed the lectern. ``Let me show
you how to do this, Norm,'' he said, and roused the crowd to chant
the slogan with fists raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is DNA?'' Sharpton called out in conclusion. ``D-O-A!''
roared the people in response.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we just saw is a perfect example of why we need
coalitions,'' Siegel said in reclaiming the microphone. ``A lawyer
alone ain't worth very much. A preacher alone ain't worth very
much. But a preacher and a lawyer together _ watch out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
