A6176 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-GOLDSTEIN-NYT &LR;      01-09 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GOLDSTEIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEON GOLDSTEIN, 66, COMMUNITY COLLEGE PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Fla.)  (mk) 
 By KAREN W. ARENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Leon Goldstein, the gentle, genial, politically savvy
president of Kingsborough Community College of the City University
of New York and a leading candidate for New York City schools
chancellor in 1995, died in his sleep Friday night at his home in
Manhattan, a CUNY spokesman said. He was 66.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's skill in building a political base for Kingsborough,
which is in Brooklyn, in New York City and beyond, and his
willingness to seek efficiency for CUNY at a time of economic
belt-tightening, brought him to the attention of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the mayor endorsed him as his candidate for schools
chancellor, and over the opposition of the board president, Carol
Gresser, put together a majority of the school board to support
him. But in the face of questions about whether he had dispensed
political patronage and about his willingness to be forthcoming
about his own resume, Goldstein withdrew his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   He was later cleared of the patronage accusations by the
Brooklyn district attorney's office. A separate CUNY investigation
cleared him of wrongdoing, except for one ``minor'' transgression
in which he used college stationery to support a Brighton Beach,
Brooklyn, real estate development.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last year, he said he was disappointed that he
was forced to withdraw due to the accusations. ``My time would have
been spent responding to the allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, his time at Kingsborough had been happy and
productive. ``I'm a very, very happy man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Borough Park, Brooklyn, the son of immigrants from
Poland, Goldstein stayed close to his roots. He attended two CUNY
schools _ City College and Brooklyn College _ for his bachelor's
and master's degrees, and was involved in CUNY's central
administration, as dean for community colleges and as deputy
chancellor and acting chancellor between 1981 and 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Amid budget cutbacks in 1992, Goldstein took on the unenviable
task of leading a committee of CUNY presidents and faculty in
recommending ways to improve academic planning. The resulting
report, which called for colleges to cut programs that duplicated
those on other CUNY campuses, caused a firestorm of protest among
faculty and other CUNY officials. Although most of the report's
specific suggestions were not adopted, campuses like Baruch
embraced some of its principles.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein's strong administrative skills, his wide political
connections and his personal charm made him often mentioned as a
possible candidate for other offices. But his primary career _ and
his pride and joy _ was at Kingsborough, which he built from a tiny
college parked in a collection of merchant marine barracks into an
innovative and successful institution housed in a sparkling complex
on 72 acres nestled between Jamaica and Sheepshead Bays.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the Robert Moses of CUNY,'' said Jay Hershenson,
Kingsborough's vice chancellor for university relations.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsborough offered the usual programs in liberal arts,
nursing, secretarial skills and business, but it also offered a
program in marine technology, replete with a former Coast Guard
cutter outfitted to conduct research and an aquarium with small
sharks and other fish. Construction on additional buildings was to
begin soon.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein also developed programs for a wide range of students,
from 5- and 6-year-olds who attended a special summer program to
teenagers who attended the college's High School for the Sciences
to a core of some 800 senior citizens who took tuition-free
classes. His ``college now'' program, which offered college
preparatory classes to high school seniors who could not pass
CUNY's placement tests, is now offered in 25 high schools and being
expanded throughout the CUNY system with backing from Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein drew support and financing for Kingsborough through
his active involvement in Brooklyn political and educational
circles. He was close to Brooklyn Borough President Howard Golden
and to William Thompson Jr., the former deputy borough president
and now president of the school board.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, even as he defended the need for remedial
classes for students, Goldstein would not criticize Giuliani for
his denunciations of CUNY and its remedial programs. Just last
month, he sent CUNY a letter saying he planned to retire as
president of Kingsborough in September.
</P>
<P>
   Goldstein is survived by his wife, Mary De Piano Rothlein; a
son, Michael of New York City; a daughter, Lisa Miller of Mahwah,
N.J.; and two sisters, Toby Alden of Brooklyn and Marilyn Alsofrom
of Royal Palm, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
