<SLUG> BC-STAMP10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Watch your pennies if you plan on sending mail
 &HT;    By Mike Morris
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The bad news is the cost of sending first-class mail
goes up today. The good news is the increase _ to 33 cents from 32
cents _ is the smallest of 10 over the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Why is the new cost of stamps only a penny more?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just enough revenue to cover our costs and expenses in
the forseeable future,'' said Michael Miles, spokesman for the U.S.
Postal Service's Atlanta region. ``The Postal Service is by mandate
required to break even over a given period of time. We believe that
1 cent will bring in enough revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   The Postal Service petitioned the Postal Rate Commission, an
independent body of private citizens appointed by the president and
confirmed by the Senate, in July 1997, and the penny increase was
approved last May, Miles said.
</P>
<P>
   There are several things to remember about the new postal rates:
</P>
<P>
   _ The new 33-cent stamps went on sale last week. Where they are
unavailable, you can obtain stamps bearing the letter ``H,'' which
also cover the new postage rate.
</P>
<P>
   _ All 32-cent stamps will need to be accompanied by a 1-cent
``makeup'' stamp.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you forget and send mail with only a 32-cent stamp, it will
still be delivered, but with postage due, Miles said. The mail will
be returned to the sender if the recipient declines to pay the
extra penny.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you dropped mail Saturday into a box that doesn't have
Saturday pickup, that mail will also be treated as ``postage due.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The rate for sending up to a half-pound by Express Mail
Next-Day Service also increases today, rising a buck to $11.75,
while the two-pound rate increases to $15.75. The Priority Mail
rate for up to two pounds goes to $3.20 from $3.
</P>
<P>
   _ The rate for mailing a postcard remains the same at 20 cents.
</P>
<P>
   _ The second-ounce price for first-class mail weighing more than
an ounce actually decreases today, to 22 cents from 23 cents, but
it won't be much consolation because relatively few first-class
letter exceed an ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
