<HEADER>
A6182 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-FREEAGENTS10-     01-09 1024
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FREEAGENTS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's a whole new money game
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The haggling is over. Now, let the haggling begin.
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA's board of governors was approving the league's
new labor agreement, Dikembe Mutombo was laughing Thursday at the
Sheraton Hotel in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a mad rush to sign guys,'' Mutombo said.
``Actually, I think it's already started.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be illegal of course, but...
</P>
<P>
   Hawks president Stan Kasten understands the reality as 29 teams
toe the starting line, waiting for the gun to sound and the
free-agent season to open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (the owners and general managers present) that we would
abide by the rules, and I expected them to do the same,'' Kasten
said, his tone arch.
</P>
<P>
   Right. And all waiters keep accurate tax records of their tip
money.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful of that, the NBA caved in late Friday afternoon and said
agents and teams can start talking but cannot make deals.
</P>
<P>
   Player signings could start as early as Jan. 18, and such teams
as the Hawks, Bulls and Suns can't wait very long. Each has only
four players under contract, and, if the Suns have their toes over
the line, well, with $18 million to spend, only a competitor could
blame them.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Chicago's stakes are higher. Those on the free-agent
sidelines include Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen. Odds are that
neither will be around this season, but the longer they wait to
announce intentions the more difficult it's going to be for the
Bulls to assemble a competitive team. In fact, the once ludicrous
notion that the Bulls might have to renounce Jordan, who made $33
million last season, could become a frightening public-relations
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks will have six players when their rookies sign in,
seven when Tyrone Corbin agrees to a $1 million deal that is
virtually done. But re-signing Alan Henderson is no lock. Neither
are there any guarantees that Antonio McDyess will re-up with the
Suns.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the money games within the games are very much
alive, even though players now are slotted at different levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think agents are no longer useful,'' Kasten said,
``but that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   No, not at all. They will survive as a breed, agent Keith Glass
said: ``We're like rats; we adapt.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is a good example of how contentious the process might
be. As a three-year player, he can make as much as $9 million this
season with 12 percent raises on the base year thereafter. But as
promising as Henderson might be, he has only been a starter for
about half a season, and he has averaged slightly fewer than 22
minutes a game in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson might prefer to remain with his teammates, but he
could be able to find a team desperate to sign a forward with
promise, hang the cost. That's the sort of thinking that got the
owners in trouble in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   The pro game constantly evolves on the court, and now the
changes will come in the way contracts are constructed. For
example, if the Hawks were willing, Henderson could sign a
seven-year contract that would start at $9 million and ultimately
be worth $87 million. The same starting point would get him to
$67.5 million with another team. That's because the Hawks can give
a ``Bird rights'' player, their own free agent, an annual raise at
12 percent, while another team could pay only 10 percent. In the
fifth year of a contract, a player can choose to get out and
negotiate again.
</P>
<P>
   But a player in Henderson's spot might ask for a four-year deal,
so he could move up to the middle level in terms of playing
experience, which allows for an $11 million top. He could then take
a three-year deal and shoot for the top level with a $14 million
salary.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't expected to happen with Henderson, but it could with
such players as Kobe Bryant, Allan Iverson and Stephon Marbury, at
some point.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the rush to sign becomes such a dicey game.
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets are under pressure to give star scoring
forward Glen Rice a new deal, but if they do, they might not be
able to afford either of their free-agent centers, Vlade Divac or
Matt Geiger.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Rockets want to add a big name, such as Pippen or
McDyess, but they also want to keep young players Matt Maloney and
Othella Harrington. Given that teams are penalized heavily for
having unsigned free agents on their cap list _ it's 300 percent
for players under the league average and 250 percent for players
over the average (Jordan counts $82.5 million against the Bulls'
cap) _ the Rockets have unenviable choices if they are to utilize
fully their $9 million for a star.
</P>
<P>
   No team has more to spend than the Suns with $18 million. That
gives them the best shot at such players as Tom Gugliotta. However,
Denver is heavily courting agent Richard Howell's client and using
an unorthodox tactic to overcome a terrible history _ 11-71 last
season _ and a coach, Mike D'Antonio, who is so obscure that his
name does not appear in the NBA Register's coaches' section.
</P>
<P>
   Denver's advantage is Gugliotta's wife, a tri-athlete who loves
Colorado. But after being trapped on bad teams earlier in his
career, the multi-purpose power forward might elect to remain in
Minnesota, where he can get his best deal and be part of a
burgeoning contender. If not, the Suns, with their magnificent
arena and weather and their commitment to do almost anything to
win, are a powerful lure.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the Lakers to be active. They already have dumped Nick
Van Exel after last spring's embarrassing four-game collapse
against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other Western contenders Seattle, Utah and Seattle
will do more tweaking than shaking up. The same is true for
Indiana, Miami and New York in the East. All have either big
rosters or salary-cap problems.
</P>
<P>
   The woeful Canadian teams, Toronto and Vancouver, and the Los
Angeles Clippers have 10 guaranteed contracts each on their 12-man
rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes stability is an unenviable condition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
