</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-ADVANCE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chrebet, the littlest Jet, plays big on third down
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Never known as a braggart, the smallest
player on the field for today's divisional-round game between the
New York Jets and Jacksonville Jaguars was confident enough last
week to suggest he might actually make the biggest impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games like this a lot of times come down to who makes the most
plays on third down,'' New York wide receiver Wayne Chrebet said.
``And I think that's where I give us an edge. That's when I want
the ball the most. I feel like third down is my down.''
</P>
<P>
   That certainly has been the case during Chrebet's four seasons
in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Of his 283 receptions, 113 have converted third downs into first
downs. Chrebet had 26 third-down catches in 1998, the sixth-most in
the league, and 412 of his career-best 1,083 yards came on third
down. Four of his career-high eight touchdown receptions were on
third-down plays. Chrebet tied with teammate Keyshawn Johnson for
the most first downs produced (60) by reception.
</P>
<P>
   Among the wide receivers who entered the league in '95, only
Arizona's Frank Sanders has more catches than Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   Those are heady numbers for the former Hofstra University
walk-on, an undersized guy (5 feet 10, 185 pounds) who originally
signed with the Jets as an undrafted free agent.
</P>
<P>
   In his book ``Just Give Me The Damn Ball,'' Johnson derisively
refers to Chrebet as a ``team mascot'' and the two barely speak.
But even the loquacious Johnson has been forced to grudgingly
concede that his colleague is a rare talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give the guy his due, he gets the job done,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he starts with Johnson in the Jets' two-wideout base
set, Chrebet moves inside on third down when Dedric Ward becomes
the third receiver. In a survey of nine AFC personnel directors
last week, Chrebet was named by six as the premier slot receiver in
the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Working primarily between the hash marks, his technical
proficiency in route-running and fearlessness in going after the
ball are huge assets. And despite relatively pedestrian speed,
Chrebet possesses good run-and-catch abilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can try to 'bracket' him with a linebacker, but most times
Chrebet is going to be working against man-to-man,'' Buffalo
secondary coach Bill Bradley said. ``And he has the smarts to beat
one guy in most situations.''
</P>
<P>
   In what might be a high-scoring shootout between the Jets and
Jaguars, the battle of Chrebet and Jacksonville ``nickel'' safety
Mike Logan could be the critical matchup of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Jacksonville secondary is suspect; the pass rush rates the
worst among clubs still in the playoffs, and Logan is more a zone
than a man-to-man defender. If the Jaguars play mostly zone
coverages, Chrebet will find some cozy creases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the caliber of receiver on both teams, there could
be some big plays made in the passing game,'' Chrebet said. ``I'm
not a big-play guy in terms of those 60-yard catches, but if we
need to keep the ball moving, I feel like I'm the guy who can do it
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1644EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
