<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-ADVANCE10-COX     01-09 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-ADVANCE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Viking stars overshadow very fine line
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Long before he started scrutinizing videotape of the
Minnesota Vikings' skill-position players last week, Dave McGinnis
was popping aspirin like it was candy. The powerful Minnesota
offensive line that left lumps on the heads of foes during the 1998
season had become a throbbing migraine for McGinnis, the Arizona
Cardinals' defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-scoring offense in NFL history may conclude most
possessions with Randy Moss or Cris Carter standing in the end zone
after a long pass from Randall Cunningham or tailback Robert Smith
getting there on a long run.
</P>
<P>
   Like most coaches, however, McGinnis realizes all the action
starts with the NFL's premier blocking unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of all those flashy guys they have on offense, people
lose sight of the fact the offensive line is so good,'' said
McGinnis, whose defensive front seven needs another stellar
performance today to stay with the Vikings. ``You've got three of
the five (linemen) going to the Pro Bowl, and the two who aren't
could make a pretty good case. It really is one of the most
talented units I've seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, few lines of the past two decades can match up with left
tackle Todd Steussie, left guard Randall McDaniel, center Jeff
Christy, right guard David Dixon and right tackle Korey Stringer.
Top backup Everett Lindsay, a versatile player who has lined up at
all five positions this season and started three games, is good
enough to start for several teams in the league.
</P>
<P>
   McDaniel, Steussie and Christy were voted to the NFC Pro Bowl
team this season. Stringer might be the best right-side power
tackle in the game, and Minnesota line coach Mike Tice thinks Dixon
is the most improved player on the team. Twice this season Dixon
manhandled Tampa Bay defensive tackle Warren Sapp.
</P>
<P>
   Even with lightweights Christy (6-3, 281) and McDaniel (6-3,
279), the unit ranks as the NFL's biggest, averaging 6 feet 4 1/4,
318.2 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't only the size, though, that will present major problems
today for the Cardinals' undersized front. The Vikings linemen are
superb technicians, well-schooled by Tice. And it doesn't hurt to
have a 10-time Pro Bowl performer like McDaniel, still one of the
league's quickest guards at age 34, around to lead by example.
</P>
<P>
   Management has been savvy enough to recently re-sign Steussie
and Stringer to new, long-term contracts. With the exception of
Christy, who soon could get an extension, all the linemen are under
contract until at least the 2000 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing free agency has affected the most, in a negative
sense, is the offensive line play,'' Steussie said. ``They've
demonstrated foresight here in trying to keep this group together,
and that's paid off for them.''
</P>
<P>
   McGinnis, who played five down linemen last week against Dallas
and often dropped undersized ends Simeon Rice and Andre Wadsworth
into the flats, figures to have some gimmick schemes for today as
well. But even he isn't confident that brains can overcome the
Vikings' brawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to fight them and hard to finesse them,'' he said.
``They make it a long day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
