<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FIRE-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE COMMISSIONER WANTS INSTRUCTIONS IN EVERY APARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BRUCE LAMBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Because of widespread ignorance about what to do in a
fire, safety instructions should be posted on the door in every
apartment in New York City, just as they are in hotel rooms, Fire
Commissioner Thomas Von Essen said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Von Essen said he planned to have fire officials meet with
landlord groups and the City Council to create a voluntary program.
But if that fails, he said he was prepared to ask the council to
require such notices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a simple thing, but it makes all the sense in the
world,'' Von Essen said in an interview Saturday at City Hall.
``Landlords should educate their own tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   His proposal is part of the Giuliani administration's response
to last month's fire at Park South Tower on West 60th Street in
Manhattan, where four residents died in a smoke-filled stairwell.
</P>
<P>
   Tenant leaders there blamed the deaths on a variety of factors,
including broken intercoms, the busy phone at the desk in the
lobby, lack of alarms, poorly marked exits and basic
misunderstanding about what to do in a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents, dutifully following instructions posted at the
elevators to use the stairs in case of fire, tried to escape via
the stairwells. But the smoke and fumes in one of them proved
deadly.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, safety experts said, people in high-rise buildings
should not use either the elevators or stairwell during a fire.
They should leave their apartments only if that is where the fire
is. Otherwise, they should stay where they are until firefighters
arrive. That is because high-rise construction is fire resistant,
and will almost always confine a fire to the apartment where it
started.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the many different types of buildings in the city,
some of which are not fireproof, Von Essen said the posted
instructions should be tailored to each location. Those
instructions could advise tenants whether a specific building is
safe to stay in if there is a fire.
</P>
<P>
   Other parts of the city administration's plan to enhance fire
safety were announced Thursday and Friday by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
and Von Essen.
</P>
<P>
   Those proposals include a requirement for sprinklers in
apartments and hallways of all new residential buildings, including
single-family homes; the installation of public-address systems,
which could be used to alert and direct residents in emergencies,
in all apartment buildings over six floors high; and a citywide
safety-education campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The council appears willing to adopt those programs. But at a
council hearing on Friday, tenant leaders, safety experts and
representatives of the sprinkler industry said the mayor's program
did not go far enough. The critics demanded that sprinklers be
required in existing high-rise buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The real estate industry has opposed sprinklers as unnecessary
and expensive, estimating the cost at thousands of dollars for each
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Saturday that putting sprinklers in existing
buildings was a complex issue that needed more study. ``We haven't
closed our minds to that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most other major cities require sprinklers in high-rise
apartments, New York _ with far more people living in high-rises
than other cities have _ does not. The city has instead relied on
codes mandating fire-resistant construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1731EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-SUBURBAN-CRIME-720     01-09 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SUBURBAN-CRIME-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIME CREEPS INTO A NEW JERSEY SUBURB 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLEMINGTON, N.J. _ Amid the sprawling fields, winding roads,
run-down farms and 19th-century stone houses that typify much of
Hunterdon County, there is an increasing intrusion more alarming
than the deer or bears that wander into people's back yards: crime.
</P>
<P>
   While the crime rate is down sharply in most parts of New
Jersey, it is rising in Hunterdon County _ and faster than anywhere
else in the state, according to statistics released the week before
last for the first half of 1998. The statistics, compiled by state
police, showed Hunterdon with a 32 percent increase, almost
entirely because of nonviolent crimes like burglary and car theft.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Hunterdon County, about an hour due west of New York
City, has suddenly become a dangerous place. In the first six
months of 1998, it reported the fewest violent crimes of any county
in the state, and not a single murder. Over all, Hunterdon had 903
reported crimes in that period. Only Sussex County had fewer, with
857.
</P>
<P>
   But officials in Flemington, the county seat, and in Trenton,
the state capital, acknowledge that crime is not as rare as it used
to be. They blame Hunterdon's swift population growth, describing
the rise in shoplifting, car thefts and house break-ins as a
natural consequence of a rural farming region being transformed
into suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are moving into that county at a very rapid pace,''
said John Hagerty, a state police spokesman. ``This is not an
unusual phenomenon. When you have a wealthier urban population
moving into rural areas, you usually see an increase in
property-related crime, a spike. It then levels off and ultimately
decreases as law enforcement responds.''
</P>
<P>
   The population in Hunterdon County has jumped nearly 14 percent
since 1990, to 122,842 in 1998, according to an estimate by the
county planning board, from 107,802, according to federal census
data. Accompanying the population growth of about 2 percent a year
has been a boom in new housing, strip malls and other stores and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Front-page articles in last week's Hunterdon County Democrat, a
newspaper published on Thursdays, convey the sense of growth: In
Lambertville there are plans to build a new police station. In
Ringoes the county wants to triple the size of a public-library
branch, and the Postal Service is trying to find a bigger post
office.
</P>
<P>
   In many towns, the growth means more work for the local police
or the state police, which patrols small towns that do not have
their own departments.
</P>
<P>
   In Franklin Township, the opening of a Wal-Mart store in 1997
was followed by some new restaurants. Now Hampton Inn is building a
motel, and there are plans for a multiplex movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting a little more congested up here,'' said the
police chief, Edward Mangini, explaining why his department hired
two more officers and now stays open 24 hours a day instead of 20.
</P>
<P>
   In Franklin, as throughout Hunterdon County, much of the rise in
crime seems to be vehicle-related. ``We have a significant increase
in DWI cases and minor drug cases,'' Mangini said. ``There's been
some burglary and theft, mostly motor-vehicle-related things.''
</P>
<P>
   Each week, the crime blotter in The Hunterdon County Democrat
describes an array of incidents that support Mangini's description
of crime in the county, like the recent arrests of a 42-year-old
Ringoes man who was charged with drunken driving and a 22-year-old
Plainfield man who was charged with possessing marijuana after
being stopped for speeding on Route 202.
</P>
<P>
   That highway, which leads from Somerville to the Pennsylvania
border, and Interstate 78, which connects Jersey City with
Allentown, Pa., are the two main roadways through Hunterdon, where
officers often discover crimes committed by drivers.
</P>
<P>
   But the majority of incidents are minor, country-town stuff,
like the driver who ran off Rosemont-Ringoes Road and knocked over
Lori Hudzik's mailbox in Delaware Township. Or the driver who
struck a deer on Route 31. Hunterdon County remains a place that
people move to so they can enjoy the fresh air and where a state
trooper, stopping to check up on your sick neighbor, might come
over and help you feed the chickens.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In Raritan Township last month, Officer Ed Barnes was dispatched
to deal with a group of rowdy teen-agers who had gathered after 11
p.m. for a milk-drinking contest. According to an article in The
County Democrat, under the headline ``Bored Teens Do Dairy,'' 15
upperclassmen from Hunterdon Central High School each bought a
gallon jug of milk and put up $10 stakes, to be taken by the winner
who could drink the most and hold it down.
</P>
<P>
   No one was arrested when Barnes broke up the Friday night event,
although he declined to turn on his lights and sirens to make the
scene more exciting for a youngster among the crowd of 15 who was
videotaping the event. As Barnes ordered everyone to break it up
and head home, several contestants were said to have been in the
bushes suffering the unhappy consequences of milk-chugging defeat.
</P>
<P>
   State Trooper William Wheatley, who is assigned to the nearby
towns of Stockton and Kingwood as part of the state community
policing program, said law enforcers in Hunterdon County spend most
of their time working to prevent problems rather than responding to
actual crimes, which are still rare.
</P>
<P>
   Making his rounds last week, Wheatley stopped to check on an
elderly Kingwood resident who had been sick, only to find that the
man was still in the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wheatley spent a few minutes chatting with the man's
neighbor, Julius Gombosi, a farmer who has lived in Hunterdon all
his life. Gombosi said he hadn't much noticed the increase in
crime, though he was robbed once, about three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Phillips, 49, whose family has owned a wine store in
Stockton for 53 years, said the growth inevitably meant more crime.
``I think it's the influx of population,'' he said. ``There's a lot
of new people moving in.'' But he said he still felt as safe as
always.
</P>
<P>
   County officials stressed that the statistics showing increased
crime did not also reflect the amount of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go from very, very little to a little,'' said the
county's principal planner, Les Varga, ``it seems like a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 1741EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
