<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6209 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRACK-BONUSES-NYT &LR;      01-09 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRACK-BONUSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH $5,000 BONUSES AT STAKE, TWO TEAR UP A FAST TRACK
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Ind., Ireland)   (jw) 
 By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a sports world in which a baseball player can earn
$13 million a year and a basketball player has just been limited to
an annual ceiling of $14 million, $5,000 sounds like tip money. But
to track and field athletes, especially those below the superstar
level of a Michael Johnson or a Jackie Joyner-Kersee, $5,000 is a
good day's pay, especially this early in the indoor season when no
one is in the best racing shape.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was a $5,000 day for Richie Boulet, a 25-year-old
Californian, and Sinead Delahunty, a 27-year-old from Ireland. In
the New Balance Games at the Armory Track and Field Center in
Washington Heights, Boulet won the men's invitation mile in 3
minutes 57.89 seconds and Delahunty the women's mile in 4:31.96.
</P>
<P>
   This was the first time elite athletes had competed on the
month-old, six-lane, 200-meter banked track, with a Mondo
artificial surface atop plywood. The track is fast, and the New
Balance, basically a high school meet with a handful of invitation
events, offered incentives for the runners to be fast, too.
</P>
<P>
   If the men's winner bettered four minutes, he was assured of a
$5,000 bonus. If the women's winner bettered 4:33, she would get
$5,000. If one broke the barrier but not the other, the barrier
breaker would get $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   The men raced first. Boulet was tired because he flew here from
California on Friday and bad weather kept him from reaching his
hotel room here until 12:30 Saturday morning. But the race pace was
easy and consistent, and Boulet finished strongly, winning by 8
meters. As fast as his race was, he had run faster _ 3:53.26
outdoors and 3:56.85 indoors.
</P>
<P>
   James Njoroge, a 25-year-old Kenyan, finished second in 3:58.78;
Matt Holthaus third in 3:59.43, Tom Nohilly fourth in 4:00.53 and
Karl Paranya fifth in 4:00.71. It was the first sub-four-minute
mile for Njoroge, a 1997 graduate of Taylor University in Indiana.
He had not run indoors for two years because of a stress fracture
in his right shin.
</P>
<P>
   This was Boulet's first race since early August, and he was not
so optimistic beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be tough going under four minutes this early in the
season,'' he said before the race. ``This is a form check. If I
don't break four minutes, I go home and train. If I break it, I
still go home and train.''
</P>
<P>
   Delahunty, who lives in Boston, took over her race Saturday with
two laps remaining, ran the last quarter-mile in 64.1 seconds and
beat Debbie Marshall (4:33.57) by 10 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done very little speed work,'' Delahunty said, ``and I
had no idea what the splits were. I went by how I felt, and I felt
good.''
</P>
<P>
   While Delahunty was racing, Boulet watched from a high-jump pit
near the finish line. Until the end, he could not tell if she would
break 4:33 and thus leave him with $5,000 instead of $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   He yelled at her to step it up, and when she did and cut into
his take-home pay, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great for her and great for all of us,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
