</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROFESSOR-HARASSMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT REJECTS PROFESSOR'S CHALLENGE OF SEX-HARASSMENT FINDING 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ITHACA, N.Y. _ A state appeals court has again rejected a
Cornell psychology professor's $1.5 million lawsuit challenging the
school's procedures in finding him guilty of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The professor, James Maas, 60, has long been one of Cornell's
most popular professors. Nearly 2,000 students attend his
introductory psychology class every fall, making it one of the
largest college courses in the country, and he is also nationally
known for his research on sleep deprivation and the educational
films and television specials he has produced.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling on Thursday came more than four years after Cornell
administrators upheld a unanimous finding by a faculty ethics
committee that Maas had behaved unprofessionally in his
relationship with four female students, and that his behavior
constituted sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   The students worked for the professor as teaching assistants,
members of his film crew and, in one case, a nanny for his
children. Three of the women told the ethics committee that Maas
had repeatedly kissed and hugged them and made sexually suggestive
comments. All four said he had bought them gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Maas acknowledged much of the activity that led the committee in
Cornell's College of Arts and Sciences to find him guilty of sexual
harassment. But he sued Cornell in 1995, asserting that his
behavior did not constitute sexual harassment and that the
procedures used to review the accusations against him were invalid.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell has since instituted campuswide procedures for
investigating and adjudicating accusations of sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Maas was on a national book tour and did not return messages
left Friday evening at his home and office. One of his lawyers,
Michael Rothman, said he had not yet seen the decision, but said
the professor would likely appeal certain issues to the state Court
of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, the Appellate Division of the state
Supreme Court affirmed the dismissal of six of Maas' eight original
claims against Cornell. The unanimous ruling last week by a
three-judge panel of the same court said a state Supreme Court
judge had properly dismissed the remaining two claims alleging that
Cornell had been negligent in failing to follow its own policies
and procedures in resolving the complaints against the professor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
