<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6222 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-NY     01-09 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS TOP 49ERS, GAIN NFC FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A spin, a twist. A spin and twist of players. A spin
and twist of fate.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco-Atlanta playoff clash Saturday afternoon at
the Georgia Dome turned immediately on spins and twists by the
teams' marquee running backs. Those moves set the tone, changed the
complexion, put the 49ers immediately on the defensive and gave the
Falcons' confidence to rise against their longtime divisional
nemesis. And the Falcons did, finishing their hard work, beating
the 49ers by 20-18 before 70,262 fanatic fans.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta (15-2) advances to the National Football Conference
championship game next Sunday against Minnesota or Arizona. The
Falcons are one victory away from Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   A spin. A twist.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was Garrison Hearst. On the game's first play from
scrimmage, the 49ers running back squirted through the line for 7
yards and then tried to plant his feet and spin, and twist, and
gain extra yardage. His left foot remained behind. Hearst was
carted away having suffered a broken fibula. How would the 49ers
come back from that? They certainly tried. They nearly did.
</P>
<P>
   Next, it was Jamal Anderson. He took a handoff with the ball at
the San Francisco 2, only three possessions after Hearst's injury.
And then Anderson tried nearly an identical move. A spin, a twist.
But for Anderson, a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Atlanta led, 7-0, with 6 minutes 25 seconds left in the
first quarter. The Falcons would build a 14-0 lead and then see the
fight that remained in the 49ers. It was not enough, though, as
Atlanta moved on. San Francisco finished its season with a 13-5
record.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta led by 14-10 at halftime and then built that lead to
20-10 in the second half with the help of two interceptions thrown
by Steve Young. The first one, by safety Eugene Robinson, was
returned 77 yards to the 49ers' 20. That set up a 29-yard field
goal by Morten Anderson late in the third quarter. The second one,
by safety William White early in the fourth quarter, gave Anderson
a chance to convert on a 32-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   Young sought redemption. Tried creating his own spin on the
game. His own twist of fate.
</P>
<P>
   He drove the 49ers 87 yards in 13 plays, taking 7 minutes 36
seconds, and then finished it with his 8-yard touchdown run. The
kick holder, the backup quarterback Ty Detmer, took a high snap and
tossed a 2-point conversion pass to tight end Greg Clark and it was
a 20-18 game with 2:57 left.
</P>
<P>
   Young and the 49ers gained one more slim chance. A drive that
began at their own 4 with 38 seconds left. It ended in a
desperation pass that the Falcons swiped. Opportunistic. Tough.
Physical. The Falcons were all of that in their first home playoff
game in the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of happy people in that locker room who deserve
this,'' said Atlanta Coach Dan Reeves. ``We fought to the very
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta used the initial 28 minutes 15 seconds of the first half
to build their 14-0 lead. But San Francisco scored 10 points in the
final 1:10, in an eyelash nearly matching the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   There were big plays and beautiful plays, more than bungled
plays, in the first half. The game-swinging moment of the half
occurred during San Francisco's initial scoring drive. Down by 14-0
with 3:06 left in the half, immediately following Anderson's
spectacular 34-yard touchdown run, San Francisco began a drive at
its 20 that quickly moved to the Atlanta 47.
</P>
<P>
   On first and 10, San Francisco tried a lateral from Young to
running back Terry Kirby. Kirby dropped it; Falcons end Chuck Smith
dove for it along with Kirby, the ball popped loose from Kirby and
Falcons linebacker Henri Crockett had apparently scooped it up and
scored on the return. But no.
</P>
<P>
   First the officials ruled that Atlanta had recovered at the spot
where Kirby dropped the ball, and the ball was dead there because
of contact. The officials quickly reversed that, saying that they
simply misspoke and that what they really meant was that Kirby had
recovered for San Francisco, and that when Kirby was touched by
Smith while both were on the ground, the ball was dead, right
there, by contact.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Jerry Markbreit said in a statement: ``The play was a
backward pass. It was recovered on the ground by San Francisco No.
41 Kirby and he was touched on the ground when he had possession.
The rule is down by contact.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a huge decision. Because San Francisco kept a good thing
going, with Young tossing a 34-yard strike to the backup running
back Chuck Levy that put the ball at the Atlanta 26. Then Jerry
Rice put his elusive touch to work, becoming the leader in
consecutive playoff games (23) with a reception. Rice vs.
cornerback Ray Buchanan figured to be one of the key matchups of
the game, and Rice won the battle on this play, a 17-yard scoring
catch with 1:10 left in the half. Rice faked inside, taking a hard
step, and Buchanan bit, bolting inside. Rice floated back outside
and Young tossed a line drive into Rice's hands and chest in the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   With 38 seconds left, San Francisco gained another scoring
chance. It was via an Atlanta turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Chandler's pass was tipped at the line by defensive end
Charles Haley and it fell into Junior Bryant's waiting arms. It was
San Francisco's ball at the Atlanta 36. Young to J.J. Stokes for 16
yards, and a Young scramble for 7 yards, set up a 36-yard Wade
Richey field goal as time expired in the half.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's work had gone for naught. It had held San Francisco
without a first down in the first quarter. It held the 49ers to 9
plays for 22 yards in the quarter, and to 1 rushing yard.
Meanwhile, the Atlanta rushing game clicked. And so did the
Falcons' special teams.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Dwight, the Atlanta rookie kick returner from Iowa, grabbed
a punt and returned it 36 yards, to the San Francisco 38 with 9:32
left in the first quarter. That play set up the game's first score,
the 2-yard run by Anderson. In between Dwight's return and
Anderson's score, the Falcons converted a third-and-8 pass from the
49ers' 22 to the 49ers' 3. It was a tricky play, a formation with
three receivers bunched near the right tight end spot, one running
an out, one running an intermediate route and one running deep.
Mathis ran the intermediate route and was wide open for the 19-yard
grab.
</P>
<P>
   There was 3:12 left in the second quarter when Anderson scored
on his 34-yarder, the longest scoring run in Falcons playoff
history. It was a strong run in which Anderson broke through the
line on a quick trap play and then stiff-armed and dove his way
into the end zone. Through the first half alone, Anderson rushed
for 83 yards, a Falcons playoff record for total rushing yards in a
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, the Falcons led in total yards (221 to 147), in
rushing yards (101 to 9) and in first downs (11 to 6). But much of
their hard work vanished in the in final seconds of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Falcons, they understood there was more work
to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
