<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   LATAM-BANANAS _ MIAMI _ A taste of the tropics, nearly everyone
loves potassium-rich bananas. But this delicate fruit has split the
United States and Europe in a nasty trans-Atlantic tug-of-war that
could soon spell trouble for American consumers. This week, the
Clinton administration is expected to announce that it will go
ahead with plans to slap 100 percent tariffs on $590 million worth
of European goods as soon as Feb. 1. The move is designed to force
the European Union _ which gives preferences to banana growers in
former colonies, particularly those in the Caribbean _ to open its
markets to bananas produced in Latin America by U.S. companies. For
U.S. consumers, the retaliatory measure could double prices on
everything from cheese to linens to candles to cashmere sweaters.
But even more is at stake than higher prices. Experts fear that one
retaliation could spark another, igniting a real trade war between
the United States and the European Union that could threaten
two-way trade estimated at more than $400 billion a year. (Emling,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   w/BANANAS-BOX _ MIAMI _ The imposition of increased tariffs as a
result of a banana trade dispute between the United States and
European Union would affect a number of European imports. The
following consumer goods are expected to increase in price if a
proposed U.S. tariff increase holds. (Emling, Cox News Service).
EDs: MOVED Thurs., Jan. 7, in the International and Financial
categories.
</P>
