   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SUICIDE-DIES _ ATLANTA _ Jeff Miller died of a head wound before
dawn Saturday, fulfilling the vow authorities said he and his
15-year-old girlfriend made to die together. Miller, 17, died at
Crawford Long Hospital in Atlanta at 6:20 a.m., about 22 hours
after he and Andrea Garrett were found in the science hall bathroom
at Central High School in Carrollton, both with .22 caliber gunshot
wounds to the head. Andrea died Friday. (Warner/Scott, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GA-INAUG _ Mainbar on Roy Barnes' road to the governor's mansion
with smart treatment of how he expects to accomplish his agenda and
the obstacles he will have to overcome. This will be the session
where Barnes tests his power and displays his leadership abilities
for the first time. What are his priorities? HMO reform, tax
relief, regional growth/transportation solutions? What can he hope
to accomplish this session? Barnes will be sworn in on Monday.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOSPEL _ The 14th annual Stellar Awards, gospel music's premier
award show, plays out at Atlanta's Civic Center this afternoon and
early evening (Saturday), and features a parade of celebrities,
including Kirk Franklin, Fred Hammond &AMP; Radical for Christ choir;
Lynn Whitfield, who starred in the 1997 film ``Eve's Bayou''; and
comedian Steve Harvey, star of the WB sitcom ``The Steve Harvey
Show.'' (Blake, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 12-15. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   NEWDEAL _ Black farmers who were once promised 40 acres and a
mule when most of the blacks in the nation were on farms now have a
genuine New Deal. For some, a consent agreement reached with the
USDA that offers $50,000 cash and repayment of debts will give them
a new lease on life, but for others, including leaders of the black
farm movement, the proposal falls short and will be challenged anew
when federal Judge Paul Friedman calls them back into court in
February and March. (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 25.
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STAMPS _ Cost of mailing a standard first-class letter goes to
33 cents from 32 cents on Sunday. Are people lining up to buy penny
stamps? How will the postal authorities deal with letters mailed
after Sunday that have 32-cent stamps affixed? (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WALLYS-WORLD _ The story of a sexual predator and how he landed
a job at Palm Beach Community College with only phone calls toi
references as background checks. The college is reviewing its
hiring practices and the former professor is somewhere doing
something and the worry is with whom and what. ( Peltz/Moffett,
Palm Beach Post). 50-60. EDs: With mug shot of the professor.
</P>
<P>
   LYONS _ Rev. Henry Lyons, embattled leader of the nation's
largest black Baptist group, goes on trial (Jan. 11) Monday in St.
Petersburg on charges that he and a one-time paramour siphoned
millions of dollars from the National Baptist Convention's accounts
to finance a lavish lifestyle. Lyons has managed to hold onto his
post as president of the convention, but may not be so successful
in court. Among the charges against him are that he took nearly
$200,000 intended to help burned-out black churches across the
South; swindled $3 million from corporations doing business with
the convention and spent money intended for black colleges on
himself and friends. We advance the trial, which is expected to
last a month. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WEALTH-GAP _ NELSONVILLE, Ohio _ This southeastern Ohio town on
the edge of Appalachia has become an outpost in a 1990s version of
class warfare. The Rev. Jesse Jackson and others are using its
poverty-scarred face to rally support for measures to bridge the
widening gap between wealthy suburbia and poorer inner cities and
rural areas. Next Thursday and Friday, Jackson takes will take the
story of Nelsonville to the epicenter of wealth, Wall Street, for a
two-day rally. (Shepard, Cox News Service) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/COX-WEALTH-DATA _ Material for graphics. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FLA-GOP-MEETINGS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Top Congressional
leaders and governors are coming here next week for three days of
private meetings and golf with six-figure contributors to the
national Republican Party. What's happened here in the past, and
what this gathering may hold. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   LIE-DETECTOR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Law enforcement agencies across
the country _ and across the Miami Valley _ have nothing but praise
for Computerized Voice Stress Analyzer, a new type of lie detector:
The innocent are cleared. The guilty confess. Cases are closed. But
it's also controversial. A look at its use in Ohio. (Grieco, Dayton
Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WILDLIFE-AGENCY-CASH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Eight months ago, Jon
Starnes and several partners agreed to sell 200 acres of hunting
land in northwestern Travis County to the U.S. Fish and Wildlife
Service. They are still waiting for the agency to come up with the
cash. And now it looks like they could be waiting a lot longer. The
agency wasn't granted the money it requested, and now others are
paying the price. (Haurwitz, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
