<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6233 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUICIDE-DIES10-COX     01-09 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUICIDE-DIES10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Suicide pact complete as second teen dies from head wound
 &HT;    By Jack Warner and Peter Scott
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARROLL COUNTY, Ga. _ Jeff Miller died of a head wound before
dawn Saturday, fulfilling the vow authorities said he and his
15-year-old girlfriend made to die together.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, 17, died at Crawford Long Hospital in Atlanta at 6:20
a.m., about 22 hours after he and Andrea Garrett were found in the
science hall bathroom at Central High School in Carrollton, both
with .22 caliber gunshot wounds to the head. Andrea died Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a suicide pact,'' Carroll County Sheriff Tony Reeves
said Friday. ``Each of them intended on dying today.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may never know what happened in that bathroom,'' Reeves
told about 200 students, parents and teachers who gathered to meet
with counselors at the school Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reeves would not assign any motive to the suicide,
fellow students said Andrea's parents felt Jeff was too old for her
and forbade her to see him any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea lived in a yellow frame house on rural Roy North Road
with her parents, Bill and Susan Garrett. Five cows grazed in a
pasture beside it Saturday and a green artificial wreath with white
ribbons adorned the gate on the white, wooden fence in front of the
house. The yard and driveway were full of vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   A bearded man answered the door and told a reporter that the
Garretts would not be making a public statement. A memorial service
will be held for Andrea at 2 p.m . Monday at the Chapel of Almon
Funeral Home in Carrollton. Funeral arrangements for Jeff were not
available, and his relatives did not return calls asking for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   In the community meeting at the high school Saturday, Principal
Scott Cowart, fighting back tears, said, ``We are facing a test of
healing that none of us hoped would be.''
</P>
<P>
   He called the deaths ``a nightmare that will forever be etched
into our memory.''
</P>
<P>
   When Cowart was finished, others walked to the microphone to
speak. Among them was Tony Mashburn, a parent, who said some of the
1,050 students at the school meet for Bible study on Wednesday
morning. He noted that Jeff and Andrea were not among that group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If these kids had Christ,'' he said, their suicides might have
been averted.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Dunlap, a classmate at whose home Jeff had been staying,
took the microphone and said Mashburn ``has no right to say that
about Jeff and Andrea. He doesn't know half the story.''
</P>
<P>
   Sean's father, Craig Dunlap, told the group reports that Jeff
did not have any friends were untrue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My two boys were his best friends, and my little girl too. He
was my friend. Jeff Miller had friends,'' said Dunlap.
</P>
<P>
   Another parent, Charles Landers, wanted to know how the handgun
_ taken from a gun safe in Andrea's house _ was brought into the
school.
</P>
<P>
   Cowart said he has launched an investigation to determine that,
but ``if somebody wanted to get one in here, they can,'' he said.
An effective metal detector program could cost as much as $1
million for a school the size of Central.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves told the audience that the rumor suggesting the death of
the two students may have been inspired by a murder-suicide
Thursday of an adult couple in Villa Rica was untrue. He said his
investigation showed the youngsters had death in mind before then.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves urged parents to know the warning signs of suicide and
talk to their children. Others urged students to report to adults
veiled threats of suicide such as Jeff had apparently made to some
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writers Bill Montgomery and Clint Williams contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
