<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCONN-LADYVOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES' COMPETITION ABOUT TO GET TOUGHER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JACK CAVANAUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To provide his starters with tougher competition, Geno Auriemma,
the women's coach at the University of Connecticut, sent two
assistants in search of male practice players a few years ago. But
with 11 players capable of starting for most teams in the Big East,
Auriemma no longer needs to find men to practice against his front
liners.
</P>
<P>
   Several players on the top-ranked and undefeated UConn women's
team, which meets No. 2 Tennessee in a showdown at Gampel Pavilion
on Sunday afternoon, have said their toughest competition to date
has come from one another during practice sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Through its first 13 games, Connecticut has surpassed 100 points
nine times while beating its opponents by an average of 40 points.
``We do score pretty easily at times,'' Auriemma said after the
Huskies trounced Pittsburgh, 106-52, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They are unlikely to score so easily against Tennessee, which
has lost only once in 13 games _ to Purdue on Nov. 15 _ and has won
three consecutive national championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols have also won three of the last four games against
UConn, including a 15-point victory last January before 24,597
people in Knoxville. Tennessee also knocked off the Huskies in both
the 1996 Final Four and the 1997 Midwest Regionals.
</P>
<P>
   However, Tennessee has lost both times it has played in
Connecticut _ at the Storrs campus in 1995 and at Hartford in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to play down the significance of Sunday's game, Auriemma
said: ``I realize that for a lot of people the world will come to
an end around 7 o'clock Sunday night when we will either have won
the national championship or wrapped up second place. It's like the
season ends on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   It will not, of course, but the game could be a portent for this
season's Final Four. The outcome, no doubt, will instill confidence
in the victor and a certain doubt in the loser.
</P>
<P>
   UConn's depth could be decisive. Eight players are averaging at
least 17 minutes of play, including sophomore Shea Ralph, who has
averaged 22 minutes though she has not started a game since
returning from a knee injury that caused her to miss all of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Her playing time is second only to Amy Duran, the team captain
and lone senior on the starting five. Duran has played 23 minutes a
game. Reflecting the Huskies' balance, five players are averaging
in double figures _ Svetlana Abrosimova (17.5 points), Ralph
(16.7), and three freshmen, Tamika Williams (12.4), Swin Cash (12)
and Asjha Jones (10.2). Cash, who is coming back from a stress
fracture in her right foot that kept her out of two games and
limited her to only seven minutes in the most recent game, is
expected to see significant playing time Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that if we don't play well, someone just as good is
right behind us,'' said Williams, who scored a career-high 21
points and pulled down 9 rebounds against Pittsburgh on Thursday
night and who is shooting at a 64 percent clip.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee counters Connecticut's depth with its three ``Meeks''
_ the incomparable senior Chamique Holdsclaw from Astoria, Queens,
and the sophomores Tamika Catchings and Semeka Randall. They each
were chosen as preseason all-Americans and they average 20, 15 and
13 points, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its ``unique blend of experience and young players,'' as
Auriemma has described his team, Connecticut is not at full
strength coming into Sunday's game. Besides Cash, Sue Bird of
Syosset, N.Y., a member of what is acknowledged as the best
freshmen class in women's Division I basketball and who had been
the starting point guard, has been lost for the rest of the season
because of a knee injury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
