</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REEVES, FALCONS SHOW A LOT OF HEART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A show of hands, please. Last August, when trying to
handicap the NFC, how many figured Atlanta, Arizona and Minnesota
as the final three teams left standing in January?
</P>
<P>
   And thanks for being truthful.
</P>
<P>
   Long-shot players, rejoice. What once was, is no more in the
NFC. Dallas, San Francisco, Green Bay _ going, going, gone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, consider the Atlanta Falcons, a franchise that had
spent its 33 years of existence serving mainly as an NFL poster
child for futility. The one place you'd never expect to find these
people is a conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, you will.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta coach Dan Reeves' surgically corrected heart passed a
serious sideline stress-test here yesterday. His football team
provided a multitude of EKG moments for Reeves, yet Atlanta
outlasted the 49ers, 20-18, in an interesting game of big plays,
big blunders, big controversy and one nasty big break, as in
Garrison Hearst's leg.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for Atlanta _ the winner of Minnesota and Arizona, which
means it's 99.9 percent certain the Falcons will be visiting just
south of the Arctic Circle next week. Then again, Reeves and Co.
have been full of surprises all season, starting with the 14-2
record that won the NFC West.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have performed so well and so consistently all
season, beating the 49ers yesterday was not an upset. But it was a
very tough chore.
</P>
<P>
   All the medical attention was supposed to be focused on Reeves,
the 55-year-old head coach just four weeks removed from quadruple
heart bypass surgery. Reeves was back on the sidelines and back
wearing the coaching headset for the first time yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I wanted to keep the focus away from me,'' he said
after the game. And from a medical standpoint, the focus did
quickly shift. On the afternoon's first play from scrimmage,
Hearst, the reborn running back for the 49ers, popped through a
hole, had a nice gain, but was suddenly twirled around by an arm
tackle from Atlanta end Chuck Smith. Hearst's legs became twisted
as he hit the turf, and the left one bent back, breaking the
fibula.
</P>
<P>
   It is not far-fetched to say Hearst was the one key to the 49ers
winning here. In fact, Reeves, always an honest sort, said so
afterward. ``Going in, we thought the outcome would be decided by
the running games, and Jamal Anderson \R113 yards on 29 carries\S
provided that for us,'' he noted. ``But the difference in the
ballgame was the unfortunate injury to Garrison Hearst. That would
be like us losing Jamal.''
</P>
<P>
   It got worse for the 49ers when backup Terry Kirby was injured
five minutes later, left for the locker room, and when he did
return was far from 100 percent.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci was gracious in defeat, but
did say, in an understatement, ``My running game took a couple of
hits.'' Actually, Mariucci had to throw out the game plan, tinted
heavily with the run, and rely totally on the arm of Steve Young.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, that's all the 49ers had. Yesterday, it wasn't
enough, mainly because the usually reliable Young threw two very
costly interceptions in the second half. In both cases, it stopped
serious scoring threats.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons safety Eugene Robinson had a perfect deep ball read on
Young late in the third, swiped a pass on the 3-yard line, and
returned it 77 yards, setting up a field goal. The other safety,
William White, made a midfield, fourth-quarter interception of a
poorly thrown ball over the middle. That also set up a field goal.
Those two picks provided the only second-half points for Atlanta _
and decided the game.
</P>
<P>
   Young will be hearing in San Francisco this week what Troy
Aikman heard in Dallas last week _ plenty of harsh criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it appeared Reeves' surgically repaired heart wouldn't
feel any stress. ``I thought we had the game under control, being
up, 21-0,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With Hearst gone and Anderson rambling, Atlanta took a 14-zip
lead, and as Reeves pointed out, appeared to make it 21-0 just
before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Then came controversy, which started when Young threw a
behind-the-line-of-scrimmage backward pass to Kirby. The free ball
ended up on the ground. Kirby pounced on it, then got to his feet,
was hit, fumbled the ball, Chuck Smith grabbed it, and raced to the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Confusion followed. First, the Jerry Markbreit officiating crew
ruled no touchdown, but an Atlanta recovery. Then that was
reversed, and the 49ers were awarded the ball on a ruling that when
Kirby fell on the ball, he was touched by a Falcons' player, so
Kirby was down.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, the officials appeared to be right, although TV replays
were a tad shaky on the play. The 49ers scored on that possession,
then added a late first-half field goal. Instead of 21-0, the
Falcons' lead was 14-10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became emotional over that call _ you can't help it on
something like that,'' said Reeves. But his heart held up, and in
the end, so did his team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
