<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 1/9/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LAKE SUCCESS, N.Y. -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- TEAMSTERS, 1-9 --
Thomas O'Donnell, a newly elected vice president at large of the
Teamsters, obtained the second-largest vote total in last month's
union election -- only the new president, James Hoffa, received
more. O' Donnell, who now faces possible expulsion from the union,
insists that he is being railroaded over accusations of filing
false campaign reports. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- NY-RESEARCHER, 1-9 -- David
Shulman, 86, a regular at the New York Public Library's rare book
room, which has received some of his assorted collections. This
self-described ``Sherlock Holmes of rare books,'' lives for the
mental adventure the library represents. In turn, Virginia Bartow,
the curator of rare books for the branch, says Shulman represents
what the library is all about. ``He collects books, he researches
endlessly and he writes for publication,'' she says. (Jack
Manning/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 1998 -- NY-GAY-SENATOR, 1-9 -- Sen.
Tom Duane, 43, the first openly gay member elected to the state
Senate, at a ceremony for the opening of a health center. Along
with Assemblywoman Deborah Glick of Greenwich Village, Duane
constitutes an ad hoc caucus of two openly homosexual state
legislators. He is the only state lawmaker who identifies himself
as carrying HIV, and has just become the nation's highest-ranking
openly HIV-positive elected official. (Linda Rosier/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 1998 -- NY-DNA-DEBATE, 1-9 -- The
Rev. Al Sharpton, left, and Norman Siegel, executive director of
the New York Civil Liberties Union, have vowed to fight against
Gov. George Pataki's proposal for a statewide database of
information on the DNA of all felons. They say the plan threatens
privacy and exceeds any legitimate law enforcement needs. ``It's a
major mistake to equate DNA samples with fingerprints and say they
are used solely for identification purposes,'' says Siegel. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- IMPEACH-HYDE, 1-9 -- Led by
Rep. Henry J. Hyde, fourth from right, the House members who will
present the impeachment case to the Senate at a meeting Friday.
After initial reports of the president's affair, Hyde reacted to
what he clearly saw as a lot of loose talk about impeachment by
saying: ``You don't impeach him for a peccadillo.'' A year later,
angered by what he came to see as Clinton's cavalier attitude
toward the law, Hyde's position hardened considerably. (Carol T.
Powers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- IMPEACH-DEFENSE, 1-9 --
Gregory B. Craig, the special White House counsel hired by
President Clinton to help in his impeachment defense. A relative
newcomer to the team, Craig still does not have the detailed
knowledge that his colleagues have of the case, White House aides
say. But as a former aide to Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., he has
close ties to the Senate. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- PET-PSYCH-REVIEW, 1-9 -- Swim
therapy helps, Duncan, a black Labrador lose weight, and Al a
greyhound, taking a break, recover from back surgery. In the pet
world, some veterinarians have found a niche treating medical and
behavioral problems in animals with alternative methods. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SUMMIT, N.J. -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- DOCS-REBEL, 1-9 -- Dr.
Greg Sachs, president of the Medical Society of New Jersey, expects
more doctors to quit HMOs. ``Doctors' opposition to managed care is
on the increase in other parts of the country as well,'' says
Sachs. Chief among doctors' complaints have been reduced fees and
more restrictions from the insurance companies on referrals and
procedures. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- NY-CHURCH-BANKLOAN, 1-9 --
Bishop Altamont G. Blackwood, 52, of the New Jerusalem Church in
front of his congregation's soon-to-be new home in Queens. Though
the congregation gives God most of the credit for the new building,
He does have a worldly partner -- the Chase Manhattan Bank, which
in keeping with a federal law requiring banks to help struggling
neighborhoods in which they do business, has lent the congregation
more than $1 million for the project. (Chester Higgins Jr./New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) OXFORD, England -- Jan. 9, 1999 -- BRITAIN-ANIMAL-RIGHTS,
1-9 -- Psychologist Colin Blakemore, 54, is one of 10 scientists
whom animal rights extremists in Britain have threatened to kill
for his belief in animal experimentation. ``It's very easy for
agitators to create the impression that mad scientists are doing
horrendous stuff to helpless pet kitties when it isn't true at
all,'' says Blakemore. ``They never mention the anesthetics we use
or the benefits we obtain.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WILKES-BARRE, Pa. -- Jan. 9, 1999 --
PA-PRISONER-ABORTION-2, 1-9 -- Karen Ptaschnik, five months
pregnant and currently serving time on drug charges, has become an
unlikely lightning rod for the abortion debate. Although her case
might not be an enormous issue, in this staunchly Catholic area of
Wilkes-Barre, Pa., it has become a tangled saga of how abortion
politics play out far from big-city abortion clinics and Washington
policy debates. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HAZELTON, Pa. -- Jan. 8, 1999 -- PA-PRISONER-ABORTION-1,
1-8 -- Maureen Rosseau plays with Jayme Ptaschnik, 7, her
neighbor's daughter. Jayme's mother, Karen Ptaschnik, who is five
months pregnant and currently serving time in a nearby prison on
drug charges, has become an unlikely lightning rod for the abortion
debate. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
