<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6252 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-BISHER10-     01-09 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-BISHER10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This time, team ready to go further
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Well, here they are, right on schedule, regular as
clockwork, making hay in the playoffs every 18 years. Our good and
honorable and trustworthy Atlanta Falcons. Once they were the most
abused team in the league, now they're a week away from playing for
the championship of the National Football Conference. And (just say
this in a whisper) one game away from the Super Bowl. Wow!
</P>
<P>
   Roll that around in your head again: Atlanta Falcons one step
away from the Super Bowl. Don't say it out loud. Somebody will look
at you cross-eyed and wonder if you're daft.
</P>
<P>
   People come from faraway places to see them play. News
conferences draw like a state of the nation speech. Some of our
press compadres haven't seen the Falcons in so long they thought
they still played outdoors. They were delighted to be in the
Georgia Dome on a savage day to watch them scrimmage the San
Francisco 49ers for the privilege of playing the Vikings or
Cardinals next Sunday for a trip to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly and earnestly, they'd prefer the Cardinals for reasons
like, well, they'd have the game at their own hearthside, and they
have a dread of playing the Vikings in that dismal warehouse known
as the HumphreyDome.
</P>
<P>
   Outside on Saturday, the weather was frightful. Inside it was so
delightful, but agonizing for the better part of three hours. You
see, the 49ers are old hands at this stuff, playing postseason,
winning Super Bowls, swashbuckling through teams unaccustomed to
all the glitter. We were issued a booklet called ``NFL Postseason
Guide'' before the game. The Falcons didn't get a lot of type. The
last time they were this close to the the Pearly Gates of pro
football was in 1980 and they blew that in the last few minutes at
the now nonexistent stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the Falcons had scored twice and led 14-0, creating a
deceptive air of comfort. Then strange stuff began to happen in
this, the Year of the Blundering Official. The last two minutes of
the second quarter would become pure hell. Steve Young threw a
lateral pass at Terry Kirby. (Kirby was in the game because
Garrison Hearst, the pride of Lincolnton, Ga., went down on the
first play with a broken leg.) It appeared that Kirby fumbled the
backward pass, two Falcons pounced on him, the ball bounced into
the hands of Chuck Smith, who strutted his way to the end zone.
Falcons score!
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Jerry Markbreit and crew got through labored
legislation, the ball had been awarded to the Falcons at the spot
where Kirby recovered, then back to the 49ers. At any rate, the
Falcons had no touchdown, nor the ball. The crowd lost its
disposition, happy now that they had heard before the game that Mr.
Markbreit was refereeing his last.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers scored.
</P>
<P>
   Then a tipped pass came down in Junior Bryant's hands, and the
49ers big lummox was tackled at Atlanta's 36. Wade Richey kicked a
field goal in the last second, all of this after the two-minute
warning, which the Falcons should have taken literally. It was a
confusing and irritating moment, enough to cause a man who has just
had heart surgery, such as Dan Reeves, to have a heart attack.
Blessedly, he didn't. You'd have sworn that every indicator of the
first half pointed toward the Falcons sinking in the end. Yet, they
survived a second 49ers touchdown, and a botched snap that Ty
Detmer turned into a two-point conversion, and they sweated it out
down to the wire.
</P>
<P>
   Through all those vexing moments the name of a player long gone
kept running through my mind. Rolland Lawrence. Lawrence was a
defensive back on the team that lost to Dallas in the last minute
in 1980, the player whose coverage broke down on the deciding
touchdown. As the insufferable memory ran past again, I turned and
looked straight into the face of Leeman Bennett, who coached the
team that lost to the Cowboys. He winced. I winced.
</P>
<P>
   But now it was over. Reeves and his reconstructed heart had made
it through a day that began with a dog show, mutts chasing
frisbees, and had turned into what he called something ``beyond my
wildest dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you ever had a team that came this far this fast?'' he
was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teams I've had before never had this far to go,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
