<HEADER>
A6254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALTLAKE10-COX     01-09 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALTLAKE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some in Salt Lake consider moving Olympics amid bribery scandal
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bribery, corruption and now a sex scandal involving
the bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics have some people in Salt Lake
City wishing the Games would go jump in the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's best to cut our losses now and get out of this
thing and let the Games go to Calgary,'' Deeda Seed, a city council
member and one of the most vocal critics of the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee, said Saturday. ``Let's spare our city the
pain and agony of being a second-rate Olympics before we even light
the flame.''
</P>
<P>
   Moving the Games would not be unprecedented: The people of
Colorado voted in a 1973 referendum to give back the '76 Games,
which went to Innsbruck, Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Seed admits that hers is a minority opinion. Still, the
controversial _ and potentially illegal _ bid practices, which
forced the committee's two top officials to resign Friday, have
Salt Lake City's 200,000 citizens reeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here in this city is people who are walking
around in numb disbelief,'' Seed said. ``We're all shocked and
horrified; it's so counter to the values that are espoused in
Utah.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOC has acknowledged that the bid committee, which lost the
1998 Games to Nagano by four votes then won in a landslide four
years later, paid as much as $70,000 to certain IOC members;
provided free medical care for IOC members and their families;
financed a scholarship program that benefitted the relatives of six
IOC members; and gave gifts that exceeded the allowable limit of
$150.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest bombshell, the Utah governor's office revealed
Friday that a SLOC internal ethics panel was investigating
allegations of prostitution. These allegations, including whether
credit cards belonging to the bid committee were used to pay for
escort services for IOC members, have not been substantiated.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Pound, an IOC member from Canada who is leading that
group's internal investigation, told the New York Times, ``There's
not anything we've seen like that. They can't even get their own
dates? If it happened, it will all come out.''
</P>
<P>
   And that would be even more embarrassing for Utah's citizens,
most of whom are members of the Church of Jesus Christ of
Latter-day Saints.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effect it's going to have on Mormons is not sinking in
yet,'' said Stephen Pace, who heads a local citizens watchdog
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be very hard for the LDS church to stay
strongly in support of the Olympics and also look each other in the
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Many fear that those who attend the Games, which are scheduled
to begin in three years and one month, will rub salt in the wounds.
Seed said it's inevitable that the Olympics will be the butt of
jokes, such as, ``The best Games that money can buy.''
</P>
<P>
   The scandal has so tarnished the Olympics that sponsors are
skittish and organizers may have to scale back the Games if some
funding falls through. And city and state officials are worried
that the 2002 Games, with a budget of $1.45 billion that was
supposed to come from private sources, will lose money. Who will
pay the difference? After the Atlanta Games, the IOC began
requiring a government entity to guarantee the Olympics in case of
a deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mike Leavitt said Friday that the 17-page contract signed
between state and Salt Lake City officials in 1991 violates Utah's
constitution, which prohibits the state from guaranteeing any
public or private debt.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt has promised that the city will not bear the debt alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is saying, `Trust me,' and the legislators are
saying, `We're not going to pay,' '' Seed said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the city council at its Tuesday meeting must examine
the validity of the contract, which could be null and void because
of the acts of bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Seed said the contract states that ``the bid city has an
obligation to maintain the good name of the Olympic movement. What
about the IOC maintaining the good name of the bid city? We have
been trashed. In order for bribery to be committed, there has to be
somebody accepting the bribe, and here we have the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Anita DeFrantz, one of two U.S. members of the 115-member IOC,
said some of her brethren involved in the scandal would be asked to
resign at a meeting Jan. 23-24 in Lausanne, Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will have executions, but we will have fewer
members,'' she told the New York Times. ``There are a few
individuals who have abused their privilege. We must have them
removed from the Olympic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the SLOC ethics panel, which hopes to wrap up its probe
by Thursday when the organizing committee's board meets, and the
IOC, the U.S. Olympic Committee and the U.S. Justice Department are
also looking into the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   The Games' focal point _ the athletes _ haven't lost their
desire to compete in Salt Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``As athletes, we all kind of shrug,'' ski star Picabo Street, a
member of SLOC's board of trustees, told the Chicago Tribune. ``We
think, `That all kind of stinks, but just let there be an Olympics
for us to compete in.' There is still pride to be felt in the
purity of going to the Olympic Games and representing your country,
regardless of the politics involved.''
</P>
<P>
   SLOC must now replace Frank Joklik, 70, and David Johnson, 40,
the Games top two organizers. Luckily, most of the facilities are
finished or will be completed by November 2000. Joklik will stay on
the job until a successor is named.
</P>
<P>
   Pace believes that members of the board of trustees should also
be forced out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not thrown enough bodies out of the lifeboat yet to
keep it afloat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leavitt called the trustees of a ``systematic cover-up,'' by
those who handled the payments, but Pace thinks there should have
been adequate oversight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their only defnese against being charged with being corrupt is
that they're incompetent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pace and Seed will speak at a public forum Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has just sapped all the enthusiasm right out of the
thing,'' Seed said. ``It's hard to be cheerful and excited about an
event that was solicited in the most unsavory fashion you can
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson broke his silence when he told the Salt Lake Tribune
that the gifts given by Olympic organizers were not bribes because
no votes were guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time was there a quid pro quo,'' he said. ``So it was
not a bribe. It was a secret ballot. Even if an IOC member said he
was going to vote for you, you never knew if he would. Salt Lake
City won on its merits.''
</P>
<P>
   But now those merits have been all but forgotten. Said Pace,
``I'm kind of amazed at how fast it seems to be coming apart.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
