<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 19:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-FEATURE10-COX     01-09 0639
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-FEATURE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Canucks in a rut
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A three-hour meeting with coaches in a Dallas hotel
room on the eve of the game must not have solved too many problems.
The Vancouver Canucks continued to play at a level consistent with
their disparaging nickname the other night, losing to the Stars 6-4
to extend their losing streak to seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Bure, the franchise centerpiece, continues to wait out a
trade in Moscow, kissing off an $8 million contract. Mark Messier,
imported from New York to draw some attention to this end of
Canada, is 38 playing like 48 and feeling like 58. Coach Mike
Keenan was so frustrated after a recent loss, he suggested it might
be time to ``fire the coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Reclining on this bed of nails is Brian Burke. The former NHL
disciplinarian was a finalist for the Thrashers general manager
position before settling for his second-choice offer as GM of the
Canucks. Burke hated living in New York and was worn down by his
role as Gary Bettman's attack dog. But now one wonders if the view
in British Columbia is worth being one of the most second-guessed
executives in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to be back on a team,'' Burke said. ``I missed
winning and losing. But being a part of losing is not much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   When the most uplifiting news is limited to defenseman Bret
Hedican announcing plans to marry Kristi Yamaguchi, things aren't
going well for your hockey team. The biggest problem for the
Canucks has been the absence of Bure _ or, at least, the absence of
someone in his place. The Russian Rocket scored a team-high 51
goals last season _ Messier was a distant second at 22 _ but has
demanded a trade. He won't say why, and he declined to play this
year.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed that Burke would have made a deal by now for
scoring help or a starting goalie. But of the two most interested
teams, Los Angeles didn't want to part with some of its talented
prospects and New York, scared off by Burke's high demands, made a
deal with Pittsburgh for Petr Nedved.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hope was that (Bure) would come in and play for us and he
would give us a deadline for a trade, like Dec. 1,'' Burke said.
``But he wouldn't do that. So I've got to make the best possible
deal for this team. If the deal's not right, I'm not making it.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke maintains that the market is heating up again, that as
many as seven teams are now talking about a deal _ Florida and New
York are the front-runners _ and that something could be close to
happening. But there have been teases before. The upside is that
the Western Conference is so down this season _ only four of 13
teams are above .500 _ that a playoff berth remains viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to look at this thing as the glass being half
empty,'' Burke said. ``But the fact is we're one point out of a
playoff spot, and we don't have Bure, and (forwards Alexander)
Mogilny and (Todd) Bertuzzi have been hurt. Given that, most people
would've thought we'd be 20 points out by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Such rose-colored views do little to appease Keenan, who has
sounded off a few times about personnel problems and is used to
having total control over such matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've disagreed at times, but that's always the case between
general managers and coaches,'' Burke said. ``The problem is the
general manager's goals are not the same as the coach's. The GM
wants to win the Stanley Cup. The coach wants to win every night.
The coach goes from 7:30 to 10 o'clock thinking about how to get
two points. The GM thinks, 'We might lose tonight, but we won't
lose in the long run.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's done a good job. But he's frustrated. He's a hot-headed
Irishman, just like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Little else is hot in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
