<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-W     01-09 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: BRIBING MILLIONAIRE DELEGATES, AND A FEW OTHER
IDIOCIES
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 7th graf, Until further ..., to ADD that Joklik has not
been linked to giving gifts and CORRECT that only other official
resigned, sted some others; minor editing changes elsewhere.) 
 (JT) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that the National Basketball Association has solved the
perplexing problem of how to share a few billion dollars, it dawns
on me that there are many more unresolved idiocies out there in the
sporting world just waiting to be attacked.
</P>
<P>
   Here's one idiocy I'd like to cut off at the pass: the fervent
American participation in bribing millionaires. Apparently, the
Salt Lake City Olympic people have been passing out money, college
tuition, health care and who-knows-what condos and other goodies up
in nouveau ski-chalet country, in return for a few little favors
from some (or maybe many) International Olympic Committee
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   These delegates, who choose Olympic sites every two years, are
already well-heeled and well-positioned in their home countries,
and the IOC effectively licenses them to roam the world with
gunnysacks, playing one bidding city against another.
</P>
<P>
   This stuff may go on in the rest of the world, but it is a
dreadful practice for America, and I'll tell you why. Nobody is
more sanctimonious about ``our way of life'' than Americans. We
like to say we are the most moral, righteous folk on the planet,
but we don't necessarily act that way when it is against our
self-interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While roaming the dreary streets of downtown Atlanta in the
fetid summer of 1996, I kept muttering, ``What were the delegates
thinking when they overlooked Toronto and Melbourne?'' (The
delegates themselves were holed up in exclusive hotels, whisked to
events in air-conditioned limousines.)
</P>
<P>
   I now have to wonder if every time I complained to an Olympic
official about the squalid T-Shirt Shack Games, I was talking to
somebody who had taken a few favors from the Atlanta organizing
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Until further notice, I will feel the same way about the
legitimacy of Salt Lake City as the host of the 2002 Winter Games.
There was a mandatory first step Friday and then with the
much-too-belated resignation of Frank Joklik, the chairman of the
organizing committee, who has not been linked to the ``gifts,'' and
one of his top officials. However, the taint of the sleaze will not
vanish by 2002. All future American bidding cities must take an
oath not to grease IOC delegates and similarly suspect characters.
</P>
<P>
   You have to nip bad ideas in the bud, before they become a
habit, like the designated-hitter rule. If only more people had
screamed, ``That's not baseball!'' we would not have had a quarter
of a century of lumbering retreads and endless games and an entire
American League without a shred of strategy. But we let it go, and
it festers still.
</P>
<P>
   Another example of rampant idiocies, this one in the real world,
is the ghastly increase in vehicles careering around corners with
drivers barely in control, gabbing animatedly into a cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   It would never have come to this if only a police officer had
pulled somebody over and said, ``See here, sir, you can't drive
with a headset on, or a dog in your lap, so you surely cannot drive
talking into a cell phone. Hold out your wrists, I'm cuffing you
and taking you down to the station.'' But it didn't happen that
way, so we all have to cringe when conversational drivers are on
the loose (disproportionately trying to control sport utility
vehicles, but that's another story).
</P>
<P>
   Here's a home-grown North American idiocy: the continued
separation of baseball umpires between National and American
leagues, producing different strike zones, different techniques,
different attitudes. Baseball was going to blend the two sets of
umpires _ as in every other major sport _ but baseball, once again,
has been divided and conquered by Richie Phillips, the head of the
umpires' union. I'm sure the new commissioner will jump right on
this when he takes over.
</P>
<P>
   My last idiocy for today concerns the greatest sports event in
the world, the World Cup of soccer. Because it is held only once
every four years, the World Cup induces billions of fans to say
``Back in Mexico in 1970'' or ``back in Italy in 1990,'' with a
sense of history and awe.
</P>
<P>
   Now, somebody wants to dilute, diminish, reduce, cheapen the
World Cup by holding it every two years. The scary thing is that
the threat to the World Cup is none other than Joseph (Sepp)
Blatter, the new secretary general of the world soccer body known
as FIFA.
</P>
<P>
   Blatter seems to forget that players spend a good deal of the
four years preparing and qualifying for the World Cup, and that
fans build up their emotions from year to year. A World Cup game is
staggeringly vital because there is not only no tomorrow, there is
also no next year.
</P>
<P>
   What really worries me about Blatter's blather is that the same
international types who run the IOC also run FIFA, and that there
is money to be made from inspection trips, from television and
construction and licensing, and that World Cups are greased by
presents from hopeful countries. The largess from Japan and South
Korea, which led to a highly shaky partnership in 2002, has become
legendary. Sepp Blatter should be far too worldly to want to be
connected to a biennial swarm to the global trough.
</P>
<P>
   This is surely just the first in a regular series exposing
idiocies, in and out of sports. We haven't even addressed obnoxious
cell-phone users on commuter trains, or four-hour college football
games, have we?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
