<DOCNO> NYT19990109.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-EVIDENCE-1STL     01-09 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-EVIDENCE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-770(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL ACCORD SHIFTS FOCUS BACK TO STARR'S EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS 3rd graf for minor style change; SUBS 9th graf, Central
to ..., to change `sought' to `subpoenaed' for clarity; minor
editing changes elsewhere ) 
 (See also IMPEACH-HYDE, IMPEACH-DEFENSE) 
(JT) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate's agreement on how to conduct the
initial phase of President Clinton's impeachment trial sent House
prosecutors and the president's lawyers diving this weekend back
into the voluminous evidence collected by Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In the 7,000 pages of grand jury testimony and boxes of
supplementary evidence, Rep. Henry Hyde, the leader of the House
prosecution team, sees a clear and convincing picture of perjury
and obstruction of justice so grave that Clinton should be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   From that same pile of evidence, the president's legal team is
putting together a more aggressive defense than the one it
presented unsuccessfully to the House _ one it now says should lead
to the president's acquittal. The White House offered to accept the
record of testimony amassed by the independent counsel, although
the president's lawyers profoundly disagree with Starr and Hyde
about what the evidence shows.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers will argue that instead of proving that
Clinton lied or obstructed justice, the evidence shows only that
Clinton tried to conceal the embarrassing details of an improper
relationship with Monica Lewinsky, according to interviews and
legal documents they have prepared for the Senate trial. Though the
president's actions and behavior were ``reprehensible,'' Charles
Ruff, the White House counsel, has said, they were not unlawful.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate's Republicans and Democrats spent this week sparring
over whether to call witnesses, virtually all of whom have already
testified under oath before Starr's grand jury. On Friday, the
senators agreed to defer until late January a decision on whether
to summon witnesses _ and if so, which ones.
</P>
<P>
   That decision will dramatically affect the length and tenor of
the trial. And perhaps more important, both the president's
prosecutors and his defenders can point to many of the same
witnesses and testimony as buttressing their respective cases.
</P>
<P>
   The impeachment proceedings in the House involved legal jousting
over the constitutional standards for high crimes and misdemeanors.
Although those arguments will be heard again in the Senate, the
House prosecutors and White House lawyers are preparing to lock
horns directly on the factual details of the case. In those
details, each side sees a starkly different picture.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the prosecution team wants to call Betty Currie,
the president's secretary, and Vernon E. Jordan Jr., a Washington
lawyer and presidential confidant, to question them, respectively,
about gifts and job help Ms. Lewinsky received from the president.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the impeachment article charging the president with
obstruction of justice are accusations that Clinton schemed with
Ms. Lewinsky to hide gifts subpoenaed in the Paula Jones lawsuit
against the president, and that efforts by Jordan to help Ms.
Lewinsky find a job were intended to buy her silence in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   But the testimony of Ms. Currie and Jordan before the grand jury
also forms the cornerstone of Clinton's defense against
obstruction. Ms. Currie testified that it was Ms. Lewinsky who
asked her to retrieve the gifts, and Jordan said there was no quid
pro quo between his help in finding Ms. Lewinsky a job and her
affidavit in the Jones case denying a sexual relationship with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of Ms. Lewinsky also cuts both ways. She testified
that the president engaged in sexual activity with her that fell
within the narrow definition of sexual relations in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   That pits her word against the president's denial before the
grand jury on Aug. 17 that he had lied in his civil deposition in
the Jones case. In the Jones deposition, he said he had not engaged
in sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky. The president's insistence
that his testimony in the Jones case was not perjurious is another
charge outlined in the impeachment article.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Lewinsky also testified that no one asked her to lie and
that she was not offered help finding a job to secure her silence
in the Jones case. That testimony undercuts the heart of the
obstruction of justice case against the president.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not witnesses are called, the prosecution and the
defense will highlight selected portions of the testimony of
crucial figures like Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Currie and Jordan for their
own purposes.
</P>
<P>
   That is all the more certain given that much of the case against
the president is circumstantial and turns on subjective views of
his intentions and interactions with Ms. Lewinsky, Ms. Currie,
Jordan, other White House aides and his lawyers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most difficult charges for the president to rebut
are contained in the article of impeachment charging him with lying
before the grand jury about the nature and details of his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. Ms. Lewinsky testified in detail
about 11 sexual encounters with the president. That testimony is
perhaps the most problematic evidence confronting the president's
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Because Clinton told the grand jury that he did not have sexual
relations with Ms. Lewinsky as defined in the Jones case, the
evidence on this point boils down to his word against hers.
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal team must decide whether to try to
undermine Ms. Lewinsky's credibility with other evidence. Among
that evidence is the testimony of witnesses and friends of Ms.
Lewinsky who said that she told them things that may have been
untrue, like that the Secret Service brought the president to Ms.
Lewinsky's apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if the president's lawyers paint Ms. Lewinsky as a
liar, their ability to use her testimony to support other aspects
of their case, particularly on obstruction of justice, could be
hindered.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution team will try to broaden its perjury case by
charging that the president lied about other details, like when his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky began, the frequency of their
meetings and the number of times they had sexually explicit
telephone conversations.
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal team will emphasize that Clinton admitted
to an ``inappropriate, intimate'' relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
before the grand jury. They will argue that differences between the
president's and Ms. Lewinsky's descriptions of the number and
specific details of their sexual encounters are not significant
enough to support a perjury charge.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the president has testified that he thought the
sexual activity in which he engaged with Ms. Lewinsky fell outside
the definition of sexual relations in the Jones case. However, this
argument has provoked criticisms that the president and his lawyers
are engaged in tortured legal hair-splitting.
</P>
<P>
   The perjury article of impeachment also charges the president
with lying when he told the grand jury that he did not lie in the
Jones case and with letting his lawyer in the Jones case, Robert S.
Bennett, falsely deny that the president and Ms. Lewinsky were
sexually involved. It also accuses the president of lying to his
aides about his dealings with Ms. Lewinsky. The charges involving
Bennett and the aides are repackaged in the second article of
impeachment involving obstruction of justice, as well.
</P>
<P>
   The president's legal team thinks these accusations are more
easily rebutted. They will argue that he thought he was being
technically truthful, even if he was misleading, during the Jones
deposition. Hardly intending to lie to his aides in order to
influence their future testimony, the president's defenders will
explain, he was trying to conceal from his friends and family an
improper relationship about which he was deeply embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   The article of impeachment charging obstruction of justice turns
on the belief of both Starr and the House prosecutors that the
president wanted Ms. Lewinsky to testify falsely in the Jones case
and that he also sought to influence other potential witnesses,
like Ms. Currie, his aides and his lawyer, Bennett, to give false
accounts of his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. In return for her
false testimony, Ms. Lewinsky was to be rewarded with help finding
a job.
</P>
<P>
   In the perjury case, Ms. Lewinsky's testimony is at odds with
crucial aspects of the president's account. In the obstruction
case, the prosecutors must make a circumstantial but highly
suggestive set of facts support a sweeping accusation. None of the
witnesses involved in the events, including Ms. Lewinsky, Ms.
Currie and Jordan, has testified that the president asked them to
lie, schemed to hide evidence or tried to enlist help to keep Ms.
Lewinsky quiet.
</P>
<P>
   In both the Starr referral and the final House impeachment
report, great weight is given to gifts that the President gave Ms.
Lewinsky that she later turned over to Ms. Currie. The gifts were
subpoenaed by the Jones lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee concluded that Ms. Currie would
not have retrieved the gifts unless asked to do so by the
president.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ms. Currie testified that Ms. Lewinsky asked her to
collect the gifts, and the president has denied asking Ms. Currie
to retrieve them.
</P>
<P>
   According to an analysis of her testimony by the president's
lawyers, Ms. Lewinsky has given 10 different accounts of her
conversations with the president about the gifts. In none of those
conversations, they will argue, did the president instruct Ms.
Lewinsky to conceal the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Currie also testified that she felt no pressure or
intimidation from the president, who is accused of trying to
influence her testimony, and she was not named as a witness in any
proceeding when the president talked to her about Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
