<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Secondary comes in 1st
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One is in his final years, and the other isn't far
behind. Or, as William White insists while distinguishing himself
from Eugene Robinson, ``He's already down the hill. I'm kind of at
the top of the hill, but I haven't gone down yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Old and slow seldom is a successful equation for an NFL safety
tandem. But Sunday, old and slow equaled three interceptions. Old
and slow helped morph the Falcons' secondary this season into
something other than standup material. Old and slow has helped
carry a perennial losing franchise into the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been to two Super Bowls, to the Pro Bowl, and I've done a
lot of special things,'' Robinson said Sunday after his
third-quarter interception helped prevent a Falcons collapse and
preserve a victory against San Francisco in the divisional
playoffs. ``But to be playing with this group of guys means a lot
to me. I mean, when I saw how hard Jessie Tuggle hit (49ers
fullback Marc Edwards) on one play, I almost cried. We were the
lowly Falcons. But not anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons secondary has made big plays all season, so it was
fitting that Robinson and White, who both left successful teams and
signed with Atlanta as unrestricted free agents (Robinson this year
from Green Bay, White in 1997 from Kansas City) made the difference
Sunday. In fact, the game ended with them briefly wrestling for the
ball and the game-ending interception by White at the Falcons' 35.
</P>
<P>
   When Young heaved the desperation pass downfield for J.J.
Stokes, Robinson said, ``I got to the ball first and I had my hand
hands on it. But when I saw Eugene there, I let him have it. I
didn't want a fumble.''
</P>
<P>
   Said White, ``I thought Eugene was one of their guys, that's why
I held onto the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   While the final interception ended a threat, earlier ones were
momentum killers. Late in the third quarter, with the 49ers
trailing only 14-10 and at the Falcons 23, Young threw into the end
zone for Terrell Owens. But Owens was well covered, the pass was
behind him and Robinson read the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I had to do was step in front of him,'' Robinson said. ``I
thought to myself, if I get this ball, I'm gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson not only made the interception, he returned it 77 yards
to the 49ers 20. That set up a Morten Andersen field goal to give
the Falcons some breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to say thanks to the Green Bay Packers for letting
Eugene get away,'' defensive end Chuck Smith said. ``He really is
like the quarterback for our defense back there. Everybody thought
he was too slow to play anymore. They said he was dead. But all
he's doing is starting in the Pro Bowl and taking us to the NFC
title game.''
</P>
<P>
   White's turn came next. After Andersen's field goal, the 49ers
drove to the Falcons 44. This time, Young threw over the middle for
tight end Greg Clark. But Clark stopped his rout, never cut outside
and White stepped in for the interception. White said Clark
actually was Tuggle's responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jessie kind of (overplayed) the run,'' White said. ``When I
saw that, I stayed inside with the tight end. Luckily, we had a lot
of pressure on (Young) and he had to get rid of the ball, and I got
a good break.''
</P>
<P>
   White set up another field goal with a 14-yard return, before
being forced out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about trying to go all the way,'' White said, ``but
I got tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the abbreviated return, the Falcons are within one
victory of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a fluke we're in this position,'' White said. ``We
need to be here; we deserve to be here. We don't want to stop now.
It's like losing can become a habit _ so can winning. There's
probably still a lot of people around the league who don't respect
us. But we don't look at ourselves as Cinderellas. We want to prove
to ourselves that we belong here, so we bust people in the mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   And take away their passes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
