<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FUMBLE10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The fumble that wasn't
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Falcons defensive end Chuck Smith telephoned
former teammate Deion Sanders on Friday night, telling the Dallas
Cowboys star that he was going to unveil his version of the ``Dirty
Bird'' on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got my own dance,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith got his opportunity in the second quarter, when he picked
up an apparent San Francisco fumble and returned it 45 yards down
the sideline for what he and almost everyone else who was watching
thought was a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   But in what has become an all too familiar occurrence in the NFL
this season, officials negated the score and awarded possession to
the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Officials ruled that San Francisco running back Terry Kirby, who
dropped a backward pass from quarterback Steve Young, recovered the
ball at the 49ers' 45-yard line. Referee Jerry Markbreit said Kirby
was down by contact. Replays seemed to indicate that Markbreit's
crew made the right call.
</P>
<P>
   After recovering the ball during a scramble, and apparently
being downed by contact, Kirby lost the ball again when he tried to
stand and run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was clearly our ball,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves
said. ``I didn't see any way they could get the ball. I still don't
understand it, even after watching the replays. But those are tough
decisions, and that's why we should have instant replay.... It
didn't look like he ever had possession. He got up and the ball was
down (on the turf).''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Kirby) never had control of the ball,'' Falcons linebacker
Henri Crockett said. ``I didn't know what was going on. He got up
and started running and fumbled the ball. We should have had the
ball. That's wrong and (the NFL) has got to get a hold on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was surprised no whistles were blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't a whistle and they let it go,'' he said. ``If the
ball is supposed to be dead, you blow the whistle.... It was still
a live ball. I was in the end zone, I was dancing. I think nobody
wanted to make the decision. If they wanted to save a lineman some
energy, they could have blown the whistle about 50 yards earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   The call seemed to stun the Falcons. San Francisco needed only
four plays to score. Young threw a 17-yard touchdown to Jerry Rice
with 1:10 left in the half, cutting Atlanta's lead to 14-7.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking a three-touchdown advantage into halftime, the
Falcons led only 14-10 after the 49ers then turned a Chris Chandler
interception into a Wade Richey 36-yard field goal as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had the game well under control, and it looked
like we were going to be up 21-0,'' Reeves said. ``All of the
sudden, they get 10 points at the end of the half. But I thought
our team did a good job of putting it behind us at the end of the
half. We've done a good job of that all year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
