<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson plays off emotions
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On a flight to Atlanta from Salt Lake City last Sunday
night, Jamal Anderson deemed himself fit and rested from the bye
week and eager get back to work. He chatted with passengers, signed
autographs and generally exhibited a demeanor that was jovial and
fresh. Not long after landing, however, he learned an uncle in New
Jersey died, and his spirit was sapped.
</P>
<P>
   His emotions told him to skip practice leading to Saturday's
49ers playoff game and fly north to comfort, and be comforted by,
family. Coach Dan Reeves told him to go, but Anderson did what
McCleveland Moore, his uncle, would want. Play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional, tough week, man,'' Anderson said. ``I
thought I needed to be here. My uncle was here (for the Miami
game), and I know that he'd want me to be ready for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was more than ready. He said he was so hyped that, ``in
the first quarter, I had to slow down my breathing, I was so fired
up. My attitude was that we were not going to lose this game.''
</P>
<P>
   He did his part to ensure they would not. ``The Catalyst'' had
113 yards on 29 carries, with touchdown runs of 2 and 34 yards. The
34-yarder was a highlight reel.
</P>
<P>
   ``A super job,'' Reeves said in assessing Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Those were not exactly the words or tone he used in addressing
Anderson with 38 seconds left. It was then that Anderson ran out of
bounds on third down, stopping the clock that gave San Francisco
one last _ and as it turned out, futile _ attempt to pull out a
victory.
</P>
<P>
   It all worked out in the end. Reserve linebacker Ben Talley
dumped R.W. McQuarters at the San Francisco 4 on the punt return,
and the defense closed matters. But Anderson's gaffe was so
inexplicable that he addressed it before being queried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know you want to ask me about the bone-headed play,'' he
said. He went on to explain that he felt a leg buckle and was
fearful of sustaining a serious knee injury, so he ran out of
bounds. ``I want both my knees for a few more years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the play was a wide pitch. Anderson said,
jokingly: ``It was a terrible play called by Dan.''
</P>
<P>
   In victory, even the most fundamental of errors are dismissed as
easily as Anderson did 49ers cornerback Merton Hanks. After getting
the wind knocked out of him early in the second quarter and sitting
out a couple plays, Anderson returned and burst into the secondary
off a solid Brian Kozlowski block. Up came Hanks, who immediately
got pushed back at the 20.
</P>
<P>
   With Hanks in pursuit Anderson rambled to the 5, where he went
airborne into the end zone. ``When I get close, I won't be
denied,'' he said. ``I practice diving. My sisters taught me to
cartwheel.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson hopes he and his offensive line taught the league a
lesson. ``People keep saying, `Jamal won't Dirty Bird on us,''' he
said. ``But nobody's stopped us yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
