<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-REACT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unexpected contributions
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pride reigned over happiness in the victorious Falcons
locker room Saturday. At the midway point of last season, they were
1-7 and showing the vital signs of a cadaver. Now, ``We're still
playing in 1999,'' linebacker Jessie Tuggle said, in accomplishment
as much as joy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone deserves what has happened to this team,''
quarterback Chris Chandler said. ``Hopefully, everyone in the city
is as happy and proud as we are in this locker room. This is a long
time coming.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the achievement of advancing to the franchise's
first-ever NFC Championship Game was duly celebrated but not over
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've settled down,'' cornerback Ray Buchanan said. ``But, I
tell you, during the game the fans had me so emotional. They saved
me. It was electrifying out there. Whenever I got tired, I just
looked into the crowd and took some of their energy.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now, we've calmed down some. We can watch (today's
Minnesota-Arizona) game and relax. But we have a lot to be proud
of. We really do. We won as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons got the expected contributions from the starters and
a few from lesser-knowns. Linebacker Ben Talley pinned the 49ers on
their 4 with an open-field tackle on punt returner R.W. McQuarters;
rookie Keith Brooking kept a punt from going into the end zone as
the Falcons down the ball at the 1. And Gary Downs had a 16-yard
run for a first down that set up Jamal Anderson's 34-yard
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a remarkable turnaround for this team,'' Downs said.
``This has been building for two years. We learned how to win. The
guys wanted it so badly. With me, it's about staying ready for an
opportunity. The hole was there for me and I hit it. Sometimes when
you get a chance, the hole doesn't develop. This time it did, and I
took advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the trademark of a quality team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of players who play hard and who play well,''
defensive tackle Chuck Smith said. ``This is so great because we
earned it as a team. The feeling right now is incredible. And we
earned the right to feel this way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You never get enough of this feeling,'' said linebacker
Cornelius Bennett, who's advanced this far five times in his
career, four with Buffalo. ``You look at the other teams that are
at home. Those guys would give their whole salary to be where we
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
