<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-TV10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fumble! Refs drop ball, hear it from announcers
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It would be easy to single out the rip job that
announcers Dick Stockton and Matt Millen laid on the officiating
for the questionable call on the 49ers fumble as the standout
moments of Fox's coverage Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about it, their criticism was as strong as
you'll ever hear out of announcers with no rooting interest for
either team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it made me mad,'' Millen said later. ``It changed the
whole game. But it did give us some drama and a better game than
the last time these two teams met.''
</P>
<P>
   During the telecast, Millen called the ruling that disallowed
the fumble recovery by the Falcons' Chuck Smith ``a complete farce.
This is unbelievable. I don't care what the league says, they are
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Then after the 49ers scored to cut Atlanta's lead to 14-7,
Stockton said Jerry Rice's touchdown ``shouldn't have been,
frankly. The crowd is disturbed over this officiating mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox studio analyst Terry Bradshaw joined the outcry, derisively
saying the officials ``huddled like a hen over a baby'' and never
blew the play dead with a whistle. But his colleague Cris
Collinsworth took the opposite view and said the call was correct
because ``his (Terry Kirby) knee was on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   But as much mileage as the Fox announcers got out of the
controversial play, the work of director Artie Kempner and his crew
was even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   It kept appropriate tabs on Falcons coach Dan Reeves' reactions,
most notably a shot of Reeves raising his arms and urging the crowd
to get loud after Atlanta went up 20-10, and delivered other gems
away from the ball like Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler slamming
down the phone in frustration after having to settle for a field
goal, and 49ers kicker Wade Richey dejectedly holding his head in
his hands after his kickoff went sailing out of bounds in the
closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   However, Fox could have cut back on those skin-crawling replays
of Garrison Hearst breaking his leg on the game's first play from
scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, like the Falcons, Millen got over his disgust with
the officiating and dropped in some clever one-liners to go along
with his keen analysis.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after Jamal Anderson picked up a big first down
with two minutes left, Millen said the play hit the 49ers like ``a
shot to the head from (Mike) Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
