<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reeves returns, his presence felt
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler and his wife,
Diane, are expecting their third child any day, so Chandler hasn't
exactly been preoccupied with the health of coach Dan Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reeves, who underwent emergency quadruple bypass surgery
on Dec. 14 and missed the Falcons' final two regular-season games,
was a welcome sight for Chandler on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, shadowed throughout the game by team physician Charles
Harrison, and protected at times by assistants when plays headed in
his direction, was back on the sideline as the Falcons advanced to
the NFC Championship Game with a 20-18 victory over San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me personally, having him on the sideline was a reassuring
feeling,'' Chandler said. ``When the game started, it was nice to
be able to talk to him and ask him some things. The two games that
he wasn't on the sideline, I was missing some of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the game starts, though, I'm not worried about his
health. It's nothing personal. My wife's due any day now, and I
don't even worry about her once the game starts.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves returned to the practice facility in Suwanee last week
and participated in planning. It wasn't officially decided until
Saturday morning, however, that he'd return to the sideline for the
first time in nearly a month.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said he couldn't yell nearly as loud as he'd like,
although he barked at officials after a controversial call in the
first half. After the game, Reeves said he felt fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt a lot better than I've felt over the last two months,
as far as my heart is concerned,'' Reeves said. ``I just know that
I can't do a lot of things that I want to. I never felt that tired.
I felt good throughout the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves wasn't as involved usual. Quarterbacks coach Jack Burns
continued to relay plays from the press box. But Chandler heard
backup quarterback Steve DeBerg in his in-helmet receiver, instead
of Reeves, who offers suggestions and sometimes changes plays.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Rich Brooks, who served as interim coach
during Reeves' absence, returned to the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could concentrate in between series, looking at all the
pictures and communicating with my defensive staff,'' Brooks said.
``I didn't have to worry about fourth-down plays or whether or not
to accept penalties. I didn't have to worry about the offense, so I
could just concentrate on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
