<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-REACT10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young ran out of time
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The dream finish for the San Francisco 49ers on the
touchdown catch by Terrell Owens in last week's miracle against
Green Bay turned into a nightmare on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It only took one play. Running back Garrison Hearst, a Pro Bowl
selection who ran for 1,570 yards this season, broke his leg while
being yanked down by defensive end Chuck Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-yard gain. Big-time loss.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst had come into the game with a hamstring strain and left
with much worse.
</P>
<P>
   Things got even worse for the 49ers moments later, when Hearst's
backup, Terry Kirby, hurt his knee on a punt. Kirby got kicked
while he was making a block and joined Hearst in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said 'What are you doing here?' `` said Kirby, who added
that Hearst's mood at the time was one of disgust.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, Kirby couldn't put any weight on his knee, but he
got a shot that numbed the pain and he was able to fight his way
through the rest of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, when you have two tailbacks, what can you do?'' Kirby
said. ``One guy has to go. ... This team has a lot of fight. There
are a lot of dogs on this team. They have a lot of character. We're
not going to lay down and give it to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Without a strong running game, San Francisco's chances hinged on
quarterback Steve Young, who was forced to try to move the team by
passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Garrison out, it was a big load on me,'' Young said.
``The great thing is we fought back to make it 20-18 with three
minutes to go. I sensed we'd win the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really had a shot. I was looking for another great finish.
With Garrison out early, we had to be perfect and we made a couple
mistakes. I tried like heck to overcome them, and I ran out of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time Young had stepped to the microphone for his
post-game interview, clean from his shower and still hoarse from
trying to yell over 70,262 mostly-Falcon fans, reality had set in.
The 1998 season was over, and any consolation was minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing shy of a Super Bowl victory usually translates into
disappointment for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can tell from this locker room that there's somewhat of a
train-wreck feeling,'' Young said. ``I don't think there's anyone
in here who thought we weren't going to go (all the way).''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
