<SLUG> BC-HKN-COLUMN-RANGERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOCKEY COLUMN: ERRATIC RANGERS TEST SMITH'S SECURITY
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS to update with Rangers suspending Tikkanen.) 
(bl) 
By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was just a coincidence, getting sick to my stomach while
covering the hurting New York Rangers this past week. In Washington
in time for Thursday's game, but unable to travel the last mile
from hotel bed to press box, I listened, instead, to the Capitals'
radio announcer screaming: ``Richter is down and out! The Capitals
score!'' He said so on every goal. Lapsing in and out of sleep,
redreaming the play-by-play between headaches, it seemed as if the
score were 15-1 instead of the 5-1 result shown in the morning
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The radio clicked on the next morning to the same station. Don
Imus was interviewing Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz. ``I hate hockey,''
Imus said to McCain. ``Well,'' McCain replied, ``you ought to go to
a game.'' It was one of the best things any senator said all week.
And it was time to shuttle back to New York ahead of the snow to
contemplate the Rangers as they approach the halfway point of the
1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   They aren't a bad team. Worse than bad, they are mediocre, good
enough to raise hopes and then dash them. They can win on the road
and lose at home, beat some good teams and lose to some bad ones.
Still possessing one of the league's oldest and most expensive
rosters, the Rangers probably have enough talent, professionalism
and stubbornness to contend for a playoff berth, at least until the
last snow melts. As bad as they have looked in losing their last
two games, their near-term schedule suggests a turnaround. Their
next four games are all against current last-place teams _ Tampa,
the Islanders, Chicago and Montreal. All except Montreal are at
home. All except Montreal are preceded by a day or two of rest,
which older Rangers really need.
</P>
<P>
   The game against the Islanders on Wednesday is No. 41 of an
82-game schedule which is as forgiving as it is long. Down the
stretch, the right trade or two could put the Rangers in the
playoffs, guaranteeing at least two lucrative gates at Madison
Square Garden. It is the sort of thing top management might
consider in evaluating Neil Smith, the president and general
manager, now in his 10th season. His bosses forgave one dark
spring. Two in a row might be pushing it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers will probably have to do it without Esa Tikkanen,
the funny Finn who refused to report for his demotion to the
Hartford farm club. He has been formally suspended by the Rangers,
the team announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tikkanen was supposed to get a salary bonus after 40 games on
the major league roster. He has threatened to file a grievance
because he cleared waivers while nursing a knee injury that
apparently worsened only when he was put on waivers. Teams can't
waive injured players. A Ranger spokesman said that Tikkanen was
due to see a doctor Friday and he had been expected to report to
Hartford on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Tikkanen's departure leaves the Rangers dressing only 10 players
ages 30 or older among the 20 in uniform for each game. Their age
could be why they looked so weary Thursday in Washington in playing
their third game in four nights, according to those who witnessed
the debacle. Tikkanen was supposed to fit in so well with Wayne
Gretzky and the whole coaching staff. He knew them back in Edmonton
in the 1980s, when all were younger. So much for cronyism and
wishful thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Smith's roster moves have worked out so badly. He has
improved the team with trades for Petr Nedved, Todd Harvey, Peter
Popovic, Mike Knuble and Mathieu Schneider. John MacLean was a
decent free-agent signing and so was Brent Fedyk. Draftees like
Marc Savard, Dan Cloutier and Manny Malhotra have been impressive.
(And how long will it be before coach John Muckler gives more
playing time to Cloutier and Malhotra?) Smith and Muckler have had
less success with pickups of Stan Neckar, Rumun Ndur, Scott Fraser,
Chris Tamer and Sean Pronger.
</P>
<P>
   More tough decisions are approaching. Brian Leetch, Adam Graves
and Ulf Samuelsson could walk away as unrestricted free agents next
summer. Wayne Gretzky has an option year left on his contract. All
four are over 30. All four are among the top 10 Rangers. Those four
might earn a combined $15 to $20 million next season. All are good
citizens, but their contracts could make Smith woozy in the
stomach, ready to head for bed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
