<SLUG> BC-BKC-LADYVOLS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tenn.-UConn rivalry renewed today
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STORRS, Conn. _ As the standard-bearer in women's college
basketball, Tennessee is finding that living up to last season's
electrifying 39-0 record and a third NCAA title in a row is a tough
task.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 2 Lady Volunteers meet top-ranked and undefeated
Connecticut this afternoon boasting impressive, if not always
spectacular, results. And they would be the first ones to concede
that they're not exactly on their best game.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the best rivalries in college basketball, Tennessee
will try to win at UConn for the first time since the series began
in the 1994-95 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Vols, whose 47-game winning streak was snapped by
Purdue in the second game of the season, have endured the loss of
three players to injuries and a typically brutal Pat Summitt
schedule. But they're not worried about playing every game with the
same unrelenting zeal they did a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we haven't come out as sharp as we did last year,''
senior point guard Kellie Jolly said. ``We're trying to get better
every day, because what counts is what we do in March.''
</P>
<P>
   So what does this game mean, then, beyond bragging rights and
the national hype that comes with it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it's a big rivalry, and we want to win every game,''
said UConn freshman forward Swin Cash, who is questionable with a
leg stress fracture. ``But it's just another game. I'd like to
play, but I'm focusing on the long term rather than right now.''
Not so for rabid Husky fans and the media, who figure it could be a
sneak preview of the national championship game. The 10,027-seat
Gampel Pavilion has been sold out for months, and scalpers were
asking as much as $200 for an upper-level ticket earlier this week.
The school handed out more than 175 media credentials.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing more popular around here _ other than
UConn's No. 1-ranked men's team _ is the Disney On Ice show that
bounced basketball out of the Hartford Civic Center, where the game
originally was scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   UConn, which has scored 100 points or more nine times, leads the
country in scoring at 100.1 points a game, while Tennessee is third
at 87.6; Georgia is sandwiched in between at 93.1.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have transformed themselves from a plodding
half-court team into a copy of Tennessee last year, with a constant
running and pressing style.
</P>
<P>
   ``They play so hard; they play so intensely,'' Lady Vols
All-American Chamique Holdsclaw said. ``It should be a great game,
but we have so many big games. We can't be overly excited about any
one game.''
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly the approach the Huskies are taking. This state
has been a madhouse for women's hoops ever since UConn topped
then-No. 1 Tennessee here four years ago on the way to a 35-0
record and a national championship. Local fans often overreact
after every game.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, we're a lock to win the national championship,''
UConn coach Geno Auriemma said sarcastically. ``If we lose, we're
not going to make the NCAA Tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
