<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    More changes expected for Lightning
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A professional sports league always wants to hold its
top events in the best surroundings. It's difficult to imagine the
NHL could have worse timing for its All-Star Game weekend in Tampa
in two weeks. Going into the weekend, the Lightning was the only
team still in single digits in the win column. The firing of Phil
Esposito, promotion of Jacques Demers and addition of former Flames
executive Cliff Fletcher have accomplished little, and it figures
to be only a matter of time before owner Art Williams, the former
Atlanta insurance executive, mandates more changes. Forward Wendel
Clark said the team has ``played just well enough to lose.'' There
had been season-long rumors that the Lightning would acquire
Toronto goalie Felix Potvin, but he was traded to the Islanders
Saturday. In any potential Tampa Bay deal, coach and general
manager Demers has nothing to give up except top prospects. ``If I
wanted to give up our kids, I could probably have had (Potvin) in a
second, but I'm not going to do that for anyone.'' Welcome to
Tampa, commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Better this way
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey goalie Martin Brodeur is not having one of his best
seasons statistically _ .901 saves percentage, 2.44 goals-against
average _ despite the Devils' place atop the Atlantic Division
standings. But he attributes the inflated numbers to New Jersey's
new wide-open style under coach Robbie Ftorek _ and prefers it this
way. ``It's a big change, but it's lot of fun,'' he said. ``The
first five years here under Jacques (Lemaire), my statistics were
really good, compared to other goalies. Now I'm in the middle of
the pack, but it's a good tradeoff. There's not as much pressure
because the team scores more goals. That's pretty cool. Now when we
get down a couple of goals, I know it's OK, and I'm not scared
we're going to lose the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Tugnutt
</P>
<P>
   In a year seemingly dominated by Buffalo goalie Dominik Hasek,
it's worth noting that Ottawa's Ron Tugnutt actually leads the
league with a 1.81 goals-against average and is third in saves
percentage, .929. Tugnutt is rotating in the Senators' lineup with
Damien Rhodes. Tugnutt: ``The way we've been playing, it's not hard
to put up good numbers It's a tribute to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Esa Tikkanen is not going to get a stronger message that it's
time to retire. Tikkanen, 33, who has played on five Stanley Cup
teams, cleared waivers and was demoted to the minors by the
Rangers. The timing of the move? If Tikkanen had been on the roster
for the team's 40th game today, he would have earned a $200,000
bonus. ... Florida is central to trade rumors with Vancouver (Pavel
Bure) and Calgary (Theo Fleury). ... This might be the most
depressing stat of all for the Isles: They are 1-12-4 in their last
17 games against lowly Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
