<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Thrashers pick up insight on draft contenders
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Thrashers had a rotating group of six people
scouting the World Junior Championships in Winnipeg, which
concluded last week, and came away with some valuable insight on
potential draft picks, according to player personnel director Bob
Owen. ``Our coverage of the players has been pretty extensive, so
we already pretty much knew what they can and can't do,'' Owen
said. ``This tournament was more about the intangibles, like how
the young handle the pressure.'' Many of the top draft-eligible
17-year-olds struggled in the spotlight. Owen said most of the
players who performed the best already are the property of NHL
teams. NHL teams usually return their top draft picks to the
juniors after the draft for experience, much like a major-league
baseball team starts a high school draftee in the low minor
leagues. Among those who had problems were Swedish twins Daniel and
Henrik Sedin, who many project as two of the top five selections.
Canadian media even took to referring to the two as the ``Sedate''
twins. Sweden, a pre-tournament favorite, also came away without a
medal. (Russia defeated Canada in the final.) ``Everybody wanted a
piece of the (Sedins),'' Owen said. ``There wasn't a game where
they weren't abused because they were so highly publicized going
in. The pre-tournament hype was, stop them and you stop the team.
They tried to fight their way through it, but this is a tough
tournament when you're only 17 years old.'' Four other top-10
prospects _ Russia's Denis Shvidki, Finland's Jani Rita, Michael
Sivek of the Czech Republic and Tim Connolly of the U.S. _ fared
slightly better than the Sedins. The Czechs' Patrik Stefan, who is
playing with Long Beach of the IHL, did not participate in the
tournament because of an injury. ... The Thrashers' scouting staff
will hold its mid-winter meetings Jan. 17-20 in Fort Lauderdale,
the week before the NHL All-Star game in Tampa. ... The Thrashers,
in conjunction with Nike and the NHL, will donate equipment and
help launch an Atlanta street hockey program for inner-city youths.
Specifics of the program will be announced in about three weeks.
Similar ventures have been launched in other NHL cities.
</P>
<P>
   BY THE NUMBERS
</P>
<P>
   _$5.4 million: Amount Colorado defenseman Sandis Ozolinsh will
earn for two seasons after his belated signing _ far short of the
$10 million he sought.
</P>
<P>
   _$1.5 million: League-record fine levied last week against St.
Louis for tampering in 1994 with New Jersey's Scott Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   _$250,000: Amount the Blues were fined in 1994 for tampering
with then-New York Rangers coach Mike Keenan.
</P>
<P>
   _$20,510: Reported value of Red Wings' Stanley Cup ring and team
watch that the son of team owner Mike Illitch claimed was stolen
from his Boca Raton hotel room.
</P>
<P>
   _65 cents: Approximate U.S. value of the Canadian dollar.
</P>
<P>
   GREAT `GRITS-KY'
</P>
<P>
   The Asheville (N.C.) Smoke of the bottom-level United Hockey
League has lost 50 percent of its marketing campaign. The Smoke, a
franchise that relocated this year from Brantford, Ontario, the
birthplace of Wayne Gretzky, and boasted two of Gretzky's brothers
on the team, lost one of them this week. Forward Brent Gretzky, who
played for the IHL's Atlanta Knights and briefly in the NHL with
Tampa, signed with the IHL's Chicago Wolves. Keith Gretzky remains
coach and general manager of the team. Brent Gretzky had signed
with Asheville after leaving a team in Austria. But he clearly was
overqualified for the UHL, scoring 26 goals and 62 points in 29
games. He has now played for nine teams in five leagues in three
countries. ``I'm definitely not ready to leave hockey,'' Gretzky
said. Of the UHL, he said, ``It's a plumber's league. There's a lot
of stuff on the ice that shouldn't be happening, a lot of cheap
shots. Some guys are a little out of shape and they get
embarrassed, so they have to stick their stick in you.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
