<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Things are unraveling quickly for the Phoenix (wily?) Coyotes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After losing only three of their first 24 games
(18-3-3), the Coyotes won only three of their next 12 (3-7-2),
including Friday's loss at Anaheim. Worse, they went 1-3-1 on a
five-game homestand that included two fights in a practice between
teammates Jeremy Roenick and Oleg Tverdovsky. Roenick yelled at the
defenseman about messing up in a drill and tempers flared. It was
coach Jim Schoenfeld's hope that the blowup actually would help
pull the team together. Instead, Phoenix was drilled the next night
by the injury-depleted Edmonton Oilers, 7-1. ``I haven't seen too
many teams that don't have a few disruptions,'' Schoenfeld said.
``If you care, you're going to get upset sometimes.'' Hold the
Stanley Cup talk.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, Patrick?
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche goalie Patrick Roy, who would be one of the most
sought-after unrestricted free agents if he doesn't re-sign with
Colorado, is downplaying a three-week-old dispute between him and
coach Bob Hartley that became public only this week. After being
pulled during a game in Anaheim Dec. 21, Roy argued with Hartley in
the locker room and busted two television sets and a VCR with his
stick. Roy now says, ``I had an argument _ that was it.''
</P>
<P>
   But some people wonder if it moves him a step closer to leaving.
A dispute between Roy and then-Montreal coach Mario Tremblay led to
the goalie demanding a trade from the Canadiens in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Couch potato
</P>
<P>
   Look for the Colorado Avalanche to get a boost on their power
play now that point man Sandis Ozolinsh has signed three months
into the season _ although the boost may not be immediate. Ozolinsh
concedes he's not in peak condition. ``I have to practice and get
more contact where I have to make quick decisions, then we'll
see,'' he said. ``I'm in pretty good shape. I actually played golf
a bit. Hey, that's a sport. They show it on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' Luc Robataille scored his 500th career goal Thursday,
not bad for a guy who was drafted five spots behind a kid out of
Boston named Tom Glavine. Yes, that one. ... Another reason for the
NHL to copy international hockey's no-touch icing rule: The Kings'
Glen Murray tore a knee ligament last week when he fell after
racing a Colorado player to the puck to secure an icing against the
Avalanche. (In the NHL, icing is waved off if the offending team
reaches the puck first.) ... Detroit is 3-13-1 against teams that
are .500 or better. ... So if Brett Hull is wrecking Dallas'
chemistry and coach Ken Hitchcock is a tyrant, how could the Stars
build a 15-game unbeaten streak?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
