<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6302 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ARTSHELL     01-09 3118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ARTSHELL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNFATHOMABLE SHELL GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.199 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sometime this morning, Art Shell will finally get the
second chance he earned in 1994. Whether it's a real chance or not,
only Carmen Policy knows.
</P>
<P>
   The former head coach of the Oakland Raiders coached the
offensive line of the Atlanta Falcons in the NFC playoffs Saturday
against the San Francisco 49ers before flying off to Cleveland to
interview for the head coaching job of the new Browns. With Steve
Mariucci's contract extension in the works in San Francisco and
Mike Holmgren having landed in Seattle, it supposedly is an open
road now. If so, Shell has earned the right to be in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Shell is truly a candidate for the job is anyone's
guess, because many believe this is just a token gesture by the new
Browns to placate the NFL, a league whose players are 73 percent
black but whose head coaches today number only two blacks out of a
possible 30.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL says it hopes someone will give another black coach a
chance after the firing in Philadelphia of Ray Rhodes, but it seems
powerless to get that done, and no amount of videotaped job
interviews is going to change that. The league recently began such
a practice, making a collection of tapes available to teams looking
for head coaches and coordinators, and Shell agreed to take part in
the charade even though he knows nobody in history ever got a job
off a videotape except in the TV business.
</P>
<P>
   When the tape idea was first made public, New York Jets
linebacker Bryan Cox ripped it, and quite rightly. Cox may be a
loon at times but he was right on this issue when he said, ``From
my perspective, if I was a black coach, how I would feel is that
I'm getting another slap in the face. (If you're a white coach)
they're flying you out to these places to talk to them face to
face, but if you're black, they want to be able to go pull out a
video.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is that saying to you? `Oh, we're trying to get to know
you?' You're not trying to get to know me because if you were,
you'd fly me out there to talk to you, too. To me, it's just a
better way to kick us in the ass without us knowing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Shell understands Cox's point, he went along because he
never wanted it said that he hadn't taken advantage of that
program. Yet he is well aware of the shoddy minority hiring record
of NFL teams looking for head coaches, coordinators, and top
personnel men, and he knows, too, that the men who run the league
(and are nearly all white, by the way) know they need to change
that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Shell is a proud man who has never asked to be given
anything but the same chance as his colleagues. He seized his
chance as an athlete and ended up in the Hall of Fame as one of the
greatest offensive linemen of all time. When he finally got his
chance as a head coach, he went 54-39 from 1989-94, a winning
percentage of nearly .600. He took three of his six teams to the
playoffs, including a 12-4 team to the AFC Championship game in
1990, before being fired in 1994 after going 9-7.
</P>
<P>
   After Shell's departure, the Raiders slumped to 8-8, 7-9, and
4-12, plowing through two more head coaches before Jon Gruden got
them back to 8-8 this season. Yet Shell has never been called to
interview for another head coaching job. Not once during a time
during which 19 white men have been hired has Shell been called,
even though only three of the men who got jobs had a record
comparable to his and many barely had a .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Shell never mentions all of that, however. He talks only of his
belief in himself and his record, a position that may not cost him.
As fellow coach Don Blackmon, the ex-Patriot linebacker, says,
``Art just goes about his business. He's old school. People from
his era believe you don't lobby for things. You earn them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is filled with self-promoters. If that's what it
takes to get a head coaching job, he won't get it. But if they go
by his performance, by his winning percentage, he'll get another
chance. His track record speaks for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does, which is why the Browns won't wait if they're
smart. They will hire Shell not because he is the best black
candidate but because he's the best candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Shell was asked this past week about being a ``minority
candidate'' and he bristled, as he always has when race is brought
into the equation. When he became the first black head coach in the
65-year history of the NFL, Shell said he understood the
significance but chose not to consider himself a ``black'' coach.
That holds true today, not as an attempt to deny who he is but
rather to ignore it, as he wishes all people could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we were well beyond that,'' Shell said after a
Falcons practice at the Georgia Dome. ``I'm a candidate as a
potential head coach. Not as a minority head coach. I'm glad to
have the opportunity to go out there and talk with them, whatever
the opportunity is.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the Raiders, Shell coached the Kansas City
offensive line for two seasons and turned the Chiefs into the
league's leading rushers in his first year and the fourth-leading
rushers in his second even though he lacked a top-drawer running
back.
</P>
<P>
   Then Dan Reeves imported him to Atlanta last year to help
transform a run-and-shoot offense into a power running game. Jamal
Anderson has rushed for more than 1,000 yards both years and this
season piled up 1,846, the ninth-highest total in NFL history. But
numbers alone cannot measure a man or tell much about a coach.
People have to do that, and Reeves is glad to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't hesitate to recommend Art,'' said Reeves, who in
his days as Broncos coach faced Shell's teams twice a year. ``I had
a difficult time beating his teams when he was at the Raiders. I
don't know his rec &UR; - &LR; ord, but he's way ahead of me.
</P>
<P>
   ``His teams were very well-coached. Art is a class individual
and a very knowledgeable guy and he has a great rapport with
players. That's both black and white players I'm talking about.
They have a great respect for him. His presence demands that. Our
offensive line would do anything for him.''
</P>
<P>
   So if he's such a great coach, why has it taken five years for
Shell to even be given an interview for a second chance, let alone
a second chance itself? Reeves believes he knows why, at least to
some degree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think nobody knew for sure how much of it was him coaching
and how much of it was Al (Davis),'' Reeves said. ``I didn't know
myself. I have a great deal more respect for him now, having worked
with him here. I have no doubt the kind of job Art would do and no
hesitation about recommending him.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether Shell gets the Cleveland job or not, he has at least
this time gotten his name in the mix. That is a start, which is
something. But it won't be finished until he gets what his record _
not his pigmentation _ has earned him.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots aren't talking about it, but they got more bad news
last week. Middle linebacker  &UR; Ted Johnson  &LR; will need surgery on his
left shoulder, according to a source close to him. That comes on
top of the torn right biceps that ended his season and would be the
second shoulder operation of his career. A year ago, it was his
right shoulder that had to be surgically cleaned out, and now it
will be the left. This has to be causing the Patriots more than a
little angst since they invested millions in him only a year ago,
and the tools of his trade _ his shoulders and biceps _ have
seemingly begun to unravel. Johnson is a hard-nosed player but he
takes a pounding at his position, and one has to wonder how long he
can hold up. If it's not for the long term, that $5 million-a-year
extension of a year ago could come back to haunt the Patriots ...
Although it appears that Patriots coach  &UR; Pete Carroll  &LR; will survive
this offseason, he has taken a pounding from several sides: former
players  &UR; Dave Meggett  &LR; and  &UR; Jimmy Hitchcock &LR; ; &UR;  &LR; more than a few of
his present players since the debacle at the Meadowlands; and
strength and conditioning coach  &UR; Johnny Parker &LR; , who conceded that
the offseason workout program since Carroll took over has not been
attended as religiously as it was under  &UR; Bill Parcells &LR; . &UR;  &LR; Parker
was telling the sad truth, which was reflected both in the
trainer's room and on the field. Carroll needs to acknowledge this,
not try to deny it, and do more than suggest workout bonuses be
increased. He needs to make clear to his players that while the
workouts technically may be voluntary, so is their inclusion on his
roster. But can he do that with any force? The jury is out on that,
but it's not a good sign that trainer  &UR; Ron O'Neil  &LR; was recently
dispatched to the home of  &UR; Terry Glenn  &LR; to check on the progress of
the receiver's recovery from ankle surgery; Glenn had not come
around to the stadium since his injury. That included the team's
breakup meeting last Monday ... Although Carroll doesn't yet appear
to realize it, he is on far shakier ground with management than he
knows. It is not simply because his team has underachieved, in the
opinion of some. It is because there is a growing concern in upper
management that his coaching philosophy does not dovetail with
personnel director  &UR; Bobby Grier's  &LR; approach to building a team. In
this era of free agency and constant roster turnover, Grier
believes teams must be built with young players and they must be
used before they are free to abandon ship for big bucks elsewhere.
But the growing concern is that Carroll's fervent belief that
players need to make the team their own by becoming responsible for
themselves is anathema to a young squad like the one Grier has
tried to put together. The fear is that Carroll's loose ways _ what
he likes to call the 49er Way _ might work with a veteran team that
has leaders such as  &UR; Jerry Rice &LR; , &UR; Steve Young &LR; , &UR; Tim McDonald &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and
 &UR; Merton Hanks &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but not with a basically rudderless ship of
younger players capable of doing something so asinine as voting out
 &UR; Bruce Armstrong  &LR; as postseason captain.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Here's the kind of thing that may explain to Tampa Bay fans why
their team is out of the playoffs again. Three of the six Pro Bowl
quarterbacks once wore the Buccaneers' logo. None do now. Young,
 &UR; Vinny Testaverde &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Chris Chandler  &LR; all labored for Tampa Bay
once. If  &UR; Trent Dilfer's  &LR; game doesn't improve, he could become the
next ex-Buccaneer ... Here's how times have changed.  &UR; today &LR;  the
state of Connecticut is ready to guarantee  &UR; Bob Kraft  &LR; $100,000 per
unsold luxury box and $4,000 per unsold club seat to lure him to
their state. Longtime Patriots season ticket-holder  &UR; Edward Modest
 &LR; sent along a copy of a 1970 renewal form for his two seats. Total
cost for the year: $117. Them were the days ... While  &UR; Peyton
Manning  &LR; did nothing but improve this season while earning the
respect of his peers, Chargers linebacker  &UR; Lew Bush &LR;  said of
hotshot  &UR; Ryan Leaf &LR; , ``He's going to have to do a lot of showing
and growing before people are going to respect him. Respect isn't
bought, it's earned. I'm not criticizing my teammate, but he did a
lot of real stupid things this season.'' Glad Bush wasn't being
critical. General manager  &UR; Bobby Beathard  &LR; doesn't disagree with
that opinion and will look to bring in a veteran who can challenge
Leaf. The most likely candidate is 36-year-old  &UR; Mark Rypien &LR; .
Beathard tried to coax Rypien out of retirement this season but
Rypien was tending to family matters that included the death of his
young son. But Rypien has alerted the Chargers and other teams that
he wants to come back ... Speaking of Beathard, how did he ever
come up with a guy who was 8-14 at Oregon State to revive the
Chargers? When  &UR; Mike Riley  &LR; was named the new San Diego coach last
week, many heads were shaking around the NFL. Riley was considered
a top offensive mind at Southern Cal, and Beathard got to know him
well. Beathard appears to be betting that Riley is the next
Mariucci. Only problem is, Riley is stuck with an immature kid in
Leaf, not someone like Young. An AFC front office rival said,
``Bobby wants to prove he can find the needle in the haystack. He
wants to keep proving he's still Bobby Beathard. The more he tries
to prove it, the farther out there he gets.'' Beathard was looking
for a younger coach with an offensive mind and may have wanted to
take a shot at Minnesota's  &UR; Brian Billick &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but he might have had
to wait until February. If he fails then, his team would be
scrambling both for a head coach and assistants when most of the
top candidates would be hired ... Even a nice guy like Rams head
coach  &UR; Dick Vermeil  &LR; got into the blame game when he chose to save
his skin by firing offensive coordinator  &UR; Jerry Rhome &LR; . Vermeil
said, ``I'm concerned about two things: No. 1, that I'm trying to
pass the buck, and No. 2 (team president)  &UR; John Shaw  &LR; told me to do
it. They're both wrong. I don't want this read as I'm blaming Jerry
Rhome for our lack of success offensively. I've spent all my time
from a technical standpoint in the offensive war room. I hired him
because I had respect for him and I still have respect for him.''
Oh, and by the way, you're fired. Why do these guys talk like this?
Two minutes later, Vermeil continued, ``This isn't all about
coaching. It's also about marketing.'' I'm sure the head coach is
more interested in that than the club's president is.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Note to the Saints. You were much improved this season but still
finished 6-10, had 10 players arrested on charges ranging from
drunken driving to assaulting a man with a golf club, had four
lawsuits filed against you (including a $650,000 one stemming from
last summer's hazing incident), and you paid $850,000 to a guy
 &UR; Mike Ditka  &LR; hated and finally traded ( &UR; Andre Royal &LR; ), $650,000 to
a guy who failed to catch a single pass ( &UR; Qadry Ismail &LR; ), &UR;  &LR; and $1
million to  &UR; Heath Shuler  &LR; for never throwing a pass. Don't put the
new broom away quite yet ... Seventeen Falcons plus team physician
 &UR; Andrew Bishop  &LR; were at the Georgia Dome Monday night but they
couldn't save their old friend, former Falcon  &UR; Bill
Goldberg &LR; , &UR;  &LR; from destruction. The WCW's former heavyweight
wrestling champion had invited them to watch his ``title'' rematch
with new champ  &UR; Kevin Nash &LR; , &UR;  &LR; but before he got in the ring,
Goldberg was ``arrested'' on trumped-up charges filed by
 &UR; ``Hollywood'' Hulk Hogan &LR; . After Hogan ended up pinning Nash,
Goldberg ran into the ring and was beaten up and handcuffed while
Hogan, Nash, and three pals spray-painted his head. Just after this
ended, Anderson,  &UR; Cornelius Bennett &LR; , &UR; Chuck Smith &LR; , &UR; Travis
Hall &LR; , &UR; Shane Dronett &LR; , &UR; Eugene Robinson &LR; , &UR; Lester Archambeau &LR; , &UR; Dave
Widell  &LR; and other Falcons players entered the arena and chased
Goldberg's enemies out of the building before flexing and doing the
Dirty Bird dance that their 14-2 season has made popular in
Georgia. The ringleader was center  &UR; Robbie Tobeck &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a longtime
wrestling fan. Shouldn't these guys have been watching film of the
49ers or something? ... Many wondered why 58-year-old  &UR; George
Seifert  &LR; decided to risk his coaching reputation by taking over the
collapsing Carolina Panthers, but he made it clear that old
coaches, like old soldiers, never die, they just fade away. ``The
last couple of years I've kind of been living in a gray twilight,''
Seifert said after accepting a contract that will pay him an
estimated $2.5 million a season. ``It's an empty feeling. I'm more
excited than I ever thought I would be about coming back into
coaching. There is a sense and a feeling I'm at home. I'm at peace
with myself.'' Next time you hear one of these coaches complaining
about lousy press or the pressures of the job, remember those
words. They love it the way  &UR; George Patton  &LR; loved combat ...
Seifert, by the way, won 76 percent of his games (108-35) in San
Francisco and was forced out to make room for Mariucci, so let's
not hear any more nonsense about Carroll not getting a fair chance
in New England. In this day of instant gratification, you get a
chance, but nobody ever said it would be fair.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Up in Green Bay, the hunt has begun for a head coach, and
sources there insist that former Yale running back  &UR; Dick Jauron  &LR; is
the favorite, with Rhodes (a former Packer defensive coordinator)
next. GM  &UR; Ron Wolf  &LR; likes both and has played it coy, but he did
say Thursday he had someone in mind but couldn't contact him. That
implied it was a coach in the playoffs, as Jauron is (Jacksonville
defensive coordinator), but not Rhodes, who is unemployed. Then
again, knowing Wolf, he could have meant that he'd called Rhodes
and gotten a busy signal. ``These are enormous shoes to fill, make
no mistake about it,'' Wolf said. ``You have to have the right
person to fill those shoes. This isn't going to be like one of
those high school prom things where you pick the best-looking or
the most compatible. This is a situation where you have to pick
somebody of championship caliber and championship quality, and
that's what we're going to do.'' Whoever gets the job is expected
to retain quarterbacks coach  &UR; Andy Reid &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been designated
a supervisor by the Packers and hence can leave only for a head
job. That probably signals the end for offensive coordinator  &UR; Sherm
Lewis &LR; , who may end up back with Holmgren in Seattle ... Fox
analyst  &UR; Matt Millen  &LR; shrugged off speculation that he is in line
to become general manager of the Detroit Lions, saying, ``Just
'cause you're in the papers doesn't mean you're in a new job.''
True, but someone who was trying to negotiate a contract with the
Lions last week was told that everything is on hold because of an
expected shakeup that will remove longtime GM  &UR; Chuck Schmidt &LR; .
Millen did say he had a preliminary discussion with the Lions about
a front office job but was not specific. He has no front office or
coaching experience but played 12 years in the NFL and is the only
player to have four Super Bowl rings from three teams (Raiders,
Redskins, and 49ers) ... Here's a stat for you numbers freaks. Six
of the NFL's top eight rushing teams earned their way to the
playoffs, but the top three teams in that category _ San Francisco,
Denver, and Buffalo _ had the lightest offensive lines among
playoff clubs. Minnesota has the heaviest at an average of 322.8
pounds per man but was 11th among playoff teams in rushing. The
49ers were first in rushing (159 yards) but 11th in average weight
at 295.4 pounds. Denver was second in rushing (154.3 yards) but
last in size (287.6 pounds). The Patriots, by the way, were 27th in
the NFL in rushing but ninth in weight among playoff teams (301.6
pounds).
</P>
</TEXT>
