<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-LEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEACH LATEST NEW ENGLANDER TO JOIN PHOENIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Leach has a place in the sun, after getting what amounted
to the cold shoulder in Ottawa. The former Bruins winger from
Lexington, who earlier this season requested his release in Ottawa,
has earned a regular spot on the Phoenix Coyotes' checking line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a weird situation in Ottawa,'' said Leach, who signed
with the Senators as a free agent over the summer. ``Originally,
when we were negotiating, they didn't want to be on the hook for
the contract because I'd had neck surgery (to repair a disk). So we
agreed to a base salary, with incentives kicking in after I played
10 games.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine games into the season, Leach found himself out of uniform
and assigned a seat in the press box on game nights. What he hoped
would be a career kick-start turned out to be a disappointing
backfire, after moving his entire family to Ontario and getting a
house. His request for a release granted, Leach soon was headed
back to New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing left a bad taste in my mouth,'' said the
33-year-old Leach. ``I was pretty bitter about it.''
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, Leach is yet another member of the Coyotes' growing
contingent of transplanted New Englanders. Keith Tkachuk (Medford)
and Jeremy Roenick (Marshfield) are the club's highest-profile Bay
Staters; Tkachuk is out at least another two weeks with a fractured
rib and Roenick is just back from what he figures is his sixth
concussion. Phoenix also has ex-Bruin Mike Sullivan (Duxbury), Bob
Corkum (Salisbury), Keith Carney (Providence), and Deron Quint
(Durham, N.H.).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said Leach, who turned up in Springfield (AHL)
before joining the Coyotes. ``I guess it's a byproduct of hockey
being such a hotbed in New England, and all around Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't necessarily strength in numbers when it comes to
fending off barbs in the dressing room about that Boston accent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ah, you get that wherever you go _ it's like that in every
room,'' said Leach, ``especially after the summah, when you've been
hanging around your buddies a few months, it gets a little
thickah.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Esa Tikkanen's  &LR; never-ending revival show hit a slump on
Broadway, as he went only 0-3_3 in his first 32 games with the
Rangers. The Blueshirts shipped him Thursday to Hartford of the AHL
after scratching him for four straight games. Keep in mind:
Tikkanen signed for a base salary of $500,000, with substantial
bonuses for games on the New York roster ($200,000 at 40 games,
another $300,000 at 60 games, another $500,000 at 70 games). ``They
know what I can do,'' said Tikkanen, who was demoted after being on
the roster for 38 games. ``If they want to keep me, I'd be happy.
But sometime, I'd like to play.'' Tikkanen began the season at
 &UR; Wayne Gretzky's  &LR; left side, on the No. 1 line. The Great One now
has  &UR; Todd Harvey  &LR; and  &UR; Adam Graves  &LR; as his wingers, and head coach
 &UR; John Muckler  &LR; is using  &UR; Darren Langdon  &LR; and  &UR; Brent Fedyk  &LR; ahead of
Tikkanen ... Ex-Bruin defenseman  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld  &LR; on why we see so
few _ if any _ NHLers race over the wing and fire in 40- and
50-foot slapshots: ``The guy who comes to mind, of course, is  &UR; Guy
Lafleur &LR; . But since his time, we've had the era of the butterfly
goalies, and no one scores on a big slapshot from outside because
the whole lower half of the net is taken away. If a guy wants to
score from out there now, he's got to shoot high and try to bury it
in a corner. You're talking about a very small area, and a lot of
those shots are going to go high. When the bottom half was there,
well, you can't shoot too low _ those shots went in the net.'' ...
 &UR; Dave Reece &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the Bruins' netminder who was torched for  &UR; Darryl
Sittler's  &LR; 10 points (6 goals, 4 assists) at Maple Leaf Gardens
Feb. 7, 1976, now lives in Rhode Island and is director of
admissions at Worcester Academy. ``What can I tell you?'' said the
affable Reece, now 50. ``The folklore is I tried to commit suicide
after the game by throwing myself in front of a train, but even the
train went through my legs.'' Boston coach  &UR; Don Cherry  &LR; never gave
Reece the hook in the 11-4 shellacking. ``But you know, I didn't
want to come out,'' said Reece. ``I was always old school like
that. When it's your turn to eat the banana, you eat it _ just one
of those games. The worst thing I did _ and I never told anyone
this _ was I broke my routine the night before the game. I was
feeling kind of sorry for myself, because I found out I was being
sent back to the minors, no matter what, and I went out on the town
with Chief ( &UR; John Bucyk &LR; ) the night before. I'm not saying I got
blotto, or anything, but I didn't maintain a good regimen.'' It was
Reece's final game in the big time. He has never talked to Sittler,
who stands alone as the only NHLer to record 10 points in a game.
``It was a magic night for the guy,'' said Reece. ``Wouldn't you
think he'd send me something _ some little gift, or something, for
crying out loud. I mean, I helped put the guy in the Hall of Fame,
and he put me in the Hall of Shame.'' ... After seeing  &UR; Scott
Gomez &LR; , &UR;  &LR; their second pick (27th overall) in last June's draft,
collect 10 points in the World Junior tournament in Winnipeg, the
Devils signed the talented Alaskan center to a three-year contract
worth upwards of $2 million. Gomez went back to junior (Tri-Cities)
and is expected to report to Albany (AHL) when his season ends
there. BC's  &UR; Brian Gionta &LR; , &UR;  &LR; another Devils pick last June (82d
overall), led the tournament with 11 points ... Russia beat Canada,
3-2, in overtime to win the Junior tournament. The Oilers played
host to the Kings in Edmonton the night of the final and the crowd
was treated to the broadcast during timeouts and intermissions.
``Gee,'' said Kings defenseman  &UR; Rod Blake &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``for a minute I
thought they might put it on the loudspeaker and let us play
through it.'' ... Yet another Bay Stater was made a team captain
last week when the Oilers tabbed  &UR; Bill Guerin  &LR; to fill in for
 &UR; Kelly Buchberger  &LR; (out at least two months with a badly broken
forearm). ``The fact the team feels I could fill in for a short
time, until Bucky's back, means a lot to me,'' said Guerin. Tkachuk
is captain in Phoenix and  &UR; Tom Fitzgerald  &LR; (Melrose) is captain in
Nashville ... Phoenix defenseman  &UR; Oleg Tverdovsky  &LR; on the success
of countryman  &UR; Sergei Samsonov &LR; : ``He's a great skater, and
personally, I thought he would have been drafted higher than he was
(No. 8 by Boston in '97). He's small, but that doesn't matter. If
you have skills and character, it doesn't matter how big you are _
I'm glad Sergei proved it.'' ... Roenick got into a scrap with
Tverdovsky at practice Wednesday, following the Coyotes' 2-2 tie
the night before with the Panthers. The confrontation escalated
from heated words to pushing, ultimately broken up by teammate  &UR; Jim
Cummins &LR; . Roenick initiated it, irate that Tverdovsky twice messed
up a practice drill. Roenick: ``I'm one of Oleg's biggest
supporters _ but we have to listen more. We have to pay attention
to detail.'' It wasn't the first time Roenick has exchanged heated
on-ice words with the talented blue liner. ``It's a game of passion
and intensity,'' said Tverdovsky. ``It's not a big deal. We've had
a few tough games, guys are on edge, and they can snap. You wish
these things don't happen, but it's sport.'' ... Former Bruin
 &UR; Terry O'Reilly &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who dabbles in real estate, purchased the
delapidated Hotel Edwards at Salisbury Beach just before the new
year. ``I heard Salisbury Beach will be making a comeback over the
next few years,'' O'Reilly told the Georgetown Record, adding that
he's not sure how he'll redevelop the groaning edifice. The deal
was closed at the Salem Registry of Deeds, with an estimated 50
title examiners clamoring for autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   San Jose tough guy  &UR; Brent Myhres  &LR; has been in rehab twice to
battle a drinking problem _ a point Devils defenseman  &UR; Scott
Stevens  &LR; knew when he told him to ``go have another beer'' and also
called him a drunk after things got rough between the Devils and
Sharks at the end the second period Tuesday night. Devils
defenseman  &UR; Ken Daneyko &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who missed more than half of last season
while he battled his own alcohol addiction, empathized with Myhres.
``It's been said to me, too, but I haven't mentioned it,'' said
Daneyko. ``I brushed it off. I wouldn't recommend saying things
like that, but they're said in the heat of the battle. I wish
(Myhres) the best, he's going through the same things I'm going
through.'' Added Myhres, ``I think there's a line that shouldn't be
crossed, and I thought (Stevens) crossed it.'' ... Rangers
netminder  &UR; Mike Richter &LR; , &UR;  &LR; in a New York Times report last week,
spoke eloquently about Gretzky: ``Maturing throughout your career
is insidious. Quietly, it starts to put limitations on what you are
able to do. Wayne sees the game probably better now than ever. But
it's a cruelty of sports that when you are mentally at your peak,
you start to deteriorate physically. He has so much willpower that
he overcomes whatever level of deterioration his body has had.''
... The Minnesota Wild won't enter the NHL until October 2000 and,
if  &UR; Jay Erckenbrach  &LR; gets his way, they'll enter under a different
name. Erckenbrach, from McGregor, Minn., for a number of years has
sold jams, jellies, and wines under the ``Wild'' label, and he
feels the hockey club is using his trademark. The club's contention
is that it is selling hockey, nothing else. In an attempt to settle
the squabble, the hockey club has offered to sell Erckenbrach's
goods at home games and help him with marketing. But, so far,
Erckenbrach's not budging. If they want the game, they'll have to
buy the name ... Meanwhile, Minnesota is expected to name its
general manager in the coming weeks. Some of the rumored
contenders:  &UR; David McNab  &LR; (brother of ex-Bruin  &UR; Peter McNab &LR; ), &UR;  &LR; now
the assistant GM in Anaheim;  &UR; Les Jackson &LR; , &UR;  &LR; assistant GM in
Atlanta; and ex-Quebec GM  &UR; Pierre Page  &LR; (dismissed as Ducks coach
after last season). Ex-Minnesotan  &UR; Bobby Smith  &LR; has been rumored,
too, but his deal as Phoenix GM runs through 2001-02 ... It took
four-plus years, but the Devils last week won their Stevens
tampering charge against St. Louis, dating back to the summer of
'94. The league _ tipped by a former Blues exec _ found a dated
FedEx receipt in the files of ex-team president  &UR; Jack
Quinn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; proof that the Blues sent Stevens a four-year, $17 million
offer prior to July 1, the annual free agency date. The Blues now
must fork over $1.5 million (all but $75,000 payable to the
Devils), one first-round pick in the next five years, and also swap
a first-round pick with New Jersey on or before the June 2004
draft. So much for detailed record keeping.
</P>
