<HEADLINE>
NBA PLAYERS MUST FOCUS ON BLURRY IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You already know about the NBA's six months of painful plastic
surgery. You know that the league rearranged its financial face
with its lockout, forcing hundreds of millionaires to mark
``unemployed'' on their 1998 income-tax forms.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what that means: If Michael Jordan happened to walk into
a grocery store during the past six months, he saw baggers and
cashiers making more cash from their full-time gigs than he was
making from his. Maybe the person checking MJ out on the ``12 items
or less'' line conveniently forgot to scan the eggs and Gatorade,
saving the game's best player a few dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But that's just the financial portrait from the past six months.
Certainly the players realize that, after half a year, money
matters are not the only things that have changed the way people
look at their game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the players don't remember the way they were beginning to
be perceived, often unfairly, by league observers just before the
lockout became official July 1. Maybe they don't remember the
whispers, the public laments that many of them were disciples of
``hiphop culture,'' as if that were something to be cursed. Maybe
they don't remember their lifestyles being scrutinized and being
labeled as self-absorbed and self-destructive.
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut woman accused Juwan Howard and Chris Webber of
sexually assaulting her in the spring. People shook their heads.
Webber was stopped on the way to practice by police, accused of
assaulting an officer and having the smell of marijuana wafting
from his vehicle. People shook their heads. Four men, three with
ties to the Celtics _ Antoine Walker, Ron Mercer, and ex-teammate
Chauncey Billups _ were accused of sexually assaulting a woman in
Waltham. People shook their heads. Sports Illustrated wrote a
6,000-word special report on NBA players fathering children with
women who weren't their wives. People shook their heads. Some of
the allegations were completely true, others were partially true,
and others were thrown out of court as lacking merit.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what. A lockout probably didn't slow the momentum of
images, images that project the NBA player as social villain.
Basketball fans will always be fans, so players probably don't have
to worry about that. But that's just for matters that relate to the
court. Off it, the image of NBA players is probably at its lowest
since the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And here's what that means if you are a Boston Celtic: Build a
bubble, if you can. Live in it for a few weeks. People say you
cannot live your life in a bubble, but many people have never had
their personal lives under attack every day. You do. You are a
target more than you realize. Especially now. Three-fifths of your
team's projected starting lineup was not born when Richard Nixon
resigned the presidency in 1974. Well, you should know that Nixon
was paranoid. He didn't trust many people. He was always looking
over his shoulder and under his desk. Maybe you should become
Nixonian in that way for a while, especially when you go to
nightclubs.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the Celtics _ one of the youngest teams in NBA history,
by the way _ do not realize there are two NBAs. There is the one
that they will experience on the FleetCenter's parquet floor,
beginning Feb. 5 or 6. And then there is the one that takes place
on the nation's dance floors. You can bet that is the NBA that
keeps Celtics coach Rick Pitino awake for a few extra minutes each
night. He certainly doesn't mind having a young team, because that
means he can mold it in his likeness and compete for a title sooner
rather than later. On the court. Off it, Pitino cannot tell his
players, grown men, where they can and cannot go. That means he has
to hope they remain camouflaged against the club's walls, dance a
little, and then go home with people they know.
</P>
<P>
   If you have to ask why, you haven't been paying attention to the
sports world in the past six months. Yes, you heard about the
Sports Illustrated story and the Webber story and the Howard story.
But maybe you didn't hear that Howard and Webber were acquitted of
their sexual assault charge and that Howard wound up countersuing
for the restoration of something very important to him: his image.
Maybe you didn't hear that Howard won his countersuit for
defamation of character. Maybe you heard that Celtics star Walker
was named in a civil negligence lawsuit relative to the alleged
Waltham assault. That was originally filed late in 1997. But fewer
people paid attention when a judge dismissed the charge against
Walker, saying that he was not at fault.
</P>
<P>
   Walker and Howard were fortunate, really. The current NBA
perception is such that they easily could have been forced into
paying off a settlement even though judges ruled that they did
nothing wrong. The perception of the NBA is that bad. Walker and
Howard are also fortunate they are not in the position of Billups.
His name has not been dismissed from the assault case. So he had to
explain to his girlfriend why he is accused of having group sex
with a woman in someone else's condo. And he had to explain why he
was doing that while his girlfriend was pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   We are witnessing an emerging trend in the NBA. As the images of
the players worsen, the more litigation is aimed at them. Some is
deserved, some is not. All can be avoided.
</P>
<P>
   It is on days like this that I am happy not to be a pro athlete.
Sometimes, you just want to go to a club and do whatever you please
without worrying about your picture being in the paper the next
day. You can say the Celtics should be able to have that luxury,
too. They can't.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, three fliers came in the mail for Boston-area
nightclubs. The young Celtics, music and dance lovers, would
probably enjoy going. They should go. And act like Nixon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
