<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6310 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REBUILD-T     01-09 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS HOPE TO DUMP SALARIES, ADD TALENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A ``sickening feeling and bitter taste'' remain
at the Cowboys' Valley Ranch training complex more than a week
after the shocking wild-card playoff loss to the Arizona Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   If Cowboys coach Chan Gailey has his way, the stench will
linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to remember what this tastes like,'' Gailey said. ``It
will give us a spur to take it further next year. We don't want to
sit in the same spot. We've got to build on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Eternally optimistic Cowboys owner Jerry Jones remains hopeful
of rebuilding a solid playoff contender largely because of the
changes made last season. Gailey will be in his second season as
head coach, and the players will be further along in their
adjustment to Gailey's offense and the altered defensive scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I see in Chan Gailey is a man who can make the changes to
make us champions again,'' Jones said. ``I see a very good plan. I
like the direction we are going here.''
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the plan, however, is upgrading the team's talent.
Jones said he always believed players, not coaches, were the key to
championship teams. It's no secret the Cowboys' fall from grace _
after winning three Super Bowl titles from 1992 through 1995 _ can
be blamed on a drop in talent.
</P>
<P>
   Since their Super Bowl season of 1992, the Cowboys have lost 46
players, including 10 starters. During that span, the Cowboys have
added only seven players via free agency and only four of those
became starters: cornerback Deion Sanders, center Ray Donaldson,
linebacker Fred Strickland and guard Everett McIver. Donaldson is
no longer with the team and Strickland is on his way out.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys compounded their problems with draft mistakes. One
player (Larry Allen) out of the 45 players picked in the past four
drafts has developed into a Pro Bowl performer. Only three players
remain from the 1994 and 1995 drafts combined.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Jones says this off-season is crucial to the team's
future. He said the Cowboys have a great opportunity to enhance
their personnel _ from the outside through the draft and free
agency and from within through expected improvement by several
younger players: guard Flozell Adams, tight end David LaFleur and
defensive end Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   The wild card in the equation is the Cleveland Browns' expansion
draft, which might allow the financially strapped Cowboys to unload
some big salaries and clear salary-cap room.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, Gailey and the Cowboys' scouts have been huddling all
week working on list of five players they will expose to the Feb. 9
expansion draft by Tuesday's deadline. The Browns will inherit the
cap impact of any bonus paid to the players they select.
</P>
<P>
   With 43 players already under contract for 1999 at a cost of
roughly $61 million, Jones will try to use the expansion draft to
ease the salary cap burden. The 1999 cap is expected to be $57.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way the expansion draft helps is easing the cap,''
Jones said. ``This is the only time you can make a move with a
player with a big cap number.''
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list of potential cost-cutting targets is cornerback
Kevin Smith, who lost his starting job to Kevin Mathis and will
count $3.334 million against the salary cap next season. Other
possibilities and how much they will count against the cap are
tight end Eric Bjornson ($859,000), Strickland ($1.117 million),
defensive tackle Hurvin McCormack ($750,000), cornerback Charlie
Williams ($600,000) and receiver Billy Davis ($1.13 million). All
are candidates to be released if they're not selected in the
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Long shots for the draft list are defensive tackle Chad Hennings
($1.486 million) and fullback Daryl Johnston ($1.65 million). Both
are solid citizens and good for the team; however, neither player's
output matches his salary.
</P>
<P>
   As for the history of poor personnel moves, Jones says he is
encouraged about the choices the Cowboys will make because of the
people who will make them. A couple of years ago, the Cowboys moved
from a coaches-directed selection process to one headed by the
scouting department and chief scout Larry Lacewell.
</P>
<P>
   The move has resulted in two solid, if not spectacular, drafts.
Six picks remain on the team from the 1997 draft, including two
starters. Seven players, including two starters, remain from 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts still have a dominant influence over player personnel,
and Gailey is expected to have a lot of input in deciding who's on
the team next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
