A6313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PETERS-     01-09 2107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PETERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETERS PERSONIFIES BEST ASPECTS OF GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having been introduced as the Massachusetts Golf Association's
Player of the Year, Justin Peters put a gentle embrace on a trophy
and a serious dose of humility on the proceedings Thursday night.
The 21-year-old from Pembroke was being honored for his athletic
talent, but he showed that it was great character that had really
brought him to this evening.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out at a crowd of several hundred at Wellesley Country
Club, Peters singled out his mother, Rosemarie, and showered her
with praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's incredible,'' said Peters. ``Every day I try and be a
little more like her.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who know Justin Peters who will tell you that he
is succeeding, that indeed Rosemarie's goodness and strength have
been inherited by her son. Dick Haskell, for one, will vouch for
that.
</P>
<P>
   Haskell is just a year retired from his post as executive
director of the MGA, and in nearly three decades in that job he saw
a lot of great golf and thousands of rounds of competition. He is
not easily impressed and he holds fast to some aspects of the game
that many may consider old-fashioned and corny; things like
behavior and etiquette, respect and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we were talking about a doctor, you would say bedside
manners,'' said Haskell, for whom the Player of the Year award is
named. ``Justin Peters has great on-course manners.''
</P>
<P>
   His summer included a victory at the prestigious Hornblower
Memorial and a fifth-place finish in the State Open, in addition to
another solid run at the US Public Links Championship and a high
finish in the Ouimet Memorial. It also included the death of his
father, John, at a time when the two were reestablishing some
semblance of a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   His parents had divorced when he was 14 and for years Justin
heard not a word from his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was never there for me,'' said Justin. ``He was struggling
in his life, drinking, and had problems he had to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Rosemarie was the center of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was always Mom taking me to baseball games, soccer games,
whatever,'' he said. ``Then golf. She was the reason I got to play
in all those tournaments.''
</P>
<P>
   John Peters reentered the picture a few years ago, though it
``was off and on,'' said Justin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was hope, and a Christmas meeting in Boston a year
ago was enjoyable. Another get-together was held early last summer
and a short while later John Peters called his son and talked about
spending a weekend on the Cape. A few days later, John Peters was
found dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He bought me my first set of clubs when I was 13,'' said
Justin. ``I said, `What are these?' I had no idea. But he got me
introduced to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a game he has grown to love, no small reason being that he
has been able to share it with his mother. Last summer, Peters was
playing in the New England Amateur at New Haven CC in Connecticut
and on the morning of the 36-hole finale, Rosemarie had an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came up to me and said, `Why don't I caddie for you?'''
said Peters. ``I couldn't believe it, but she did. What a trooper.
I didn't play that well, but I'll treasure that memory forever.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that Peters has pro aspirations, he found the
timing to be perfect Thursday night because the guest speaker was
 &UR; Geoff Sisk &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the popular Marshfield golfer who leaves for Hawaii
Sunday as he embarks on his rookie season on the PGA Tour. It's a
dream come true for the 32-year-old Sisk, a two-time State Open and
New England Open champion who finished tied for fourth at
Qualifying School in December to secure his 1999 Tour card.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk and Peters were the last two to leave Wellesley CC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to talk to him, to pick his brain,'' said Peters.
``He was great. He gave me his phone number and told me to call
anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Peters will soon return to the University of Nevada-Reno, where
he is a senior and star of the golf team. He is behind in credits
so he'll stay out there this summer, take classes, then finish up
next fall. The good news: He is determined to get his degree. The
bad news (though perhaps not for the competition): Peters will miss
next summer's state competition that has played such a huge part in
his life.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk, meanwhile, is a mixed bag of emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled but I'm nervous,'' he said. ``I've never played
before 40,000 people before. But a friend told me that the size of
the hole hasn't changed, so we'll just do the best we can.''
</P>
<P>
   His early schedule calls for the Sony Open in Hawaii, the Bob
Hope Chrysler Classic, possibly Phoenix, then the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach
National Pro-Am. It is just the start of a journey, said Sisk, that
he figures will mean $70,000-$90,000 in travel expenses, an
overwhelming figure to be sure, but he is, after all, chasing a
dream that involves millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows?'' he joked to a crowd that included his wife,
Denise. ``Maybe in a few years we can retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Does he have the game?
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the best of feelings going into Tour School and
I shot 20 under,'' said Sisk. ``How did I do it? I don't know. If I
did, I would do it all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Also honored Thursday night were  &UR; Ed Fletcher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; senior player
of the year;  &UR; Kenny Lewis &LR; , &UR;  &LR; junior player of the year;  &UR; Laura
Torrisi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; player of the year in the Women's Golf Association of
Massachusetts;  &UR; Tracy Welch &LR; , &UR;  &LR; WGAM Association champion; and
winners of the major MGA events.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes Championship, which kicks off the 1999 PGA Tour
schedule and concludes this evening in Hawaii, is a select-field
event with one simple criterion for entry: You must have won a
tournament the previous year. That would seem to make it a
can't-miss date, but five eligible players did not take advantage,
for various reasons.  &UR; Olin Browne &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the Greater Hartford
Open, is recovering from arm surgery, and  &UR; Hal Sutton  &LR; (Tour
Championship) stayed home with his wife, who is expecting twins.
Understandable absences on both counts. But the fact that three
others ( &UR; Nick Price &LR; , &UR; Lee Westwood &LR; , &UR; Ernie Els &LR; ) &UR;  &LR; were no-shows
underscores just how much money is out there for elite players:
They shrugged off a $2.6 million purse. Their schedules were full,
and they will have ample opportunities in the coming months to play
for purses twice that size ... File this under Long Story Made
Short.  &UR; Hank Kuehne &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the reigning US Amateur champ who could
leave  &UR; Tiger Woods  &LR; and  &UR; John Daly  &LR; fighting for second place in a
three-way driving contest, showed a soft side to his game at a
recent visit to Augusta National. Kuehne made seven birdies and
shot 20 on the par-3 course, then told a reporter he felt he should
have shot 18. The senior at Southern Methodist will be in the
Masters field in April, and it's even money that one of the first
story lines that week will be Kuehne's enormous length off the tee,
particularly if he plays a practice round with Woods, which is
almost a certainty ... Speaking of Woods, he will gladly relinquish
(at least for 1999) his place as the most sought-after interview in
golf. For now, it belongs to  &UR; Ben Crenshaw &LR; , &UR;  &LR; thanks to his status
as US Ryder Cup captain. Crenshaw's schedule is punctuated by press
conferences that will do wonders for his frequent-flier program:
Feb. 17 in Los Angeles, March 3 in Miami, May 19 in Fort Worth,
June 28 in New York, and June 30 and Aug. 11 in Chicago. Not to
mention all the other ones that will pop up along the way,
including a stop in Boston March 11, when he will be presented the
third annual Francis Ouimet Award for Lifelong Contributions to
Golf at the Ouimet Scholarship Fund's 50th anniversary celebration.
(Tickets for that event are available. Call 781-891-6400 for
information.) Crenshaw hopes to be able to celebrate a quiet 47th
birthday Monday with his wife and three daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   His return to the professional golf battles has been delayed a
few more weeks, but  &UR; Pat Burke  &LR; can take solace in the fact that a
doctor finally located the source of his pain. Burke finished 79th
on the money list in 1996, then started experiencing hand problems
the next season and watched as his exempt status slipped away. He
was able to play in just one Tour event and four Nike stops last
year, all the while trying to shake off the nagging pain. Then,
just two weeks before the second stage of Tour Qualifying in
November, Burke was told by a doctor that surgery would be needed
to clean out bone spurs in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   Burke, 36, made it through the second stage, securing his Nike
card for 1999, but missed by two shots at the final stage in a bid
to return to the PGA Tour, on which he played from 1992-97.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get a job first, then have the surgery,'' said
Burke, explaining why he put off the operation until Dec. 10. ``I
had been running around in circles for 16 months.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke will play the Nike Tour this year, though he probably
won't enter an event until March. The layoff is frustrating, said
Burke, and while his game may be his rusty, his refreshing humor
and honesty are as sharp as ever. He supports the controversial
plan to form a players association, though he warns against waging
a ``confrontational'' campaign against the PGA Tour, and he
subscribes to the theory (as do a lot of people) that the new World
Golf Championships is not necessarily a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Burke paints a picture that is very real, of the elite players
concentrating on the WGC events (three this year, four per year
beginning in 2000), the four majors, then those tournaments that
are just a notch below the majors, i.e. the TPC, the Colonial, the
Memorial. By then a player would probably have come close to the
minimum of 15 events, and thus be more apt to lean toward worldwide
events with mega-purses (and appearance fees) such as the Loch
Lomond in Scotland, the Holden Classic in Australia, and those in
Japan (Bridgestone, Phoenix Dunlap). All of which leads to the
obvious conclusion: Many traditional Tour stops could face a
shortage of name players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what happened at Pleasant Valley,'' said Burke. ``That
was a tournament for us, for the guys fighting to make a living,
not for the stars. It was like the Tour said, `Thanks for putting
up your own money all those years. Now we're taking the event away
from you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Which is how the organizers in Tucson must feel. A staple on
Tour for 54 years, the Tucson Open (now the Touchstone Energy
Tucson Open) gets second-class treatment in 1999, thrown up against
the first of the WGC events, the Andersen Consulting Match Play
Championship in late February. Tournament organizers still had to
come up with millions for a purse, and for that they get a TV date
with CNBC without any shot at the world's best players.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Casey Martin  &LR; was recently voted winner of the Ben Hogan Award,
given annually by the Golf Writers Association of America to a
golfer who overcomes physical handicaps or illness. A year ago,
Martin was a focal point as he took the PGA Tour to court in an
effort to use a cart in competition. Born with a circulatory
disease in his right leg, Martin cannot walk without great pain,
and the case drew widespread debate, with the PGA Tour taking a
public relations beating. A year later, Martin is back for his
second try on the Nike Tour (he birdied the last hole Friday to
make the cut in this week's season opener, shooting 75-71) and he's
got to be glad that the spotlight has dimmed ... Not a good start
to the Nike campaign for local notables  &UR; Fran Quinn  &LR; of
Northborough (78-70),  &UR; Kevin Johnson  &LR; of Pembroke (74-73), and
 &UR; Jamie Neher  &LR; of Weston (70-80), all of whom missed the cut in
Pompano Beach, Fla. ...  &UR; Rodney Butcher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the State Open winner,
was one champion unable to attend Thursday's MGA event, as he is
playing in the Panama Open ... Forms are available at Ponkapoag GC
in Canton for junior golfers interested in passes for the upcoming
season. Only 250 junior passes will be issued, on a first-come,
first-served basis. Call  &UR; Dave Folan  &LR; at 781-828-4242 for
information ... It was a summer victory with a memorable winter
payoff for a local foursome:  &UR; Jim McDermott  &LR; and  &UR; Sharon McDermott
 &LR; of Watertown, and  &UR; J.D. Smeallie  &LR; and  &UR; William Machen  &LR; of Boston.
They will be teeing it up at Pebble Beach this week in the Cadillac
Invitational National Finals to benefit the National Kidney
Foundation. The group finished first at a regional event in August
at Ledgemont CC in Seekonk.
</P>
</TEXT>
