<HEADER>
A6315 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HITCHCOCK     01-09 1597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-HITCHCOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HITCHCOCK'S HAPPINESS NO MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; EDEN PRAIRIE, Minn. _ Outside, it was snowing, and the
mid-afternoon temperature was zero, give or take a few degrees. The
Vikings' practice field was covered with snow, a small drift here
or there. The replica of the original Vikings' Scandinavian skiff
outside the practice facility was locked in a snowbank, going
nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Too cold.
</P>
<P>
   But inside, the smile on Jimmy Hitchcock's face was wide and
warm. The warmth virtually radiated from the former Patriot, so
happy to be with the 15-1 Vikings ``and to be on a team that really
wants me.'' It was only when Hitchcock thought back to last spring
in New England and talked of the trauma of Draft Day that the chill
could be felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was crushed,'' said Hitchcock of the moment he learned the
Patriots had traded him to Minnesota. ``Anytime you're in a
situation where people say, `We don't want you anymore,' and,
`You're not good enough to be here,' it's a crushing blow. More to
my ego than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Jimmy Hitchcock's ego. Seldom has any ego in professional
football been as battered and bruised as that of Jimmy Hitchcock.
Only if Job himself had played football would any individual
seemingly be tested as much as Hitchcock was tested.
</P>
<P>
   First, Bill Parcells rode him relentlessly; then opposing
quarterbacks seemingly threw every pass toward the right side of
the Patriots' defense, Hitchcock's side; next Parcells benched
Hitchcock, virtually giving up on the young cornerback, not even
letting him feel he had been part of the team in the moments before
the Super Bowl game against Green Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that was hard on me,'' said Hitchcock. ``But it just made
me stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock survived when Parcells gave up on him, but soon Bobby
Grier gave up on him, too, taking Chris Canty as New England's
first pick in 1997 to replace Hitchcock. Hitchcock survived that,
also. But last April, Grier gave up on Hitchcock a second time, and
Pete Carroll concurred. After seeing Tebucky Jones in drills, Grier
and Carroll decidedthat Hitchcock could go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know how I found out about it?'' asked Hitchcock. ``The
media. I found out about it over the television. That's how I found
out I'd been traded. Pete Carroll never told me to my face.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Hitchcock, Carroll told him, ``There's no way I'll
trade you,'' and, ``There's no way I'd let you go, because you're a
coachable guy and you had a good year. Why would I let you go?
You're a coach-able guy and you do what I ask you to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll, said Hitchcock, didn't keep his word.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it that it came to me that way,'' said Hitchcock. ``I
wish he had told me the truth. Like Coach Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know me and Coach Parcells had problems, but Coach Parcells
told me the truth. And when I found out on Draft Day I'd been
traded over the television, I began to have more respect for Coach
Parcells. At least he told me the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hitchcock trade seemed odd, no matter how promising Jones
had been in his workouts before the draft. The Patriots' defense
was strong and cohesive at the end of the 1997 season, and
Hitchcock was getting better and better each year. Clearly, Canty
was much more of a liability than Hitchcock, but Canty had a
protective shield around him: He was the first choice after the
Parcells-Bob Kraft divorce the previous year; so Canty had to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots fans know the result of that thinking. Hitchcock's old
corner position was a sore spot all season, as Canty was not up to
the job and Steve Israel was not healthy enough to play until late
October. Jones, the promising rookie, was relegated to special
teams for much of the season. The reverberations from Hitchcock's
departure were felt all the way down to the Patriots' nickel and
dime pass defenses, which were abysmal on third downs. The talent
had been thinned by Hitchcock's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I followed them closely because those guys there are my
friends, and my heart was there to see how they would do,'' said
Hitchcock. ``I always wanted the guys to do well, but you kind of
want the organization not to do well. It was kind of a love-hate
thing, but I followed them closely. I just kept thinking that,
well, maybe I could have been a positive factor. Maybe the seven
interceptions I had (with the Vikings) and the three touchdowns (on
returns), maybe they would have helped them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock talked regularly with New England receiver Troy Brown,
a close friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be talking to Troy about his injury and about how things
were going on the team, and I knew they were going to struggle,''
said Hitchcock. ``Giving up Curtis Martin, myself, and Sam Gash,
and Keith Byars going ... these guys were the heart of the team,
the soul of the team. Not only could these guys play, but the moral
conviction they brought and the role models they were ... you can't
lose that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock and Martin were close.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curtis had such an effect on me,'' said Hitchcock of the
intangibles that sometimes meld a football team. ``Every day I'd
see Curtis go home right after practice and I'd see that and I'd
say, `Maybe I should go home.' You know what I'm saying. That's
very, very, very important to have that on a team. We have that on
this team with leaders such as Cris (Carter), but the Patriots had
that, too. And they let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock observed other things about the Patriots' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know why (safety) Willie Clay slipped this year?'' said
Hitchcock. ``It was because he had to help out and look out for the
guys they had at corner and he couldn't just do his job. Really,
the Patriots lost two guys from the (defensive backfield) when they
let me go _ me and Willie Clay.''
</P>
<P>
   The wounds are still open even though Hitchcock is far from New
England. The Vikings just may be the best team in football,
Hitchcock has had a superlative year, and coach Dennis Green
``wants me on the team,'' said Hitchcock. ``That's a great feeling,
to be wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Lord put me all through that for a reason, and now
I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock smiled warmly enough to melt the ice in Minnesota in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the call
</P>
<P>
   Both the Jets and Vikings had bye weeks for the first round, and
so it was natural that Hitchcock and Martin would be together.
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock chuckled at the memory of his trip to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now Curtis is The Man in New York,'' he said. ``People don't
know this about Curtis, because he doesn't show it publicly, but
Curtis has always wanted to be a superstar. I mean, undercover kind
of like, being Curtis and all. It's tough to do, wanting to be a
superstar and being modest, but Curtis has always wanted that. And
now he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the two pals talked much about the Patriots. They
reminded each other of what they talked about after the Patriots
lost to Pittsburgh in the playoffs a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We remembered how we'd speculated about what was going to
happen,'' said Hitchcock. ``Curtis said, `I wonder if Bill comes to
get me; I'd love to play for Bill. And I'd love to go down there to
New York City and that'd be a great thing.' And I was like, `Man, I
don't even know what my situation is going to be.' I said,
`Hopefully, things will work out where I can come back and be
productive.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Hitchcock went on, ``Curtis got picked up by Bill and I
was kind of left out in limbo and Curtis and me'd be talking a lot
then. And I said to him, `Curtis, let's pray to God that I'm out of
here, because the best thing for me would be to go where I'm
wanted. They don't want me in New England and I can tell.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock talked of how he knew from the exhibition game in
Foxborough when the Vikings shut out the Patriots that his new team
was very good and his old team was slipping.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what that game in Foxborough reminded me of?'' he
said. ``Remember the time in our Super Bowl year when we went down
to Dallas for an exhibition game and we killed the Cowboys?
Something like 34-14? And I remember walking off the field and
(Parcells) was saying, `Either we're very good or the Cowboys are
on the downslide.' Well, both were true. And that's exactly what I
was thinking when I walked off the field in Foxborough when we beat
the Patriots: `Man, we're good and maybe they're not so good
anymore.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock talked of his Vikings, of how their defense receives
little attention because the offense scores so many points, ``but
we're good. And we're going to show it in these playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked of going against Randy Moss each day in practice, and
he marveled at Minnesota's rookie receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you,'' said Hitchcock, ``Moss is the best receiver
I've ever seen, maybe the best ever. In a lot of ways, Terry Glenn
has a lot of talent like Randy does, but you want to know the
difference? Randy just loves the game; he just loves to play
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock was prodded into saying what is deep in his thoughts
as his team prepares to take on Arizona this afternoon. His dream,
he acknowledges, is to get back to the Super Bowl, this time with a
uniform on, this time ``playing for a coach who wants me'' and this
time making the plays that will beat the other team.
</P>
<P>
   For the true poetry of justice, the ``other team,'' of course,
would be the New York Jets. Coached by Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   One of many supposedly wise football people who were wrong about
Jimmy Hitchcock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
