<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-09 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6317 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-     01-09 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIDELINE VIEWS OF THE GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL McDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A look at Sunday's playoff games, through the eyes of experts.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville at New York, as assessed by Joe Pendry, offensive
coordinator of the Buffalo Bills: ``The Jets do a wonderful job
every week getting their players in position to make plays, on both
offense and defense. Jacksonville will want to run Fred Taylor and
get the ball to their speed on the outside, (Jimmy) Smith and
(Keenan) McCardell. The Jets know this and will come with three or
four defensive packages, and all of them will be designed not to
give up the big play. The Jets' defense is just not going to give
you the big play. They always have that covered on the pass or run.
They do a good job getting their safe-tyman into position to take
away the deep ball, and protecting their corners, and coming up to
play the run. Jacksonville likes to move their defensive players
around, shift just before the snap of the ball, give you a lot of
defensive looks, trying to create confusion. They blitz more than
the Jets, and they play a lot of zone dogs against both the run and
the pass. Jacksonville has sound schemes on both sides of the ball.
All coaches are copycats, and these are two teams I look at a lot
to see what they are doing, because they come up with so many good
ideas. When we played in New York this year, the noise was very
difficult to handle. And I think that Jets crowd will be even more
pumped up because this is a playoff game, and give the Jets a big
edge. Jacksonville must do a good job with the snap count, getting
off on the right count and not playing back on their heels because
they are not sure of the count.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona at Minnesota, assessed by Cowboys head coach Chan
Gailey: ``We played Minnesota, scored 36 points, Troy (Aikman)
threw for over 400 yards, and we still got beat. The Vikings have
tremendous firepower on offense, the best in the league. Look at
the way they can score points. They've got great weapons, but what
they do starts with the offensive line. They are probably the best
in the league. They've got a bunch of No. 1s in that group. Then
you've got (Randall) Cunningham having a great year; (Randy) Moss,
(Cris) Carter, (Jake) Reed coming back, Robert Smith, (Leroy)
Hoard, and a good tight end (Andrew Glover). We tried all kinds of
different things on defense to slow them down and we couldn't.
Randy Moss had three big plays for touchdowns against us. That will
be an interesting matchup, Moss against Aeneas Williams. That will
be a real good one, but Williams is giving up 4 or 5 inches in
height. How good Arizona does will depend on Jake (Plummer). When
he is up, they play good. When he is down, they don't. He's a
big-play maker, and he'll have to be in this game. I think
Arizona's big hope is to keep it close, and then let Jake win it at
the end like he has done in so many games this year. It's going to
be hard to beat Minnesota up there with that team, the crowd noise,
playing in a dome.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Giunta, defensive coordinator of the St. Louis Rams (who
is from Salem via St. John's Prep, by the way), on the
Minnesota-Arizona matchup: ``The best way to stop the Vikings'
offense is with your own offense. Arizona must control the clock
and move the ball. Time of possession is critical. You want to hold
the ball as long as you can because they are so explosive. Adrian
Murrell must have a good day running, and I think you will see Jake
Plummer bootleg a lot and try to run for some first downs. I was
with Randall for four years in Philadelphia. He is much more mature
now as a quarterback. You can see he is really focused on what he
is doing. In Philly, he seemed to be distracted. He is more patient
than ever. In our game, the score was 31-31 late in the game, and
we blitzed Todd Lyght off the corner. He came clean. Randall saw
him coming and still held the ball. Todd splattered him. But
Randall threw it for a touchdown to Cris Carter. In his Philly days
that would not have happened. He'd have seen Todd coming and
started to run himself to make a play. He's playing great football
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kuharich, general manager of the New Orleans Saints,
seconds what Giunta had to offer: ``Clearly, you have to keep the
Minnesota offense off the field. They can score from any place on
the field at any time on any play with a bunch of different guys.
With all of their great offensive weapons, they spread you out,
create mismatches, and go to work on your weakness. We held Moss to
one catch for 6 yards. We shut down the other big guys. So they
beat us by throwing nine completions to Glover, the tight end. We
had to cover him with a linebacker in our scheme, so they kept on
throwing to him in the seams and he made the catches. But we kept
them from the big play, and that kept us in the game. It was 24-24
with six minutes to play. If Arizona is to win, they have to do it
with great special teams play and a big day running from Murrell.
The Vikings are not that great against the run. That's how Tampa
beat them, running for 240 yards. Arizona will have to be patient
and slow down the pace of the game. They should try to limit the
number of chances Minnesota's offense gets with the ball in the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   I asked one NFL playoff coach what the chances were of a game
official making a call in favor of the visiting team in a crucial
situation late in the game. ``Five percent,'' he said. ``I'd say
it's 95-5 in favor of the home team if it's a call that could go
either way.'' I think that's high; 1 percent of officials might
have the courage to face 80,000 screaming fans and make the call
for the visitors, and I think that is the No. 1 reason to bring
back instant replay. Replay would overturn the calls that on-field
officials do not want to make. Let's take a look at some of the
most controversial calls this season.
</P>
<P>
   In the Buffalo-at-New England game, two calls go in favor of the
Patriots on their home field in the closing seconds to give them a
victory. The loss costs Buffalo home-field advantage in playoffs.
In the first round, Buffalo goes to Miami, where three critical
calls in the fourth period go against the Bills, including a
15-yard penalty at the Miami 1, which results in Andre Reed being
thrown out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seattle-at-New York game, Vinny Testaverde's quarterback
sneak comes up short of the goal line, but officials give the home
team the call, and the win helps the Jets to the AFC East title.
The loss knocks Seattle out of the playoff picture, and probably
costs Dennis Erickson his job.
</P>
<P>
   In the Green Bay-at-San Francisco playoff game, Jerry Rice
fumbles in the final minute, but officials give the ball back to
San Francisco, which wins with three seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the season, the NFL office apologized for officials
making two calls that cost the Colts a victory in San Francisco.
Again, the home team got the edge. Remember the coin toss in
Detroit on Thanksgiving? The Steelers get robbed. The Lions got the
ball in overtime, and won on a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Something has to be done. Replay certainly could help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
