<HEADER>
A6319 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-VIKINGS-CARDINALS     01-09 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-VIKINGS-CARDINALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLUMMER NEEDS HELPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The thermometer had plummeted to 17 degrees below
zero on the day the Arizona Cardinals arrived from the desert. Yet
it was the Minnesota heat the Cardinals most feared _ the heat from
the NFL's best offense.
</P>
<P>
   The refreshing, resurgent, and upstart Cardinals will meet the
15-1 Vikings this afternoon in an NFC semifinal at the Metrodome
(always 72 degrees, no matter the wind chill outside).
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Vikings are monstrous favorites, this game still
should be a treat _ at least for a while _ for true football fans,
because of the Flutiesque quarterback of the Cardinals, Jake
Plummer, who in only his second season has moved toward earning
that rare distinction for NFL QBs _ ``winner'' _ and because of the
spunk of the Cardinals, who are 7-1 this season in games decided by
3 points or fewer, the best such record in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   And the Vikings, of course, feature the terrifying threat of
three exceptional wide receivers, Cris Carter, Jake Reed, and Randy
Moss.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the game will not be a treat for one individual _ Dave
McGinnis, the defensive coordinator of the Cardinals. Even before
drafting Moss, the brilliant rookie, Minnesota generally was
regarded as having the best pair of wide receivers in the league.
With Moss, the Vikings might have the most dangerous passing game
in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of Randy made such a difference,'' said Carter,
the wise and talented leader of the Vikings' offense. ``In the last
few years, we had gotten to the point where we wanted to do some
things on offense but we couldn't do them. But Randy is such a
phenomenal player that he gives us the option of doing a lot of
things that we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The result is that ``we want to score points,'' said Carter,
``and we know we're going to score them.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden of stopping this awesome scoring machine will be on
McGinnis and, to a point, Aeneas Williams, the superb cornerback of
the Cardinals. But even on his best days, Williams has been known
to cover only one receiver, not three.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aeneas is kind of unorthodox,'' said Carter. ``Aeneas is very
different from any other DB that you see. By that, I mean he
changes what he's going to do more than anyone else. And if he gets
an opportunity, he's going to try and make a play (i.e. an
interception).''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of cornerbacks are just satisfied with coverage, just
making sure they cover their guy,'' said Carter. ``But Aeneas is
one of four or five in the league who want to cover but they also
want to make plays. Deion (Sanders) is the best at that, but Aeneas
is in that group, too. If he sees a chance for an interception, he
wants to go for that play.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter isn't concerned that Williams shut down Dallas's Michael
Irvin last week in Arizona's upset of the Cowboys in a wild-card
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's because Aeneas is used to playing Michael because they
see each other two games a year, and he kind of knows Michael, and
he's looked at a lot of film,'' said Carter. ``I could see that
Aeneas could read Michael's routes and he could jump Michael's
routes.''
</P>
<P>
   But, promised Carter, Williams and McGinnis aren't going to see
any such similar concentration of passing Sunday. The Vikings will
spread the ball around, he said, ``and we're not going to throw to
one side more than the other. We're going to test Aeneas, we're
going to test the other side, we're going to test the safeties.
That's what we do anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the field, the Cardinals also have a fine
pair of receivers, Rob Moore and Frank Sanders. Moore, the former
Jet, is a true professional and, said Vikings cornerback Jimmy
Hitchcock, ``He's a different kind of receiver. He's tall and lanky
and has decent speed. He's not physical like Cris, but he goes up
and gets balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona surely will not be able to beat the Vikings in any
shootout. The Cardinals' defense, even with lineman Eric Swann out
with an injury, has been impressive the last three weeks _ but it
faced the Cowboys, Chargers, and Saints, a far cry from these
Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   In so many ways, Arizona's chances of staying close to the
Vikings will depend on its defense, but also on Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have a quarterback who can win a game that's seemingly
lost,'' said Arizona coach Vince Tobin. ``He gives us that
intangible, and that's comforting to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   But Plummer doesn't play defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
