<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-IOCPERKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW IOC WON'T BE AS PERKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether or not any of the Lords of the Rings gets booted out of
the brotherhood for vote-peddling (and word is that eight or more
could be expelled), it's all but certain that none of them except
for the International Olympic Committee's 11-member executive
committee will get to choose future sites.
</P>
<P>
   That's the big change that IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch
has indicated will come in the wake of the Salt Lake City payoff
scandal. Having all 115 members vote is what created the lavish
junketeering culture, with bid cities treating the Lords to free
first-class plane trips, luxury hotel suites, gourmet meals,
expensive gifts, and shopping sprees. Not to mention reported cash
payoffs of up to $70,000.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, the IOC already has an evaluation commission that
visits each city and provides a detailed technical report on
everything from sports facilities to hotels. So there's no reason
why the executive committee would need much more than a cursory
group visit to make up its mind.
</P>
<P>
   It may be too late to make the change, though, before the 2006
Winter Games are awarded in June, since the IOC would have to
reform the voting procedure on the same weekend that it would be
choosing the site.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The IOC turned a quick thumbs-down on the US Olympic Committee's
request that the 1976 medley relay swimmers be given ``appropriate
medal recognition'' now that one of the East German victors was
proven to be doped before the Montreal Games. Since nobody tested
positive at the competition, the IOC decided it had no grounds to
change the results. ``There is no legal basis to withdraw the
medals or present medals to other athletes,'' said IOC director
general  &UR; Francois Carrard &LR; . ``Unfortunately, there are too many
variables to attempt to redraw Olympic history.'' If the East
Germans want to give their medals to the Americans or donate them
to the IOC museum, the Lords say, that's up to them.  &UR; Shirley
Babashoff &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who might well have had five gold medals at Montreal
if the DDR madchen hadn't been doped, expected no consolation
prizes. ``(The IOC) doesn't care,'' she told the Orange County
Register. ``Why would they care? It's like putting mud in their
faces. They didn't catch it in time. If something would have
happened sooner ... But it's been, what, 20 years?'' The USOC has
promised to do something for the Americans, even if it's a makeup
medal at a banquet ... Lost in the uproar over the Salt Lake
scandal was a charge by IOC member (and eternal international ski
federation president)  &UR; Marc Hodler  &LR; of Switzerland that Fiat bribed
voters with free vans to make sure that the Italian resort of
Sestriere got the 1997 World Alpine Championships. Since Turin
(where Fiat is based) is vying with the Swiss resort of Sion for
the 2006 Winter Games, the Italians accused Hodler of trying to
sabotage their bid. ``A low blow to Turin 2006,'' charged La
Gazzetta dello Sport. ``The most vile accusations.'' ... Beijing
and Toronto are the front-runners in a crowded field for the 2008
Summer Games, which won't even be awarded for another two years.
The Chinese figure it's their turn since the Games haven't been
held in Asia since 1988. That's why Osaka (Japan) and Kuala Lumpur
(Malaysia) jumped in. Also in the mix are Paris, Istanbul, Buenos
Aires, Seville, and possibly Cairo. No US city is bidding, since
Atlanta was host in 1996 and Salt Lake will in 2002, but eight are
in the chase for 2012.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Startling results at last week's Russian figure skating
championships. World champion  &UR; Alexei Yagudin  &LR; was knocked off by
16-year-old  &UR; Yevgeny Plushenko  &LR; in the men's event and world
runner-up  &UR; Irina Slutskaya  &LR; finished fourth among the women. If she
were an American, Slutskaya probably would miss out on the world
team. But the Russians, who don't have to worry about due process,
might well dump  &UR; Viktoria Volchkova  &LR; and send Slutskaya, a two-time
medalist, anyway ... Why did  &UR; Elvis Stojko  &LR; ask for a medical
release for an event (the Grand Prix final) that's still two months
off? Because his schedule is so brutal that Stojko knows he'll risk
reinjuring his cranky groin if he pushes it. As it is, the former
world champ has the Canadian nationals at month's end, then the
Four Continents competition in late February and the world
championships in late March, just two weeks after the GP final ...
Texas running back  &UR; Ricky Williams  &LR; could become the third man in
six years to win both the Heisman Trophy and the AAU's Sullivan
Award as the nation's top amateur athlete.  &UR; Peyton Manning  &LR; hit the
double last year, as  &UR; Charlie Ward  &LR; did in 1993. Other finalists
include Kentucky quarterback  &UR; Tim Couch &LR; , &UR;  &LR; basketball players
 &UR; Elton Brand  &LR; (Duke) and  &UR; Chamique Holdsclaw  &LR; (Tennessee), hurdler
 &UR; Angelo Taylor &LR; , &UR;  &LR; baseball player  &UR; Pat Burrell  &LR; (Miami), golfers
 &UR; Matt Kuchar  &LR; and  &UR; Jenny Chuasiriporn &LR; , &UR;  &LR; diver  &UR; Mark
Ruiz &LR; , &UR;  &LR; gymnast  &UR; Kristen Maloney &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and wrestler  &UR; Sammie Henson &LR; 
... Skiers  &UR; Picabo Street  &LR; and  &UR; Jonny Moseley  &LR; are the first
athletes from the same sport to win the USOC's Sportsman and
Sportswoman of the Year award since speedskaters  &UR; Dan Jansen  &LR; and
 &UR; Bonnie Blair  &LR; did it in 1994. Street is one of only five women to
win it twice, and the first since Blair.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Olympic ski champions have been dropping like flies since
Nagano. Street (broken leg/blown knee), Germany's  &UR; Katja Seizinger
 &LR; (fractured shin/knee ligaments), and France's  &UR; Jean-Luc Cretier
 &LR; (torn ACL) all are down for the season, and Seizinger and Cretier
may retire ... Disappointing placement for the US junior ice hockey
team, which finished eighth at the world championships after
winning silver two years ago. Though the Yanks won their final
three games, stunning the host Canadians, 5-2, they were already
dead meat after dropping their first three. Star of the squad was
BC sophomore  &UR; Brian Gionta &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who scored six goals. The Russians
beat Canada in overtime to claim their 10th title in 23 years ...
Three-way wrangle among the IOC and the international federations
for soccer and track and field. When FIFA said it was considering
holding biennial World Cups in odd-numbered years, which would
conflict with the IAAF world outdoor championships, the IAAF said
it might shift to even-numbered years and make the Olympic
track-and-field competition an under-23 event, which soccer does.
Nobody expects that to happen, but it was a warning shot put across
a couple of bows ... Even if drug labs come up with reliable tests
for banned human growth hormones and erythropoietin by 2000, it's
unlikely that they'll be used at the Sydney Games. The tests
probably would involve blood instead of urine and since that's more
invasive and controversial, the IOC won't use them unless they are
100 percent accurate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
