<HEADLINE>
GETTING ON BOARD AS JETS TAKE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ New England sports fans are taught to hate all
things New York. As children, we learn to loathe pinstripes and all
forms of Yankees, Knicks, and Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   In our dozens of local colleges and universities, young adults
from New England and New York spend countless hours arguing and
hazing one another. It usually starts with something like ``Yankees
(expletive),'' which solicits the clever retort of ``Red Sox
(expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   This is why it is so hard to come to you this morning with the
suggestion that you root for the New York Jets for the rest of this
NFL playoff season.
</P>
<P>
   Give it up, Patriots fans. Your season is over. Much as it
hurts, you might as well start rooting for the Jets. Maybe they'll
remind you of jambalaya and the magic Patriot ride of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets actually look a lot like the Patriot team that went to
the Super Bowl two years ago. They have Bill Parcells, Al Groh,
Bill Belichick, Curtis Martin, and Dave Meggett. Like the Patriots
of '96, they won the AFC East and got a first-round playoff bye.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets Sunday play Jacksonville in their first home playoff
game in 12 years. When the '96 Patriots met Pittsburgh, it was New
England's first home playoff game in 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   There's a feeling in New York that is remarkably similar to the
good atmosphere that permeated New England two years ago. Parcells
has a heady mix of old and young guys, peaking at the end of the
year, yet is not quite sure what to expect when the playoffs start.
There haven't been many big Jet games in recent years, just as
there weren't many important Patriot games in the years before
Parcells rescued the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Like the pre-Tuna Patriots, the Jets were an NFL joke for years.
But now they are favored to play in the AFC Championship Game next
week. With a little luck, they could make it all the way to the
Super Bowl. Just like You Know Who two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Jet locker room is sprinkled with ex-Patriots who made the
ride to New Orleans including Martin, Meggett, Keith Byars, Corwin
Brown, Otis Smith, Mike Gisler, and Ray Lucas. Jerome Henderson
also played for Parcells with the Patriots in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The coaching staff is even more familiar. Belichick was
Parcells's assistant head coach for Super Bowl XXXI. Groh, Maurice
Carthon, Romeo Crennel, Mike Sweatman, and Charlie Weis also worked
with Parcells in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuna was in his glory this past week. In '96 he talked about
how much he liked his team. It's the same here now. He's reached
the comfort stage where he even teases some of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   Reminded that rookie offensive tackle Jason Fabini was heavily
penalized early in the season, Parcells said, ``We were calling him
`False-Start Fabini.''' In contrast, guard Todd Burger was not
penalized once all year, which prompted the Tuna to say, ``We tell
him, `Maybe you can't get close enough to hold 'em.'''
</P>
<P>
   He said that cornerback Aaron Glenn, who missed the last three
games with a sprained ankle, won't start. In typical Tuna fashion,
Parcells quipped, ``I don't want anyone playing this game that's
got a built-in excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmm. The Tuna sounded like he was talking about Terry Glenn's
sister.
</P>
<P>
   He said this Jet team reminds him of the '94 Patriot team that
put New England in the playoffs for the first time in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to win seven games in a row to get in,'' he remembered.
``We were 3-6 and down, 20-0 (to Minnesota). So the prospects
weren't very good. The similarity is, the confidence level of that
team, I think, is similar to the confidence level of this team.
They had been in a pressure game every week, so they'd been under
the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with this team, the Miami and Buffalo games
back-to-back on the road were like playoff games for us. Both teams
were ready, both crowds hostile, both national games against tough
division rivals.''
</P>
<P>
   And now he's back in the playoffs. Just like with the Patriots
in '96.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled and said, ``If you don't have a little excitement
about this, you're in the wrong game.''
</P>
<P>
   So go ahead and root for the Jets, you New England football
fans. Maybe it will remind you of the good old days from two years
ago. It's no big deal, really _ especially when you remember that
someday soon you'll be asked to support a team that plays home
games in Hartford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
