<HEADER>
A6330 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-1S     01-09 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NINERS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS TOP 49ERS, GAIN NFC FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS throughout to ADD quotes, recast.) 
 (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A spin, a twist, changed the entire complexion of the
playoff clash between San Francisco and Atlanta in the Georgia Dome
on Saturday. It was a 7-yard run and a spinning move by running
back Garrison Hearst on the game's first play from scrimmage that
made the 49ers play the rest of the game looking backward. Hearst
broke the fibula in his left leg on the play.
</P>
<P>
   A spin, a twist, that tossed the 49ers for a loop.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, though, played this game full throttle. Smashing faces.
Pulverizing bodies. It was a punishing defense and a rugged,
run-oriented offense _ Falcons staples this season _ that Atlanta
used once again to make its mark. This one is lasting. The Falcons
beat San Francisco, 20-18, before 70,262 fans and improved to 15-2.
Atlanta moves on to the National Football Conference championship
game for the first time next Sunday, where it will play the winner
of Sunday's Arizona-Minnesota game.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta won by intercepting Steve Young three times, by
committing fewer penalties and by winning in possession time. It
won with staying power and resolve, withstanding a late Young rally
and then the 49ers' last-gasp drive for another miracle finish.
Atlanta won with speed and youth and veteran leadership, with a
solid game plan that played to its strengths of power and quickness
and intelligence. It won with the emotional return of its head
coach, Dan Reeves, from heart surgery. It won with nifty
special-teams play. It advanced because it enjoyed superb success
in strategy and in execution.
</P>
<P>
   But the critical factor was the running game. Atlanta produced
one. San Francisco could not.
</P>
<P>
   After Hearst went down, San Francisco ran the ball 19 times. No
49ers back had a run longer than Hearst's seven yards. Then
Hearst's backup, Terry Kirby, bruised his leg. That hurt the 49ers,
too. The 49ers averaged 2.3 yards a carry and finished with only 46
rushing yards. Young threw the ball 37 times.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta featured Jamal Anderson, a bruising back who crushed the
49ers. He scored on runs of two and 34 yards that put Atlanta
ahead, 14-0, with 3 minutes 12 seconds left before halftime. He
finished with 113 rushing yards; the Falcons totaled 136 and
averaged 4.1 yards a carry. Atlanta ran the ball 33 times and
passed it only 19.
</P>
<P>
   No Hearst, a Pro Bowl back.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of Anderson, a Pro Bowl back.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides could deduce the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``My running game took a couple of hits,'' 49ers Coach Steve
Mariucci said. ``A lot of responsibility was placed on Steve
Young's shoulders and our passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco cornerback Marquez Pope said: ``It changed the way
the whole offense was going to flow. We got down, 14-0, and,
coupled with that, it really changed the offense. We knew coming in
that Anderson was going to be a key, too. We did not want him to be
in control like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan cringed when he saw Hearst's leg
twist and then break.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot, I grabbed my leg and my ankle,'' Buchanan said. ``It
looked that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Falcons linebacker Jessie Tuggle said: ``When Hearst went down,
it changed the game a lot because though they have capable backups,
Hearst is their man in the running game. Their main man.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco, nonetheless, fought back.
</P>
<P>
   It scored 10 points in the final 3:12 of the first half, a
touchdown on a Young-to-Jerry Rice throw of 17 yards and a Wade
Richey field goal as time expired. Atlanta led, 14-10, at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' first-half touchdown drive featured a bizarre lateral
by Young to Kirby that Atlanta thought it had scooped up and
returned for a touchdown. The officials ruled, however, that Kirby
had recovered the ball and was down by contact before it became
loose again. Following their touchdown, the 49ers quickly gained an
interception that set up Richey's field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in and our guys looked kind of puzzled,'' Atlanta
receiver Terance Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler (13 of 19 for 169 yards with
one interception and eight passes for first downs) said: ``Terance
kept telling us it wasn't going to be easy. He told as at halftime.
He told us all during the second half. He kept pushing everybody to
stay focused. It made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis said: ``I realized that we were playing that team for the
third time and they are the San Francisco 49ers. They have come in
here in games past and embarrassed us. I kept telling our guys to
expect them to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuggle remembered this about the 49ers: ``There was one game
here a few years ago when they scored more than 50 points on us.
There was a game where I think they got 24 points in one quarter.
Steve Young said after that game that he felt like he was in a
practice session. That hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   So, Atlanta stuck together.
</P>
<P>
   It intercepted Young with 4:44 left in the third quarter, with
safety Eugene Robinson returning the pass meant for receiver J.J.
Stokes 77 yards to the San Francisco 20. That set up Morten
Anderson's 29-yard field goal with 1:16 left for the only points in
the third quarter. ``I read the route,'' Robinson said of his
leaping grab near the Atlanta goal line.
</P>
<P>
   On the 49ers' next drive early in the fourth quarter, safety
William White intercepted a Young pass meant for tight end Greg
Clark and returned it 14 yards to the San Francisco 36. Another
Anderson field goal followed, from 32 yards, and the Falcons led,
20-10, with 10:33 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first one,'' Young said, ``J.J. beat his man so badly off
the ball that I was going to give it to him right away, so I threw
it and he kept going into his route and the defender came over and
took it. On the second one, I assumed that Greg Clark was going to
break off of the linebacker, but he read it differently. It is my
fault that it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Young (23 of 37 for 289 yards) then drove the 49ers 87 yards in
13 plays in 7:36, running eight yards for the score, and after a
two-point conversion, it was suddenly a 20-18 game with 2:57 left.
Plenty of time for another rally by Young and the 49ers, who got to
this game by defeating Green Bay on the last play of last Sunday's
wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
   This time the rally didn't happen. The 49ers got the ball back
for one last-ditch try on a drive that started at their four with
38 seconds left. The game ended on another White interception, on a
desperation toss from the San Francisco 26 that was swiped at the
Atlanta 35.
</P>
<P>
   A spin, a twist, of fate and fortune. Reeves _ who coached on
the sideline for the entire game _ knows plenty about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made all of the difference in the world playing at home,
getting that home-field advantage; I'm convinced that's a big
reason why we won this game,'' Reeves said. ``You preach and teach,
and these guys listened and accomplished this. This group
collectively is as good as I've been around. They sacrifice to win.
They respond. This is such a fragile business; you never know. But
with this group of guys, I'll take my chances.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, 49ers defensive end Chris Doleman announced his
retirement after 14 seasons with Minnesota, Atlanta and San
Francisco. He had 15 sacks this season, the second-highest total of
his career, and is fourth in career sacks with 142{.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
