<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLANDERS-POTVIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY TRADING BERARD FOR POTVIN, ISLANDERS GO ON DEFENSIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also HKN-ISLANDERS) 
(nk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In order to implement their new philosophy _ defensive
practicality over offensive flair _ the Islanders had to make some
personnel changes. They started Saturday, acquiring discontented
goalie Felix Potvin from the Toronto Maple Leafs for offensive
defenseman Bryan Berard.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin, 27, who left the Maple Leafs without permission on Dec.
2 and demanded a trade, joined the Islanders for Saturday night's
game in Montreal. He was the back-up goalie to Marcel Cousineau,
who started instead of Tommy Salo, whom Potvin is expected to
replace eventually. At the request of Mike Milbury, the Islanders'
coach and general manager, Salo remained at the team hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin, who was 160-149-49 with a 2.87 goals against average and
12 shutouts in seven seasons with the Maple Leafs, led Toronto to
the Campbell Conference finals in 1993. He became a reserve this
season after the Leafs signed free agent Curtis Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   ``Felix Potvin's experience at this level is a little bit
deeper,'' said Milbury, who indicated that he and the Maple Leafs
had worked out the trade before Christmas. The trade was put on
hold when Berard suffered a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin told television reporters in Montreal, ``I'm real happy,
it's a relief to finally be able to wear another uniform and I'm
really looking forward to playing.''
</P>
<P>
   The teams also traded sixth-round draft picks in this year's
entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Berard, who won the Calder Trophy as the National
Hockey League's top rookie just two seasons ago, Milbury said: ``He
is a dynamic young player. I'm concerned that he'll make me look a
bit foolish in a run-and-gun offense like Toronto's. But I can't
worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, 0-5-1 in their last six games, entered Saturday
night's game tied for 12th in the 14-team Eastern Conference, and
it was clear that changes were coming. Salo, who may be dealt
(Edmonton and Nashville are the leading candidates) as early as
Sunday, has been inconsistent again this season. He most recently
missed six games with a broken finger on his stick hand.
</P>
<P>
   Salo has cooled considerably after a hot start. His shaky
performance in a 5-0 loss in Philadelphia last Thursday may have
forced Saturday's trade. The Islanders were 22nd in the NHL in
goals against average and had more scoring chances than their
opponents in 20 of the last 24 games, but had little to show for
it.
</P>
<P>
   Berard, once considered the future of the franchise, had
struggled since winning the Calder Trophy in 1996. After a
disastrous sophomore season, in which his plus-minus rating was a
minus-32, Islanders coaches tried to rein in his puck-rushing
style, but the result appeared to confuse the 21-year-old
defenseman. Unsure of his standing on the team, Berard went to
Milbury last month and asked if he was being offered around the
league. He was told that he wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Berard was leading Islanders defensemen with 15 points this
season, despite missing the last eight games. He is in the final
year of his contract and will be a restricted free agent this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited to go to a team like Toronto with a great
tradition and they are playing great,'' Berard said in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin has one more year on his contract at about $2.7 million,
part of which Toronto will pick up. He likes to stay in the crease,
allowing shooters to see more of the net. But his quickness offsets
his positioning. He is a butterfly goalie, much like his idol,
Patrick Roy of Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The knock on Potvin is that he is susceptible to high shots. He
is also not known for his puck-handling ability.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's deal will probably not be the last the Islanders
make. In addition to the possibilty of trading Salo, most likely
for a forward, the Islanders are thought to be shopping center
Robert Reichel and wing Bryan Smolinski.
</P>
</TEXT>
