   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Jan. 10. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PENSIONS (undated) _ Valley land speculators have borrowed millions
of dollars from government worker pension funds in deals that
involve potentially high risks. An Arizona Republic &UR; review of
public records shows that three retirement funds currently have
more than $88 million invested in real estate ventures. And at
least two of the many loans involve developers who helped wipe out
Arizona thrifts a decade ago when the land market nose-dived. All
told, pension real estate deals account for just 2 percent of a $5
billion pool, and there is no evidence that the retirement plans
are in financial danger. Managers, in fact, boast of the high
return on pension-fund investments. By DENNIS WAGNER. Story will
move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
SENATE _ Nothing can prepare senators for the immense, conflicting
pressures they face in convening the first presidential impeachment
trial of their lifetimes. A combination of all of these powerful
forces that makes this moment almost unique in history and at the
same time so politically volatile. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
KYL-DIARY _ Excerpts from Sen. Jon Kyl's personal diary of the
impeachment trial of President William Jefferson Clinton. The
excepts will appear in The Arizona Republic throughout the trial. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MISSING (Mesa, Ariz.) _ They are perfect strangers. The weeping
middle-age womanwho strolled up to Darien Biggs' front porch,
thrust a 20-pound ham into his hands and promised to pray. The
gentleman who plunked down $20 on a copier's counter to help pay
for fliers. They are just three of the hundreds who are turning out
to help find 11-year-old Mikelle Biggs. And for the missing Mesa
child's terrified family, they have provided a sliver of relief. By
ALEXA HAUSSLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) _ In time it took to say, ``I do,'' the
number of high-profile American politicians who should be
prosecuted for the crime of perjury rose by one hundred. It
happened with members of the U.S. Senate swore under oath to ``do
impartial justice'' in the trial of Bill Clinton. By E.J. MONTINI.
Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.  &QL; 
CHOIR (Phoenix) _ Half a millennium of musical tradition meets 50
years of innovation July 1, when Georg Stangelberger arrives from
the Vienna Boys Choir to become the next artistic director of the
Phoenix Boys Choir. Stangelberger, a Vienna Boys Choir conductor
since 1986 and currently its deputy artistic director, will replace
Harvey Smith, Phoenix Boys Choir artistic director since 1960. By
KEN LAFAVE. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
