<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broncos stampede past Dolphins
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Next to Saturday afternoon's divisional playoff game,
the big event here this weekend was something called the National
Western Stock Show. About six miles from where horses and cattles
cavorted, however, was the real stampede.
</P>
<P>
   Led by former University of Georgia spare part Terrell Davis,
who rushed for 199 yards and two touchdowns, the Denver Broncos ran
roughshod over the Miami Dolphins. Their 38-3 victory, which lifted
the Broncos to next Sunday's AFC Championship Game against the
winner of today's Jacksonville-New York Jets matchup was an
impressive display of power football.
</P>
<P>
   Denver scored on its first three series, driving 92, 66 and 87
yards for touchdowns. On all three possessions, Davis provided the
impetus. Davis was chosen by the Associated Press as the NFL's Most
Valuable Player earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Limited to just 29 yards on 16 carries in the Broncos 31-21
regular-season defeat at Miami on Dec. 21, the four-year pro
punched out 38 yards on Denver's initial possession. The drive was
highlighted by his consecutive runs of 13 and 11 yards and he
completed the march with a 1-yard blast over left guard.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Broncos ran at the left side of the Miami defense
much of the day and their line opened huge gashes in the Dolphins'
injury-decimated front four. By halftime, the Broncos led 21-3 and
Davis already had 16 rushes for 129 yards. On the first snap of the
second half, he roared through a crevice at left guard and sped 62
yards to set up a Jason Elam field goal.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared the Denver offensive staff targeted Dolphins
defensive left tackle Daryl Gardener as a weak link, even though
Miami coaches have insisted he is the team's best interior
defender. Playing without partner Tim Bowens (biceps), Gardener
simply could not anchor the inside. When he wasn't double-teamed,
he was finessed out of position, and that set up cutback runs for
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Denver had 18 offensive snaps in the first half and six of them
produced gains of 11 yards or more.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the efficient Denver offense, the Dolphins were out of
sync most of the day. On the game's opening series, Miami receivers
dropped two Dan Marino passes. Marino then connected on eight
straight passes as the Dolphins went to a no-huddle offense, but
penalties and a running game stuck in reverse killed any momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
