<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOSPEL10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gospel awards show simply stellar
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The mercury may have dipped below freezing but the
roof was being raised inside the Atlanta Civic Center last night as
gospel music honored its elite during the 14th Annual Stellar
Awards show.
</P>
<P>
   The Stellar Awards, gospel music's version of the Grammy Awards,
opened with gospel singer Fred Hammond asking the crowd during a
high-energy opening number if they were ``ready for a blessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammond could have directed that question at himself as he won
eight Stellar awards, more than any other gospel artists Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Hammond, a gospel veteran, was honored with Artist of the Year,
Song of the Year, Male Vocalist of the Year, Album of the Year,
Producer of the Year and Contemporary Album of the Year. He also
received the Contemporary Choir of the Year award for his work with
the Radical for Christ Choir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just praise God,'' Hammond said as he hoisted one of many
awards during the night. ``Don't quit,'' he told the audience
before sitting down.
</P>
<P>
   The show also saw the emergence of Karen Clark Sheard. Sheard, a
fiery gospel singer, was named Female Vocalist of the Year and
Contemporary Female Vocalist of the Year and was honored with best
Music Video of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   As with any awards show, there were some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Mass Choir won Choir of the Year, beating out the
formidable John P. Kee and the New Life Community Choir and the
popular O'Landa Draper &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   The show offstage was just as colorful as the performances on
stage. The crowd of was full of elegant women wearing furs and
pumps and men wearing elegantly tailored _ and in some cases
extremely loud _ suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen so many white suits in my life,'' comedian
Steve Harvey, the show's host, told the audience at one point.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey was just one of many celebrities who attended the show.
Actress Lynn Whitfield, who starred in the film, ``Eve's Bayou,''
the R&AMP;B group Boyz II Men and gospel celebrities such as Bobby
Jones and Dottie Peoples also attended.
</P>
<P>
   The show was marred by several technical glitches. At varying
points, producers stopped the show, leaving the audience mumbling
in their seats as Harvey bantered with the audience.
</P>
<P>
   During one of the pauses, a woman, shouting from the audience,
asked Harvey if he knew Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't, do you think this would be the right time to ask
me?'' Harvey shot back, breaking up the audience.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Bill Campbell, who personally persuaded the producers of
the Stellar Awards to come to Atlanta, greeted the crowd at the
opening of the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's the blues or jazz, it all started with gospel
music,'' Campbell, a gospel music fan, said.
</P>
<P>
   Gospel music's influence on all American music was a theme
repeated during much of the night. In the past few years, gospel
music has exploded, incorporating various music forms such as rap
and R&AMP;B to reach a younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   But many of the gospel fans at Saturday's event were not worried
that gospel music will become too diluted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the roots of gospel music are too firmly planted to be
uprooted,'' said Francine Greer, a gospel music fan who prefers
traditional gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no studio enhancement,'' she said of the old-style
gospel artists. ``They can sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though gospel music may now mimic other types of music, the
message distinguishes it, said Phle' Kilcrease, who listens to
gospel every morning to prepare for her job as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a peace when I listen to it,'' she said. ``It helps me
start the day with something positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
