<HEADER>
A6350 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     01-09 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIVEN CHOICE, MARTIN WOULD STAY A CLIPPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A dandy attribute often associated with NBA
point-guard success is the ability to make wise decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Darrick Martin is talking after Saturday's A-list pickup game at
UCLA's men's gym, sounding like a very intelligent NBA point guard.
And now, even though the former Bruins star apparently has the
wherewithal to work for a more highly regarded organization, Martin
if full-court pressed to make a choice says he'd still prefer to be
a Clipper.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't wink or anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've always been good to me,'' says Martin, who cut his NBA
wisdom teeth as the Clippers' starting playmaker for most of the
last two seasons. ``I'd really like to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, 27, became a free agent after the Clippers finished
losing 65 of last season's 82 games. He averaged 10.3 points and
four assists per game while splitting time with Pooh Richardson. At
5-foot-11, the quick lefty is drawing employment interest around
the league as someone who can reduce a team's time in moving
between points A and B.
</P>
<P>
   But the Clippers, while not dismissing the possibility of
bringing Martin back, freely admit planning an upgrade for the role
of floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to get stronger at the point-guard position,''
Elgin Baylor, the team's vice president of basketball operations,
said soon after the NBA was unlocked.
</P>
<P>
   Stronger, in Clippers terms, may be defined as a point guard who
prevents dribble penetration by opposing point guards. When asked
to list the goodies he's looking for in a point guard, Baylor began
with defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good point guards out there,'' Baylor said,
``but very few point guards who can defend.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be even fewer point guards who would choose to be a
Clipper. This may give Martin an edge.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the smoke clears after the NBA's upcoming talent
safari, the Clippers may not find themselves with what they think
they want at point guard.
</P>
<P>
   All Martin wants is to be wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really so much about money,'' says Martin, who as a
candidate for stepping up to the NBA's middle class should benefit
from the league's new deal with the players' union. ``I just want
to find the best situation. I just want to go where I'm wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't wanted enough to be drafted out of UCLA but worked his
way into the NBA after touring with Magic Johnson's traveling team
and experiencing life in the CBA.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after two seasons with the Clippers, Martin wouldn't mind
staying home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys take more money and end up in a situation they're
not familiar with,'' he says. ``I'm not opposed to doing that, and
sometimes the new situation works out, but I feel comfortable with
the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the talent to build a good team. People seem to be
forgetting that we made the playoffs just two years ago. After you
hear so many Clipper jokes, it was good to put that back in their
faces. I wouldn't mind doing it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
