u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-     01-09 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-DOLPHINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS RUN RAMPANT ON DOLPHINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The ultimate indignity in this game has to be taking
the concession knee with 1:19 left, the ball at your own 20, and
the scoreboard indicating that you are down by 35.
</P>
<P>
   By then it was 38-3, Denver, and the Miami Dolphins had been
humiliated. Terrell Davis had run for 199 yards and three
touchdowns; the Denver defense had toyed with them, and lumbering
defensive end Neil Smith had scooped up a disputed fumble _ this
year, is there any other kind? _ and taken it 79 yards for the
final score. Coach Mike Shanahan had just extended Jimmy Johnson a
professional courtesy by ordering backup quarterback Bubby Brister
to take two knees after Denver had bogged down at the Miami 3, and
so The Hairsprayed One reciprocated by having Dan Marino's backup,
Damon Huard, do the same when the ball changed hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a shame for one of our guys, or one of
their guys, to get hurt, and hurt their chances in the playoffs,''
Johnson explained.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was done. The Denver Broncos had proven every point
necessary. They had demonstrated the meaninglessness of Miami's
31-21 Week 15 victory 19 days earlier. They had shown how much they
appreciated the bye week and extra preparation time. And they had
reminded everyone in the AFC that, as loquacious tight end Shannon
Sharpe would say, ``If you want to go to Miami in late January,
you've got to have a five-hour layover in Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody was going to beat the Broncos Saturday, not least a team
that couldn't scare MIT with its ground game. Davis had 9 more
yards by his third carry (23) than the Dolphins would have all day.
He would also have 5 more yards (34) by his fourth carry than he
had in 16 carries against these same Dolphins back on Dec. 21 in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game didn't mean anything,'' Davis said. ``This was do or
die. And when you have that kind of success early in the game, it
gives you a feel for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Very seldom is it true that a game is over after two
possessions, but this one was. For after the Dolphins had a quick
three-and-out punctuated by a pair of clear dropped passes, the
Broncos put on an offensive clinic, moving 92 yards in 14 plays for
the game's first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   You want balance? Try 41 yards (38 by Davis) on the ground and
51 more (John Elway going 5 for 6) in the air. In one five-play
stretch, the Broncos picked up 8, 7, 13, 11, and 12 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took it in from the 1 to finish off the time-consuming
(7:56) drive.
</P>
<P>
   After a second futile Miami possession, Denver went for the
quick kill. Taking over on his own 34, Elway (a casual, efficient
14 for 23, 189 yards, one TD) got his team into the end zone in
just four plays, the first of which was a dazzling 33-yard hookup
with wide receiver Ed McCaffrey, who put a superb move on safety
Brock Marion before extending himself to make a finger-tip grab.
The capper was a scintillating 20-yard scamper by Davis, who burst
through the line before turning both Marion and rookie loudmouth
Sam Madison into embarrassed DBs before both the 75,729 in
attendance and the millions watching on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is known for what he refers to as his ``north-south''
running style, but Saturday he ran every way but north by
northwest, and had that been required, he could have done that,
too. Suffice it to say we were all looking at a great player having
a great day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just instincts,'' he said of his many phenomenal cuts. ``Today
I took a page out of the Barry Sanders book.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 21-3 at the half and 24-3 early in the third quarter when
a 62-yard Davis romp on the first play from scrimmage set up a
34-yard Jason Elam field goal. The Broncos scored on four of their
first five possessions, the fifth being rendered moot by halftime.
Denver's first punt came 39 minutes into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's only semblance of a scoring threat was a penetration to
the Denver 17 (trailing, 31-3). That's when Oronde Gadsden was
ruled to have fumbled following a fourth-down reception, and
11-year veteran Smith set out on his majestic excursion to the
distant end zone.
</P>
<P>
   In matters like this, it is customary for both coaches and
players to spout the ``total team effort'' cliches as media eyes
roll. But there was no other way to describe this 100 percent
trashing of a Miami team that had absolutely no chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played for 60 minutes,'' said linebacker Bill Romanowski,
one of nine Denver Pro Bowlers. ``Offense, defense, special teams.
We had to prove to the country, and to ourselves, that if we are
focused and ready to play we can beat anyone. And our attitude is
that what we did today won't be good enough to win next week. We
have to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching this, the idea of them getting ``better'' is an
abstract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
