r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN     01-09 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BECK-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LOCKOUT'S WINNERS AND LOSERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (begin ital)``I've been locked out, I've been locked in, but I
always seem to come back again.... I've been locked out, and I know
we're through, but I can't begin to face up to the truth. I wait so
long for the walls to crack, but I know that I will one day have
you back.''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Shaq's rap ballad of NBA lockout despair, as sung to
commissioner David Stern?
</P>
<P>
   Er, no. The lyrics are borrowed, with apologies, from '80s rock
group Crowded House, whose breakup song, ``Locked out,'' tidily
sums up the owners-players love spat as well as anything.
</P>
<P>
   In a lovers' quarrel, the sides reconcile and all is bliss. No
such luck in a greed contest. So without further delay, or further
pop-music reference, the Winners and Losers of the Lockout from
Hell:
</P>
<P>
   Winner: Stern and NBA owners. Not even a close call. The first
league to implement a salary cap just became the first to get an
absolute ceiling on individual player salaries. Add the longer,
five-year rookie deals, the marijuana policy, the pseudo-hard cap
escrow system, the reduction in annual player raises, and the
lockout ended with a knockout.
</P>
<P>
   If Stern had held out another week, the union would have gladly
thrown in Kobe Bryant's shoe contract and a year's supply of Jordan
cologne.
</P>
<P>
   Loser: David Falk. He was demonized as the Evil Genius
Puppetmaster running the union, but that's of no consequence to
Falk. What does matter to him is money, and he lost that too: The
new ceiling on player salaries means the man who represents Allen
Iverson and other young free-agents-to-be will get 5 percent of $9
million a year instead of $25 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Winner: Charities, and we're not talking about the poor
minimum-salaried players who were supposed to receive welfare from
the Showtime game. UNICEF and others made a few hundred grand
(roughly equivalent to Kevin Garnett's pay during the national
anthem) from that game in Atlantic City, while other needy
nonprofits benefited from locked-out player exhibition games in Los
Angeles, Dallas and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Loser: Charles Oakley. The veteran forward, long underpaid by
NBA standards, was to receive a $10 million balloon payment this
season to offset years of substandard salaries. Now he'll get about
$6 million instead (maybe UNICEF can help).
</P>
<P>
   Winner: The Clippers. By not hiring a coach and assistants, they
saved at least $7.35 per game, per coach (not counting per diem).
</P>
<P>
   Loser: The Clippers. OK, let's face it, they squandered months
of spare time that coaches could have used to help plan a
roster-retooling strategy. And 48 hours before the lockout's
resolution, top draft pick Michael Olowakandi signed to play in
Italy _ through Feb. 15. The whole situation is just so... well, so
!ital!Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Winner: Elden Campbell/Nick Van Exel. Van Exel's sentence for
bad behavior, a one-year banishment to Denver, has been cut by 30
games. Campbell got to extend his Lakers career by six months, his
inevitable trade put on hold by the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Loser: Kobe Bryant. Under the old system, Bryant, a free agent
this summer, would expect a Garnett-type contract paying in excess
of $21 million per year. Under the new system, he'll be capped at a
mere $9 million to start with. Lucky for him, he's got a rap album
due out soon to provide some hanging-out cash.
</P>
<P>
   Winner: Shaquille O'Neal. True, the big guy's ``Respect'' CD
didn't get Aretha Franklin-like raves, and he's had to endure such
indignities as an assault accusation at DisneyWorld and _ ack! _
bench-pressing Regis Philbin on national TV. But the long layoff
gave Shaq Daddy plenty of time to rehab the pesky abdominal muscle
that knocked him out of 22 games last season. Now he just needs to
shed a couple of pounds near said abdominal...
</P>
<P>
   Loser: Shawn Kemp. When last seen in Atlantic City, the former
Reign Man had the body of the Maytag Man. Possible explanations:
auditioning for true life story of Fat Albert; starving without a
paycheck, ate Muggsy Bogues and Spud Webb; perhaps carrying his
next seven children himself?
</P>
<P>
   Winner: Latrell Sprewell. Well, he's still a loser in spirit,
but the lockout-related drivel spewed by Alonzo ``we make a lot,
but we spend a lot'' Mourning and other nitwits made Spree looked
almost rational by comparison. And at least everyone forgot about
him for a while.
</P>
<P>
   Loser: Miami Heat locker room. Tim Hardaway and Keith Askins
were vocal critics of teammate Mourning and the union negotiating
committee. And to think, the Heat might still add Sprewell to this
warm-n-fuzzy group. Maybe Bill Parcells can teach 'em ``Kumbaya.''
</P>
<P>
   Dream on: Fans always blame player salaries for unaffordable
ticket prices, and Suns coach Danny Ainge went so far as to say the
NBA's new maximum salary will help. ``They've had to (raise ticket
prices) because of the rising costs, but if they can control
spending it shouldn't hurt the fans, it should help them,'' Ainge
said.
</P>
<P>
   A nice sentiment, but it ignores an American economic truism:
You charge what the market will bear. So we pay $7.50 for the same
movie that cost $5 a few years ago, $150 for a pair Nike Air
Jordans that cost $10 to make in a sweatshop and $30 for a Tommy
Hilfiger T-shirt, even though it's made of the same stuff as Hanes'
$10 Beefy-T.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same in the NBA. Teams will charge you as much as
you'll pay, and if someone keeps buying $50-$200 seats, they're not
going to lower them _ even if the average player salary dropped to
$20 a week. Lower overhead just means owners will pocket the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   Wish for the week: That the NBA's truncated schedule means fewer
Nuggets-Clippers and Warriors-Mavericks games. If you're going to
lop off 30 games, why not kill the ones no one wanted to see in the
first place?
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the week: The new salary limits appear to diminish the
importance of agents, but Atlanta Hawks president Stan Kasten and
agent Keith Glass said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think agents are no longer useful,'' Kasten said,
``but that's not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Glass: ``We're like rats; we adapt.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
