<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CHARGES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POINT AND COUNTERPOINT IN THE IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: In defense section under `accusations,' restores (NU)6, which
had been dropped; This sidebar to IMPEACH-EVIDENCE replaces skedded
graphic) 
 (JT) 
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The articles of impeachment voted by the House made 11 specific
charges against President Clinton, against which his lawyers have
raised specific defenses.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE ACCUSATIONS &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``William Jefferson Clinton willfully provided perjurious, false
and misleading testimony to the grand jury concerning one or more
of the following:''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. Giving a false account of the nature and details of his
relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky;
</P>
<P>
   2. Refusing to admit that he gave prior false testimony in the
Paula Corbin Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit;
</P>
<P>
   3. Allowing his attorney, Robert Bennett, to make false
statements during the president's deposition in the Jones case;
</P>
<P>
   4. Lying to aides about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky in an
effort to influence their grand jury testimony. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE DEFENSE &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's legal defense against these allegations has
been:
</P>
<P>
   1. The president admitted he had an ``inappropriate, intimate''
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky before the grand jury;
</P>
<P>
   2. The president contends that under the very narrow definition
of sexual relations allowed by the judge in the Jones case, he did
not lie.
</P>
<P>
   3. No perjury was involved in the statements made by Bennett at
the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   4. There is no evidence to contradict the president's testimony
regarding comments he made to his aides; about his conversations
with Ms. Lewinsky about gifts or his description of conversations
with Betty Currie. Even Kenneth Starr did not allege perjury in
these statements.
</P>
<P>
   THE ACCUSATIONS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   William Jefferson Clinton ``has prevented, obstructed, and
impeded the administration of justice, and has to that end engaged
personally, and through his subordinates and agents, in a course of
conduct or scheme designed to delay, impede, cover up and conceal
the existence of evidence and testimony related to a federal civil
rights action brought against him.'' The article cites these
particulars:
</P>
<P>
   1. Encouraging Ms. Lewinsky to file a false affidavit in the
Jones case;
</P>
<P>
   2. Encouraging her to give false testimony if she was called to
appear in the Jones case;
</P>
<P>
   3. Encouraging Ms. Lewinsky to conceal gifts he had given her;
</P>
<P>
   4. Helping Ms. Lewinsky secure employment to insure her silence;
</P>
<P>
   5. Allowing Bennett to make false and misleading statements
during the Jones deposition;
</P>
<P>
   6. Attempting to influence the testimony of Betty Currie;
</P>
<P>
   7. Attempting to influence the testimony of aides by giving a
false account of his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   THE DEFENSE
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's legal defense against these allegations has
been:
</P>
<P>
   1. &AMP; 2. Ms. Lewinsky's grand jury testimony that ``No one ever
asked me to lie'' flatly contradicts charges that Clinton
encouraged Ms. Lewinsky to file a false affidavit or give false
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   3. Ms. Lewinsky gave 10 accounts in her testimony of
conversations with Clinton about gifts and did not testify that he
suggested she hide gifts or give them to Ms. Currie.
</P>
<P>
   4. Ms. Lewinsky testified that ``no one ever offered me a job
for my silence.'' Efforts to assist Ms. Lewinsky in finding a job
began months before she appeared on the witness list in the Jones
case.
</P>
<P>
   5. The president was not paying close attention to Bennett's
statements during the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   6. When Clinton spoke to Betty Currie she was not a witness in
any legal proceeding and she testified that she did not feel
pressured by the president.
</P>
<P>
   7. In discussions with his aides, the president was concealing
an improper relationship, not trying to influence future testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: Report of the House Judiciary Committee. Submission by
counsel for President Clinton to the House Judiciary Committee and
summary of arguments against the articles of impeachment prepared
by the president's legal team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-09-99 2310EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
