r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     01-09 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORUM DESERVES PROPER SENDOFF
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ They show up even on the days the old building is
dark, tourists from Albania and Slovenia and Japan with rental cars
and cameras and dazzled expressions, here to view an American
landmark with their own eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum. Just as it appears on TV, only no Jack Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, it's like going to Rome and seeing the
Colosseum or going to New York and seeing Yankee Stadium,'' said
Forum director of guest services Jack Peirson, who might not
believe it himself if he didn't occasionally help out visitors by
snapping photos and leading impromptu tours. ``It's amazing to see
the magic on those people's faces.''
</P>
<P>
   The Forum. To the world's sports fans, it's a legend.
</P>
<P>
   And now, in its final season as a major-league arena, let's hope
we, the sports fans of Los Angeles, will show it the same
reverence.
</P>
<P>
   For months, it seemed we wouldn't get the chance. The basketball
Lakers weren't playing and the hockey Kings weren't playing well.
There was no reason to go. The Forum, home of Magic and Wayne and
the Laker Girls _ and Jack _ was destined to just fade into
history, without a proper farewell.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us might have attended our final Forum event _ without
even knowing it at the time _ last April when the Kings were swept
out of the NHL playoffs by the St. Louis Blues, or last May when
the Lakers were swept out of the NBA playoffs by the Utah Jazz.
Nice memories.
</P>
<P>
   That changed in the past week. The Kings went on a winning
streak. The Lakers prepared to have a season after all.
</P>
<P>
   The Forum is the place to be again _ until its two famous
tenants move downtown to the Staples Center in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   And so we write today to say: Savor it while you can. Take one
last look around. Make like a tourist and fire off a flashbulb. And
_ this is directed to Lakers and Kings management _ how about a
going-away party while we're at it?
</P>
<P>
   The good news is it's going to happen, the only question being
whether any bash will be big enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'd be nice to give it a champagne-soaked farewell,'' said
Lakers spokesman John Black, meaning an NBA title, which would be
the team's seventh of the Forum era. But no specific plans have yet
been announced for a public commemoration.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Kings, team executives held their first meeting a few
days ago to plan a goodbye but aren't yet sure how they'll do it. A
public skating session on the Forum ice? A hockey-star-studded
banquet?
</P>
<P>
   The first Forum event was a 2-0 Kings loss to the Philadelphia
Flyers on the afternoon of Saturday, Dec. 30, 1967. The Lakers
played the next night and beat the San Diego Rockets 147-118.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of memories in this place,'' said Stu Nahan, who
broadcast that first Forum hockey game to the nation on CBS-TV.
``It doesn't seem old to me. It's 31 years and a month, and to me
it looks the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Once, the arena's $18 million price tag, its Forum Club bar and
its A-list customers made it a modern wonder. To say nothing of its
featured acts: two Lakers dynasties, the Gretzky-led Kings,
Ali-Norton, Elvis. Or its warmup acts: the WNBA's Sparks, Strings
team tennis, Lazers indoor soccer, Blades roller hockey,
Monday-night boxing.
</P>
<P>
   But after 31 years and a month, its locker rooms are small, its
weight rooms outdated, its revenue stream a trickle.
</P>
<P>
   The men and women who have been at the Forum all their
professional lives are realists. Its time has come. They know the
youngsters aren't impressed at all by the Forum, once called
Fabulous, now called Great Western but increasingly old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   So just as Boston Garden, Chicago Stadium, the Philadelphia
Spectrum and the Montreal Forum were abandoned, the Forum will be
too, at a much younger age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts a lot, emotionally,'' said Elliott Berland, the Forum
press-room attendant since that first game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard part is we don't know when that (last game) will
be,'' said Bill Gurney, who was 12 when he sat in a $4.50 rafters
seat for the first Kings game, and now is the coaches' video
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   It could end with the regular season. Or, as lately appears
likely, the Kings could make the playoffs but get knocked out at
any time. Or the Kings' Forum era could end with an exhibition game
before their first Staples Center season opens in October.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Forum will still be here, perhaps to play host to
boxing and women's basketball and concerts for decades to come. But
the big-league teams and most of the fans will be gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Staples Center will create its own memories,'' said
Peirson, who's been a Forum employee since 1978 and intends to
stay. ``But for the fans who have been coming here for 31 years,
the Forum will always be a special place.''
</P>
<P>
   They know it in Albania. Let's show it here. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
