</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-335&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS GET INTO THE GAME TOO LATE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In the opening minute of the third
period Saturday night, a handful of hats flew onto the ice at the
Continental Arena. There was no hat trick, just a hat giveaway at
the arena and a disappointing performance by the home team.
</P>
<P>
   The tossing of the hats came when the Washington Capitals scored
just 35 seconds into the third period, taking a three-goal lead on
their way to a 3-2 victory over the Devils. While the gesture might
have been a show of derision for the Devils, it might also have
served as a reward for the Capitals, who have rebounded from a
seemingly endless string of injuries to put together their first
three-game winning streak of the season.
</P>
<P>
   If it took this long for the Capitals to realize their season
was slipping away, it seemed that the Capitals' third goal _ Joe
Juneau's first since Nov. 7 _ was enough to make the Devils realize
that this game was slipping away. The Devils finally scored three
minutes later when Vadim Sharifijanov stuffed in a rebound of a
Bobby Holik shot to cut the deficit to two goals.
</P>
<P>
   A chance make it a one-goal game was ruined by Washington
goaltender Olaf Kolzig, who collided with Denis Pederson behind the
net, then skidded back just in time to extend his stick and deflect
what looked to Jay Pandolfo like a shot toward an open net. Kolzig
then stopped Pandolfo from close range with six minutes to play
when the Devils wing took a feed from Pederson after Brendan
Morrison stole the puck. Kolzig then came up big again on a shot by
Randy McKay from the left circle with 4 minutes 9 seconds to play.
The Capitals goalie finished with 39 saves.
</P>
<P>
   It was not until the Devils pulled goaltender Chris Terreri and
there were just 47.4 seconds left that they were able to convert.
Patrik Elias scored on a rush with assists from Morrison and
Pandolfo. The Devils called timeout with 13.6 seconds left, but
could not stuff the puck by Kolzig. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After a 4-0 start on the season, Terreri lost his second
straight game. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Devils had beaten the Capitals in two previous meetings this
season, including a 3-2 decision 10 days ago in Washington. But in
winning their two games before this one, the Capitals, who are tied
as the third-worst scoring team in the National Hockey League, had
scored 10 goals.
</P>
<P>
   With Terreri in net for just the second time since Dec. 5, when
he picked up his last victory, the Capitals' offense continued to
produce. The Capitals got on the board first, scoring with just 59
seconds remaining in the opening period. Brian Bellows picked up a
loose puck along the boards behind the Devils' net and set up
there, faking left and right until Terreri turned his head to the
right and defenseman Lyle Odelein moved away from the net. Bellows
lunged to the post and stuffed the puck in under Terreri's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals increased the lead to 2-0 at 7:18 of the second
period. The Devils' Kevin Dean deflected a Peter Bondra pass
intended for Steve Konowalchuk, but Michal Pivonka retrieved the
puck and skated in alone from the right circle. Terreri tried to
close off the near side of the net, but Pivonka continued past,
easily tucking the puck into the open side. The goal came just
three seconds after a Capitals' power play had ended.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils did not challenge Kolzig until the final seconds of
the second period. With 30 seconds left, Elias fed Jason Arnott
alone in front. But Kolzig stopped Arnott's shot, and the rebound
came back to Arnott, whose backhand shot went sliding wide of the
sprawling goalie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
