</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MERCEDES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHEAD BY 5, DUVAL OUTRUNS THE PACK
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This story subs for GLF-SINGH that moved earlier.) 
(nk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAPALUA, Hawaii _ While his pursuers tried to remain in
contention Saturday, David Duval remained in a class by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a five-under-par 68, Duval stood at 21 under (198) at
the Mercedes Championships and took the same five-stroke lead into
Sunday's final round that he began Saturday with. Fred Funk was in
second place at 16 under, Billy Mayfair was third at 15 under, and
Vijay Singh, Tiger Woods and Jim Furyk were tied for fourth at 14
under, a distant seven strokes behind Duval.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning the third round with a five-stroke lead can feel like
starting the day with a bull's-eye painted on your back, and lesser
players can be intimidated by the role of front-runner. But Duval
doesn't seem to care what anyone else does, and he refused to let
up after tying the course record Friday with a 63.
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent players made charges Saturday, including
Woods, whose 67 was the day's best round, as well as Funk and
Furyk, who both shot 68's. But Duval's steadiness was
extraordinary, as he refused to flinch despite the pursuit of the
pack. Seeing names climbing up the leader board only seemed to
increase Duval's concentration and intensity. And unless someone
catches Duval on Sunday, he will begin 1999 with a $468,000
first-place check and a new Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   For the contenders chasing Duval, Saturday's mission was to keep
him from running away. But most of the field seemed ready to
concede.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's threatening to run away with it,'' said Woods. ``I think
he should give me a stroke on each side. That way, I'd only be two
strokes back. My hat's off to him. You would think after shooting
10 under par yesterday, he might come out a little flat.'' Asked if
he looked at Duval as the player to beat right now, Woods said:
``Yeah, I do _ him, Mark O'Meara, Lee Westwood. You have to go into
tournaments looking at those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   At least Funk managed to keep Duval from ending the day with an
even bigger advantage. With his wife, Sharon, caddying for him this
week, Funk has enjoyed this working vacation in Hawaii perhaps even
more than the other players. ``I don't have any history on this
course at all, other than having fun,'' said Funk, not a long
hitter but one of the tour's most accurate drivers. ``This course
has eaten me alive before. I'm just glad to finally play well
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody has been better than Duval, who has seven victories
in his last 26 starts on tour. The more Duval wins, the more people
search for superlatives to describe his game, and many of his peers
believe that Duval is the world's best player right now. Asked
about that, Duval continued to be modest. ``When your peers would
even breathe something in those terms, it's flattering,'' said
Duval, who is ranked No. 3 in the world, behind Woods and O'Meara.
``You're talking about guys who have really worked hard and long
for many years to be exceptional. For them to say that about
another player, you have to take that in the highest regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day with a five-stroke lead over Singh, Funk and
Mayfair, Duval had another splendid day, although the increased
wind made the Kapalua Plantation Course play a little tougher.
Duval's round included six birdies and one bogey, and he never led
by fewer than four strokes. He birdied Nos. 5, 8. and 9 on the
front side, then birdied Nos. 12, 14 and 15 on the back side. His
only bogey came at No.16 after he had reached 22 under, but even if
the wind blows harder on Sunday, few seemed to expect Duval to
falter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never say never, but he's in a zone right now,'' O'Meara said.
``David has great composure on the golf course. He is playing as
well as anyone in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   By winning two majors last year, the Masters and the British
Open, O'Meara was voted player of the year by his peers, although
Duval led the tour in victories last year with four. Duval has yet
to win a major, and that remains perhaps his primary goal for this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the type of year that could warrant player of the year,
but what Mark did was historical,'' Duval said. ``I didn't have a
historical year compared to his. I think because of that, he was
probably more deserving of player of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval won't have another chance to win a major until the Masters
in April. But in the meantime, he seems determined to keep winning
tournaments. And he will begin Sunday with an excellent chance to
win another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
