<HEADER>
A6611 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      01-09 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE LIE MULTIPLIED BY 100 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
In the time it took to say, ``I do,'' the number of high-profile
politicians who should be prosecuted for the crime of perjury rose
by 100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The alleged crime happened on live TV, although you didn't see
it.
</P>
<P>
   Like all sensible Americans, you quit watching anything that had
to do with impeachment months ago.
</P>
<P>
   That's OK, it's on tape.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the U.S. Senate stood in front of Chief Justice
William H. Rehnquist last week.
</P>
<P>
   They had on dark suits and dark ties. They wore their dark
dispositions on their sleeves and raised their right hands to
heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking clearly and sternly, the chief justice asked them, ``Do
you solemnly swear that in all things appertaining to the trial of
the impeachment of William Jefferson Clinton, president of the
United States, now pending, you will do impartial justice according
to the Constitution and laws: So help you God.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a single one of them dropped his arm or faked a sneeze or
bent down to tie his shoe. None crossed his fingers behind his back
(Probably because there were cameras in the back of the room, too).
Instead, each senator answered, ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Starr is gonna need a whole lot more lawyers. &QL; 
PLENTY OF EVIDENCE
</P>
<P>
   All the evidence needed to prosecute the alleged perjurers is on
tape, and it's better than anything they've got on Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspects tried to be coy.
</P>
<P>
   None tried to be evasive.
</P>
<P>
   None even asked the chief justice for the definition of
``impartial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do,'' they said darkly, joining themselves in unholy
matrimony with the devil himself, then dragging the rest of us to
their wedding reception in hell.
</P>
<P>
   You've asked them to stop what they're doing and they do it,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   They have no choice, they say. The Constitution, which cannot be
ignored, commands them to hold an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   You asked them to make the trial speedy and they drag it out.
They have no choice, they say. The Constitution cannot be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   You asked them to stop playing games, to stop acting like they
don't have all the information they need, to stop pretending they
haven't already made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   They swear to God they are impartial. &QL; 
TAUNTING LIKE A BULLY
</P>
<P>
   They're like the bully who taunts a smaller, weaker kid by
repeating the last few words of everything he says, everything he
says. Sometimes, even using the torment to twist the argument their
way.
</P>
<P>
   You say, ``Under no circumstances do we want a long trial.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Want a long trial,'' they answer.
</P>
<P>
   You say, ``We'd prefer you didn't call many witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Call many witnesses,'' they answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to listen to sex talk . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to sex talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . or watch our politicians ignore real problems . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ignore real problems.''
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . while you boldly and stupidly conduct a political
vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Conduct a political vendetta.''
</P>
<P>
   It's one thing to go after a guy because he's a Democrat and
you're a Republican and you don't like him or what he stands for or
how he acts. It's different when you take an oath.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton didn't get into trouble for wagging his finger and
saying on TV he didn't have sexual relations with that woman, Miss
Lewinsky. It's the stuff he said under oath that got him impeached.
</P>
<P>
   An oath very much like the one taken by senators last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the dictionary on my desk, the defi nition of ``impartial''
is: ``Favoring no one side or party more than another; without
prejudice or bias; fair; just.''
</P>
<P>
   The definition of ``perjury'' is: ``The willful telling of a lie
while under lawful oath or affirmation to tell the truth in a
matter material to the point of inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's Senate trial is just get ting started and
already there's a whole lot of lying going on.
</P>
<P>
   I'd swear to it. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
