<SLUG> BC-BKC-SETON-STJOHN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED STORM REGAINS CONFIDENCE AND ITS TOUCH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Perhaps it was the abysmal shooting from the field.
Maybe it was the sense that St. John's had simply forgotten where
the rim was when standing at the line. Or was it St. John's
somnolence in its loss to Miami last week that stirred Mike Jarvis
before Saturday night's game against Seton Hall?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motive, Jarvis did a bit of coachly tinkering he
said he had been considering for a while, starting a smaller,
quicker, better-shooting group that had Tyrone Grant at center and
Reggie Jessie and Ron Artest at the forwards.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's snapped out of its slumber that had taken over the
Miami game, churning up and down the court with renewed vigor for
an 86-75 victory. Behind the all-around play of Ron Artest, who
finished with a triple-double (13 points, 12 rebounds and 10
assists) _ the first at St. John's since Mark Jackson, now of the
Indiana Pacers, did it during the 1985-86 season _ St. John's
opened a 20-point lead with 4:26 left in the first half and held
off a late charge by the Pirates. St. John's never trailed, and
played perhaps its finest half of the season, shooting 65.5 percent
from the field and outrebounding Seton Hall 22-11 in the first 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very impressive how hungry they were,'' Seton Hall
Coach Tommy Amaker said. ``They were creating havoc for us. We
couldn't guard them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10th-ranked Red Storm (13-3, 4-1) entered the game seeking a
measure of reassurance after last Wednesday's loss to Miami: that
its roll through the first part of the season wasn't an aberration,
that its ranking wouldn't soon be fodder for ridicule, that its
shooting touch hadn't abandoned the players just when the schedule
was getting treacherous.
</P>
<P>
   The first half gave the Red Storm and the 11,107 fans at Madison
Square Garden the answer. Seton Hall (10-5, 4-2), a team on the
rise in the Big East, had beaten St. John's in the Garden last
season and has already defeated then No. 12 Syracuse by 16 points
in the Carrier Dome. But the cross-Hudson rivalry that once was is
not back just yet.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's made sure this would not be another listless evening
when two unanswered first-half runs _ one of 7 points and another
of 13 _ put St. John's safely ahead, and provided great theater,
full of fast breaks and easy layups in the lane. Bootsy Thornton,
who finished with a game high 27 points, hit a 3-pointer (St.
John's had made just 5 of 23 in Miami), Artest rifled a bullet pass
underneath to Grant for an easy layup (they weren't so easy in
Miami when St. John's shot just 41.4 percent from the field) and
Erick Barkley led Thornton with an outlet pass that Thornton placed
in the basket for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were sharp with the offense, sharp on the break,'' Jarvis
said. ``They were really running. They were playing team
basketball. I don't know if it was the best half, but it was
close.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, in particular, had struggled in his last three games,
failing to deliver the play-making passes, losing his way at the
line, and getting into foul trouble. He picked up his third foul
with 4:49 left in the first half, but not before he launched a
gorgeous alley oop pass to Artest. Artest, who had an abysmal 6 of
15 performance against Miami, came back Saturday night with a
strong all-around performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't scoring a lot of points,'' Artest said, ``so I was
trying to do other things to help the team win.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the lead was up to 21 with 15:05 left in the game, St.
John's showed it is still vulnerable to a lapse of attention. And
when Barkley, seemingly the only player who can adequately guard
Seton Hall's superb point guard Shaheen Holloway, got his fourth
foul with 13:38 left and the lead at 17, the tightly-played game
began to unravel, and Seton Hall closed the lead to eight points
with 4:41 left. But Barkley returned intermittently (he finished
with 16 points, 11 from the foul line, and five assists), and when
Artest, standing near the baseline, passed out to Jessie at the
foul line, who found reserve guard Collin Charles (16 points),
inside for a layup the lead was back to 12 with 3:16 left.
</P>
<P>
   The alarm had gone off and another nap was over.
</P>
</TEXT>
