<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-W.VA.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOUNTAINEERING PROVES MUCH TO UCONN'S LIKING
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MORGANTOWN, W.Va. _ Connecticut had little to prove against West
Virginia Saturday night, but there were a few matters to address.
</P>
<P>
   There was the settlement of accounts. West Virginia was the last
team to defeat UConn in a Big East game.
</P>
<P>
   And the No. 1-ranked Huskies could show that they travel well.
Their plane to nearby Pittsburgh had been delayed more than 24
hours because of bad weather, denying the Huskies their routine of
arriving a day early and having a shoot-around the morning of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Huskies should hang out in airports more often.
Richard Hamilton scored 30 points as UConn ran past West Virginia,
80-45. Kevin Freeman added 14 for the Huskies (12-0, 5-0 Big East),
who stopped the Mountaineers' upset hopes from the start with
tenacious defense and opportunistic fast breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The UConn reserve guard Albert Mouring scored 11 points, and
Jake Voskuhl scored 8 points to go with his 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jarett Kearse was the only West Virginia player in double
figures, scoring 13 points. West Virginia (7-8, 2-4) made 6 of 19
free throws, but that was a small part of its shooting woes. The
Mountaineers were 17 of 58 (29.3 percent) from the field while the
Huskies were 30 of 57 (52.6 percent) and 12 of 14 (85.7 percent) at
the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hit 5 of 10 3-point attempts and was 11 of 19 from the
field. West Virginia's best player, Marcus Goree, made just 4 of 13
shots in scoring 9 points, although he did have four blocked shots.
</P>
<P>
   West Virginia showed signs of improving on its laughable
shooting at the end of the first half, but Hamilton kept the
Mountaineers out of the game. He lofted in a 3-pointer, rolled in a
layup off Ricky Moore's steal and then drained another 3-pointer
off his own steal to give UConn a 44-19 lead early in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton gave the crowd something to cheer by missing a put-back
with UConn ahead by 50-22. But for most of the night, the Coliseum
faithful were rendered silent by the superior Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   UConn led by 55-28 with 9 minutes 53 seconds to go, and many
fans were wriggling into their parkas and leaving the arena.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a far cry from the teams' meeting last Feb. 6. That
night, UConn Coach Jim Calhoun yelled at Hamilton and Khalid
El-Amin as they returned to the bench while West Virginia was
upsetting the Huskies, 80-62. UConn has won 13 straight Big East
games since, and Saturday night the Huskies got their revenge on
the Mountaineers.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, UConn will play host to Notre Dame while celebrating
its seventh week at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies came into Saturday night leading the Big East in
scoring (86.7 points a game) and most other offensive categories.
But their defense did most of the work in staking them to a 34-17
lead at halftime. UConn played tight man-to-man, occasionally
trapping with up to three players in the front court. The
Mountaineers helped the visitors' cause with their wretched
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton hit two 3-pointers and a layup in guiding Connecticut
to a 16-4 lead. The Huskies then went through a stretch of 5:27
without a point, but West Virginia barely capitalized, making just
3 of 7 free throws. The Mountaineers would eventually go nearly 13
minutes without a field goal. Coach Gale Catlett substituted
furiously, trying to find anybody who would not make the basket
look the diameter of a thimble.
</P>
<P>
   The revolving-door approach did not work. The Huskies strung
together a 12-1 run to take a 28-8 lead with 3:45 left in the half.
At that point, West Virginia was shooting 10 percent (2 of 20) from
the field. Lionel Armstead made a 3-pointer with 3:40 to go that
brought sarcastic cheers from the fans. The basket inspired the
Mountaineers. After Hamilton, who scored 15 points in the first
half, sank three free throws to give UConn a 31-8 lead, the
Mountaineers received baskets from Kearse, Goree and Jamar Gaither
to outscore the Huskies by 6-3 in the last 45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   That the Mountaineers could shoot 23 percent from the field and
40 percent (4 of 10) from the free-throw line and be down by just
17 points to the nation's top-ranked team must have been some sort
of consolation. But it was forgotten as the second half wore on.
</P>
